\pard\qc Dudley Demented\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\fs24\par
The hottest day of the summer so far was drawing to a close and a drowsy silence lay over the large, square houses of Privet Drive. Cars that were usually gleaming stood dusty in their drives and lawns that were once emerald green lay parched and yellowing; the use of hosepipes had been banned due to drought. Deprived of their usual car-washing and lawn-mowing pursuits, the inhabitants of Privet Drive had retreated into the shade of their cool houses, windows thrown wide in the hope of tempting in a nonexistent breeze. The only person left outdoors was a teenage boy who was lying flat on his back in a flower bed outside number four.\par
He was a skinny, black-haired, bespectacled boy who had the pinched, slightly unhealthy look of someone who has grown a lot in a short space of time. His jeans were torn and dirty, his T-shirt baggy and faded, and the soles of his trainers were peeling away from the up\-pers. Harry Potter\rquote s appearance did not endear him to the neighbors, who were the sort of people who thought scruffiness ought to be pun\-ishable by law, but as he had hidden himself behind a large hydrangea bush this evening he was quite invisible to passersby. In fact, the only way he would be spotted was if his Uncle Vernon or Aunt Petunia stuck their heads out of the living room window and looked straight down into the flower bed below.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 On the whole, Harry thought he was to be congratulated on his idea of hiding here. He was not, perhaps, very comfortable lying on the hot, hard earth, but on the other hand, nobody was glaring at him, grinding their teeth so loudly that he could not hear the news, or shooting nasty questions at him, as had happened every time he had tried sitting down in the living room and watching television with his aunt and uncle.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Almost as though this thought had fluttered through the open win\-dow, Vernon Dursley, Harry\rquote s uncle, suddenly spoke. \ldblquote Glad to see the boy\rquote s stopped trying to butt in. Where is he anyway?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t know,\rdblquote  said Aunt Petunia unconcernedly. \ldblquote Not in the house.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Uncle Vernon grunted.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Watching the news\i0  \'85\rdblquote  he said scathingly. \ldblquote I\rquote d like to know what he\rquote s really up to. As if a normal boy cares what\rquote s on the news \emdash  Dud\-ley hasn\rquote t got a clue what\rquote s going on, doubt he knows who the Prime Minister is! Anyway, it\rquote s not as if there\rquote d be anything about \i his lot\i0  on \i our\i0  news \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Vernon, \i shh\i0 !\rdblquote  said Aunt Petunia. \ldblquote The window\rquote s open!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh \emdash  yes \emdash  sorry, dear \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The Dursleys fell silent. Harry listened to a jingle about Fruit \rquote N Bran breakfast cereal while he watched Mrs. Figg, a batty, cat-loving old lady from nearby Wisteria Walk, amble slowly past. She was frowning and muttering to herself. Harry was very pleased that he was concealed behind the bush; Mrs. Figg had recently taken to asking him around for tea whenever she met him in the street. She had rounded the corner and vanished from view before Uncle Vernon\rquote s voice floated out of the window again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Dudders out for tea?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote At the Polkisses\rquote ,\rdblquote  said Aunt Petunia fondly. \ldblquote He\rquote s got so many lit\-tle friends, he\rquote s so popular \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry repressed a snort with difficulty. The Dursleys really were as\-tonishingly stupid about their son, Dudley; they had swallowed all his dim-witted lies about having tea with a different member of his gang every night of the summer holidays. Harry knew perfectly well that Dudley had not been to tea anywhere; he and his gang spent every evening vandalizing the play park, smoking on street corners, and throwing stones at passing cars and children. Harry had seen them at it during his evening walks around Little Whinging; he had spent most of the holidays wandering the streets, scavenging newspapers from bins along the way.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The opening notes of the music that heralded the seven o\rquote clock news reached Harry\rquote s ears and his stomach turned over. Perhaps tonight \emdash  after a month of waiting \emdash  would be the night \emdash\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Record numbers of stranded holidaymakers fill airports as the Spanish baggage-handlers\rquote  strike reaches its second week \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Give \rquote em a lifelong siesta, I would,\rdblquote  snarled Uncle Vernon over the end of the newsreader\rquote s sentence, but no matter: Outside in the flower bed, Harry\rquote s stomach seemed to unclench. If anything had happened, it would surely have been the first item on the news; death and de\-struction were more important than stranded holidaymakers. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He let out a long, slow breath and stared up at the brilliant blue sky. Every day this summer had been the same: the tension, the expecta\-tion, the temporary relief, and then mounting tension again \'85 and always, growing more insistent all the time, the question of \i why\i0  noth\-ing had happened yet. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He kept listening, just in case there was some small clue, not rec\-ognized for what it really was by the Muggles \emdash  an unexplained disappearance,   perhaps,   or   some   strange   accident\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 but   the baggage-handlers\rquote  strike was followed by news on the drought in the Southeast (\ldblquote I hope he\rquote s listening next door!\rdblquote  bellowed Uncle Vernon, \ldblquote with his sprinklers on at three in the morning!\rdblquote ); then a helicopter that had almost crashed in a field in Surrey, then a famous actress\rquote s di\-vorce from her famous husband (\ldblquote as if we\rquote re interested in their sordid affairs,\rdblquote  sniffed Aunt Petunia, who had followed the case obsessively in every magazine she could lay her bony hands on).\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry closed his eyes against the now blazing evening sky as the newsreader said, \ldblquote And finally, Bungy the budgie has found a novel way of keeping cool this summer. Bungy, who lives at the Five Feath\-ers in Barnsley, has learned to water-ski! Mary Dorkins went to find out more. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry opened his eyes again. If they had reached water-skiing budgerigars, there was nothing else worth hearing. He rolled cau\-tiously onto his front and raised himself onto his knees and elbows, preparing to crawl out from under the window.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He had moved about two inches when several things happened in very quick succession.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A loud, echoing \i crack\i0  broke the sleepy silence like a gunshot; a cat streaked out from under a parked car and flew out of sight; a shriek, a bellowed oath, and the sound of breaking china came from the Durs\-leys\rquote  living room, and as though Harry had been waiting for this signal, he jumped to his feet, at the same time pulling from the waist\-band of his jeans a thin wooden wand as if he were unsheathing a sword. But before he could draw himself up to full height, the top of his head collided with the Dursleys\rquote  open window, and the resultant crash made Aunt Petunia scream even louder.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry felt as if his head had been split in two; eyes streaming, he swayed, trying to focus on the street and spot the source of the noise, but he had barely staggered upright again when two large purple hands reached through the open window and closed tightly around his throat.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Put \i0\emdash  \i it \i0\emdash  \i away\i0 !\rdblquote\i  \i0 Uncle Vernon snarled into Harry\rquote s ear. \ldblquote\i Now\i0 !\i  Before \i0\emdash  \i anyone \i0\emdash  \i sees\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Get \emdash  off\lang3081  \lang1033\emdash  me!\rdblquote  Harry gasped; for a few seconds they strug\-gled, Harry pulling at his uncle\rquote s sausage-like fingers with his left hand, his right maintaining a firm grip on his raised wand. Then, as the pain in the top of Harry\rquote s head gave a particularly nasty throb, Un\-cle Vernon yelped and released Harry as though he had received an electric shock \emdash  some invisible force seemed to have surged through his nephew, making him impossible to hold.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Panting, Harry fell forward over the hydrangea bush, straightened up, and stared around. There was no sign of what had caused the loud cracking noise, but there were several faces peering through various nearby windows. Harry stuffed his wand hastily back into his jeans and tried to look innocent.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Lovely evening!\rdblquote  shouted Uncle Vernon, waving at Mrs. Number Seven, who was glaring from behind her net curtains. \ldblquote Did you hear that car backfire just now? Gave Petunia and me quite a turn!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He continued to grin in a horrible, manic way until all the curious neighbors had disappeared from their various windows, then the grin became a grimace of rage as he beckoned Harry back toward him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry moved a few steps closer, taking care to stop just short of the point at which Uncle Vernon\rquote s outstretched hands could resume their strangling.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What the \i devil\i0  do you mean by it, boy?\rdblquote  asked Uncle Vernon in a croaky voice that trembled with fury.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What do I mean by what?\rdblquote  said Harry coldly. He kept looking left and right up the street, still hoping to see the person who had made the cracking noise.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Making a racket like a starting pistol right outside our \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I didn\rquote t make that noise,\rdblquote  said Harry firmly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Aunt Petunia\rquote s thin, horsey face now appeared beside Uncle Ver\-non\rquote s wide, purple one. She looked livid.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Why were you lurking under our window?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes \emdash  yes, good point, Petunia! \i What were you doing under our window, boy\i0 ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Listening to the news,\rdblquote  said Harry in a resigned voice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 His aunt and uncle exchanged looks of outrage.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Listening to the news! \i Again\i0 ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, it changes every day, you see,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Don\rquote t you be clever with me, boy! I want to know what you\rquote re re\-ally up to \emdash  and don\rquote t give me any more of this \i listening to the news\i0  tosh! You know perfectly well that \i your lot\lang3081\i0  \lang1033\'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Careful, Vernon!\rdblquote  breathed Aunt Petunia, and Uncle Vernon low\-ered his voice so that Harry could barely hear him, \ldblquote\'85 that \i your lot \i0 don\rquote t get on \i our\i0  news!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That\rquote s all you know,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The Dursleys goggled at him for a few seconds, then Aunt Petunia said, \ldblquote You\rquote re a nasty little liar. What are all those \emdash\rdblquote  she too lowered her voice so that Harry had to lip-read the next word, \ldblquote\emdash  \i owls\i0  \emdash  doing if they\rquote re not bringing you news?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Aha!\rdblquote  said Uncle Vernon in a triumphant whisper. \ldblquote Get out of that one, boy! As if we didn\rquote t know you get all your news from those pesti\-lential birds!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry hesitated for a moment. It cost him something to tell the truth this time, even though his aunt and uncle could not possibly know how bad Harry felt at admitting it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The owls \'85 aren\rquote t bringing me news,\rdblquote  said Harry tonelessly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t believe it,\rdblquote  said Aunt Petunia at once.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No more do I,\rdblquote  said Uncle Vernon forcefully.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We know you\rquote re up to something funny,\rdblquote  said Aunt Petunia.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We\rquote re not stupid, you know,\rdblquote  said Uncle Vernon.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, \i that\rquote s\i0  news to me,\rdblquote  said Harry, his temper rising, and before the Dursleys could call him back, he had wheeled about, crossed the front lawn, stepped over the low garden wall, and was striding off up the street.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He was in trouble now and he knew it. He would have to face his aunt and uncle later and pay the price for his rudeness, but he did not care very much just at the moment; he had much more pressing mat\-ters on his mind.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry was sure that the cracking noise had been made by someone Apparating or Disapparating. It was exactly the sound Dobby the house-elf made when he vanished into thin air. Was it possible that Dobby was here in Privet Drive? Could Dobby be following him right at this very moment? As this thought occurred he wheeled around and stared back down Privet Drive, but it appeared to be completely de\-serted again and Harry was sure that Dobby did not know how to become invisible. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He walked on, hardly aware of the route he was taking, for he had pounded these streets so often lately that his feet carried him to his fa\-vorite haunts automatically. Every few steps he glanced back over his shoulder. Someone magical had been near him as he lay among Aunt Petunias dying begonias, he was sure of it. Why hadn\rquote t they spoken to him, why hadn\rquote t they made contact, why were they hiding now?\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And then, as his feeling of frustration peaked, his certainty leaked away.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Perhaps it hadn\rquote t been a magical sound after all. Perhaps he was so desperate for the tiniest sign of contact from the world to which he belonged that he was simply overreacting to perfectly ordinary noises. Could he be \i sure\i0  it hadn\rquote t been the sound of something breaking in\-side a neighbor\rquote s house?\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry felt a dull, sinking sensation in his stomach and, before he knew it, the feeling of hopelessness that had plagued him all summer rolled over him once again. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Tomorrow morning he would be awoken by the alarm at five o\rquote clock so that he could pay the owl that delivered the \i Daily Prophet\i0  \emdash  but was there any point in continuing to take it? Harry merely glanced at the front page before throwing it aside these days; when the idiots who ran the paper finally realized that Voldemort was back it would be headline news, and that was the only kind Harry cared about.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 If he was lucky, there would also be owls carrying letters from his best friends, Ron and Hermione, though any expectation he had had that their letters would bring him news had long since been dashed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i We can\rquote t say much about you-know-what, obviously\i0 . \'85\rdblquote  \ldblquote\i We\rquote ve been told not to say anything important in case our letters go astray. \'85\i0\rdblquote\i  \i0\ldblquote\i We\rquote re quite busy but I can\rquote t give you details here\i0 . \'85\rdblquote  \ldblquote\i There\rquote s a fair amount going on, we\rquote ll tell you everything when we see you\i0 . \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But when were they going to see him? Nobody seemed too both\-ered with a precise date. Hermione had scribbled, \i\ldblquote I expect we\rquote ll be see\-ing you quite soon\i0\rdblquote  inside his birthday card, but how soon was soon? As far as Harry could tell from the vague hints in their letters, Hermione and Ron were in the same place, presumably at Ron\rquote s parents\rquote  house. He could hardly bear to think of the pair of them having fun at the Burrow when he was stuck in Privet Drive. In fact, he was so angry at them that he had thrown both their birthday presents of Honeydukes chocolates away unopened, though he had regretted this after eating the wilting salad Aunt Petunia had provided for dinner that night.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And what were Ron and Hermione busy with? Why wasn\rquote t he, Harry, busy? Hadn\rquote t he proved himself capable of handling much more than they? Had they all forgotten what he had done? Hadn\rquote t it been \i he\i0  who had entered that graveyard and watched Cedric being murdered and been tied to that tombstone and nearly killed \'85 ?\lang3081\par
\lang1033\i Don\rquote t think about that, \i0 Harry told himself sternly for the hundredth time that summer. It was bad enough that he kept revisiting the grave\-yard in his nightmares, without dwelling on it in his waking moments too.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He turned a corner into Magnolia Crescent; halfway along he passed the narrow alleyway down the side of a garage where he had first clapped eyes on his godfather. Sirius, at least, seemed to under\-stand how Harry was feeling; admittedly his letters were just as empty of proper news as Ron and Hermione\rquote s, but at least they contained words of caution and consolation instead of tantalizing hints:\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i I know this must be frustrating for you\i0 . \'85\rdblquote  \ldblquote\i Keep your nose clean and everything will be okay\i0 . \'85\rdblquote  \ldblquote\i Be careful and don\rquote t do anything rash\i0 . \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Well, thought Harry, as he crossed Magnolia Crescent, turned into Magnolia Road, and headed toward the darkening play park, he had (by and large) done as Sirius advised; he had at least resisted the temp\-tation to tie his trunk to his broomstick and set off for the Burrow by himself. In fact Harry thought his behavior had been very good considering how frustrated and angry he felt at being stuck in Privet Drive this long, reduced to hiding in flower beds in the hope of hear\-ing something that might point to what Lord Voldemort was doing. Nevertheless, it was quite galling to be told not to be rash by a man who had served twelve years in the wizard prison, Azkaban, escaped, attempted to commit the murder he had been convicted for in the first place, then gone on the run with a stolen hippogriff. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry vaulted over the locked park gate and set off across the parched grass. The park was as empty as the surrounding streets. When he reached the swings he sank onto the only one that Dudley and his friends had not yet managed to break, coiled one arm around the chain, and stared moodily at the ground. He would not be able to hide in the Dursleys\rquote  flower bed again. Tomorrow he would have to think of some fresh way of listening to the news. In the meantime, he had nothing to look forward to but another restless, disturbed night, because even when he escaped nightmares about Cedric he had unset\-tling dreams about long dark corridors, all finishing in dead ends and locked doors, which he supposed had something to do with the trapped feeling he had when he was awake. Often the old scar on his forehead prickled uncomfortably, but he did not fool himself that Ron or Hermione or Sirius would find that very interesting any\-more. \'85 In the past his scar hurting had warned that Voldemort was getting stronger again, but now that Voldemort was back they would probably remind him that its regular irritation was only to be ex\-pected. \'85 Nothing to worry about\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 old news \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The injustice of it all welled up inside him so that he wanted to yell with fury. If it hadn\rquote t been for him, nobody would even have known Voldemort was back! And his reward was to be stuck in Little Whing\-ing for four solid weeks, completely cut off from the magical world, reduced to squatting among dying begonias so that he could hear about water-skiing budgerigars! How could Dumbledore have forgot\-ten him so easily? Why had Ron and Hermione got together without inviting him along too? How much longer was he supposed to endure Sirius telling him to sit tight and be a good boy; or resist the tempta\-tion to write to the stupid \i Daily Prophet\i0  and point out that Volde\-mort had returned? These furious thoughts whirled around in Harry\rquote s head, and his insides writhed with anger as a sultry, velvety night fell around him, the air full of the smell of warm, dry grass and the only sound that of the low grumble of traffic on the road beyond the park railings.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He did not know how long he had sat on the swing before the sound of voices interrupted his musings and he looked up. The street-lamps from the surrounding roads were casting a misty glow strong enough to silhouette a group of people making their way across the park. One of them was singing a loud, crude song. The others were laughing. A soft ticking noise came from several expensive racing bikes that they were wheeling along.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry knew who those people were. The figure in front was unmis\-takably his cousin, Dudley Dursley, wending his way home, accom\-panied by his faithful gang.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dudley was as vast as ever, but a year\rquote s hard dieting and the discov\-ery of a new talent had wrought quite a change in his physique. As Uncle Vernon delightedly told anyone who would listen, Dudley had recently become the Junior Heavyweight Inter-School Boxing Cham\-pion of the Southeast. \ldblquote The noble sport,\rdblquote  as Uncle Vernon called it, had made Dudley even more formidable than he had seemed to Harry in the primary school days when he had served as Dudley\rquote s first punching bag. Harry was not remotely afraid of his cousin anymore but he still didn\rquote t think that Dudley learning to punch harder and more accurately was cause for celebration. Neighborhood children all around were terrified of him \emdash  even more terrified than they were of \ldblquote that Potter boy,\rdblquote  who, they had been warned, was a hardened hooli\-gan who attended St. Brutus\rquote s Secure Center for Incurably Criminal Boys.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry watched the dark figures crossing the grass and wondered whom they had been beating up tonight. \i Look round,\i0  Harry found himself thinking as he watched them. \i Come on \'85 look round\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 I\rquote m sitting here all alone. \'85 Come and have ago. \'85\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033 If Dudley\rquote s friends saw him sitting here, they would be sure to make a beeline for him, and what would Dudley do then? He wouldn\rquote t want to lose face in front of the gang, but he\rquote d be terrified of provoking Harry. \'85 It would be really fun to watch Dudley\rquote s dilemma; to taunt him, watch him, with him powerless to respond \'85 and if any of the others tried hitting Harry, Harry was ready \emdash  he had his wand \'85 let them try \'85 He\rquote d love to vent some of his frus\-tration on the boys who had once made his life hell \emdash\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But they did not turn around, they did not see him, they were al\-most at the railings. Harry mastered the impulse to call after them. \'85 Seeking a fight was not a smart move. \'85 He must not use magic. \'85 He would be risking expulsion again. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dudley\rquote s gang\rquote s voices died; they were out of sight, heading along Magnolia Road.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\i There you go, Sirius,\i0  Harry thought dully. \i Nothing rash. Kept my nose clean. Exactly the opposite of what you\rquote d have done\lang3081\i0  \lang1033\'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He got to his feet and stretched. Aunt Petunia and Uncle Vernon seemed to feel that whenever Dudley turned up was the right time to be home, and anytime after that was much too late. Uncle Vernon had threatened to lock Harry in the shed if he came home after Dudley again, so, stifling a yawn, still scowling, Harry set off toward the park gate.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Magnolia Road, like Privet Drive, was full of large, square houses with perfectly manicured lawns, all owned by large, square owners who drove very clean cars similar to Uncle Vernon\rquote s. Harry preferred Little Whinging by night, when the curtained windows made patches of jewel-bright colors in the darkness and he ran no danger of hearing disapproving mutters about his \ldblquote delinquent\rdblquote  appearance when he passed the householders. He walked quickly, so that halfway along Magnolia Road Dudley\rquote s gang came into view again; they were saying their farewells at the entrance to Magnolia Crescent. Harry stepped into the shadow of a large lilac tree and waited.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\'85 squealed like a pig, didn\rquote t he?\rdblquote  Malcolm was saying, to guffaws from the others.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Nice right hook, Big D,\rdblquote  said Piers.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Same time tomorrow?\rdblquote  said Dudley.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Round at my place, my parents are out,\rdblquote  said Gordon.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote See you then,\rdblquote  said Dudley.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Bye Dud!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote See ya, Big D!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry waited for the rest of the gang to move on before setting off again. When their voices had faded once more he headed around the corner into Magnolia Crescent and by walking very quickly he soon came within hailing distance of Dudley, who was strolling along at his ease, humming tunelessly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hey, Big D!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dudley turned.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh,\rdblquote  he grunted. \ldblquote It\rquote s you.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How long have you been \lquote Big D\rquote  then?\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Shut it,\rdblquote  snarled Dudley, turning away again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Cool name,\rdblquote  said Harry, grinning and falling into step beside his cousin. \ldblquote But you\rquote ll always be Ickle Diddykins to me.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
