\lang1033 But at these words of Uncle Vernon\rquote s, Harry\rquote s exhausted brain ground back into action. Why \i had\i0  the dementors come to Little Whinging? How \i could\i0  it be coincidence that they had arrived in the alleyway where Harry was? Had they been sent? Had the Ministry of Magic lost control of the dementors, had they deserted Azkaban and joined Voldemort, as Dumbledore had predicted they would?\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote These demembers guard some weirdos\rquote  prison?\rdblquote  said Uncle Ver\-non, lumbering in the wake of Harry\rquote s train of thought.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 If only his head would stop hurting, if only he could just leave the kitchen and get to his dark bedroom and \i think. \'85\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oho! They were coming to arrest you!\rdblquote  said Uncle Vernon, with the triumphant air of a man reaching an unassailable conclusion. \ldblquote That\rquote s it, isn\rquote t it, boy? You\rquote re on the run from the law!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Of course I\rquote m not,\rdblquote  said Harry, shaking his head as though to scare off a fly, his mind racing now.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Then why \emdash  ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He must have sent them,\rdblquote  said Harry quietly, more to himself than to Uncle Vernon.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What\rquote s that? Who must have sent them?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Lord Voldemort,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He registered dimly how strange it was that the Dursleys, who flinched, winced, and squawked if they heard words like \ldblquote wizard,\rdblquote  \ldblquote magic,\rdblquote  or \ldblquote wand,\rdblquote  could hear the name of the most evil wizard of all time without the slightest tremor.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Lord \emdash  hang on,\rdblquote  said Uncle Vernon, his face screwed up, a look of dawning comprehension in his piggy eyes. \ldblquote I\rquote ve heard that name \'85 that was the one who \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Murdered my parents, yes,\rdblquote  Harry said.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But he\rquote s gone,\rdblquote  said Uncle Vernon impatiently, without the slight\-est sign that the murder of Harry\rquote s parents might be a painful topic to anybody. \ldblquote That giant bloke said so. He\rquote s gone.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He\rquote s back,\rdblquote  said Harry heavily.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It felt very strange to be standing here in Aunt Petunia\rquote s surgically clean kitchen, beside the top-of-the-range fridge and the wide-screen television, and talking calmly of Lord Voldemort to Uncle Vernon. The arrival of the dementors in Little Whinging seemed to have caused a breach in the great, invisible wall that divided the relentlessly non-magical world of Privet Drive and the world beyond. Harry\rquote s two lives had somehow become fused and everything had been turned up\-side down: The Dursleys were asking for details about the magical world and Mrs. Figg knew Albus Dumbledore; dementors were soar\-ing around Little Whinging and he might never go back to Hogwarts. Harry\rquote s head throbbed more painfully.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Back?\rdblquote  whispered Aunt Petunia.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She was looking at Harry as she had never looked at him before. And all of a sudden, for the very first time in his life, Harry fully ap\-preciated that Aunt Petunia was his mother\rquote s sister. He could not have said why this hit him so very powerfully at this moment. All he knew was that he was not the only person in the room who had an inkling of what Lord Voldemort being back might mean. Aunt Petunia had never in her life looked at him like that before. Her large, pale eyes (so unlike her sister\rquote s) were not narrowed in dislike or anger: They were wide and fearful. The furious pretense that Aunt Petunia had main\-tained all Harry\rquote s life \emdash  that there was no magic and no world other than the world she inhabited with Uncle Vernon \emdash  seemed to have fallen away.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  Harry said, talking directly to Aunt Petunia now. \ldblquote He came back a month ago. I saw him.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Her hands found Dudley\rquote s massive leather-clad shoulders and clutched them.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hang on,\rdblquote  said Uncle Vernon, looking from his wife to Harry and back again, apparently dazed and confused by the unprecedented un\-derstanding that seemed to have sprung up between them. \ldblquote Hang on. This Lord Voldything\rquote s back, you say.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The one who murdered your parents.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And now he\rquote s sending dismembers after you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Looks like it,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I see,\rdblquote  said Uncle Vernon, looking from his white-faced wife to Harry and hitching up his trousers. He seemed to be swelling, his great purple face stretching before Harry\rquote s eyes. \ldblquote Well, that settles it,\rdblquote  he said, his shirt front straining as he inflated himself, \ldblquote\i you can get out of this house, boy\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What?\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You heard me \emdash  OUT!\rdblquote  Uncle Vernon bellowed, and even Aunt\lang3081  \lang1033 Petunia and Dudley jumped. \ldblquote OUT! OUT! I should\rquote ve done it years ago! Owls treating the place like a rest home, puddings exploding, half the lounge destroyed, Dudley\rquote s tail, Marge bobbing around on the ceiling, and that flying Ford Anglia \emdash  OUT! OUT! You\rquote ve had it! You\rquote re history! You\rquote re not staying here if some loony\rquote s after you, you\rquote re not endangering my wife and son, you\rquote re not bringing trouble down on us, if you\rquote re going the same way as your useless parents, I\rquote ve had it! OUT!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry stood rooted to the spot. The letters from the Ministry, Mr. Weasley, and Sirius were crushed in his left hand. \i Don\rquote t leave the house again, whatever you do. DO NOT LEAVE YOUR AUNT AND UNCLE\rquote S HOUSE\i0 .\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You heard me!\rdblquote  said Uncle Vernon, bending forward now, so that his massive purple face came closer to Harry\rquote s, so that Harry actually felt flecks of spit hit his face. \ldblquote Get going! You were all keen to leave half an hour ago! I\rquote m right behind you! Get out and never darken our doorstep again! Why we ever kept you in the first place I don\rquote t know. Marge was right, it should have been the orphanage, we were too damn soft for our own good, thought we could squash it out of you, thought we could turn you normal, but you\rquote ve been rotten from the beginning, and I\rquote ve had enough \emdash  OWLS!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The fifth owl zoomed down the chimney so fast it actually hit the floor before zooming into the air again with a loud screech. Harry raised his hand to seize the letter, which was in a scarlet envelope, but it soared straight over his head, flying directly at Aunt Petunia, who let out a scream and ducked, her arms over her face. The owl dropped the red envelope on her head, turned, and flew straight up the chimney again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry darted forward to pick up the letter, but Aunt Petunia beat him to it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You can open it if you like,\rdblquote  said Harry, \ldblquote but I\rquote ll hear what it says anyway. That\rquote s a Howler.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Let go of it, Petunia!\rdblquote  roared Uncle Vernon. \ldblquote Don\rquote t touch it, it could be dangerous!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s addressed to me,\rdblquote  said Aunt Petunia in a shaking voice. \ldblquote It\rquote s addressed to \i me\i0 , Vernon, look! \i Mrs. Petunia Dursley, The Kitchen, Number Four, Privet Drive\i0  \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She caught her breath, horrified. The red envelope had begun to smoke.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Open it!\rdblquote  Harry urged her. \ldblquote Get it over with! It\rquote ll happen anyway \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Aunt Petunia\rquote s hand was trembling. She looked wildly around the kitchen as though looking for an escape route, but too late \emdash  the en\-velope burst into flames. Aunt Petunia screamed and dropped it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 An awful voice filled the kitchen, echoing in the confined space, is\-suing from the burning letter on the table.\lang3081\par
\par
