\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\par
\lang1033 Aunt Petunia looked as though she might faint. She sank into the chair beside Dudley, her face in her hands. The remains of the enve\-lope smoldered into ash in the silence.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What is this?\rdblquote  Uncle Vernon said hoarsely. \ldblquote What \emdash  I don\rquote t \emdash  Petunia?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Aunt Petunia said nothing. Dudley was staring stupidly at his mother, his mouth hanging open. The silence spiraled horribly. Harry was watching his aunt, utterly bewildered, his head throbbing fit to burst.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Petunia, dear?\rdblquote  said Uncle Vernon timidly. \ldblquote P-Petunia?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She raised her head. She was still trembling. She swallowed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The boy \emdash  the boy will have to stay, Vernon,\rdblquote  she said weakly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote W-what?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He stays,\rdblquote  she said. She was not looking at Harry. She got to her feet again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He \'85 but Petunia \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote If we throw him out, the neighbors will talk,\rdblquote  she said. She was re\-gaining her usual brisk, snappish manner rapidly, though she was still very pale. \ldblquote They\rquote ll ask awkward questions, they\rquote ll want to know where he\rquote s gone. We\rquote ll have to keep him.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Uncle Vernon was deflating like an old tire.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But Petunia, dear \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Aunt Petunia ignored him. She turned to Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote re to stay in your room,\rdblquote  she said. \ldblquote You\rquote re not to leave the house. Now get to bed.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry didn\rquote t move.\lang3081\par
