\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\lang1033 But Hedwig didn\rquote t return next morning. Harry spent the day in his bedroom, leaving it only to go to the bathroom. Three times that day Aunt Petunia shoved food into his room through the cat flap Uncle Vernon had installed three summers ago. Every time Harry heard her approaching he tried to question her about the Howler, but he might as well have interrogated the doorknob for all the answers he got. Otherwise the Dursleys kept well clear of his bedroom. Harry couldn\rquote t see the point of forcing his company on them; another row would achieve nothing except perhaps making him so angry he\rquote d perform more illegal magic.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 So it went on for three whole days. Harry was filled alternately with restless energy that made him unable to settle to anything, during which he paced his bedroom again, furious at the whole lot of them for leaving him to stew in this mess, and with a lethargy so complete that he could lie on his bed for an hour at a time, staring dazedly into space, aching with dread at the thought of the Ministry hearing.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 What if they ruled against him? What if he \i was\i0  expelled and his wand was snapped in half? What would he do, where would he go? He could not return to living full-time with the Dursleys, not now that he knew the other world, the one to which he really belonged. \'85 Was it possible that he might be able to move into Sirius\rquote s house, as Sirius had suggested a year ago, before he had been forced to flee from the Ministry himself? Would he be allowed to live there alone, given that he was still underage? Or would the matter of where he went next be decided for him; had his breach of the International Statute of Secrecy been severe enough to land him in a cell in Azka\-ban? Whenever this thought occurred, Harry invariably slid off his bed and began pacing again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 On the fourth night after Hedwig\rquote s departure Harry was lying in one of his apathetic phases, staring at the ceiling, his exhausted mind\lang3081  \lang1033 quite blank, when his uncle entered his bedroom. Harry looked slowly around at him. Uncle Vernon was wearing his best suit and an expression of enormous smugness.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We\rquote re going out,\rdblquote  he said.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sorry?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We \emdash  that is to say, your aunt, Dudley, and I \emdash  are going out.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Fine,\rdblquote  said Harry dully, looking back at the ceiling.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You are not to leave your bedroom while we are away.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Okay.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You are not to touch the television, the stereo, or any of our possessions.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Right.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You are not to steal food from the fridge.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Okay.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I am going to lock your door.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You do that.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Uncle Vernon glared at Harry, clearly suspicious of this lack of ar\-gument, then stomped out of the room and closed the door behind him. Harry heard the key turn in the lock and Uncle Vernon\rquote s foot\-steps walking heavily down the stairs. A few minutes later he heard the slamming of car doors, the rumble of an engine, and the unmistakable sound of the car sweeping out of the drive.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry had no particular feeling about the Dursleys leaving. It made no difference to him whether they were in the house or not. He could not even summon the energy to get up and turn on his bedroom light. The room grew steadily darker around him as he lay listening to the night sounds through the window he kept open all the time, waiting for the blessed moment when Hedwig returned.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The empty house creaked around him. The pipes gurgled. Harry lay there in a kind of stupor, thinking of nothing, suspended in misery.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And then, quite distinctly, he heard a crash in the kitchen below.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He sat bolt upright, listening intently. The Dursleys couldn\rquote t be back, it was much too soon, and in any case he hadn\rquote t heard their car.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was silence for a few seconds, and then he heard voices.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\i Burglars,\i0  he thought, sliding off the bed onto his feet \emdash  but a split second later it occurred to him that burglars would keep their voices down, and whoever was moving around in the kitchen was certainly not troubling to do so.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He snatched up his wand from his bedside table and stood facing his bedroom door, listening with all his might. Next moment he jumped as the lock gave a loud click and his door swung open.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry stood motionless, staring through the open door at the dark upstairs landing, straining his ears for further sounds, but none came. He hesitated for a moment and then moved swiftly and silently out of his room to the head of the stairs.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 His heart shot upward into his throat. There were people standing in the shadowy hall below, silhouetted against the streetlight glowing through the glass door; eight or nine of them, all, as far as he could see, looking up at him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Lower your wand, boy, before you take someone\rquote s eye out,\rdblquote  said a low, growling voice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry\rquote s heart was thumping uncontrollably. He knew that voice, but he did not lower his wand.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Professor Moody?\rdblquote  he said uncertainly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t know so much about \lquote Professor,\rquote  \rdblquote  growled the voice, \ldblquote never got round to much teaching, did I? Get down here, we want to see you properly.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry lowered his wand slightly but did not relax his grip on it, nor did he move. He had very good reason to be suspicious. He had re\-cently spent nine months in what he had thought was Mad-Eye Moody\rquote s company only to find out that it wasn\rquote t Moody at all, but an impostor; an impostor, moreover, who had tried to kill Harry before\lang3081  \lang1033 being unmasked. But before he could make a decision about what to do next, a second, slightly hoarse voice floated upstairs.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s all right, Harry. We\rquote ve come to take you away.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry\rquote s heart leapt. He knew that voice too, though he hadn\rquote t heard it for more than a year.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote P-Professor Lupin?\rdblquote  he said disbelievingly. \ldblquote Is that you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Why are we all standing in the dark?\rdblquote  said a third voice, this one completely unfamiliar, a woman\rquote s. \ldblquote\i Lumos.\i0\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A wand tip flared, illuminating the hall with magical light. Harry blinked. The people below were crowded around the foot of the stairs, gazing intently up at him, some craning their heads for a better look.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Remus Lupin stood nearest to him. Though still quite young, Lupin looked tired and rather ill; he had more gray hair than when Harry had said good-bye to him, and his robes were more patched and shabbier than ever. Nevertheless, he was smiling broadly at Harry, who tried to smile back through his shock.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oooh, he looks just like I thought he would,\rdblquote  said the witch who was holding her lit wand aloft. She looked the youngest there; she had a pale heart-shaped face, dark twinkling eyes, and short spiky hair that was a violent shade of violet. \ldblquote Wotcher, Harry!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, I see what you mean, Remus,\rdblquote  said a bald black wizard standing farthest back; he had a deep, slow voice and wore a single gold hoop in his ear. \ldblquote He looks exactly like James.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Except the eyes,\rdblquote  said a wheezy-voiced, silver-haired wizard at the back. \ldblquote Lily\rquote s eyes.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mad-Eye Moody, who had long grizzled gray hair and a large chunk missing from his nose, was squinting suspiciously at Harry through his mismatched eyes. One of the eyes was small, dark, and beady, the other large, round, and electric blue \emdash  the magical eye that could see through walls, doors, and the back of Moody\rquote s own head.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Are you quite sure it\rquote s him, Lupin?\rdblquote  he growled. \ldblquote It\rquote d be a nice\lang3081  \lang1033 lookout if we bring back some Death Eater impersonating him. We ought to ask him something only the real Potter would know. Unless anyone brought any Veritaserum?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry, what form does your Patronus take?\rdblquote  said Lupin.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote A stag,\rdblquote  said Harry nervously.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That\rquote s him, Mad-Eye,\rdblquote  said Lupin.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry descended the stairs, very conscious of everybody still staring at him, stowing his wand into the back pocket of his jeans as he came.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Don\rquote t put your wand there, boy!\rdblquote  roared Moody. \ldblquote What if it ig\-nited? Better wizards than you have lost buttocks, you know!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Who d\rquote you know who\rquote s lost a buttock?\rdblquote  the violet-haired woman asked Mad-Eye interestedly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Never you mind, you just keep your wand out of your back pocket!\rdblquote  growled Mad-Eye. \ldblquote Elementary wand safety, nobody bothers about it anymore. \'85\rdblquote  He stumped off toward the kitchen. \ldblquote And I saw that,\rdblquote  he added irritably, as the woman rolled her eyes at the ceiling.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Lupin held out his hand and shook Harry\rquote s.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How are you?\rdblquote  he asked, looking at Harry closely.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote F-fine \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry could hardly believe this was real. Four weeks with nothing, not the tiniest hint of a plan to remove him from Privet Drive, and suddenly a whole bunch of wizards was standing matter-of-factly in the house as though this were a long-standing arrangement. He glanced at the people surrounding Lupin; they were still gazing avidly at him. He felt very conscious of the fact that he had not combed his hair for four days.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m \emdash  you\rquote re really lucky the Dursleys are out\lang3081  \lang1033\'85\rdblquote  he mumbled.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Lucky, ha!\rdblquote  said the violet-haired woman. \ldblquote It was me that lured them out of the way. Sent a letter by Muggle post telling them they\rquote d been short-listed for the All-England Best-Kept Suburban Lawn Competition. They\rquote re heading off to the prize-giving right now. \'85 Or they think they are.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry had a fleeting vision of Uncle Vernon\rquote s face when he realized there was no All-England Best-Kept Suburban Lawn Competition.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We are leaving, aren\rquote t we?\rdblquote  he asked. \ldblquote Soon?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Almost at once,\rdblquote  said Lupin, \ldblquote we\rquote re just waiting for the all-clear.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Where are we going? The Burrow?\rdblquote  Harry asked hopefully.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Not the Burrow, no,\rdblquote  said Lupin, motioning Harry toward the kitchen; the little knot of wizards followed, all still eyeing Harry curi\-ously. \ldblquote Too risky. We\rquote ve set up headquarters somewhere undetectable. It\rquote s taken a while. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mad-Eye Moody was now sitting at the kitchen table swigging from a hip flask, his magical eye spinning in all directions, taking in the Dursleys\rquote  many labor-saving appliances.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote This is Alastor Moody, Harry,\rdblquote  Lupin continued, pointing toward Moody.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, I know,\rdblquote  said Harry uncomfortably; it felt odd to be intro\-duced to somebody he\rquote d thought he\rquote d known for a year.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And this is Nymphadora \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Don\rquote t\i0  call me Nymphadora, Remus,\rdblquote  said the young witch with a shudder. \ldblquote It\rquote s\lang3081  \lang1033 Tonks.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  Nymphadora Tonks, who prefers to be known by her surname only,\rdblquote  finished Lupin.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So would you if your fool of a mother had called you \lquote Nympha\-dora,\rquote  \rdblquote  muttered Tonks.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And this is Kingsley Shacklebolt\rdblquote  \emdash  he indicated the tall black wizard, who bowed \emdash  \ldblquote Elphias Doge\rdblquote  \emdash  the wheezy-voiced wizard nodded \emdash  \ldblquote Dedalus Diggle \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We\rquote ve met before,\rdblquote  squeaked the excitable Diggle, dropping his top hat.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  Emmeline Vance\rdblquote  \emdash  a stately looking witch in an emerald-green shawl inclined her head \emdash  \ldblquote Sturgis Podmore\rdblquote  \emdash  a square-jawed wizard with thick, straw-colored hair winked \emdash  \ldblquote and Hestia Jones.\rdblquote  A pink-cheeked, black-haired witch waved from next to the toaster.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry inclined his head awkwardly at each of them as they were in\-troduced. He wished they would look at something other than him; it was as though he had suddenly been ushered onstage. He also won\-dered why so many of them were there.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote A surprising number of people volunteered to come and get you,\rdblquote  said Lupin, as though he had read Harry\rquote s mind; the corners of his mouth twitched slightly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, well, the more the better,\rdblquote  said Moody darkly. \ldblquote We\rquote re your guard, Potter.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We\rquote re just waiting for the signal to tell us it\rquote s safe to set off,\rdblquote  said Lupin, glancing out of the kitchen window. \ldblquote We\rquote ve got about fifteen minutes.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Very \i clean,\i0  aren\rquote t they, these Muggles?\rdblquote  said the witch called Tonks, who was looking around the kitchen with great interest. \ldblquote My dad\rquote s Muggle-born and he\rquote s a right old slob. I suppose it varies, just like with wizards?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Er \emdash  yeah,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote Look\rdblquote  \emdash  he turned back to Lupin \emdash  \ldblquote what\rquote s going on, I haven\rquote t heard anything from anyone, what\rquote s Vol \emdash  ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Several of the witches and wizards made odd hissing noises; Dedalus Diggle dropped his hat again, and Moody growled, \ldblquote\i Shut up\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What?\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We\rquote re not discussing anything here, it\rquote s too risky,\rdblquote  said Moody, turning his normal eye on Harry; his magical eye remained pointing up at the ceiling. \ldblquote\i Damn it,\i0\rdblquote  he added angrily, putting a hand up to the magical eye, \ldblquote it keeps sticking \emdash  ever since that scum wore it \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And with a nasty squelching sound much like a plunger being pulled from a sink, he popped out his eye.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Mad-Eye, you do know that\rquote s disgusting, don\rquote t you?\rdblquote  said Tonks conversationally.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Get me a glass of water, would you, Harry?\rdblquote  asked Moody.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry crossed to the dishwasher, took out a clean glass, and filled it\lang3081  \lang1033 with water at the sink, still watched eagerly by the band of wizards. Their relentless staring was starting to annoy him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Cheers,\rdblquote  said Moody, when Harry handed him the glass. He dropped the magical eyeball into the water and prodded it up and down; the eye whizzed around, staring at them all in turn. \ldblquote I want three-hundred-and-sixty degrees visibility on the return journey.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How\rquote re we getting \emdash  wherever we\rquote re going?\rdblquote  Harry asked.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Brooms,\rdblquote  said Lupin. \ldblquote Only way. You\rquote re too young to Apparate, they\rquote ll be watching the Floo Network, and it\rquote s more than our life\rquote s worth to set up an unauthorized Portkey.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Remus says you\rquote re a good flier,\rdblquote  said Kingsley Shacklebolt in his deep voice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He\rquote s excellent,\rdblquote  said Lupin, who was checking his watch. \ldblquote Any\-way, you\rquote d better go and get packed, Harry, we want to be ready to go when the signal comes.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote ll come and help you,\rdblquote  said Tonks brightly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She followed Harry back into the hall and up the stairs, looking around with much curiosity and interest.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Funny place,\rdblquote  she said, \ldblquote it\rquote s a bit \i too\i0  clean, d\rquote you know what I mean? Bit unnatural. Oh, this is better,\rdblquote  she added, as they entered Harry\rquote s bedroom and he turned on the light.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 His room was certainly much messier than the rest of the house. Confined to it for four days in a very bad mood, Harry had not both\-ered tidying up after himself. Most of the books he owned were strewn over the floor where he\rquote d tried to distract himself with each in turn and thrown it aside. Hedwig\rquote s cage needed cleaning out and was starting to smell, and his trunk lay open, revealing a jumbled mixture of Muggle clothes and wizard\rquote s robes that had spilled onto the floor around it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry started picking up books and throwing them hastily into his trunk. Tonks paused at his open wardrobe to look critically at her re\-flection in the mirror on the inside of the door.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You know, I don\rquote t think purple\rquote s really my color,\rdblquote  she said pen\-sively, tugging at a lock of spiky hair. \ldblquote D\rquote you think it makes me look a bit peaky?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Er \emdash\rdblquote  said Harry, looking up at her over the top of \i Quidditch Teams of Britain and Ireland\i0 .\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, it does,\rdblquote  said Tonks decisively. She screwed up her eyes in a strained expression as though she were struggling to remember some\-thing. A second later, her hair had turned bubble-gum pink.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How did you do that?\rdblquote  said Harry, gaping at her as she opened her eyes again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m a Metamorphmagus,\rdblquote  she said, looking back at her reflection and turning her head so that she could see her hair from all directions. \ldblquote It means I can change my appearance at will,\rdblquote  she added, spotting Harry\rquote s puzzled expression in the mirror behind her. \ldblquote I was born one. I got top marks in Concealment and Disguise during Auror training without any study at all, it was great.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote re an Auror?\rdblquote  said Harry, impressed. Being a Dark wizard catcher was the only career he\rquote d ever considered after Hogwarts.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah,\rdblquote  said Tonks, looking proud. \ldblquote Kingsley is as well; he\rquote s a bit higher up than I am, though. I only qualified a year ago. Nearly failed on Stealth and Tracking, I\rquote m dead clumsy, did you hear me break that plate when we arrived downstairs?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Can you learn how to be a Metamorphmagus?\rdblquote  Harry asked her, straightening up, completely forgetting about packing.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Tonks chuckled.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Bet you wouldn\rquote t mind hiding that scar sometimes, eh?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Her eyes found the lightning-shaped scar on Harry\rquote s forehead.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, I wouldn\rquote t mind,\rdblquote  Harry mumbled, turning away. He did not like people staring at his scar.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, you\rquote ll have to learn the hard way, I\rquote m afraid,\rdblquote  said Tonks. \ldblquote Metamorphmagi are really rare, they\rquote re born, not made. Most wiz\-ards need to use a wand or potions to change their appearance. \'85 But we\rquote ve got to get going, Harry, we\rquote re supposed to be packing,\rdblquote  she added guiltily, looking around at all the mess on the floor.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh \emdash  yeah,\rdblquote  said Harry, grabbing up a few more books.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Don\rquote t be stupid, it\rquote ll be much quicker if I \emdash\lang3081  \lang1033\i pack\i0 !\rdblquote  cried Tonks, waving her wand in a long, sweeping movement over the floor.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Books, clothes, telescope, and scales all soared into the air and flew pell-mell into the trunk.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s not very neat,\rdblquote  said Tonks, walking over to the trunk and look\-ing down at the jumble inside. \ldblquote My mum\rquote s got this knack of getting stuff to fit itself in neatly \emdash  she even gets the socks to fold them\-selves \emdash  but I\rquote ve never mastered how she does it \emdash  it\rquote s a kind of flick\lang3081  \lang1033\emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She flicked her wand hopefully; one of Harry\rquote s socks gave a feeble sort of wiggle and flopped back on top of the mess within.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ah, well,\rdblquote  said Tonks, slamming the trunk\rquote s lid shut, \ldblquote at least it\rquote s all in. That could do with a bit of cleaning, too \emdash  \i Scourgify\i0  \emdash\rdblquote  She pointed her wand at Hedwig\rquote s cage; a few feathers and droppings van\-ished. \ldblquote Well, that\rquote s a \i bit\i0  better \emdash  I\rquote ve never quite got the hang of these sort of householdy spells. Right \emdash  got everything? Cauldron? Broom? Wow! A \i Firebolt\i0 ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Her eyes widened as they fell on the broomstick in Harry\rquote s right hand. It was his pride and joy, a gift from Sirius, an international stan\-dard broomstick.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And I\rquote m still riding a Comet Two Sixty,\rdblquote  said Tonks enviously. \ldblquote Ah well\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 wand still in your jeans? Both buttocks still on? Okay, let\rquote s go. \i Locomotor Trunk.\i0\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry\rquote s trunk rose a few inches into the air. Holding her wand like a conductor\rquote s baton, Tonks made it hover across the room and out of the door ahead of them, Hedwig\rquote s cage in her left hand. Harry followed her down the stairs carrying his broomstick.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Back in the kitchen, Moody had replaced his eye, which was spinning so fast after its cleaning it made Harry feel sick. Kingsley\lang3081  \lang1033 Shacklebolt and Sturgis Podmore were examining the microwave and Hestia Jones was laughing at a potato peeler she had come across while rummaging in the drawers. Lupin was sealing a letter addressed to the Dursleys.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Excellent,\rdblquote  said Lupin, looking up as Tonks and Harry entered. \ldblquote We\rquote ve got about a minute, I think. We should probably get out into the garden so we\rquote re ready. Harry, I\rquote ve left a letter telling your aunt and uncle not to worry \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote They won\rquote t,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That you\rquote re safe \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That\rquote ll just depress them.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  and you\rquote ll see them next summer.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Do I have to?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Lupin smiled but made no answer.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Come here, boy,\rdblquote  said Moody gruffly, beckoning Harry toward him with his wand. \ldblquote I need to Disillusion you.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You need to what?\rdblquote  said Harry nervously.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Disillusionment Charm,\rdblquote  said Moody, raising his wand. \ldblquote Lupin says you\rquote ve got an Invisibility Cloak, but it won\rquote t stay on while we\rquote re flying; this\rquote ll disguise you better. Here you go \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He rapped Harry hard on the top of the head and Harry felt a cu\-rious sensation as though Moody had just smashed an egg there; cold trickles seemed to be running down his body from the point the wand had struck.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Nice one, Mad-Eye,\rdblquote  said Tonks appreciatively, staring at Harry\rquote s midriff.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry looked down at his body, or rather, what had been his body, for it didn\rquote t look anything like his anymore. It was not invisible; it had simply taken on the exact color and texture of the kitchen unit behind him. He seemed to have become a human chameleon.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Come on,\rdblquote  said Moody, unlocking the back door with his wand.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They all stepped outside onto Uncle Vernon\rquote s beautifully kept lawn.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Clear night,\rdblquote  grunted Moody, his magical eye scanning the heav\-ens. \ldblquote Could\rquote ve done with a bit more cloud cover. Right, you,\rdblquote  he barked at Harry, \ldblquote we\rquote re going to be flying in close formation. Tonks\rquote ll be right in front of you, keep close on her tail. Lupin\rquote ll be covering you from below. I\rquote m going to be behind you. The rest\rquote ll be circling us. We don\rquote t break ranks for anything, got me? If one of us is killed \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Is that likely?\rdblquote  Harry asked apprehensively, but Moody ignored him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  the others keep flying, don\rquote t stop, don\rquote t break ranks. If they take out all of us and you survive, Harry, the rear guard are standing by to take over; keep flying east and they\rquote ll join you.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Stop being so cheerful, Mad-Eye, he\rquote ll think we\rquote re not taking this seriously,\rdblquote  said Tonks, as she strapped Harry\rquote s trunk and Hedwig\rquote s cage into a harness hanging from her broom.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m just telling the boy the plan,\rdblquote  growled Moody. \ldblquote Our job\rquote s to deliver him safely to headquarters and if we die in the attempt \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No one\rquote s going to die,\rdblquote  said Kingsley Shacklebolt in his deep, calming voice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Mount your brooms, that\rquote s the first signal!\rdblquote  said Lupin sharply, pointing into the sky.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Far, far above them, a shower of bright red sparks had flared among the stars. Harry recognized them at once as wand sparks. He swung his right leg over his Firebolt, gripped its handle tightly, and felt it vibrating very slightly, as though it was as keen as he was to be up in the air once more.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Second signal, let\rquote s go!\rdblquote  said Lupin loudly, as more sparks, green this time, exploded high above them.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry kicked off hard from the ground. The cool night air rushed through his hair as the neat square gardens of Privet Drive fell away, shrinking rapidly into a patchwork of dark greens and blacks, and every thought of the Ministry hearing was swept from his mind as though the rush of air had blown it out of his head. He felt as though\lang3081  \lang1033 his heart was going to explode with pleasure; he was flying again, fly\-ing away from Privet Drive as he\rquote d been fantasizing about all summer, he was going home. \'85 For a few glorious moments, all his problems seemed to recede into nothing, insignificant in the vast, starry sky.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hard left, hard left, there\rquote s a Muggle looking up!\rdblquote  shouted Moody from behind him. Tonks swerved and Harry followed her, watching his trunk swinging wildly beneath her broom. \ldblquote We need more height. \'85 Give it another quarter of a mile!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry\rquote s eyes watered in the chill as they soared upward; he could see nothing below now but tiny pinpricks of light that were car headlights and streetlamps. Two of those tiny lights might belong to Uncle Ver\-non\rquote s car. \'85 The Dursleys would be heading back to their empty house right now, full of rage about the nonexistent lawn competition \'85 and Harry laughed aloud at the thought, though his voice was drowned by the flapping of the others\rquote  robes, the creaking of the har\-ness holding his trunk and the cage, the \i whoosh\i0  of the wind in their ears as they sped through the air. He had not felt this alive in a month, or this happy. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Bearing south!\rdblquote  shouted Mad-Eye. \ldblquote Town ahead!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They soared right, so that they did not pass directly over the glit\-tering spiderweb of lights below.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Bear southeast and keep climbing, there\rquote s some low cloud ahead we can lose ourselves in!\rdblquote  called Moody.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We\rquote re not going through clouds!\rdblquote  shouted Tonks angrily. \ldblquote We\rquote ll get soaked, Mad-Eye!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry was relieved to hear her say this; his hands were growing numb on the Firebolt\rquote s handle. He wished he had thought to put on a coat; he was starting to shiver.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They altered their course every now and then according to Mad-Eye\rquote s instructions. Harry\rquote s eyes were screwed up against the rush of icy wind that was starting to make his ears ache. He could remember be\-ing this cold on a broom only once before, during the Quidditch\lang3081  \lang1033 match against Hufflepuff in his third year, which had taken place in a storm. The guard around him was circling continuously like giant birds of prey. Harry lost track of time. He wondered how long they had been flying; it felt like an hour at least.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Turning southwest!\rdblquote  yelled Moody. \ldblquote We want to avoid the motorway!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry was now so chilled that he thought longingly for a moment of the snug, dry interiors of the cars streaming along below, then, even more longingly, of traveling by Floo powder; it might be uncomfort\-able to spin around in fireplaces but it was at least warm in the flames. \'85 Kingsley Shacklebolt swooped around him, bald pate and earring gleaming slightly in the moonlight. \'85 Now Emmeline Vance was on his right, her wand out, her head turning left and right\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 then she too swooped over him, to be replaced by Sturgis Podmore. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We ought to double back for a bit, just to make sure we\rquote re not be\-ing followed!\rdblquote  Moody shouted.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote ARE YOU MAD, MAD-EYE?\rdblquote  Tonks screamed from the front. \ldblquote We\rquote re all frozen to our brooms! If we keep going off course we\rquote re not going to get there until next week! We\rquote re nearly there now!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Time to start the descent!\rdblquote  came Lupin\rquote s voice. \ldblquote Follow Tonks, Harry!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry followed Tonks into a dive. They were heading for the largest collection of lights he had yet seen, a huge, sprawling, crisscrossing mass, glittering in lines and grids, interspersed with patches of deep\-est black. Lower and lower they flew, until Harry could see individual headlights and streetlamps, chimneys, and television aerials. He wanted to reach the ground very much, though he felt sure that some\-one would have to unfreeze him from his broom.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Here we go!\rdblquote  called Tonks, and a few seconds later she had landed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry touched down right behind her and dismounted on a patch of unkempt grass in the middle of a small square. Tonks was already unbuckling Harry\rquote s trunk. Shivering, Harry looked around. The grimy\lang3081  \lang1033 fronts of the surrounding houses were not welcoming; some of them had broken windows, glimmering dully in the light from the street-lamps, paint was peeling from many of the doors, and heaps of rubbish lay outside several sets of front steps.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Where are we?\rdblquote  Harry asked, but Lupin said quietly, \ldblquote In a minute.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Moody was rummaging in his cloak, his gnarled hands clumsy with cold.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Got it,\rdblquote  he muttered, raising what looked like a silver cigarette lighter into the air and clicking it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The nearest streetlamp went out with a pop. He clicked the un-lighter again; the next lamp went out. He kept clicking until every lamp in the square was extinguished and the only light in the square came from curtained windows and the sickle moon overhead.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Borrowed it from Dumbledore,\rdblquote  growled Moody, pocketing the Put-Outer. \ldblquote That\rquote ll take care of any Muggles looking out of the win\-dow, see? Now, come on, quick.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He took Harry by the arm and led him from the patch of grass, across the road, and onto the pavement. Lupin and Tonks followed, carrying Harry\rquote s trunk between them, the rest of the guard, all with their wands out, flanking them.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The muffled pounding of a stereo was coming from an upper win\-dow in the nearest house. A pungent smell of rotting rubbish came from the pile of bulging bin-bags just inside the broken gate.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Here,\rdblquote  Moody muttered, thrusting a piece of parchment toward Harry\rquote s Disillusioned hand and holding his lit wand close to it, so as to illuminate the writing. \ldblquote Read quickly and memorize.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry looked down at the piece of paper. The narrow handwriting was vaguely familiar. It said:\par
\par
\i The headquarters of the Order of the Phoenix may be found\lang3081  \lang1033 at number twelve, Grimmauld Place, London.\par
