\lang1033 Harry, who had expected a better welcome, noted how hard and bitter Sirius\rquote s voice sounded. He followed his godfather to the bottom of the stairs and through a door leading into the basement kitchen.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It was scarcely less gloomy than the hall above, a cavernous room with rough stone walls. Most of the light was coming from a large fire at the far end of the room. A haze of pipe smoke hung in the air like battle fumes, through which loomed the menacing shapes of heavy\lang3081  \lang1033 iron pots and pans hanging from the dark ceiling. Many chairs had been crammed into the room for the meeting and a long wooden table stood in the middle of the room, littered with rolls of parchment, gob\-lets, empty wine bottles, and a heap of what appeared to be rags. Mr. Weasley and his eldest son, Bill, were talking quietly with their heads together at the end of the table.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mrs. Weasley cleared her throat. Her husband, a thin, balding, red-haired man, who wore horn-rimmed glasses, looked around and jumped to his feet.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry!\rdblquote  Mr. Weasley said, hurrying forward to greet him and shaking his hand vigorously. \ldblquote Good to see you!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Over his shoulder Harry saw Bill, who still wore his long hair in a ponytail, hastily rolling up the lengths of parchment left on the table.\lang3081\par
