\lang1033\ldblquote Of course he doesn\rquote t,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley. \ldblquote He\rquote s never wanted the Minister\rquote s job, even though a lot of people wanted him to take it when Millicent Bagnold retired. Fudge came to power instead, but he\rquote s never quite forgotten how much popular support Dumbledore had, even though Dumbledore never applied for the job.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Deep down, Fudge knows Dumbledore\rquote s much cleverer than he is, a much more powerful wizard, and in the early days of his Ministry he was forever asking Dumbledore for help and advice,\rdblquote  said Lupin. \ldblquote But it seems that he\rquote s become fond of power now, and much more confi\-dent. He loves being Minister of Magic, and he\rquote s managed to convince himself that he\rquote s the clever one and Dumbledore\rquote s simply stirring up trouble for the sake of it.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How can he think that?\rdblquote  said Harry angrily. \ldblquote How can he think Dumbledore would just make it all up \emdash  that \i I\rquote d\i0  make it all up?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Because accepting that Voldemort\rquote s back would mean trouble like the Ministry hasn\rquote t had to cope with for nearly fourteen years,\rdblquote  said Sirius bitterly. \ldblquote Fudge just can\rquote t bring himself to face it. It\rquote s so much more comfortable to convince himself Dumbledore\rquote s lying to destabi\-lize him.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You see the problem,\rdblquote  said Lupin. \ldblquote While the Ministry insists there is nothing to fear from Voldemort, it\rquote s hard to convince people he\rquote s back, especially as they really don\rquote t want to believe it in the first place. What\rquote s more, the Ministry\rquote s leaning heavily on the \i Daily Prophet\i0  not to report any of what they\rquote re calling Dumbledore\rquote s rumor\-mongering, so most of the Wizarding community are completely un\-aware anything\rquote s happened, and that makes them easy targets for the Death Eaters if they\rquote re using the Imperius Curse.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But you\rquote re telling people, aren\rquote t you?\rdblquote  said Harry, looking around at Mr. Weasley, Sirius, Bill, Mundungus, Lupin, and Tonks. \ldblquote You\rquote re letting people know he\rquote s back?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They all smiled humorlessly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, as everyone thinks I\rquote m a mad mass murderer and the Min\-istry\rquote s put a ten-thousand-Galleon price on my head, I can hardly stroll up the street and start handing out leaflets, can I?\rdblquote  said Sirius restlessly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And I\rquote m not a very popular dinner guest with most of the commu\-nity,\rdblquote  said Lupin. \ldblquote It\rquote s an occupational hazard of being a werewolf.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Tonks and Arthur would lose their jobs at the Ministry if they started shooting their mouths off,\rdblquote  said Sirius, \ldblquote and it\rquote s very important for us to have spies inside the Ministry, because you can bet Volde\-mort will have them.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We\rquote ve managed to convince a couple of people, though,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley. \ldblquote Tonks here, for one \emdash  she\rquote s too young to have been in the Order of the Phoenix last time, and having Aurors on our side is a huge advantage \emdash  Kingsley Shacklebolt\rquote s been a real asset too. He\rquote s in charge of the hunt for Sirius, so he\rquote s been feeding the Ministry infor\-mation that Sirius is in Tibet.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But if none of you\rquote s putting the news out that Voldemort\rquote s back \emdash\rdblquote  Harry began.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Who said none of us was putting the news out?\rdblquote  said Sirius. \ldblquote Why d\rquote you think Dumbledore\rquote s in such trouble?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What d\rquote you mean?\rdblquote  Harry asked.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote They\rquote re trying to discredit him,\rdblquote  said Lupin. \ldblquote Didn\rquote t you see the \i Daily Prophet\i0  last week? They reported that he\rquote d been voted out of the Chairmanship of the International Confederation of Wizards because he\rquote s getting old and losing his grip, but it\rquote s not true, he was voted out by Ministry wizards after he made a speech announcing Voldemort\rquote s return. They\rquote ve demoted him from Chief Warlock on the Wizen\-gamot \emdash  that\rquote s the Wizard High Court \emdash  and they\rquote re talking about taking away his Order of Merlin, First Class, too.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But Dumbledore says he doesn\rquote t care what they do as long as they don\rquote t take him off the Chocolate Frog cards,\rdblquote  said Bill, grinning.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s no laughing matter,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley shortly. \ldblquote If he carries on defying the Ministry like this, he could end up in Azkaban and the last thing we want is Dumbledore locked up. While You-Know-Who knows Dumbledore\rquote s out there and wise to what he\rquote s up to, he\rquote s going to go cautiously for a while. If Dumbledore\rquote s out of the way \emdash  well, You-Know-Who will have a clear field.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But if Voldemort\rquote s trying to recruit more Death Eaters, it\rquote s bound to get out that he\rquote s come back, isn\rquote t it?\rdblquote  asked Harry desperately.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Voldemort doesn\rquote t march up to people\rquote s houses and bang on their front doors, Harry,\rdblquote  said Sirius. \ldblquote He tricks, jinxes, and blackmails them. He\rquote s well-practiced at operating in secrecy. In any case, gather\-ing followers is only one thing he\rquote s interested in, he\rquote s got other plans too, plans he can put into operation very quietly indeed, and he\rquote s con\-centrating on them at the moment.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What\rquote s he after apart from followers?\rdblquote  Harry asked swiftly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He thought he saw Sirius and Lupin exchange the most fleeting of looks before Sirius said, \ldblquote Stuff he can only get by stealth.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 When Harry continued to look puzzled, Sirius said, \ldblquote Like a weapon. Something he didn\rquote t have last time.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote When he was powerful before?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Like what kind of weapon?\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote Something worse than the \i Avada Kedavra\i0  \emdash  ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That\rquote s enough.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mrs. Weasley spoke from the shadows beside the door. Harry had not noticed her return from taking Ginny upstairs. Her arms were crossed and she looked furious.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I want you in bed, now. All of you,\rdblquote  she added, looking around at Fred, George, Ron, and Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You can\rquote t boss us \emdash\rdblquote  Fred began.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Watch me,\rdblquote  snarled Mrs. Weasley. She was trembling slightly as she looked at Sirius. \ldblquote You\rquote ve given Harry plenty of information. Any more and you might just as well induct him into the Order straightaway.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Why not?\rdblquote  said Harry quickly. \ldblquote I\rquote ll join, I want to join, I want to fight \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It was not Mrs. Weasley who spoke this time, but Lupin.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The Order is comprised only of overage wizards,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote Wiz\-ards who have left school,\rdblquote  he added, as Fred and George opened their mouths. \ldblquote There are dangers involved of which you can have no idea, any of you \'85 I think Molly\rquote s right, Sirius. We\rquote ve said enough.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Sirius half-shrugged but did not argue. Mrs. Weasley beckoned im\-periously to her sons and Hermione. One by one they stood up and Harry, recognizing defeat, followed suit.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\par
