Mrs. Weasley followed them upstairs looking grim.\par
\ldblquote I want you all to go straight to bed, no talking,\rdblquote  she said as they reached the first landing. \ldblquote We\rquote ve got a busy day tomorrow. I expect Ginny\rquote s asleep,\rdblquote  she added to Hermione, \ldblquote so try not to wake her up.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Asleep, yeah, right,\rdblquote  said Fred in an undertone, after Hermione bade them good night and they were climbing to the next floor. \ldblquote If Ginny\rquote s not lying awake waiting for Hermione to tell her everything they said downstairs, then I\rquote m a flobberworm. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote All right, Ron, Harry,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley on the second landing, pointing them into their bedroom. \ldblquote Off to bed with you.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \rquote Night,\rdblquote  Harry and Ron said to the twins.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sleep tight,\rdblquote  said Fred, winking.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mrs. Weasley closed the door behind Harry with a sharp snap. The bedroom looked, if anything, even danker and gloomier than it had on first sight. The blank picture on the wall was now breathing very slowly and deeply, as though its invisible occupant was asleep. Harry put on his pajamas, took off his glasses, and climbed into his chilly\lang3081  \lang1033 bed while Ron threw Owl Treats up on top of the wardrobe to pacify Hedwig and Pigwidgeon, who were clattering around and rustling their wings restlessly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We can\rquote t let them out to hunt every night,\rdblquote  Ron explained as he pulled on his maroon pajamas. \ldblquote Dumbledore doesn\rquote t want too many owls swooping around the square, thinks it\rquote ll look suspicious. Oh yeah \'85 I forgot. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He crossed to the door and bolted it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What\rquote re you doing that for?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Kreacher,\rdblquote  said Ron as he turned off the light. \ldblquote First night I was here he came wandering in at three in the morning. Trust me, you don\rquote t want to wake up and find him prowling around your room. Anyway \'85\rdblquote  He got into his bed, settled down under the covers, then turned to look at Harry in the darkness. Harry could see his outline by the moonlight filtering in through the grimy window. \ldblquote\i What d\rquote you reckon\i0 ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry didn\rquote t need to ask what Ron meant.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, they didn\rquote t tell us much we couldn\rquote t have guessed, did they?\rdblquote  he said, thinking of all that had been said downstairs. \ldblquote I mean, all they\rquote ve really said is that the Order\rquote s trying to stop people joining Vol \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a sharp intake of breath from Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  \i demort,\i0\rdblquote\lang3081  \lang1033 said Harry firmly. \ldblquote When are you going to start using his name? Sirius and Lupin do.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron ignored this last comment. \ldblquote Yeah, you\rquote re right,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote We already knew nearly everything they told us, from using the Extend\-able Ears. The only new bit was \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\i Crack.\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\ldblquote OUCH!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Keep your voice down, Ron, or Mum\rquote ll be back up here.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You two just Apparated on my knees!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, well, it\rquote s harder in the dark \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry saw the blurred outlines of Fred and George leaping down from Ron\rquote s bed. There was a groan of bedsprings and Harry\rquote s mattress descended a few inches as George sat down near his feet.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So, got there yet?\rdblquote  said George eagerly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The weapon Sirius mentioned?\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Let slip, more like,\rdblquote  said Fred with relish, now sitting next to Ron. \ldblquote We didn\rquote t hear about \i that\i0  on the old Extendables, did we?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What d\rquote you reckon it is?\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Could be anything,\rdblquote  said Fred.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But there can\rquote t be anything worse than the \i Avada Kedavra\i0  curse, can there?\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote What\rquote s worse than death?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Maybe it\rquote s something that can kill loads of people at once,\rdblquote  sug\-gested George.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Maybe it\rquote s some particularly painful way of killing people,\rdblquote  said Ron fearfully.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He\rquote s got the Cruciatus Curse for causing pain,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote He doesn\rquote t need anything more efficient than that.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a pause and Harry knew that the others, like him, were wondering what horrors this weapon could perpetrate.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So who d\rquote you thinks got it now?\rdblquote  asked George.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I hope it\rquote s our side,\rdblquote  said Ron, sounding slightly nervous.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote If it is, Dumbledore\rquote s probably keeping it,\rdblquote  said Fred.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Where?\rdblquote  said Ron quickly. \ldblquote Hogwarts?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Bet it is!\rdblquote  said George. \ldblquote That\rquote s where he hid the Sorcerer\rquote s Stone!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote A weapon\rquote s going to be a lot bigger than the Stone, though!\rdblquote  said Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Not necessarily,\rdblquote  said Fred.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, size is no guarantee of power,\rdblquote  said George. \ldblquote Look at Ginny.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What d\rquote you mean?\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote ve never been on the receiving end of one of her Bat-Bogey Hexes, have you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Shhh!\rdblquote  said Fred, half-rising from the bed. \ldblquote Listen!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They fell silent. Footsteps were coming up the stairs again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Mum,\rdblquote  said George, and without further ado there was a loud crack and Harry felt the weight vanish from the end of his bed. A few seconds later and they heard the floorboard creak outside their door; Mrs. Weasley was plainly listening to see whether they were talking or not.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hedwig and Pigwidgeon hooted dolefully. The floorboard creaked again and they heard her heading upstairs to check on Fred and George.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote She doesn\rquote t trust us at all, you know,\rdblquote  said Ron regretfully.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry was sure he would not be able to fall asleep; the evening had been so packed with things to think about that he fully expected to lie awake for hours mulling it all over. He wanted to continue talking to Ron, but Mrs. Weasley was now creaking back downstairs again, and once she had gone he distinctly heard others making their way up\-stairs. \'85 In fact, many-legged creatures were cantering softly up and down outside the bedroom door, and Hagrid, the Care of Magical Creatures teacher, was saying, \ldblquote\i Beauties, aren\rquote  they, eh, Harry? We\rquote ll be studyin\rquote  weapons this term. \'85\i0\rdblquote\lang3081  \lang1033 And Harry saw that the creatures had cannons for heads and were wheeling to face him. \'85 He ducked. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The next thing he knew, he was curled in a warm ball under his bedclothes, and George\rquote s loud voice was filling the room.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Mum says get up, your breakfast is in the kitchen and then she needs you in the drawing room, there are loads more doxies than she thought and she\rquote s found a nest of dead puffskeins under the sofa.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Half an hour later, Harry and Ron, who had dressed and break\-fasted quickly, entered the drawing room, a long, high-ceilinged room on the first floor with olive-green walls covered in dirty tapestries. The carpet exhaled little clouds of dust every time someone put their foot on it and the long, moss-green velvet curtains were buzzing as though swarming with invisible bees. It was around these that Mrs. Weasley,\lang3081  \lang1033 Hermione, Ginny, Fred, and George were grouped, all looking rather peculiar, as they had tied cloths over their noses and mouths. Each of them was also holding a large bottle of black liquid with a nozzle at the end.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Cover your faces and take a spray,\rdblquote  Mrs. Weasley said to Harry and Ron the moment she saw them, pointing to two more bottles of black liquid standing on a spindle-legged table. \ldblquote It\rquote s Doxycide. I\rquote ve never seen an infestation this bad \emdash  \i what\i0  that house-elf\rquote s been doing for the last ten years \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione\rquote s face was half concealed by a tea towel but Harry dis\-tinctly saw her throw a reproachful look at Mrs. Weasley at these words.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Kreacher\rquote s really old, he probably couldn\rquote t manage \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote d be surprised what Kreacher can manage when he wants to, Hermione,\rdblquote  said Sirius, who had just entered the room carrying a bloodstained bag of what appeared to be dead rats. \ldblquote I\rquote ve just been feed\-ing Buckbeak,\rdblquote  he added, in reply to Harry\rquote s inquiring look. \ldblquote I keep him upstairs in my mother\rquote s bedroom. Anyway \'85 this writing desk \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He dropped the bag of rats onto an armchair, then bent over to ex\-amine the locked cabinet which, Harry now noticed for the first time, was shaking slightly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, Molly, I\rquote m pretty sure this is a boggart,\rdblquote  said Sirius, peering through the keyhole, \ldblquote but perhaps we ought to let Mad-Eye have a shifty at it before we let it out \emdash  knowing my mother it could be something much worse.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Right you are, Sirius,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They were both speaking in carefully light, polite voices that told Harry quite plainly that neither had forgotten their disagreement of the night before.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A loud, clanging bell sounded from downstairs, followed at once by the cacophony of screams and wails that had been triggered the previ\-ous night by Tonks knocking over the umbrella stand.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I keep telling them not to ring the doorbell!\rdblquote  said Sirius exasperat\-edly, hurrying back out of the room. They heard him thundering down the stairs as Mrs. Black\rquote s screeches echoed up through the house once more: \ldblquote\i Stains of dishonor, filthy half-breeds, blood traitors, children of filth\lang3081\i0  \lang1033\'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Close the door, please, Harry,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry took as much time as he dared to close the drawing room door; he wanted to listen to what was going on downstairs. Sirius had obviously managed to shut the curtains over his mother\rquote s portrait be\-cause she had stopped screaming. He heard Sirius walking down the hall, then the clattering of the chain on the front door, and then a deep voice he recognized as Kingsley Shacklebolt\rquote s saying, \ldblquote Hestia\rquote s just relieved me, so she\rquote s got Moody\rquote s cloak now, thought I\rquote d leave a re\-port for Dumbledore. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Feeling Mrs. Weasley\rquote s eyes on the back of his head, Harry regret\-fully closed the drawing room door and rejoined the doxy party.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mrs. Weasley was bending over to check the page on doxies in \i Gilderoy Lockhart\rquote s Guide to Household Pests,\i0  which was lying open on the sofa.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Right, you lot, you need to be careful, because doxies bite and their teeth are poisonous. I\rquote ve got a bottle of antidote here, but I\rquote d rather nobody needed it.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She straightened up, positioned herself squarely in front of the cur\-tains, and beckoned them all forward.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote When I say the word, start spraying immediately,\rdblquote  she said. \ldblquote They\rquote ll come flying out at us, I expect, but it says on the sprays one good squirt will paralyze them. When they\rquote re immobilized, just throw them in this bucket.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She stepped carefully out of their line of fire and raised her own spray. \ldblquote All right \emdash  \i squirt\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry had been spraying only a few seconds when a fully grown doxy came soaring out of a fold in the material, shiny beetlelike wings\lang3081  \lang1033 whirring, tiny needle-sharp teeth bared, its fairylike body covered with thick black hair and its four tiny fists clenched with fury. Harry caught it full in the face with a blast of Doxycide; it froze in midair and fell, with a surprisingly loud \i thunk\i0 , onto the worn carpet below. Harry picked it up and threw it in the bucket.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Fred, what are you doing?\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley sharply. \ldblquote Spray that at once and throw it away!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry looked around. Fred was holding a struggling doxy between his forefinger and thumb.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Right-o,\rdblquote  Fred said brightly, spraying the doxy quickly in the face so that it fainted, but the moment Mrs. Weasley\rquote s back was turned he pocketed it with a wink.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We want to experiment with doxy venom for our Skiving Snack-boxes,\rdblquote  George told Harry under his breath.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Deftly spraying two doxies at once as they soared straight for his nose, Harry moved closer to George and muttered out of the corner of his mouth, \ldblquote What are Skiving Snackboxes?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Range of sweets to make you ill,\rdblquote  George whispered, keeping a wary eye on Mrs. Weasley\rquote s back. \ldblquote Not seriously ill, mind, just ill enough to get you out of a class when you feel like it. Fred and I have been developing them this summer. They\rquote re double-ended, color-coded chews. If you eat the orange half of the Puking Pastilles, you throw up. Moment you\rquote ve been rushed out of the lesson for the hos\-pital wing, you swallow the purple half\lang3081  \lang1033\emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \lquote\emdash\lang3081  \lang1033 which restores you to full fitness, enabling you to pursue the leisure activity of your own choice during an hour that would other\-wise have been devoted to unprofitable boredom.\rquote  That\rquote s what we\rquote re putting in the adverts, anyway,\rdblquote  whispered Fred, who had edged over out of Mrs. Weasley\rquote s line of vision and was now sweeping a few stray doxies from the floor and adding them to his pocket. \ldblquote But they still need a bit of work. At the moment our testers are having a bit of trou\-ble stopping puking long enough to swallow the purple end.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Testers?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Us,\rdblquote  said Fred. \ldblquote We take it in turns. George did the Fainting Fan\-cies \emdash  we both tried the Nosebleed Nougat \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Mum thought we\rquote d been dueling,\rdblquote  said George.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Joke shop still on, then?\rdblquote  Harry muttered, pretending to be ad\-justing the nozzle on his spray.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, we haven\rquote t had a chance to get premises yet,\rdblquote  said Fred, dropping his voice even lower as Mrs. Weasley mopped her brow with her scarf before returning to the attack, \ldblquote so we\rquote re running it as a mail-order service at the moment. We put advertisements in the \i Daily Prophet\i0  last week.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote All thanks to you, mate,\rdblquote  said George. \ldblquote But don\rquote t worry \'85 Mum hasn\rquote t got a clue. She won\rquote t read the \i Daily Prophet\i0  anymore, \rquote cause of it telling lies about you and Dumbledore.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry grinned. He had forced the Weasley twins to take the thou\-sand-Galleon prize money he had won in the Triwizard Tournament to help them realize their ambition to open a joke shop, but he was still glad to know that his part in furthering their plans was unknown to Mrs. Weasley, who did not think that running a joke shop was a suitable career for two of her sons.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The de-doxying of the curtains took most of the morning. It was past midday when Mrs. Weasley finally removed her protective scarf, sank into a sagging armchair, and sprang up again with a cry of dis\-gust, having sat on the bag of dead rats. The curtains were no longer buzzing; they hung limp and damp from the intensive spraying; un\-conscious doxies lay crammed in the bucket at the foot of them beside a bowl of their black eggs, at which Crookshanks was now sniffing and Fred and George were shooting covetous looks.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I think we\rquote ll tackle \i those\i0  after lunch.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mrs. Weasley pointed at the dusty glass-fronted cabinets standing on either side of the mantelpiece. They were crammed with an odd assortment of objects: a selection of rusty daggers, claws, a coiled snakeskin, a number of tarnished silver boxes inscribed with languages Harry could not understand and, least pleasant of all, an ornate crys\-tal bottle with a large opal set into the stopper, full of what Harry was quite sure was blood.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The clanging doorbell rang again. Everyone looked at Mrs. Weasley.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Stay here,\rdblquote  she said firmly, snatching up the bag of rats as Mrs. Blacks screeches started up again from down below. \ldblquote I\rquote ll bring up some sandwiches.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She left the room, closing the door carefully behind her. At once, everyone dashed over to the window to look down onto the doorstep. They could see the top of an unkempt gingery head and a stack of pre\-cariously balanced cauldrons.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Mundungus!\rdblquote  said Hermione. \ldblquote What\rquote s he brought all those caul\-drons for?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Probably looking for a safe place to keep them,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote Isn\rquote t that what he was doing the night he was supposed to be tailing me? Picking up dodgy cauldrons?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, you\rquote re right!\rdblquote  said Fred, as the front door opened; Mundun\-gus heaved his cauldrons through it and disappeared from view. \ldblquote Blimey, Mum won\rquote t like that. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He and George crossed to the door and stood beside it, listening intently. Mrs. Black\rquote s screaming had stopped again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Mundungus is talking to Sirius and Kingsley,\rdblquote  Fred muttered, frowning with concentration. \ldblquote Can\rquote t hear properly \'85 d\rquote you reckon we can risk the Extendable Ears?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Might be worth it,\rdblquote  said George. \ldblquote I could sneak upstairs and get a pair \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But at that precise moment there was an explosion of sound from downstairs that rendered Extendable Ears quite unnecessary. All of them could hear exactly what Mrs. Weasley was shouting at the top of her voice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote WE ARE NOT RUNNING A HIDEOUT FOR STOLEN GOODS!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I love hearing Mum shouting at someone else,\rdblquote  said Fred, with a satisfied smile on his face as he opened the door an inch or so to allow Mrs. Weasley\rquote s voice to permeate the room better. \ldblquote It makes such a nice change.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  COMPLETELY IRRESPONSIBLE, AS IF WE HAVEN\rquote T GOT ENOUGH TO WORRY ABOUT WITHOUT YOU DRAG\-GING STOLEN CAULDRONS INTO THE HOUSE \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The idiots are letting her get into her stride,\rdblquote  said George, shaking his head. \ldblquote You\rquote ve got to head her off early, otherwise she builds up a head of steam and goes on for hours. And she\rquote s been dying to have a go at Mundungus ever since he sneaked off when he was supposed to be following you, Harry \emdash  and there goes Sirius\rquote s mum again \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mrs. Weasley\rquote s voice was lost amid fresh shrieks and screams from the portraits in the hall. George made to shut the door to drown the noise, but before he could do so, a house-elf edged into the room.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Except for the filthy rag tied like a loincloth around its middle, it was completely naked. It looked very old. Its skin seemed to be several times too big for it and though it was bald like all house-elves, there was a quantity of white hair growing out of its large, batlike ears. Its eyes were a bloodshot and watery gray, and its fleshy nose was large and rather snoutlike.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The elf took absolutely no notice of Harry and the rest. Acting as though it could not see them, it shuffled hunchbacked, slowly and doggedly, toward the far end of the room, muttering under its breath all the while in a hoarse, deep voice like a bullfrog\rquote s, \ldblquote\'85 Smells like a drain and a criminal to boot, but she\rquote s no better, nasty old blood traitor with her brats messing up my Mistress\rquote s house, oh my poor Mistress, if she knew, if she knew the scum they\rquote ve let in her house, what would she say to old Kreacher, oh the shame of it, Mudbloods\lang3081  \lang1033 and werewolves and traitors and thieves, poor old Kreacher, what can he do. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hello, Kreacher,\rdblquote  said Fred very loudly, closing the door with a snap.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The house-elf froze in his tracks, stopped muttering, and then gave a very pronounced and very unconvincing start of surprise.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Kreacher did not see Young Master,\rdblquote  he said, turning around and bowing to Fred. Still facing the carpet, he added, perfectly audibly, \ldblquote Nasty little brat of a blood traitor it is.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sorry?\rdblquote  said George. \ldblquote Didn\rquote t catch that last bit.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Kreacher said nothing,\rdblquote  said the elf, with a second bow to George, adding in a clear undertone, \ldblquote and there\rquote s its twin, unnatural little beasts they are.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry didn\rquote t know whether to laugh or not. The elf straightened up, eyeing them all very malevolently, and apparently convinced that they could not hear him as he continued to mutter.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\'85 and there\rquote s the Mudblood, standing there bold as brass, oh if my Mistress knew, oh how she\rquote d cry, and there\rquote s a new boy, Kreacher doesn\rquote t know his name, what is he doing here, Kreacher doesn\rquote t know \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote This is Harry, Kreacher,\rdblquote  said Hermione tentatively. \ldblquote Harry Potter.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Kreacher\rquote s pale eyes widened and he muttered faster and more furi\-ously than ever.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The Mudblood is talking to Kreacher as though she is my friend, if Kreacher\rquote s Mistress saw him in such company, oh what would she say \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Don\rquote t call her a Mudblood!\rdblquote  said Ron and Ginny together, very angrily.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It doesn\rquote t matter,\rdblquote  Hermione whispered, \ldblquote he\rquote s not in his right mind, he doesn\rquote t know what he\rquote s \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Don\rquote t kid yourself, Hermione, he knows \i exactly\i0  what he\rquote s saying,\rdblquote  said Fred, eyeing Kreacher with great dislike.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Kreacher was still muttering, his eyes on Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Is it true? Is it Harry Potter? Kreacher can see the scar, it must be true, that\rquote s that boy who stopped the Dark Lord, Kreacher wonders how he did it \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Don\rquote t we all, Kreacher?\rdblquote  said Fred.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What do you want anyway?\rdblquote  George asked.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Kreacher\rquote s huge eyes darted onto George.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Kreacher is cleaning,\rdblquote  he said evasively.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote A likely story,\rdblquote  said a voice behind Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Sirius had come back; he was glowering at the elf from the door\-way. The noise in the hall had abated; perhaps Mrs. Weasley and Mundungus had moved their argument down into the kitchen. At the sight of Sirius, Kreacher flung himself into a ridiculously low bow that flattened his snoutlike nose on the floor.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Stand up straight,\rdblquote  said Sirius impatiently. \ldblquote Now, what are you up to?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Kreacher is cleaning,\rdblquote  the elf repeated. \ldblquote Kreacher lives to serve the noble house of Black \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  and it\rquote s getting blacker every day, it\rquote s filthy,\rdblquote  said Sirius.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Master always liked his little joke,\rdblquote  said Kreacher, bowing again, and continuing in an undertone, \ldblquote Master was a nasty ungrateful swine who broke his mother\rquote s heart \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote My mother didn\rquote t have a heart, Kreacher,\rdblquote  Sirius snapped. \ldblquote She kept herself alive out of pure spite.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Kreacher bowed again and said, \ldblquote Whatever Master says,\rdblquote  then muttered furiously, \ldblquote Master is not fit to wipe slime from his mother\rquote s boots, oh my poor Mistress, what would she say if she saw Kreacher serving him, how she hated him, what a disappointment he was \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I asked you what you were up to,\rdblquote  said Sirius coldly. \ldblquote Every time\lang3081  \lang1033 you show up pretending to be cleaning, you sneak something off to your room so we can\rquote t throw it out.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Kreacher would never move anything from its proper place in Master\rquote s house,\rdblquote  said the elf, then muttered very fast, \ldblquote Mistress would never forgive Kreacher if the tapestry was thrown out, seven centuries it\rquote s been in the family, Kreacher must save it, Kreacher will not let Master and the blood traitors and the brats destroy it \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I thought it might be that,\rdblquote  said Sirius, casting a disdainful look at the opposite wall. \ldblquote She\rquote ll have put another Permanent Sticking Charm on the back of it, I don\rquote t doubt, but if I can get rid of it I certainly will. Now go away, Kreacher.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It seemed that Kreacher did not dare disobey a direct order; never\-theless, the look he gave Sirius as he shuffled out past him was redolent of deepest loathing and he muttered all the way out of the room.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  comes back from Azkaban ordering Kreacher around, oh my poor Mistress, what would she say if she saw the house now, scum liv\-ing in it, her treasures thrown out, she swore he was no son of hers and he\rquote s back, they say he\rquote s a murderer too \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Keep muttering and I will be a murderer!\rdblquote  said Sirius irritably, and he slammed the door shut on the elf.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sirius, he\rquote s not right in the head,\rdblquote  said Hermione pleadingly, \ldblquote I don\rquote t think he realizes we can hear him.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He\rquote s been alone too long,\rdblquote  said Sirius, \ldblquote taking mad orders from my mother\rquote s portrait and talking to himself, but he was always a foul little \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote If you just set him free,\rdblquote  said Hermione hopefully, \ldblquote maybe \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We can\rquote t set him free, he knows too much about the Order,\rdblquote  said Sirius curtly. \ldblquote And anyway, the shock would kill him. You suggest to him that he leaves this house, see how he takes it.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Sirius walked across the room, where the tapestry Kreacher had been trying to protect hung the length of the wall. Harry and the oth\-ers followed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The tapestry looked immensely old; it was faded and looked as though doxies had gnawed it in places; nevertheless, the golden thread with which it was embroidered still glinted brightly enough to show them a sprawling family tree dating back (as far as Harry could tell) to the Middle Ages. Large words at the very top of the tapestry read:\par
\par
\pard\qc THE NOBLE AND MOST ANCIENT HOUSE OF BLACK\par
\ldblquote TOUJOURS PUR\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\lang1033\par
\ldblquote You\rquote re not on here!\rdblquote  said Harry, after scanning the bottom of the tree.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I used to be there,\rdblquote  said Sirius, pointing at a small, round, charred hole in the tapestry, rather like a cigarette burn. \ldblquote My sweet old mother blasted me off after I ran away from home \emdash  Kreacher\rquote s quite fond of muttering the story under his breath.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You ran away from home?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote When I was about sixteen,\rdblquote  said Sirius. \ldblquote I\rquote d had enough.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Where did you go?\rdblquote  asked Harry, staring at him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Your dad\rquote s place,\rdblquote  said Sirius. \ldblquote Your grandparents were really good about it; they sort of adopted me as a second son. Yeah, I camped out at your dad\rquote s during the school holidays, and then when I was seven\-teen I got a place of my own, my Uncle Alphard had left me a decent bit of gold \emdash  he\rquote s been wiped off here too, that\rquote s probably why \emdash  anyway, after that I looked after myself. I was always welcome at Mr. and Mrs. Potter\rquote s for Sunday lunch, though.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 why did you \'85 ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Leave?\rdblquote  Sirius smiled bitterly and ran a hand through his long, un\-kempt hair. \ldblquote Because I hated the whole lot of them: my parents, with their pure-blood mania, convinced that to be a Black made you prac\-tically royal\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 my idiot brother, soft enough to believe them \'85 that\rquote s him.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Sirius jabbed a finger at the very bottom of the tree, at the name\lang3081  \lang1033 REGULUS BLACK. A date of death (some fifteen years previously) fol\-lowed the date of birth.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He was younger than me,\rdblquote  said Sirius, \ldblquote and a much better son, as I was constantly reminded.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But he died,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah,\rdblquote  said Sirius. \ldblquote Stupid idiot\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 he joined the Death Eaters.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote re kidding!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Come on, Harry, haven\rquote t you seen enough of this house to tell what kind of wizards my family were?\rdblquote  said Sirius testily.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Were \emdash  were your parents Death Eaters as well?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, no, but believe me, they thought Voldemort had the right idea, they were all for the purification of the Wizarding race, getting rid of Muggle-borns and having purebloods in charge. They weren\rquote t alone either, there were quite a few people, before Voldemort showed his true colors, who thought he had the right idea about things. \'85 They got cold feet when they saw what he was prepared to do to get power, though. But I bet my parents thought Regulus was a right lit\-tle hero for joining up at first.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Was he killed by an Auror?\rdblquote  Harry asked tentatively.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh no,\rdblquote  said Sirius. \ldblquote No, he was murdered by Voldemort. Or on Voldemort\rquote s orders, more likely, I doubt Regulus was ever important enough to be killed by Voldemort in person. From what I found out after he died, he got in so far, then panicked about what he was being asked to do and tried to back out. Well, you don\rquote t just hand in your resignation to Voldemort. It\rquote s a lifetime of service or death.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Lunch,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley\rquote s voice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She was holding her wand high in front of her, balancing a huge tray loaded with sandwiches and cake on its tip. She was very red in the face and still looked angry. The others moved over to her, eager for some food, but Harry remained with Sirius, who had bent closer to the tapestry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I haven\rquote t looked at this for years. There\rquote s Phineas Nigellus \'85 my great-great-grandfather, see? Least popular headmaster Hogwarts ever had \'85 and Araminta Meliflua \'85 cousin of my mother\rquote s \'85 tried to force through a Ministry Bill to make Muggle-hunting legal\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 and dear Aunt Elladora \'85 she started the family tradition of beheading house-elves when they got too old to carry tea trays \'85 of course, anytime the family produced someone halfway decent they were dis\-owned. I see Tonks isn\rquote t on here. Maybe that\rquote s why Kreacher won\rquote t take orders from her \emdash  he\rquote s supposed to do whatever anyone in the family asks him. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You and Tonks are related?\rdblquote  Harry asked, surprised.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh yeah, her mother, Andromeda, was my favorite cousin,\rdblquote  said Sirius, examining the tapestry carefully. \ldblquote No, Andromeda\rquote s not on here either, look \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He pointed to another small round burn mark between two names, Bellatrix and Narcissa.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Andromeda\rquote s sisters are still here because they made lovely, re\-spectable pure-blood marriages, but Andromeda married a Muggle-born, Ted Tonks, so \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Sirius mimed blasting the tapestry with a wand and laughed sourly. Harry, however, did not laugh; he was too busy staring at the names to the right of Andromeda\rquote s burn mark. A double line of gold embroidery linked Narcissa Black with Lucius Malfoy, and a single vertical gold line from their names led to the name Draco.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote re related to the Malfoys!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The pure-blood families are all interrelated,\rdblquote  said Sirius. \ldblquote If you\rquote re only going to let your sons and daughters marry purebloods your choice is very limited, there are hardly any of us left. Molly and I are cousins by marriage and Arthur\rquote s something like my second cousin once removed. But there\rquote s no point looking for them on here \emdash  if ever a family was a bunch of blood traitors it\rquote s the Weasleys.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But Harry was now looking at the name to the left of Andromeda\rquote s burn: Bellatrix Black, which was connected by a double line to Rodol\-phus Lestrange.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Lestrange \'85\rdblquote  Harry said aloud. The name had stirred something in his memory; he knew it from somewhere, but for a moment he couldn\rquote t think where, though it gave him an odd, creeping sensation in the pit of his stomach.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote They\rquote re in Azkaban,\rdblquote  said Sirius shortly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry looked at him curiously.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Bellatrix and her husband Rodolphus came in with Barty Crouch, Junior,\rdblquote  said Sirius in the same brusque voice. \ldblquote Rodolphus\rquote s brother, Rabastan, was with them too.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And Harry remembered: He had seen Bellatrix Lestrange inside Dumbledore\rquote s Pensieve, the strange device in which thoughts and memories could be stored: a tall dark woman with heavy-lidded eyes, who had stood at her trial and proclaimed her continuing allegiance to Lord Voldemort, her pride that she had tried to find him after his downfall and her conviction that she would one day be rewarded for her loyalty.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You never said she was your \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Does it matter if she\rquote s my cousin?\rdblquote  snapped Sirius. \ldblquote As far as I\rquote m concerned, they\rquote re not my family. \i She\rquote s\i0  certainly not my family. I haven\rquote t seen her since I was your age, unless you count a glimpse of her coming in to Azkaban. D\rquote you think I\rquote m proud of having relatives like her?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sorry,\rdblquote  said Harry quickly, \ldblquote I didn\rquote t mean \emdash  I was just surprised, that\rquote s all \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It doesn\rquote t matter, don\rquote t apologize,\rdblquote  Sirius mumbled at once. He turned away from the tapestry, his hands deep in his pockets. \ldblquote I don\rquote t like being back here,\rdblquote  he said, staring across the drawing room. \ldblquote I never thought I\rquote d be stuck in this house again.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry understood completely. He knew how he would feel if\lang3081  \lang1033 forced, when he was grown up and thought he was free of the place forever, to return and live at number four, Privet Drive.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s ideal for headquarters, of course,\rdblquote  Sirius said. \ldblquote My father put every security measure known to Wizard-kind on it when he lived here. It\rquote s Unplottable, so Muggles could never come and call \emdash  as if they\rquote d have wanted to \emdash  and now Dumbledore\rquote s added his protec\-tion, you\rquote d be hard put to find a safer house anywhere. Dumbledore\rquote s Secret-Keeper for the Order, you know \emdash  nobody can find headquar\-ters unless he tells them personally where it is \emdash  that note Moody showed you last night, that was from Dumbledore. \'85\rdblquote  Sirius gave a short, barklike laugh. \ldblquote If my parents could see the use it was being put to now \'85 well, my mother\rquote s portrait should give you some idea. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He scowled for a moment, then sighed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I wouldn\rquote t mind if I could just get out occasionally and do some\-thing useful. I\rquote ve asked Dumbledore whether I can escort you to your hearing \emdash  as Snuffles, obviously \emdash  so I can give you a bit of moral support, what d\rquote you think?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry felt as though his stomach had sunk through the dusty carpet. He had not thought about the hearing once since dinner the previous evening; in the excitement of being back with the people he liked best, of hearing everything that was going on, it had completely flown his mind. At Sirius\rquote s words, however, the crushing sense of dread returned to him. He stared at Hermione and the Weasleys, all tucking into their sandwiches, and thought how he would feel if they went back to Hogwarts without him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Don\rquote t worry,\rdblquote  Sirius said. Harry looked up and realized that Sirius had been watching him. \ldblquote I\rquote m sure they\rquote re going to clear you, there\rquote s definitely something in the International Statute of Secrecy about be\-ing allowed to use magic to save your own life.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But if they do expel me,\rdblquote  said Harry, quietly, \ldblquote can I come back here and live with you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Sirius smiled sadly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We\rquote ll see.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote d feel a lot better about the hearing if I knew I didn\rquote t have to go back to the Dursleys,\rdblquote  Harry pressed him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote They must be bad if you prefer this place,\rdblquote  said Sirius gloomily.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hurry up, you two, or there won\rquote t be any food left,\rdblquote  Mrs. Weasley called.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Sirius heaved another great sigh, cast a dark look at the tapestry, and he and Harry went to join the others.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry tried his best not to think about the hearing while they emp\-tied the glass cabinets that afternoon. Fortunately for him, it was a job that required a lot of concentration, as many of the objects in there seemed very reluctant to leave their dusty shelves. Sirius sustained a bad bite from a silver snuffbox; within seconds, his bitten hand had developed an unpleasant crusty covering like a tough brown glove.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s okay,\rdblquote  he said, examining the hand with interest before tap\-ping it lightly with his wand and restoring its skin to normal, \ldblquote must be Wartcap powder in there.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He threw the box aside into the sack where they were depositing the debris from the cabinets; Harry saw George wrap his own hand carefully in a cloth moments later and sneak the box into his already doxy-filled pocket.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They found an unpleasant-looking silver instrument, something like a many-legged pair of tweezers, which scuttled up Harry\rquote s arm like a spider when he picked it up, and attempted to puncture his skin; Sirius seized it and smashed it with a heavy book entitled \i Nature\rquote s Nobility: A Wizarding Genealogy.\i0  There was a musical box that emitted a faintly sinister, tinkling tune when wound, and they all found themselves becoming curiously weak and sleepy until Ginny had the sense to slam the lid shut; also a heavy locket that none of them could open, a number of ancient seals and, in a dusty box, an Order of Merlin, First Class, that had been awarded to Sirius\rquote s grand\-father for \ldblquote Services to the Ministry.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It means he gave them a load of gold,\rdblquote  said Sirius contemptuously, throwing the medal into the rubbish sack.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Several times, Kreacher sidled into the room and attempted to smuggle things away under his loincloth, muttering horrible curses every time they caught him at it. When Sirius wrested a large golden ring bearing the Black crest from his grip Kreacher actually burst into furious tears and left the room sobbing under his breath and calling Sirius names Harry had never heard before.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It was my father\rquote s,\rdblquote  said Sirius, throwing the ring into the sack. \ldblquote Kreacher wasn\rquote t \i quite\i0  as devoted to him as to my mother, but I still caught him snogging a pair of my father\rquote s old trousers last week.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\par
\lang1033 Mrs. Weasley kept them all working very hard over the next few days. The drawing room took three days to decontaminate; finally the only undesirable things left in it were the tapestry of the Black family tree, which resisted all their attempts to remove it from the wall, and the rattling writing desk; Moody had not dropped by headquarters yet, so they could not be sure what was inside it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They moved from the drawing room to a dining room on the ground floor where they found spiders large as saucers lurking in the dresser (Ron left the room hurriedly to make a cup of tea and did not return for an hour and a half). The china, which bore the Black crest and motto, was all thrown unceremoniously into a sack by Sirius, and the same fate met a set of old photographs in tarnished silver frames, all of whose occupants squealed shrilly as the glass covering them smashed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Snape might refer to their work as \ldblquote cleaning,\rdblquote  but in Harry\rquote s opin\-ion they were really waging war on the house, which was putting up a very good fight, aided and abetted by Kreacher. The house-elf kept appearing wherever they were congregated, his muttering becoming more and more offensive as he attempted to remove anything he could from the rubbish sacks. Sirius went as far as to threaten him\lang3081  \lang1033 with clothes, but Kreacher fixed him with a watery stare and said, \ldblquote Master must do as Master wishes,\rdblquote  before turning away and mutter\-ing very loudly, \ldblquote but Master will not turn Kreacher away, no, because Kreacher knows what they are up to, oh yes, he is plotting against the Dark Lord, yes, with these Mudbloods and traitors and scum. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 At which Sirius, ignoring Hermione\rquote s protests, seized Kreacher by the back of his loincloth and threw him bodily from the room.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The doorbell rang several times a day, which was the cue for Sirius\rquote s mother to start shrieking again, and for Harry and the others to at\-tempt to eavesdrop on the visitor, though they gleaned very little from the brief glimpses and snatches of conversation they were able to sneak before Mrs. Weasley recalled them to their tasks. Snape flitted in and out of the house several times more, though to Harry\rquote s relief they never came face-to-face; he also caught sight of his Transfiguration teacher, Professor McGonagall, looking very odd in a Muggle dress and coat, though she also seemed too busy to linger.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Sometimes, however, the visitors stayed to help; Tonks joined them for a memorable afternoon in which they found a murderous old ghoul lurking in an upstairs toilet, and Lupin, who was staying in the house with Sirius but who left it for long periods to do mysterious work for the Order, helped them repair a grandfather clock that had developed the unpleasant habit of shooting heavy bolts at passersby. Mundungus redeemed himself slightly in Mrs. Weasley\rquote s eyes by res\-cuing Ron from an ancient set of purple robes that had tried to stran\-gle him when he removed them from their wardrobe.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Despite the fact that he was still sleeping badly, still having dreams about corridors and locked doors that made his scar prickle, Harry was managing to have fun for the first time all summer. As long as he was busy he was happy; when the action abated, however, whenever he dropped his guard, or lay exhausted in bed watching blurred shad\-ows move across the ceiling, the thought of the looming Ministry\lang3081  \lang1033 hearing returned to him. Fear jabbed at his insides like needles as he wondered what was going to happen to him if he was expelled. The idea was so terrible that he did not dare voice it aloud, not even to Ron and Hermione, who, though he often saw them whispering to\-gether and casting anxious looks in his direction, followed his lead in not mentioning it. Sometimes he could not prevent his imagination showing him a faceless Ministry official who was snapping his wand in two and ordering him back to the Dursleys\rquote  \'85 but he would not go. He was determined on that. He would come back here to Grim\-mauld Place and live with Sirius.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He felt as though a brick had dropped into his stomach when Mrs. Weasley turned to him during dinner on Wednesday evening and said quietly, \ldblquote I\rquote ve ironed your best clothes for tomorrow morning, Harry, and I want you to wash your hair tonight too. A good first impression can work wonders.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron, Hermione, Fred, George, and Ginny all stopped talking and looked over at him. Harry nodded and tried to keep eating his chops, but his mouth had become so dry he could not chew.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How am I getting there?\rdblquote  he asked Mrs. Weasley, trying to sound unconcerned.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Arthur\rquote s taking you to work with him,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley gently.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mr. Weasley smiled encouragingly at Harry across the table.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You can wait in my office until it\rquote s time for the hearing,\rdblquote  he said.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry looked over at Sirius, but before he could ask the question, Mrs. Weasley had answered it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Professor Dumbledore doesn\rquote t think it\rquote s a good idea for Sirius to go with you, and I must say I \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  think he\rquote s \i quite right,\i0\rdblquote\i  \i0 said Sirius through clenched teeth.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mrs. Weasley pursed her lips.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote When did Dumbledore tell you that?\rdblquote  Harry said, staring at Sirius.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He came last night, when you were in bed,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Sirius stabbed moodily at a potato with his fork. Harry dropped his own eyes to his plate. The thought that Dumbledore had been in the house on the eve of his hearing and not asked to see him made him feel, if that were possible, even worse.\lang3081\par
