Harry awoke at half-past five the next morning as abruptly and completely as if somebody had yelled in his ear. For a few moments he lay immobile as the prospect of the hearing filled every tiny particle of his brain, then, unable to bear it, he leapt out of bed and put on his glasses. Mrs. Weasley had laid out his freshly laundered jeans and T-shirt at the foot of his bed. Harry scrambled into them. The blank picture on the wall sniggered again.\par
Ron was lying sprawled on his back with his mouth wide open, fast asleep. He did not stir as Harry crossed the room, stepped out onto the landing, and closed the door softly behind him. Trying not to think of the next time he would see Ron, when they might no longer be fellow students at Hogwarts, Harry walked quietly down the stairs, past the heads of Kreacher\rquote s ancestors, and into the kitchen.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He had expected it to be empty, but it was not. When he reached the door he heard the soft rumble of voices on the other side and when he pushed it open he saw Mr. and Mrs. Weasley, Sirius, Lupin, and Tonks sitting there almost as though they were waiting for him.\lang3081  \lang1033 All were fully dressed except Mrs. Weasley, who was wearing a quilted, purple dressing gown. She leapt to her feet the moment he entered.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Breakfast,\rdblquote  she said as she pulled out her wand and hurried over to the fire.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote M-m-morning, Harry,\rdblquote  yawned Tonks. Her hair was blonde and curly this morning. \ldblquote Sleep all right?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote ve b-b-been up all night,\rdblquote  she said, with another shuddering yawn. \ldblquote Come and sit down. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She drew out a chair, knocking over the one beside it in the process.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What do you want, Harry?\rdblquote  Mrs. Weasley called. \ldblquote Porridge? Muffins? Kippers? Bacon and eggs? Toast?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Just \emdash  just toast, thanks,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Lupin glanced at Harry, then said to Tonks, \ldblquote What were you saying about Scrimgeour?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh \'85 yeah \'85 well, we need to be a bit more careful, he\rquote s been asking Kingsley and me funny questions. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry felt vaguely grateful that he was not required to join in the conversation. His insides were squirming. Mrs. Weasley placed a cou\-ple of pieces of toast and marmalade in front of him; he tried to eat, but it was like chewing carpet. Mrs. Weasley sat down on his other side and started fussing with his T-shirt, tucking in the label and smoothing out creases across the shoulders. He wished she wouldn\rquote t.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\'85 and I\rquote ll have to tell Dumbledore I can\rquote t do night duty tomor\-row, I\rquote m just t-t-too tired,\rdblquote  Tonks finished, yawning hugely again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote ll cover for you,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley. \ldblquote I\rquote m okay, I\rquote ve got a report to finish anyway. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mr. Weasley was not wearing wizard\rquote s robes but a pair of pin\-striped trousers and an old bomber jacket. He turned from Tonks to Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How are you feeling?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry shrugged.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote ll all be over soon,\rdblquote  Mr. Weasley said bracingly. \ldblquote In a few hours\rquote  time you\rquote ll be cleared.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry said nothing.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The hearing\rquote s on my floor, in Amelia Bones\rquote s office. She\rquote s Head of the Department of Magical Law Enforcement and she\rquote s the one who\rquote ll be questioning you.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Amelia Bones is okay, Harry,\rdblquote  said Tonks earnestly. \ldblquote She\rquote s fair, she\rquote ll hear you out.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry nodded, still unable to think of anything to say.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Don\rquote t lose your temper,\rdblquote  said Sirius abruptly. \ldblquote Be polite and stick to the facts.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry nodded again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The law\rquote s on your side,\rdblquote  said Lupin quietly. \ldblquote Even underage wiz\-ards are allowed to use magic in life-threatening situations.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Something very cold trickled down the back of Harry\rquote s neck; for a moment he thought someone was putting a Disillusionment Charm on him again, then he realized that Mrs. Weasley was attacking his hair with a wet comb. She pressed hard on the top of his head.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Doesn\rquote t it ever lie flat?\rdblquote  she said desperately.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry shook his head.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mr. Weasley checked his watch and looked up at Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I think we\rquote ll go now,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote We\rquote re a bit early, but I think you\rquote ll be better off there than hanging around here.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Okay,\rdblquote  said Harry automatically, dropping his toast and getting to his feet.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote ll be all right, Harry,\rdblquote  said Tonks, patting him on the arm.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Good luck,\rdblquote  said Lupin. \ldblquote I\rquote m sure it will be fine.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And if it\rquote s not,\rdblquote  said Sirius grimly, \ldblquote I\rquote ll see to Amelia Bones for you. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry smiled weakly. Mrs. Weasley hugged him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We\rquote ve all got our fingers crossed,\rdblquote  she said.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Right,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote Well\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 see you later then.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He followed Mr. Weasley upstairs and along the hall. He could hear Sirius\rquote s mother grunting in her sleep behind her curtains. Mr. Weasley unbolted the door and they stepped out into the cold, gray dawn.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You don\rquote t normally walk to work, do you?\rdblquote  Harry asked him, as they set off briskly around the square.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, I usually Apparate,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, \ldblquote but obviously you can\rquote t, and I think it\rquote s best we arrive in a thoroughly non-magical fashion \'85 makes a better impression, given what you\rquote re being disciplined for. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mr. Weasley kept his hand inside his jacket as they walked. Harry knew it was clenched around his wand. The run-down streets were almost deserted, but when they arrived at the miserable little Under\-ground station they found it already full of early morning commuters. As ever when he found himself in close proximity to Muggles going about their daily business, Mr. Weasley was hard put to contain his enthusiasm.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Simply fabulous,\rdblquote  he whispered, indicating the automatic ticket machines. \ldblquote Wonderfully ingenious.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote They\rquote re out of order,\rdblquote  said Harry, pointing at the sign.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, but even so \'85\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, beaming fondly at them.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They bought their tickets instead from a sleepy-looking guard (Harry handled the transaction, as Mr. Weasley was not very good with Muggle money) and five minutes later they were boarding an Underground train that rattled them off toward the center of London. Mr. Weasley kept anxiously checking and rechecking the Under\-ground map above the windows.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Four stops, Harry\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 three stops left now\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 two stops to go, Harry \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They got off at a station in the very heart of London, swept from the train in a tide of besuited men and women carrying briefcases. Up\lang3081  \lang1033 the escalator they went, through the ticket barrier (Mr. Weasley delighted with the way the stile swallowed his ticket), and emerged onto a broad street lined with imposing-looking buildings, already full of traffic.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Where are we?\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley blankly, and for one heart-stopping moment Harry thought they had gotten off at the wrong sta\-tion despite Mr. Weasley\rquote s continual references to the map; but a second later he said, \ldblquote Ah yes \'85 this way, Harry,\rdblquote  and led him down a side road.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sorry,\rdblquote  he said, \ldblquote but I never come by train and it all looks rather different from a Muggle perspective. As a matter of fact I\rquote ve never even used the visitor\rquote s entrance before.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The farther they walked, the smaller and less imposing the build\-ings became, until finally they reached a street that contained several rather shabby-looking offices, a pub, and an overflowing dumpster. Harry had expected a rather more impressive location for the Ministry of Magic.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Here we are,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley brightly, pointing at an old red telephone box, which was missing several panes of glass and stood be\-fore a heavily graffittied wall. \ldblquote After you, Harry.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He opened the telephone box door.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry stepped inside, wondering what on earth this was about. Mr. Weasley folded himself in beside Harry and closed the door. It was a tight fit; Harry was jammed against the telephone apparatus, which was hanging crookedly from the wall as though a vandal had tried to rip it off. Mr. Weasley reached past Harry for the receiver.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Mr. Weasley, I think this might be out of order too,\rdblquote  Harry said.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, no, I\rquote m sure it\rquote s fine,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, holding the receiver above his head and peering at the dial. \ldblquote Let\rquote s see \'85 six \'85\rdblquote  he dialed the number, \ldblquote two \'85 four \'85 and another four \'85 and another two \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 As the dial whirred smoothly back into place, a cool female voice sounded inside the telephone box, not from the receiver in Mr. Weasley\rquote s hand, but as loudly and plainly as though an invisible woman were standing right beside them.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Welcome to the Ministry of Magic. Please state your name and business.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Er \'85\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, clearly uncertain whether he should talk into the receiver or not; he compromised by holding the mouthpiece to his ear, \ldblquote Arthur Weasley, Misuse of Muggle Artifacts Office, here to escort Harry Potter, who has been asked to attend a disciplinary hearing. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Thank you,\rdblquote  said the cool female voice. \ldblquote Visitor, please take the badge and attach it to the front of your robes.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a click and a rattle, and Harry saw something slide out of the metal chute where returned coins usually appeared. He picked it up: It was a square silver badge with \i Harry Potter, Disciplinary Hear\-ing\i0  on it. He pinned it to the front of his T-shirt as the female voice spoke again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Visitor to the Ministry, you are required to submit to a search and present your wand for registration at the security desk, which is lo\-cated at the far end of the Atrium.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The floor of the telephone box shuddered. They were sinking slowly into the ground. Harry watched apprehensively as the pave\-ment rose up past the glass windows of the telephone box until dark\-ness closed over their heads. Then he could see nothing at all; he could only hear a dull grinding noise as the telephone box made its way down through the earth. After about a minute, though it felt much longer to Harry, a chink of golden light illuminated his feet and, widening, rose up his body, until it hit him in the face and he had to blink to stop his eyes from watering.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The Ministry of Magic wishes you a pleasant day,\rdblquote  said the woman\rquote s voice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The door of the telephone box sprang open and Mr. Weasley stepped out of it, followed by Harry, whose mouth had fallen open.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They were standing at one end of a very long and splendid hall with a highly polished, dark wood floor. The peacock-blue ceiling was inlaid with gleaming golden symbols that were continually moving and chang\-ing like some enormous heavenly notice board. The walls on each side were paneled in shiny dark wood and had many gilded fireplaces set into them. Every few seconds a witch or wizard would emerge from one of the left-hand fireplaces with a soft \i whoosh\i0 ; on the right-hand side, short queues of wizards were forming before each fireplace, waiting to depart.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Halfway down the hall was a fountain. A group of golden statues, larger than life-size, stood in the middle of a circular pool. Tallest of them all was a noble-looking wizard with his wand pointing straight up in the air. Grouped around him were a beautiful witch, a centaur, a goblin, and a house-elf. The last three were all looking adoringly up at the witch and wizard. Glittering jets of water were flying from the ends of the two wands, the point of the centaur\rquote s arrow, the tip of the goblin\rquote s hat, and each of the house-elf\rquote s ears, so that the tinkling hiss of falling water was added to the pops and cracks of Apparators and the clatter of footsteps as hundreds of witches and wizards, most of whom were wearing glum, early-morning looks, strode toward a set of golden gates at the far end of the hall.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote This way,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They joined the throng, wending their way between the Ministry workers, some of whom were carrying tottering piles of parchment, others battered briefcases, still others reading the \i Daily Prophet\i0  as they walked. As they passed the fountain Harry saw silver Sickles and bronze Knuts glinting up at him from the bottom of the pool. A small, smudged sign beside it read:\lang3081\par
\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\qc\lang1033\i All proceeds from\lang3081  \lang1033 the Fountain of\lang3081  \lang1033 Magical Brethren will be\lang3081  \lang1033 given\lang3081  t\lang1033 o\par
St. Mungo\rquote s Hospital\lang3081  f\lang1033 or Magical Maladies and Injuries\par
