If\lang3081  I\rquote m not\lang1033  expelled from Hogwarts, I\rquote ll put in ten Galleons,\i0  Harry found himself thinking desperately.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Over here, Harry,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, and they stepped out of the stream of Ministry employees heading for the golden gates, toward a desk on the left, over which hung a sign saying SECURITY. A badly shaven wizard in peacock-blue robes looked up as they approached and put down his \i Daily Prophet.\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m escorting a visitor,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, gesturing toward Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Step over here,\rdblquote  said the wizard in a bored voice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry walked closer to him and the wizard held up a long golden rod, thin and flexible as a car aerial, and passed it up and down Harry\rquote s front and back.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Wand,\rdblquote  grunted the security wizard at Harry, putting down the golden instrument and holding out his hand.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry produced his wand. The wizard dropped it onto a strange brass instrument, which looked something like a set of scales with only one dish. It began to vibrate. A narrow strip of parchment came speeding out of a slit in the base. The wizard tore this off and read the writing upon it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Eleven inches, phoenix-feather core, been in use four years. That correct?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Harry nervously.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I keep this,\rdblquote  said the wizard, impaling the slip of parchment on a small brass spike. \ldblquote You get this back,\rdblquote  he added, thrusting the wand at Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Thank you.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hang on. \'85\rdblquote  said the wizard slowly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 His eyes had darted from the silver visitor\rquote s badge on Harry\rquote s chest to his forehead.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Thank you, Eric,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley firmly, and grasping Harry by the shoulder, he steered him away from the desk and back into the stream of wizards and witches walking through the golden gates.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Jostled slightly by the crowd, Harry followed Mr. Weasley through the gates into the smaller hall beyond, where at least twenty lifts stood behind wrought golden grilles. Harry and Mr. Weasley joined the crowd around one of them. A big, bearded wizard holding a large cardboard box stood nearby. The box was emitting rasping noises.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote All right, Arthur?\rdblquote  said the wizard, nodding at Mr. Weasley.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What\rquote ve you got there, Bob?\rdblquote  asked Mr. Weasley, looking at the box.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We\rquote re not sure,\rdblquote  said the wizard seriously. \ldblquote We thought it was a bog-standard chicken until it started breathing fire. Looks like a seri\-ous breach of the Ban on Experimental Breeding to me.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 With a great jangling and clattering a lift descended in front of them; the golden grille slid back and Harry and Mr. Weasley moved in\-side it with the rest of the crowd. Harry found himself jammed against the back wall of the lift. Several witches and wizards were looking at him curiously; he stared at his feet to avoid catching anyone\rquote s eye, flat\-tening his fringe as he did so. The grilles slid shut with a crash and the lift ascended slowly, chains rattling all the while, while the same cool female voice Harry had heard in the telephone box rang out again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Level seven, Department of Magical Games and Sports, incorpo\-rating the British and Irish Quidditch League Headquarters, Official Gobstones Club, and Ludicrous Patents Office.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The lift doors opened; Harry glimpsed an untidy-looking corridor, with various posters of Quidditch teams tacked lopsidedly on the walls; one of the wizards in the lift, who was carrying an armful of broomsticks, extricated himself with difficulty and disappeared down the corridor. The doors closed, the lift juddered upward again, and the woman\rquote s voice said, \ldblquote Level six, Department of Magical Transport, in\-corporating the Floo Network Authority, Broom Regulatory Control, Portkey Office, and Apparation Test Center.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Once again the lift doors opened and four or five witches and wizards got out; at the same time, several paper airplanes swooped\lang3081  \lang1033 into the lift. Harry stared up at them as they flapped idly around above his head; they were a pale violet color and he could see MINISTRY OF MAGIC stamped along the edges of their wings.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Just Interdepartmental memos,\rdblquote  Mr. Weasley muttered to him. \ldblquote We used to use owls, but the mess was unbelievable \'85 droppings all over the desks \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 As they clattered upward again, the memos flapped around the swaying lamp in the lift\rquote s ceiling.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Level five, Department of International Magical Cooperation, in\-corporating the International Magical Trading Standards Body, the International Magical Office of Law, and the International Confeder\-ation of Wizards, British Seats.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 When the doors opened, two of the memos zoomed out with a few more witches and wizards, but several more memos zoomed in, so that the light from the lamp in the ceiling flickered and flashed as they darted around it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Level four, Department for the Regulation and Control of Magical Creatures, incorporating Beast, Being, and Spirit Divisions, Goblin Liaison Office, and Pest Advisory Bureau.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \rquote S\rquote cuse,\rdblquote  said the wizard carrying the fire-breathing chicken and he left the lift pursued by a little flock of memos. The doors clanged shut yet again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Level three, Department of Magical Accidents and Catastrophes, including the Accidental Magic Reversal Squad, Obliviator Head\-quarters, and Muggle-Worthy Excuse Committee.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Everybody left the lift on this floor except Mr. Weasley, Harry, and a witch who was reading an extremely long piece of parchment that was trailing on the ground. The remaining memos continued to soar around the lamp as the lift juddered upward again, and then the doors opened and the voice said, \ldblquote Level two, Department of Magical Law Enforcement, including the Improper Use of Magic Office, Auror Headquarters, and Wizengamot Administration Services.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote This is us, Harry,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, and they followed the witch out of the lift into a corridor lined with doors. \ldblquote My office is on the other side of the floor.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Mr. Weasley,\rdblquote  said Harry, as they passed a window through which sunlight was streaming, \ldblquote aren\rquote t we underground?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, we are,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, \ldblquote those are enchanted windows; Magical Maintenance decide what weather we\rquote re getting every day. We had two months of hurricanes last time they were angling for a pay raise. \'85 Just round here, Harry.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They turned a corner, walked through a pair of heavy oak doors, and emerged in a cluttered, open area divided into cubicles, which were buzzing with talk and laughter. Memos were zooming in and out of cubicles like miniature rockets. A lopsided sign on the nearest cu\-bicle read AUROR HEADQUARTERS.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry looked surreptitiously through the doorways as they passed. The Aurors had covered their cubicle walls with everything from pic\-tures of wanted wizards and photographs of their families, to posters of their favorite Quidditch teams and articles from the \i Daily Prophet.\i0  A scarlet-robed man with a ponytail longer than Bill\rquote s was sitting with his boots up on his desk, dictating a report to his quill. A little farther along, a witch with a patch over her eye was talking over the top of her cubicle wall to Kingsley Shacklebolt.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Morning, Weasley,\rdblquote  said Kingsley carelessly, as they drew nearer. \ldblquote I\rquote ve been wanting a word with you, have you got a second?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, if it really is a second,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, \ldblquote I\rquote m in rather a hurry.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They were talking to each other as though they hardly knew each other, and when Harry opened his mouth to say hello to Kingsley, Mr. Weasley stood on his foot. They followed Kingsley along the row and into the very last cubicle.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry received a slight shock; Sirius\rquote s face was blinking down at him from every direction. Newspaper cuttings and old photographs\lang3081  \lang1033\emdash  even the one of Sirius being best man at the Potters\rquote  wedding \emdash  papered the walls. The only Sirius-free space was a map of the world in which little red pins were glowing like jewels.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Here,\rdblquote  said Kingsley brusquely to Mr. Weasley, shoving a sheaf of parchment into his hand, \ldblquote I need as much information as possible on flying Muggle vehicles sighted in the last twelve months. We\rquote ve re\-ceived information that Black might still be using his old motorcycle.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Kingsley tipped Harry an enormous wink and added, in a whisper, \ldblquote Give him the magazine, he might find it interesting.\rdblquote  Then he said in normal tones, \ldblquote And don\rquote t take too long, Weasley, the delay on that firelegs report held our investigation up for a month.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote If you had read my report you would know that the term is \lquote firearms,\rquote  \rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley coolly. \ldblquote And I\rquote m afraid you\rquote ll have to wait for information on motorcycles, we\rquote re extremely busy at the mo\-ment.\rdblquote  He dropped his voice and said, \ldblquote If you can get away before seven, Molly\rquote s making meatballs.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He beckoned to Harry and led him out of Kingsley\rquote s cubicle, through a second set of oak doors, into another passage, turned left, marched along another corridor, turned right into a dimly lit and dis\-tinctly shabby corridor, and finally reached a dead end, where a door on the left stood ajar, revealing a broom cupboard, and a door on the right bore a tarnished brass plaque reading MISUSE OF MUGGLE\lang3081  \lang1033 ARTIFACTS.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mr. Weasley\rquote s dingy office seemed to be slightly smaller than the broom cupboard. Two desks had been crammed inside it and there was barely room to move around them because of all the overflowing filing cabinets lining the walls, on top of which were tottering piles of files. The little wall space available bore witness to Mr. Weasley\rquote s obsessions; there were several posters of cars, including one of a dismantled engine, two illustrations of postboxes he seemed to have cut out of Muggle children\rquote s books, and a diagram showing how to wire a plug.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Sitting on top of Mr. Weasley\rquote s overflowing in-tray was an old\lang3081  \lang1033 toaster that was hiccuping in a disconsolate way and a pair of empty leather gloves that were twiddling their thumbs. A photograph of the Weasley family stood beside the in-tray. Harry noticed that Percy ap\-peared to have walked out of it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We haven\rquote t got a window,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley apologetically, taking off his bomber jacket and placing it on the back of his chair. \ldblquote We\rquote ve asked, but they don\rquote t seem to think we need one. Have a seat, Harry, doesn\rquote t look as if Perkins is in yet.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry squeezed himself into the chair behind Perkins\rquote s desk while Mr. Weasley rifled through the sheaf of parchment Kingsley Shackle\-bolt had given him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ah,\rdblquote  he said, grinning, as he extracted a copy of a magazine enti\-tled \i The Quibbler\i0  from its midst, \ldblquote yes \'85\rdblquote  He flicked through it. \ldblquote Yes, he\rquote s right, I\rquote m sure Sirius will find that very amusing \emdash  oh dear, what\rquote s this now?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A memo had just zoomed in through the open door and fluttered to rest on top of the hiccuping toaster. Mr. Weasley unfolded it and read aloud, \ldblquote  \lquote Third regurgitating public toilet reported in Bethnal Green, kindly investigate immediately.\rquote\lang3081  \lang1033 This is getting ridiculous. \'85\lang3081\rdblquote\par
\lang1033\ldblquote A regurgitating toilet?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Anti-Muggle pranksters,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, frowning. \ldblquote We had two last week, one in Wimbledon, one in Elephant and Castle. Mug\-gles are pulling the flush and instead of everything disappearing \emdash  well, you can imagine. The poor things keep calling in those \emdash  those \i pumbles,\i0  I think they\rquote re called \emdash  you know, the ones who mend pipes and things \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Plumbers?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  exactly, yes, but of course they\rquote re flummoxed. I only hope we can catch whoever\rquote s doing it.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Will it be Aurors who catch them?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh no, this is too trivial for Aurors, it\rquote ll be the ordinary Magical Law Enforcement Patrol \emdash  ah, Harry, this is Perkins.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A stooped, timid-looking old wizard with fluffy white hair had just entered the room, panting.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh Arthur!\rdblquote  he said desperately, without looking at Harry. \ldblquote Thank goodness, I didn\rquote t know what to do for the best, whether to wait here for you or not, I\rquote ve just sent an owl to your home but you\rquote ve obviously missed it \emdash  an urgent message came ten minutes ago \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I know about the regurgitating toilet,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, no, it\rquote s not the toilet, it\rquote s the Potter boy\rquote s hearing \emdash  they\rquote ve changed the time and venue \emdash  it starts at eight o\rquote clock now and it\rquote s down in old Courtroom Ten \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Down in old \emdash  but they told me \emdash  Merlin\rquote s beard \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mr. Weasley looked at his watch, let out a yelp, and leapt from his chair.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Quick, Harry, we should have been there five minutes ago!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Perkins flattened himself against the filing cabinets as Mr. Weasley left the office at a run, Harry on his heels.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Why have they changed the time?\rdblquote  Harry said breathlessly as they hurtled past the Auror cubicles; people poked out their heads and stared as they streaked past. Harry felt as though he had left all his in\-sides back at Perkins\rquote s desk.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote ve no idea, but thank goodness we got here so early, if you\rquote d missed it it would have been catastrophic!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mr. Weasley skidded to a halt beside the lifts and jabbed impa\-tiently at the down button.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Come ON!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The lift clattered into view and they hurried inside. Every time it stopped Mr. Weasley cursed furiously and pummelled the number nine button.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Those courtrooms haven\rquote t been used in years,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley angrily. \ldblquote I can\rquote t think why they\rquote re doing it down there \emdash  unless \emdash  but no \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A plump witch carrying a smoking goblet entered the lift at that moment, and Mr. Weasley did not elaborate.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The Atrium,\rdblquote  said the cool female voice and the golden grilles slid open, showing Harry a distant glimpse of the golden statues in the fountain. The plump witch got out and a sallow-skinned wizard with a very mournful face got in.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Morning, Arthur,\rdblquote  he said in a sepulchral voice as the lift began to descend. \ldblquote Don\rquote t often see you down here. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Urgent business, Bode,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, who was bouncing on the balls of his feet and throwing anxious looks over at Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ah, yes,\rdblquote  said Bode, surveying Harry unblinkingly. \ldblquote Of course.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry barely had emotion to spare for Bode, but his unfaltering gaze did not make him feel any more comfortable.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Department of Mysteries,\rdblquote  said the cool female voice, and left it at that.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Quick, Harry,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley as the lift doors rattled open, and they sped up a corridor that was quite different from those above. The walls were bare; there were no windows and no doors apart from a plain black one set at the very end of the corridor. Harry expected them to go through it, but instead Mr. Weasley seized him by the arm and dragged him to the left, where there was an opening leading to a flight of steps.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Down here, down here,\rdblquote  panted Mr. Weasley, taking two steps at a time. \ldblquote The lift doesn\rquote t even come down this far \'85 \i why\i0  they\rquote re do\-ing it there \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They reached the bottom of the steps and ran along yet another corridor, which bore a great resemblance to that which led to Snape\rquote s dungeon at Hogwarts, with rough stone walls and torches in brackets. The doors they passed here were heavy wooden ones with iron bolts and keyholes.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Courtroom \'85 ten \'85 I think \'85 we\rquote re nearly \'85 yes.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mr. Weasley stumbled to a halt outside a grimy dark door with an immense iron lock and slumped against the wall, clutching at a stitch in his chest.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Go on,\rdblquote  he panted, pointing his thumb at the door. \ldblquote Get in there.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Aren\rquote t \emdash  aren\rquote t you coming with \emdash  ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, no, I\rquote m not allowed. Good luck!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry\rquote s heart was beating a violent tattoo against his Adam\rquote s apple. He swallowed hard, turned the heavy iron door handle, and stepped inside the courtroom.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\par
