\pard\qc The Hearing\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\fs24\par
Harry gasped; he could not help himself. The large dungeon he had entered was horribly familiar. He had not only seen it before, he had \i been\i0  here before: This was the place he had visited in\-side Dumbledore\rquote s Pensieve, the place where he had watched the Lestranges sentenced to life imprisonment in Azkaban.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The walls were made of dark stone, dimly lit by torches. Empty benches rose on either side of him, but ahead, in the highest benches of all, were many shadowy figures. They had been talking in low voices, but as the heavy door swung closed behind Harry an ominous silence fell.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A cold male voice rang across the courtroom.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote re late.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sorry,\rdblquote  said Harry nervously. \ldblquote I-I didn\rquote t know the time had changed.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That is not the Wizengamot\rquote s fault,\rdblquote  said the voice. \ldblquote An owl was sent to you this morning. Take your seat.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry dropped his gaze to the chair in the center of the room, the arms of which were covered in chains. He had seen those chains spring\lang3081  \lang1033 to life and bind whoever sat between them. His footsteps echoed loudly as he walked across the stone floor. When he sat gingerly on the edge of the chair the chains clinked rather threateningly but did not bind him. Feeling rather sick he looked up at the people seated at the bench above.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There were about fifty of them, all, as far as he could see, wearing plum-colored robes with an elaborately worked silver W on the left-hand side of the chest and all staring down their noses at him, some with very austere expressions, others looks of frank curiosity.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 In the very middle of the front row sat Cornelius Fudge, the Min\-ister of Magic. Fudge was a portly man who often sported a lime-green bowler hat, though today he had dispensed with it; he had dispensed too with the indulgent smile he had once worn when he spoke to Harry. A broad, square-jawed witch with very short gray hair sat on Fudge\rquote s left; she wore a monocle and looked forbidding. On Fudge\rquote s right was another witch, but she was sitting so far back on the bench that her face was in shadow.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Very well,\rdblquote  said Fudge. \ldblquote The accused being present \emdash  finally \emdash  let us begin. Are you ready?\rdblquote  he called down the row.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, sir,\rdblquote  said an eager voice Harry knew. Ron\rquote s brother Percy was sitting at the very end of the front bench. Harry looked at Percy, ex\-pecting some sign of recognition from him, but none came. Percy\rquote s eyes, behind his horn-rimmed glasses, were fixed on his parchment, a quill poised in his hand.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Disciplinary hearing of the twelfth of August,\rdblquote  said Fudge in a ringing voice, and Percy began taking notes at once, \ldblquote into offenses committed under the Decree for the Reasonable Restriction of Un\-derage Sorcery and the International Statute of Secrecy by Harry James Potter, resident at number four, Privet Drive, Little Whinging, Surrey.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Interrogators: Cornelius Oswald Fudge, Minister of Magic; Amelia Susan Bones, Head of the Department of Magical Law En\-forcement; Dolores Jane Umbridge, Senior Undersecretary to the Minister. Court Scribe, Percy Ignatius Weasley \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  Witness for the defense, Albus Percival Wulfric Brian Dumble\-dore,\rdblquote  said a quiet voice from behind Harry, who turned his head so fast he cricked his neck.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore was striding serenely across the room wearing long midnight-blue robes and a perfectly calm expression. His long silver beard and hair gleamed in the torchlight as he drew level with Harry and looked up at Fudge through the half-moon spectacles that rested halfway down his very crooked nose.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The members of the Wizengamot were muttering. All eyes were now on Dumbledore. Some looked annoyed, others slightly fright\-ened; two elderly witches in the back row, however, raised their hands and waved in welcome.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A powerful emotion had risen in Harry\rquote s chest at the sight of Dum\-bledore, a fortified, hopeful feeling rather like that which phoenix song gave him. He wanted to catch Dumbledore\rquote s eye, but Dumble\-dore was not looking his way; he was continuing to look up at the obviously flustered Fudge.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ah,\rdblquote  said Fudge, who looked thoroughly disconcerted. \ldblquote Dumble\-dore. Yes. You \emdash  er \emdash  got our \emdash  er \emdash  message that the time and \emdash  er \emdash  place of the hearing had been changed, then?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I must have missed it,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore cheerfully. \ldblquote However, due to a lucky mistake I arrived at the Ministry three hours early, so no harm done.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes \emdash  well \emdash  I suppose we\rquote ll need another chair \emdash  I \emdash  Weasley, could you \emdash  ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Not to worry, not to worry,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore pleasantly; he took out his wand, gave it a little flick, and a squashy chintz armchair ap\-peared out of nowhere next to Harry. Dumbledore sat down, put the tips of his long fingers together, and looked at Fudge over them with an expression of polite interest. The Wizengamot was still muttering\lang3081  \lang1033 and fidgeting restlessly; only when Fudge spoke again did they settle down.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Fudge again, shuffling his notes. \ldblquote Well, then. So. The charges. Yes.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He extricated a piece of parchment from the pile before him, took a deep breath, and read, \ldblquote The charges against the accused are as fol\-lows: That he did knowingly, deliberately, and in full awareness of the illegality of his actions, having received a previous written warning from the Ministry of Magic on a similar charge, produce a Patronus Charm in a Muggle-inhabited area, in the presence of a Muggle, on August the second at twenty-three minutes past nine, which consti\-tutes an offense under paragraph C of the Decree for the Reasonable Restriction of Underage Sorcery, 1875, and also under section thir\-teen of the International Confederation of Wizards\rquote  Statute of Secrecy.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You are Harry James Potter, of number four, Privet Drive, Little Whinging, Surrey?\rdblquote  Fudge said, glaring at Harry over the top of his parchment.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  Harry said.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You received an official warning from the Ministry for using ille\-gal magic three years ago, did you not?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, but \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And yet you conjured a Patronus on the night of the second of August?\rdblquote  said Fudge.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Harry, \ldblquote but \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Knowing that you are not permitted to use magic outside school while you are under the age of seventeen?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, but \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Knowing that you were in an area full of Muggles?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, but \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Fully aware that you were in close proximity to a Muggle at the time?\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Yes,\i0\rdblquote  said Harry angrily, \ldblquote but I only used it because we were \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The witch with the monocle on Fudge\rquote s left cut across him in a booming voice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You produced a fully fledged Patronus?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Harry, \ldblquote because \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote A corporeal Patronus?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote A \emdash  what?\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Your Patronus had a clearly defined form? I mean to say, it was more than vapor or smoke?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Harry, feeling both impatient and slightly desperate, \ldblquote it\rquote s a stag, it\rquote s always a stag.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Always?\rdblquote  boomed Madam Bones. \ldblquote You have produced a Patronus before now?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Yes,\i0\rdblquote  said Harry, \ldblquote I\rquote ve been doing it for over a year \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And you are fifteen years old?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, and \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You learned this at school?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, Professor Lupin taught me in my third year, because of the \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Impressive,\rdblquote  said Madam Bones, staring down at him, \ldblquote a true Patronus at that age \'85 very impressive indeed.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Some of the wizards and witches around her were muttering again; a few nodded, but others were frowning and shaking their heads.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s not a question of how impressive the magic was,\rdblquote  said Fudge in a testy voice. \ldblquote In fact, the more impressive the worse it is, I would have thought, given that the boy did it in plain view of a Muggle!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Those who had been frowning now murmured in agreement, but it was the sight of Percy\rquote s sanctimonious little nod that goaded Harry into speech.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I did it because of the dementors!\rdblquote  he said loudly, before anyone could interrupt him again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He had expected more muttering, but the silence that fell seemed to be somehow denser than before.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Dementors?\rdblquote  said Madam Bones after a moment, raising her thick\lang3081  \lang1033 eyebrows so that her monocle looked in danger of falling out. \ldblquote What do you mean, boy?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I mean there were two dementors down that alleyway and they went for me and my cousin!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ah,\rdblquote  said Fudge again, smirking unpleasantly as he looked around at the Wizengamot, as though inviting them to share the joke. \ldblquote Yes. Yes, I thought we\rquote d be hearing something like this.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Dementors in Little Whinging?\rdblquote  Madam Bones said in tones of great surprise. \ldblquote I don\rquote t understand \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Don\rquote t you, Amelia?\rdblquote  said Fudge, still smirking. \ldblquote Let me explain. He\rquote s been thinking it through and decided dementors would make a very nice little cover story, very nice indeed. Muggles can\rquote t see demen\-tors, can they, boy? Highly convenient, highly convenient\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 so it\rquote s just your word and no witnesses. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m not lying!\rdblquote  said Harry loudly, over another outbreak of mut\-tering from the court. \ldblquote There were two of them, coming from oppo\-site ends of the alley, everything went dark and cold and my cousin felt them and ran for it \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Enough, enough!\rdblquote  said Fudge with a very supercilious look on his face. \ldblquote I\rquote m sorry to interrupt what I\rquote m sure would have been a very well-rehearsed story \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore cleared his throat. The Wizengamot fell silent again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We do, in fact, have a witness to the presence of dementors in that alleyway,\rdblquote  he said, \ldblquote other than Dudley Dursley, I mean.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Fudge\rquote s plump face seemed to slacken, as though somebody had let air out of it. He stared down at Dumbledore for a moment or two, then, with the appearance of a man pulling himself back together, said, \ldblquote We haven\rquote t got time to listen to more taradiddles, I\rquote m afraid, Dumbledore. I want this dealt with quickly \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I may be wrong,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore pleasantly, \ldblquote but I am sure that under the Wizengamot Charter of Rights, the accused has the right to\lang3081  \lang1033 present witnesses for his or her case? Isn\rquote t that the policy of the De\-partment of Magical Law Enforcement, Madam Bones?\rdblquote  he contin\-ued, addressing the witch in the monocle.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote True,\rdblquote  said Madam Bones. \ldblquote Perfectly true.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, very well, very well,\rdblquote  snapped Fudge. \ldblquote Where is this person?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I brought her with me,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote She\rquote s just outside the door. Should I \emdash  ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No \emdash  Weasley, you go,\rdblquote  Fudge barked at Percy, who got up at once, hurried down the stone steps from the judge\rquote s balcony, and has\-tened past Dumbledore and Harry without glancing at them.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A moment later, Percy returned, followed by Mrs. Figg. She looked scared and more batty than ever. Harry wished she had thought to change out of her carpet slippers.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore stood up and gave Mrs. Figg his chair, conjuring a second one for himself.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Full name?\rdblquote  said Fudge loudly, when Mrs. Figg had perched her\-self nervously on the very edge of her seat.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Arabella Doreen Figg,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Figg in her quavery voice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And who exactly are you?\rdblquote  said Fudge, in a bored and lofty voice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m a resident of Little Whinging, close to where Harry Potter lives,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Figg.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We have no record of any witch or wizard living in Little Whing\-ing other than Harry Potter,\rdblquote  said Madam Bones at once. \ldblquote That situ\-ation has always been closely monitored, given \'85 given past events.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m a Squib,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Figg. \ldblquote So you wouldn\rquote t have me registered, would you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote A Squib, eh?\rdblquote  said Fudge, eyeing her suspiciously. \ldblquote We\rquote ll be check\-ing that. You\rquote ll leave details of your parentage with my assistant, Weasley. Incidentally, can Squibs see dementors?\rdblquote  he added, looking left and right along the bench where he sat.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, we can!\rdblquote  said Mrs. Figg indignantly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Fudge looked back down at her, his eyebrows raised. \ldblquote Very well,\rdblquote  he said coolly. \ldblquote What is your story?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I had gone out to buy cat food from the corner shop at the end of Wisteria Walk, shortly after nine on the evening of the second of August,\rdblquote  gabbled Mrs. Figg at once, as though she had learned what she was saying by heart, \ldblquote when I heard a disturbance down the alley\-way between Magnolia Crescent and Wisteria Walk. On approaching the mouth of the alleyway I saw dementors running \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Running?\rdblquote  said Madam Bones sharply. \ldblquote Dementors don\rquote t run, they glide.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That\rquote s what I meant to say,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Figg quickly, patches of pink appearing in her withered cheeks. \ldblquote Gliding along the alley to\-ward what looked like two boys.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What did they look like?\rdblquote  said Madam Bones, narrowing her eyes so that the monocle\rquote s edges disappeared into her flesh.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, one was very large and the other one rather skinny \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, no,\rdblquote  said Madam Bones impatiently, \ldblquote the dementors \'85 de\-scribe them.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Figg, the pink flush creeping up her neck now. \ldblquote They were big. Big and wearing cloaks.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry felt a horrible sinking in the pit of his stomach. Whatever Mrs. Figg said to the contrary, it sounded to him as though the most she had ever seen was a picture of a dementor, and a picture could never convey the truth of what these beings were like: the eerie way they moved, hovering inches over the ground, or the rotting smell of them, or that terrible, rattling noise they made as they sucked on the surrounding air \'85 A dumpy wizard with a large black mustache in the second row leaned close to his neighbor, a frizzy-haired witch, and whispered something in her ear. She smirked and nodded.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Big and wearing cloaks,\rdblquote  repeated Madam Bones coolly, while Fudge snorted derisively. \ldblquote I see. Anything else?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Figg. \ldblquote I felt them. Everything went cold, and this was a very warm summer\rquote s night, mark you. And I felt\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 as though all happiness had gone from the world \'85 and I remembered \'85 dreadful things. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Her voice shook and died.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Madam Bones\rquote  eyes widened slightly. Harry could see red marks under her eyebrow where the monocle had dug into it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What did the dementors do?\rdblquote  she asked, and Harry felt a rush of hope.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote They went for the boys,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Figg, her voice stronger and more confident now, the pink flush ebbing away from her face. \ldblquote One of them had fallen. The other was backing away, trying to repel the dementor. That was Harry. He tried twice and produced silver vapor. On the third attempt, he produced a Patronus, which charged down the first dementor and then, with his encouragement, chased away the second from his cousin. And that\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 that was what happened,\rdblquote  Mrs. Figg finished, somewhat lamely.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Madam Bones looked down at Mrs. Figg in silence; Fudge was not looking at her at all, but fidgeting with his papers. Finally he raised his eyes and said, rather aggressively \ldblquote That\rquote s what you saw, is it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That was what happened,\rdblquote  Mrs. Figg repeated.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Very well,\rdblquote  said Fudge. \ldblquote You may go.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mrs. Figg cast a frightened look from Fudge to Dumbledore, then got up and shuffled off toward the door again. Harry heard it thud shut behind her.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Not a very convincing witness,\rdblquote  said Fudge loftily.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, I don\rquote t know,\rdblquote  said Madam Bones in her booming voice. \ldblquote She certainly described the effects of a dementor attack very accurately. And I can\rquote t imagine why she would say they were there if they weren\rquote t \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But dementors wandering into a Muggle suburb and just \i happening\lang3081\i0  \lang1033 to come across a wizard?\rdblquote  snorted Fudge. \ldblquote The odds on that must be very, very long, even Bagman wouldn\rquote t have bet \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, I don\rquote t think any of us believe the dementors were there by coincidence,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore lightly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The witch sitting to the right of Fudge with her face in shadow moved slightly, but everyone else was quite still and silent.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And what is that supposed to mean?\rdblquote  asked Fudge icily.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It means that I think they were ordered there,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I think we might have a record of it if someone had ordered a pair of dementors to go strolling through Little Whinging!\rdblquote  barked Fudge.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Not if the dementors are taking orders from someone other than the Ministry of Magic these days,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore calmly. \ldblquote I have already given you my views on this matter, Cornelius.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, you have,\rdblquote  said Fudge forcefully, \ldblquote and I have no reason to be\-lieve that your views are anything other than bilge, Dumbledore. The dementors remain in place in Azkaban and are doing everything we ask them to.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Then,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, quietly but clearly, \ldblquote we must ask our\-selves why somebody within the Ministry ordered a pair of dementors into that alleyway on the second of August.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 In the complete silence that greeted these words, the witch to the right of Fudge leaned forward so that Harry saw her for the first time.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He thought she looked just like a large, pale toad. She was rather squat with a broad, flabby face, as little neck as Uncle Vernon, and a very wide, slack mouth. Her eyes were large, round, and slightly bulging. Even the little black velvet bow perched on top of her short curly hair put him in mind of a large fly she was about to catch on a long sticky tongue.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The Chair recognizes Dolores Jane Umbridge, Senior Undersecre\-tary to the Minister,\rdblquote  said Fudge.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The witch spoke in a fluttery, girlish, high-pitched voice that took Harry aback; he had been expecting a croak.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m sure I must have misunderstood you, Professor Dumbledore,\rdblquote  she said with a simper that left her big, round eyes as cold as ever. \ldblquote So silly of me. But it sounded for a teensy moment as though you were sug\-gesting that the Ministry of Magic had ordered an attack on this boy!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She gave a silvery laugh that made the hairs on the back of Harry\rquote s neck stand up. A few other members of the Wizengamot laughed with her. It could not have been plainer that not one of them was really amused.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote If it is true that the dementors are taking orders only from the Min\-istry of Magic, and it is also true that two dementors attacked Harry and his cousin a week ago, then it follows logically that somebody at the Ministry might have ordered the attacks,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore po\-litely. \ldblquote Of course, these particular dementors may have been outside Ministry control \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote There are no dementors outside Ministry control!\rdblquote  snapped Fudge, who had turned brick red.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore inclined his head in a little bow.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Then undoubtedly the Ministry will be making a full inquiry into why two dementors were so very far from Azkaban and why they at\-tacked without authorization.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It is not for you to decide what the Ministry of Magic does or does not do, Dumbledore!\rdblquote  snapped Fudge, now a shade of magenta of which Uncle Vernon would have been proud.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Of course it isn\rquote t,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore mildly. \ldblquote I was merely ex\-pressing my confidence that this matter will not go uninvestigated.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He glanced at Madam Bones, who readjusted her monocle and stared back at him, frowning slightly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I would remind everybody that the behavior of these dementors, if indeed they are not figments of this boy\rquote s imagination, is not the subject of this hearing!\rdblquote  said Fudge. \ldblquote We are here to examine Harry Potter\rquote s offenses under the Decree for the Reasonable Restriction of Underage Sorcery!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Of course we are,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, \ldblquote but the presence of demen\-tors in that alleyway is highly relevant. Clause seven of the Decree states that magic may be used before Muggles in exceptional circum\-stances, and as those exceptional circumstances include situations that threaten the life of the wizard or witch himself, or witches, wizards, or Muggles present at the time of the \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We are familiar with clause seven, thank you very much!\rdblquote  snarled Fudge.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Of course you are,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore courteously. \ldblquote Then we are in agreement that Harry\rquote s use of the Patronus Charm in these circum\-stances falls precisely into the category of exceptional circumstances it describes?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote If there were dementors, which I doubt \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You have heard from an eyewitness,\rdblquote  Dumbledore interrupted. \ldblquote If you still doubt her truthfulness, call her back, question her again. I am sure she would not object.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I \emdash  that \emdash  not \emdash\rdblquote  blustered Fudge, fiddling with the papers be\-fore him. \ldblquote It\rquote s \emdash  I want this over with today, Dumbledore!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But naturally, you would not care how many times you heard from a witness, if the alternative was a serious miscarriage of justice,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Serious miscarriage, my hat!\rdblquote  said Fudge at the top of his voice. \ldblquote Have you ever bothered to tot up the number of cock-and-bull sto\-ries this boy has come out with, Dumbledore, while trying to cover up his flagrant misuse of magic out of school? I suppose you\rquote ve forgotten the Hover Charm he used three years ago \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That wasn\rquote t me, it was a house-elf!\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote YOU SEE?\rdblquote  roared Fudge, gesturing flamboyantly in Harry\rquote s di\-rection. \ldblquote A house-elf! In a Muggle house! I ask you \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The house-elf in question is currently in the employ of Hogwarts School,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote I can summon him here in an instant to give evidence if you wish.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I \emdash  not \emdash  I haven\rquote t got time to listen to house-elves! Anyway, that\rquote s not the only \emdash  he blew up his aunt, for God\rquote s sake!\rdblquote  Fudge shouted, banging his fist on the judge\rquote s bench and upsetting a bottle of ink.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And you very kindly did not press charges on that occasion, ac\-cepting, I presume, that even the best wizards cannot always control their emotions,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore calmly, as Fudge attempted to scrub the ink off his notes.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And I haven\rquote t even started on what he gets up to at school \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  but as the Ministry has no authority to punish Hogwarts students for misdemeanors at school, Harry\rquote s behavior there is not rel\-evant to this inquiry,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, politely as ever, but now with a suggestion of coolness behind his words.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oho!\rdblquote  said Fudge. \ldblquote Not our business what he does at school, eh? You think so?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The Ministry does not have the power to expel Hogwarts stu\-dents, Cornelius, as I reminded you on the night of the second of August,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote Nor does it have the right to confiscate wands until charges have been successfully proven, again, as I re\-minded you on the night of the second of August. In your admirable haste to ensure that the law is upheld, you appear, inadvertently I am sure, to have overlooked a few laws yourself.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Laws can be changed,\rdblquote  said Fudge savagely.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Of course they can,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, inclining his head. \ldblquote And you certainly seem to be making many changes, Cornelius. Why, in the few short weeks since I was asked to leave the Wizengamot, it has already become the practice to hold a full criminal trial to deal with a simple matter of underage magic!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A few of the wizards above them shifted uncomfortably in their seats. Fudge turned a slightly deeper shade of puce. The toadlike witch on his right, however, merely gazed at Dumbledore, her face quite expressionless.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote As far as I am aware, however,\rdblquote  Dumbledore continued, \ldblquote there is no law yet in place that says this court\rquote s job is to punish Harry for every bit of magic he has ever performed. He has been charged with a specific offense and he has presented his defense. All he and I can do now is to await your verdict.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore put his fingertips together again and said no more. Fudge glared at him, evidently incensed. Harry glanced sideways at Dumbledore, seeking reassurance; he was not at all sure that Dumble\-dore was right in telling the Wizengamot, in effect, that it was about time they made a decision. Again, however, Dumbledore seemed oblivious to Harry\rquote s attempt to catch his eye. He continued to look up at the benches where the entire Wizengamot had fallen into urgent, whispered conversations.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry looked at his feet. His heart, which seemed to have swollen to an unnatural size, was thumping loudly under his ribs. He had ex\-pected the hearing to last longer than this. He was not at all sure that he had made a good impression. He had not really said very much. He ought to have explained more fully about the dementors, about how he had fallen over, about how both he and Dudley had nearly been kissed. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Twice he looked up at Fudge and opened his mouth to speak, but his swollen heart was now constricting his air passages and both times he merely took a deep breath and looked back at his shoes.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Then the whispering stopped. Harry wanted to look up at the judges, but found that it was really much, much easier to keep exam\-ining his laces.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Those in favor of clearing the accused of all charges?\rdblquote  said Madam Bones\rquote s booming voice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry\rquote s head jerked upward. There were hands in the air, many of them \'85 more than half! Breathing very fast, he tried to count, but before he could finish Madam Bones had said, \ldblquote And those in favor of conviction?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Fudge raised his hand; so did half a dozen others, including the witch on his right and the heavily mustached wizard and the frizzy-haired witch in the second row.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Fudge glanced around at them all, looking as though there was something large stuck in his throat, then lowered his own hand. He took two deep breaths and then said, in a voice distorted by sup\-pressed rage, \ldblquote Very well, very well\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 cleared of all charges.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Excellent,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore briskly, springing to his feet, pulling out his wand, and causing the two chintz armchairs to vanish. \ldblquote Well, I must be getting along. Good day to you all.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And without looking once at Harry, he swept from the dungeon.\lang3081\par
