Dumbledore\rquote s abrupt departure took Harry completely by sur\-prise. He remained sitting where he was in the chained chair, struggling with his feelings of shock and relief. The Wizengamot were all getting to their feet, talking, and gathering up their papers and packing them away. Harry stood up. Nobody seemed to be paying him the slightest bit of attention except the toadlike witch on Fudge\rquote s right, who was now gazing down at him instead of at Dumbledore. Ig\-noring her, he tried to catch Fudge\rquote s eye, or Madam Bones\rquote s, wanting to ask whether he was free to go, but Fudge seemed quite determined not to notice Harry, and Madam Bones was busy with her briefcase, so he took a few tentative steps toward the exit and when nobody called him back, broke into a very fast walk.\par
He took the last few steps at a run, wrenched open the door, and al\-most collided with Mr. Weasley, who was standing right outside, looking pale and apprehensive.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Dumbledore didn\rquote t say \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Cleared,\rdblquote  Harry said, pulling the door closed behind him, \ldblquote of all charges!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Beaming, Mr. Weasley seized Harry by the shoulders.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry, that\rquote s wonderful! Well, of course, they couldn\rquote t have found you guilty, not on the evidence, but even so, I can\rquote t pretend I wasn\rquote t \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But Mr. Weasley broke off, because the courtroom door had just opened again. The Wizengamot were filing out.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Merlin\rquote s beard,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley wonderingly, pulling Harry aside to let them all pass, \ldblquote you were tried by the full court?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I think so,\rdblquote  said Harry quietly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 One or two of the passing wizards nodded to Harry as they passed and a few, including Madam Bones, said, \ldblquote Morning, Arthur,\rdblquote  to Mr. Weasley, but most averted their eyes. Cornelius Fudge and the toad\-like witch were almost the last to leave the dungeon. Fudge acted as though Mr. Weasley and Harry were part of the wall, but again, the witch looked almost appraisingly at Harry as she passed. Last of all to pass was Percy. Like Fudge, he completely ignored his father and Harry; he marched past clutching a large roll of parchment and a handful of spare quills, his back rigid and his nose in the air. The lines around Mr. Weasley\rquote s mouth tightened slightly, but other than this he gave no sign that he had noticed his third son.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m going to take you straight back so you can tell the others the good news,\rdblquote  he said, beckoning Harry forward as Percy\rquote s heels disap\-peared up the stairs to the ninth level. I\rquote ll drop you off on the way to that toilet in Bethnal Green. Come on. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So what will you have to do about the toilet?\rdblquote  Harry asked, grin\-ning. Everything suddenly seemed five times funnier than usual. It was starting to sink in: He was cleared, \i he was going back to Hogwarts.\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, it\rquote s a simple enough anti-jinx,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley as they mounted the stairs, \ldblquote but it\rquote s not so much having to repair the damage, it\rquote s more the attitude behind the vandalism, Harry. Muggle-baiting might strike some wizards as funny, but it\rquote s an expression of some\-thing much deeper and nastier, and I for one \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mr. Weasley broke off in mid-sentence. They had just reached the ninth-level corridor, and Cornelius Fudge was standing a few feet away from them, talking quietly to a tall man with sleek blond hair and a pointed, pale face.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The second man turned at the sound of their footsteps. He too broke off in mid-conversation, his cold gray eyes narrowed and fixed upon Harry\rquote s face.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, well, well\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 Patronus Potter,\rdblquote  said Lucius Malfoy coolly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry felt winded, as though he had just walked into something heavy. He had last seen those cool gray eyes through slits in a Death Eater\rquote s hood, and last heard that man\rquote s voice jeering in a dark grave\-yard while Lord Voldemort tortured him. He could not believe that Lucius Malfoy dared look him in the face; he could not believe that he was here, in the Ministry of Magic, or that Cornelius Fudge was talk\-ing to him, when Harry had told Fudge mere weeks ago that Malfoy was a Death Eater.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The Minister was just telling me about your lucky escape, Potter,\rdblquote  drawled Mr. Malfoy. \ldblquote Quite astonishing, the way you continue to wriggle out of very tight holes. \'85 \i Snakelike,\i0  in fact\lang3081  \lang1033\'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mr. Weasley gripped Harry\rquote s shoulder in warning.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah,\rdblquote  said Harry, \ldblquote yeah, I\rquote m good at escaping. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Lucius Malfoy raised his eyes to Mr. Weasley\rquote s face.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And Arthur Weasley too! What are you doing here, Arthur?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I work here,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley shortly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Not \i here,\i0  surely?\rdblquote  said Mr. Malfoy, raising his eyebrows and glanc\-ing toward the door over Mr. Weasley\rquote s shoulder. \ldblquote I thought you were up on the second floor. \'85 Don\rquote t you do something that involves sneaking Muggle artifacts home and bewitching them?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley curtly, his fingers now biting into Harry\rquote s shoulder.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What are \i you\i0  doing here anyway?\rdblquote  Harry asked Lucius Malfoy.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t think private matters between myself and the Minister are any concern of yours, Potter,\rdblquote  said Malfoy, smoothing the front of his\lang3081  \lang1033 robes; Harry distinctly heard the gentle clinking of what sounded like a full pocket of gold. \ldblquote Really, just because you are Dumbledore\rquote s fa\-vorite boy, you must not expect the same indulgence from the rest of us. \'85 Shall we go up to your office, then, Minister?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Certainly,\rdblquote  said Fudge, turning his back on Harry and Mr. Weasley. \ldblquote This way, Lucius.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They strode off together, talking in low voices. Mr. Weasley did not let go of Harry\rquote s shoulder until they had disappeared into the lift.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Why wasn\rquote t he waiting outside Fudge\rquote s office if they\rquote ve got busi\-ness to do together?\rdblquote  Harry burst out furiously. \ldblquote What was he doing down here?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Trying to sneak down to the courtroom, if you ask me,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, looking extremely agitated as he glanced over his shoulder as though making sure they could not be overheard. \ldblquote Trying to find out whether you\rquote d been expelled or not. I\rquote ll leave a note for Dumbledore when I drop you off, he ought to know Malfoy\rquote s been talking to Fudge again.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What private business have they got together anyway?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Gold, I expect,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley angrily. \ldblquote Malfoy\rquote s been giving generously to all sorts of things for years. \'85 Gets him in with the right people \'85 then he can ask favors \'85 delay laws he doesn\rquote t want passed \'85 Oh, he\rquote s very well connected, Lucius Malfoy. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The lift arrived; it was empty except for a flock of memos that flapped around Mr. Weasley\rquote s head as he pressed the button for the Atrium and the doors clanged shut; he waved them away irritably.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Mr. Weasley,\rdblquote  said Harry slowly, \ldblquote if Fudge is meeting Death Eaters like Malfoy, if he\rquote s seeing them alone, how do we know they haven\rquote t put the Imperius Curse on him?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Don\rquote t think it hadn\rquote t occurred to us, Harry,\rdblquote  muttered Mr. Weasley. \ldblquote But Dumbledore thinks Fudge is acting of his own accord at the moment \emdash  which, as Dumbledore says, is not a lot of comfort. \'85 Best not talk about it anymore just now, Harry. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The doors slid open and they stepped out into the now almost-deserted Atrium. Eric the security man was hidden behind his \i Daily Prophet\i0  again. They had walked straight past the golden fountain be\-fore Harry remembered.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Wait. \'85\rdblquote  he told Mr. Weasley, and pulling his money bag from his pocket, he turned back to the fountain.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He looked up into the handsome wizard\rquote s face, but up close, Harry thought he looked rather weak and foolish. The witch was wearing a vapid smile like a beauty contestant, and from what Harry knew of goblins and centaurs, they were most unlikely to be caught staring this soppily at humans of any description. Only the house-elf\rquote s attitude of creeping servility looked convincing. With a grin at the thought of what Hermione would say if she could see the statue of the elf, Harry turned his money bag upside down and emptied not just ten Galleons, but the whole contents into the pool at the statues\rquote  feet.\lang3081\par
