Harry was the first to awake in his dormitory next morning. He lay for a moment watching dust swirl in the chink of sunlight falling through the gap in his four-poster\rquote s hangings and sa\-vored the thought that it was Saturday. The first week of term seemed to have dragged on forever, like one gigantic History of Magic lesson.\par
Judging by the sleepy silence and the freshly minted look of that beam of sunlight, it was just after daybreak. He pulled open the cur\-tains around his bed, got up, and started to dress. The only sound apart from the distant twittering of birds was the slow, deep breathing of his fellow Gryffindors. He opened his schoolbag carefully, pulled out parchment and quill, and headed out of the dormitory for the common room.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Making straight for his favorite squashy old armchair beside the now extinct fire, Harry settled himself down comfortably and un\-rolled his parchment while looking around the room. The detritus of crumpled-up bits of parchment, old Gobstones, empty ingredient jars, and candy wrappers that usually covered the common room at the end of each day was gone, as were all Hermione\rquote s elf hats. Wondering\lang3081  \lang1033 vaguely how many elves had now been set free whether they wanted to be or not, Harry uncorked his ink bottle, dipped his quill into it, and then held it suspended an inch above the smooth yellowish sur\-face of his parchment, thinking hard. \'85 But after a minute or so he found himself staring into the empty grate, at a complete loss for what to say.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He could now appreciate how hard it had been for Ron and Hermione to write him letters over the summer. How was he sup\-posed to tell Sirius everything that had happened over the past week and pose all the questions he was burning to ask without giving po\-tential letter-thieves a lot of information he did not want them to have?\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He sat quite motionless for a while, gazing into the fireplace, then, finally coming to a decision, he dipped his quill into the ink bottle once more and set it resolutely upon the parchment.\par
\lang3081\par
\lang1033\i Dear Snuffles,\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\i Hope you\rquote re okay, the first week back here\rquote s been terrible, I\rquote m really glad it\rquote s the weekend.\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\i We\rquote ve got a new Defense Against the Dark Arts teacher, Pro\-fessor Umbridge. She\rquote s nearly as nice as your mum. I\rquote m writing because that thing I wrote to you about last summer happened again last night when I was doing a detention with Umbridge.\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\i We\rquote re all missing our biggest friend, we hope he\rquote ll be back soon.\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\i Please write back quickly.\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\i Best,\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\i Harry\par
\i0\par
Harry reread this letter several times, trying to see it from the point of view of an outsider. He could not see how they would know what he was talking about \emdash  or who he was talking to \emdash  just from reading\lang3081  \lang1033 this letter. He did hope Sirius would pick up the hint about Hagrid and tell them when he might be back: Harry did not want to ask di\-rectly in case it drew too much attention to what Hagrid might be up to while he was not at Hogwarts.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Considering it was a very short letter it had taken a long time to write; sunlight had crept halfway across the room while he had been working on it, and he could now hear distant sounds of movement from the dormitories above. Sealing the parchment carefully he climbed through the portrait hole and headed off for the Owlery.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I would \i not\i0  go that way if I were you,\rdblquote  said Nearly Headless Nick, drifting disconcertingly through a wall just ahead of him as he walked down the passage. \ldblquote Peeves is planning an amusing joke on the next person to pass the bust of Paracelsus halfway down the corridor.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Does it involve Paracelsus falling on top of the person\rquote s head?\rdblquote  asked Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Funnily enough, it \i does,\i0\rdblquote  said Nearly Headless Nick in a bored voice. \ldblquote Subtlety has never been Peeves\rquote s strong point. I\rquote m off to try and find the Bloody Baron. \'85 He might be able to put a stop to it. \'85 See you, Harry. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, \rquote bye,\rdblquote  said Harry and instead of turning right, he turned left, taking a longer but safer route up to the Owlery. His spirits rose as he walked past window after window showing brilliantly blue sky; he had training later, he would be back on the Quidditch pitch at last \emdash\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Something brushed his ankles. He looked down and saw the care\-taker\rquote s skeletal gray cat, Mrs. Norris, slinking past him. She turned lamplike yellow eyes upon him for a moment before disappearing be\-hind a statue of Wilfred the Wistful.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m not doing anything wrong,\rdblquote  Harry called after her. She had the unmistakable air of a cat that was off to report to her boss, yet Harry could not see why; he was perfectly entitled to walk up to the Owlery on a Saturday morning.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The sun was high in the sky now and when Harry entered the\lang3081  \lang1033 Owlery the glassless windows dazzled his eyes; thick silvery beams of sunlight crisscrossed the circular room in which hundreds of owls nes\-tled on rafters, a little restless in the early morning light, some clearly just returned from hunting. The straw-covered floor crunched a little as he stepped across tiny animal bones, craning his neck for a sight of Hedwig.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote There you are,\rdblquote  he said, spotting her somewhere near the very top of the vaulted ceiling. \ldblquote Get down here, I\rquote ve got a letter for you.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 With a low hoot she stretched her great white wings and soared down onto his shoulder.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Right, I know this says \lquote Snuffles\rquote  on the outside,\rdblquote  he told her, giv\-ing her the letter to clasp in her beak and, without knowing exactly why, whispering, \ldblquote but it\rquote s for Sirius, okay?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She blinked her amber eyes once and he took that to mean that she understood.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Safe flight, then,\rdblquote  said Harry and he carried her to one of the win\-dows; with a moment\rquote s pressure on his arm Hedwig took off into the blindingly bright sky. He watched her until she became a tiny black speck and vanished, then switched his gaze to Hagrid\rquote s hut, clearly vis\-ible from this window, and just as clearly uninhabited, the chimney smokeless, the curtains drawn.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The treetops of the Forbidden Forest swayed in a light breeze. Harry watched them, savoring the fresh air on his face, thinking about Quidditch later \'85 and then he saw it. A great, reptilian winged horse, just like the ones pulling the Hogwarts carriages, with leathery black wings spread wide like a pterodactyl\rquote s, rose up out of the trees like a grotesque, giant bird. It soared in a great circle and then plunged once more into the trees. The whole thing had happened so quickly Harry could hardly believe what he had seen, except that his heart was hammering madly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The Owlery door opened behind him. He leapt in shock, and turn\-ing quickly, saw Cho Chang holding a letter and a parcel in her hands.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hi,\rdblquote  said Harry automatically.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh \'85 hi,\rdblquote  she said breathlessly. \ldblquote I didn\rquote t think anyone would be up here this early. \'85 I only remembered five minutes ago, it\rquote s my mum\rquote s birthday.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She held up the parcel.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Right,\rdblquote  said Harry. His brain seemed to have jammed. He wanted to say something funny and interesting, but the memory of that terri\-ble winged horse was fresh in his mind.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Nice day,\rdblquote  he said, gesturing to the windows. His insides seemed to shrivel with embarrassment. The weather. He was talking about the \i weather. \'85\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah,\rdblquote  said Cho, looking around for a suitable owl. \ldblquote Good Quid\-ditch conditions. I haven\rquote t been out all week, have you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Cho had selected one of the school barn owls. She coaxed it down onto her arm where it held out an obliging leg so that she could attach the parcel.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hey, has Gryffindor got a new Keeper yet?\rdblquote  she asked.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote It\rquote s my friend Ron Weasley, d\rquote you know him?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The Tornado-hater?\rdblquote  said Cho rather coolly. \ldblquote Is he any good?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah,\rdblquote  said Harry, \ldblquote I think so. I didn\rquote t see his tryout, though, I was in detention.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Cho looked up, the parcel only half-attached to the owl\rquote s legs.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That Umbridge woman\rquote s foul,\rdblquote  she said in a low voice. \ldblquote Putting you in detention just because you told the truth about how \emdash  how \emdash  how he died. Everyone heard about it, it was all over the school. You were really brave standing up to her like that.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry\rquote s insides reinflated so rapidly he felt as though he might ac\-tually float a few inches off the dropping-strewn floor. Who cared about a stupid flying horse, Cho thought he had been really brave. \'85 For a moment he considered accidentally-on-purpose showing her his cut hand as he helped her tie her parcel onto her owl. \'85 But the very\lang3081  \lang1033 instant that this thrilling thought occurred, the Owlery door opened again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Filch, the caretaker, came wheezing into the room. There were pur\-ple patches on his sunken, veined cheeks, his jowls were aquiver and his thin gray hair disheveled; he had obviously run here. Mrs. Norris came trotting at his heels, gazing up at the owls overhead and mewing hungrily. There was a restless shifting of wings from above, and a large brown owl snapped his beak in a menacing fashion.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Aha!\rdblquote  said Filch, taking a flat-footed step toward Harry, his pouchy cheeks trembling with anger. \ldblquote I\rquote ve had a tip-off that you are intending to place a massive order for Dungbombs!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry folded his arms and stared at the caretaker.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Who told you I was ordering Dungbombs?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Cho was looking from Harry to Filch, also frowning; the barn owl on her arm, tired of standing on one leg, gave an admonitory hoot but she ignored it.\lang3081\par
