\lang1033\ldblquote You saw him \emdash  ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That\rquote s right, I saw him,\rdblquote  she said fiercely.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a moment\rquote s pause in which Filch glared at Cho and Cho\lang3081  \lang1033 glared right back, then the caretaker turned and shuffled back toward the door. He stopped with his hand on the handle and looked back at Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote If I get so much as a whiff of a Dungbomb \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He stumped off down the stairs. Mrs. Norris cast a last longing look at the owls and followed him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry and Cho looked at each other.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Thanks,\rdblquote  Harry said.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No problem,\rdblquote  said Cho, finally fixing the parcel to the barn owl\rquote s other leg, her face slightly pink. \ldblquote You \i weren\rquote t\i0  ordering Dungbombs, were you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I wonder why he thought you were, then?\rdblquote  she said, as she carried the owl to the window.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry shrugged; he was quite as mystified by that as she was, though, oddly, it was not bothering him very much at the moment.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They left the Owlery together. At the entrance of a corridor that led toward the west wing of the castle, Cho said, \ldblquote I\rquote m going this way. Well, I\rquote ll\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 I\rquote ll see you around, Harry.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah \'85 see you.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She smiled at him and departed. He walked on, feeling quietly elated. He had managed to have an entire conversation with her and not embarrassed himself once. \'85 \i You were really brave standing up to her like that. \'85 \i0 She had called him brave. \'85 She did not hate him for being alive. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Of course, she had preferred Cedric, he knew that. \'85 Though if he\rquote d only asked her to the ball before Cedric had, things might have turned out differently. \'85 She had seemed sincerely sorry that she had to refuse when Harry had asked her. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Morning,\rdblquote  Harry said brightly to Ron and Hermione, joining them at the Gryffindor table in the Great Hall.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What are you looking so pleased about?\rdblquote  said Ron, eyeing Harry in surprise.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Erm \'85 Quidditch later,\rdblquote  said Harry happily, pulling a large plat\-ter of bacon and eggs toward him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh \'85 yeah \'85\rdblquote  said Ron. He put down the bit of toast he was eating and took a large swig of pumpkin juice. Then he said, \ldblquote Listen \'85 you don\rquote t fancy going out a bit earlier with me, do you? Just to \emdash  er \emdash  give me some practice before training? So I can, you know, get my eye in a bit\lang3081  \lang1033\'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, okay,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Look, I don\rquote t think you should,\rdblquote  said Hermione seriously, \ldblquote you\rquote re both really behind on homework as it \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But she broke off; the morning post was arriving and, as usual, the \i Daily Prophet\i0  was soaring toward her in the beak of a screech owl, which landed perilously close to the sugar bowl and held out a leg; Hermione pushed a Knut into its leather pouch, took the newspaper, and scanned the front page critically as the owl took off again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Anything interesting?\rdblquote  said Ron; Harry smiled \emdash  he knew Ron was keen to get her off the subject of homework.\lang3081\par
