Hermione made no mention of Harry giving Defense Against\lang3081  \lang1033 the Dark Arts lessons for two whole weeks after her original\lang3081  \lang1033 suggestion. Harry\rquote s detentions with Umbridge were finally over (he doubted whether the words now etched on the back of his hand would ever fade entirely); Ron had had four more Quidditch practices and not been shouted at during the last two; and all three of them had managed to vanish their mice in Transfiguration (Hermione had actu\-ally progressed to vanishing kittens), before the subject was broached again, on a wild, blustery evening at the end of September, when the three of them were sitting in the library, looking up potion ingredients for Snape.\par
\ldblquote I was wondering,\rdblquote  Hermione said suddenly, \ldblquote whether you\rquote d thought any more about Defense Against the Dark Arts, Harry.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \rquote Course I have,\rdblquote  said Harry grumpily. \ldblquote Can\rquote t forget it, can we, with that hag teaching us \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I meant the idea Ron and I had\rdblquote  \emdash  Ron cast her an alarmed, threatening kind of look; she frowned at him \emdash  \ldblquote oh, all right, the idea \i I\lang3081\i0  \lang1033 had, then \emdash  about you teaching us.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry did not answer at once. He pretended to be perusing a page of \i Asiatic Anti-Venoms,\i0  because he did not want to say what was in his mind.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The fact was that he had given the matter a great deal of thought over the past fortnight. Sometimes it seemed an insane idea, just as it had on the night Hermione had proposed it, but at others, he had found himself thinking about the spells that had served him best in his various encounters with Dark creatures and Death Eaters \emdash  found himself, in fact, subconsciously planning lessons. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well,\rdblquote  he said slowly, when he could not pretend to find Asiatic anti-venoms interesting much longer, \ldblquote yeah, I \emdash  I\rquote ve thought about it a bit.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And?\rdblquote  said Hermione eagerly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I dunno,\rdblquote  said Harry, playing for time. He looked up at Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I thought it was a good idea from the start,\rdblquote  said Ron, who seemed keener to join in this conversation now that he was sure that Harry was not going to start shouting again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry shifted uncomfortably in his chair.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You did listen to what I said about a load of it being luck, didn\rquote t you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, Harry,\rdblquote  said Hermione gently, \ldblquote but all the same, there\rquote s no point pretending that you\rquote re not good at Defense Against the Dark Arts, because you are. You were the only person last year who could throw off the Imperius Curse completely, you can produce a Patronus, you can do all sorts of stuff that full-grown wizards can\rquote t, Viktor al\-ways said \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron looked around at her so fast he appeared to crick his neck; rub\-bing it, he said, \ldblquote Yeah? What did Vicky say?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ho ho,\rdblquote  said Hermione in a bored voice. \ldblquote He said Harry knew how to do stuff even he didn\rquote t, and he was in the final year at Durmstrang.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron was looking at Hermione suspiciously.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote re not still in contact with him, are you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So what if I am?\rdblquote  said Hermione coolly, though her face was a lit\-tle pink. \ldblquote I can have a pen pal if I \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He didn\rquote t only want to be your pen pal,\rdblquote  said Ron accusingly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione shook her head exasperatedly and, ignoring Ron, who was continuing to watch her, said to Harry, \ldblquote Well, what do you think? Will you teach us?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Just you and Ron, yeah?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well,\rdblquote  said Hermione, now looking a mite anxious again. \ldblquote Well \'85 now, don\rquote t fly off the handle again, Harry, please. \'85 But I really think you ought to teach anyone who wants to learn. I mean, we\rquote re talking about defending ourselves against V-Voldemort \emdash  oh, don\rquote t be pathetic, Ron \emdash  it doesn\rquote t seem fair if we don\rquote t offer the chance to other people.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry considered this for a moment, then said, \ldblquote Yeah, but I doubt anyone except you two would want to be taught by me. I\rquote m a nutter, remember?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, I think you might be surprised how many people would be interested in hearing what you\rquote ve got to say,\rdblquote  said Hermione seriously. \ldblquote Look,\rdblquote  she leaned toward him; Ron, who was still watching her with a frown on his face, leaned forward to listen too, \ldblquote you know the first weekend in October\rquote s a Hogsmeade weekend? How would it be if we tell anyone who\rquote s interested to meet us in the village and we can talk it over?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Why do we have to do it outside school?\rdblquote  said Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Because,\rdblquote  said Hermione, returning to the diagram of the Chinese Chomping Cabbage she was copying, \ldblquote I don\rquote t think Umbridge would be very happy if she found out what we were up to.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\par
\lang1033 Harry had been looking forward to the weekend trip into Hogs\-meade, but there was one thing worrying him. Sirius had maintained a stony silence since he had appeared in the fire at the beginning of\lang3081  \lang1033 September; Harry knew they had made him angry by saying that they did not want him to come \emdash  but he still worried from time to time that Sirius might throw caution to the winds and turn up anyway. What were they going to do if the great black dog came bounding up the street toward them in Hogsmeade, perhaps under the nose of Draco Malfoy?\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, you can\rquote t blame him for wanting to get out and about,\rdblquote  said Ron, when Harry discussed his fears with him and Hermione. \ldblquote I mean, he\rquote s been on the run for over two years, hasn\rquote t he, and I know that can\rquote t have been a laugh, but at least he was free, wasn\rquote t he? And now he\rquote s just shut up all the time with that lunatic elf.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione scowled at Ron, but otherwise ignored the slight on Kreacher.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The trouble is,\rdblquote  she said to Harry, \ldblquote until V-Voldemort \emdash  oh for heaven\rquote s \i sake,\i0  Ron \emdash  comes out into the open, Sirius is going to have to stay hidden, isn\rquote t he? I mean, the stupid Ministry isn\rquote t going to re\-alize Sirius is innocent until they accept that Dumbledore\rquote s been telling the truth about him all along. And once the fools start catch\-ing real Death Eaters again it\rquote ll be obvious Sirius isn\rquote t one \'85 I mean, he hasn\rquote t got the Mark, for one thing.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t reckon he\rquote d be stupid enough to turn up,\rdblquote  said Ron brac\-ingly. \ldblquote Dumbledore\rquote d go mad if he did and Sirius listens to Dumble\-dore even if he doesn\rquote t like what he hears.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 When Harry continued to look worried, Hermione said, \ldblquote Listen, Ron and I have been sounding out people who we thought might want to learn some proper Defense Against the Dark Arts, and there are a couple who seem interested. We\rquote ve told them to meet us in Hogsmeade.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Right,\rdblquote  said Harry vaguely, his mind still on Sirius.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Don\rquote t worry, Harry,\rdblquote  Hermione said quietly. \ldblquote You\rquote ve got enough on your plate without Sirius too.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She was quite right, of course; he was barely keeping up with his\lang3081  \lang1033 homework, though he was doing much better now that he was no longer spending every evening in detention with Umbridge. Ron was even further behind with his work than Harry, because while they both had Quidditch practices twice a week, Ron also had prefect du\-ties. However, Hermione, who was taking more subjects than either of them, had not only finished all her homework but was also finding time to knit more elf clothes. Harry had to admit that she was getting better; it was now almost always possible to distinguish between the hats and the socks.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The morning of the Hogsmeade visit dawned bright but windy. Af\-ter breakfast they queued up in front of Filch, who matched their names to the long list of students who had permission from their par\-ents or guardian to visit the village. With a slight pang, Harry re\-membered that if it hadn\rquote t been for Sirius, he would not have been going at all.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 When Harry reached Filch, the caretaker gave a great sniff as though trying to detect a whiff of something from Harry. Then he gave a curt nod that set his jowls aquiver again and Harry walked on, out onto the stone steps and the cold, sunlit day.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Er \emdash  why was Filch sniffing you?\rdblquote  asked Ron, as he, Harry, and Hermione set off at a brisk pace down the wide drive to the gates.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I suppose he was checking for the smell of Dungbombs,\rdblquote  said Harry with a small laugh. \ldblquote I forgot to tell you \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And he recounted the story of sending his letter to Sirius and Filch bursting in seconds later, demanding to see the letter. To his slight sur\-prise, Hermione found this story highly interesting, much more, in\-deed, than he did himself.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He said he was tipped off you were ordering Dungbombs? But who had tipped him off?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I dunno,\rdblquote  said Harry, shrugging. \ldblquote Maybe Malfoy, he\rquote d think it was a laugh.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They walked between the tall stone pillars topped with winged\lang3081  \lang1033 boars and turned left onto the road into the village, the wind whip\-ping their hair into their eyes.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Malfoy?\rdblquote  said Hermione, very skeptically. \ldblquote Well\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 yes \'85 maybe \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And she remained deep in thought all the way into the outskirts of Hogsmeade.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Where are we going anyway?\rdblquote  Harry asked. \ldblquote The Three Broom\-sticks?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh \emdash  no,\rdblquote  said Hermione, coming out of her reverie, \ldblquote no, it\rquote s al\-ways packed and really noisy. I\rquote ve told the others to meet us in the Hog\rquote s Head, that other pub, you know the one, it\rquote s not on the main road. I think it\rquote s a bit\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 you know \'85 \i dodgy\i0  \'85 but students don\rquote t normally go in there, so I don\rquote t think we\rquote ll be overheard.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They walked down the main street past Zonko\rquote s Joke Shop, where they were unsurprised to see Fred, George, and Lee Jordan, past the post office, from which owls issued at regular intervals, and turned up a side street at the top of which stood a small inn. A battered wooden sign hung from a rusty bracket over the door, with a picture upon it of a wild boar\rquote s severed head leaking blood onto the white cloth around it. The sign creaked in the wind as they approached. All three of them hesitated outside the door.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, come on,\rdblquote  said Hermione slightly nervously. Harry led the way inside.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It was not at all like the Three Broomsticks, whose large bar gave an impression of gleaming warmth and cleanliness. The Hog\rquote s Head bar comprised one small, dingy, and very dirty room that smelled strongly of something that might have been goats. The bay windows were so encrusted with grime that very little daylight could permeate the room, which was lit instead with the stubs of candles sitting on rough wooden tables. The floor seemed at first glance to be earthy, though as Harry stepped onto it he realized that there was stone beneath what seemed to be the accumulated filth of centuries.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry remembered Hagrid mentioning this pub in his first year: \ldblquote\i Yeh get a lot o\rquote  funny folk in the Hog\rquote s Head,\i0\rdblquote  he had said, explaining how he had won a dragons egg from a hooded stranger there. At the time Harry had wondered why Hagrid had not found it odd that the stranger kept his face hidden throughout their encounter; now he saw that keeping your face hidden was something of a fashion in the Hog\rquote s Head. There was a man at the bar whose whole head was wrapped in dirty gray bandages, though he was still managing to gulp endless glasses of some smoking, fiery substance through a slit over his mouth. Two figures shrouded in hoods sat at a table in one of the windows; Harry might have thought them dementors if they had not been talk\-ing in strong Yorkshire accents; in a shadowy corner beside the fireplace sat a witch with a thick, black veil that fell to her toes. They could just see the tip of her nose because it caused the veil to protrude slightly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t know about this, Hermione,\rdblquote  Harry muttered, as they crossed to the bar. He was looking particularly at the heavily veiled witch. \ldblquote Has it occurred to you Umbridge might be under that?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione cast an appraising eye at the veiled figure.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Umbridge is shorter than that woman,\rdblquote  she said quietly. \ldblquote And anyway, even if Umbridge \i does\i0  come in here there\rquote s nothing she can do to stop us, Harry, because I\rquote ve double- and triple-checked the school rules. We\rquote re not out-of-bounds; I specifically asked Professor Flitwick whether students were allowed to come in the Hog\rquote s Head, and he said yes, but he advised me strongly to bring our own glasses. And I\rquote ve looked up everything I can think of about study groups and homework groups and they\rquote re definitely allowed. I just don\rquote t think it\rquote s a good idea if\lang3081  \lang1033 we\lang3081  \lang1033\i parade\i0  what we\rquote re doing.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Harry dryly, \ldblquote especially as it\rquote s not exactly a homework group you\rquote re planning, is it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The barman sidled toward them out of a back room. He was a grumpy-looking old man with a great deal of long gray hair and beard. He was tall and thin and looked vaguely familiar to Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What?\rdblquote  he grunted.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Three butterbeers, please,\rdblquote  said Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The man reached beneath the counter and pulled up three very dusty, very dirty bottles, which he slammed on the bar.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Six Sickles,\rdblquote  he said.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote ll get them,\rdblquote  said Harry quickly, passing over the silver. The bar\-man\rquote s eyes traveled over Harry, resting for a fraction of a second on his scar. Then he turned away and deposited Harry\rquote s money in an ancient wooden till whose drawer slid open automatically to receive it. Harry, Ron, and Hermione retreated to the farthest table from the bar and sat down, looking around, while the man in the dirty gray bandages rapped the counter with his knuckles and received another smoking drink from the barman.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You know what?\rdblquote  Ron murmured, looking over at the bar with enthusiasm. \ldblquote We could order anything we liked in here, I bet that bloke would sell us anything, he wouldn\rquote t care. I\rquote ve always wanted to try firewhisky \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
