\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But that\rquote s \'85 that\rquote s N.E.W.T. standard, that is,\rdblquote  he said weakly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh,\rdblquote  said Hermione, trying to look modest. \ldblquote Oh \'85 well\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 yes, I suppose it is. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How come you\rquote re not in Ravenclaw?\rdblquote  he demanded, staring at Hermione with something close to wonder. \ldblquote With brains like yours?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, the Sorting Hat did seriously consider putting me in Raven\-claw during my Sorting,\rdblquote  said Hermione brightly, \ldblquote but it decided on Gryffindor in the end. So does that mean we\rquote re using the Galleons?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a murmur of assent and everybody moved forward to collect one from the basket. Harry looked sideways at Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You know what these remind me of?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, what\rquote s that?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The Death Eaters\rquote  scars. Voldemort touches one of them, and all their scars burn, and they know they\rquote ve got to join him.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 yes,\rdblquote  said Hermione quietly. \ldblquote That \i is \i0 where I got the idea \'85 but you\rquote ll notice I decided to engrave the date on bits of metal rather than on our members\rquote  skin. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah \'85 I prefer your way,\rdblquote  said Harry, grinning, as he slipped his Galleon into his pocket. \ldblquote I suppose the only danger with these is that we might accidentally spend them.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Fat chance,\rdblquote  said Ron, who was examining his own fake Galleon with a slightly mournful air. \ldblquote I haven\rquote t got any real Galleons to con\-fuse it with.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 As the first Quidditch match of the season, Gryffindor versus Slytherin, drew nearer, their D.A. meetings were put on hold because Angelina insisted on almost daily practices. The fact that the Quid\-ditch Cup had not been held for so long added considerably to the in\-terest and excitement surrounding the forthcoming game. The Ravenclaws and Hufflepuffs were taking a lively interest in the out\-come, for they, of course, would be playing both teams over the com\-ing year; and the Heads of House of the competing teams, though they attempted to disguise it under a decent pretense of sportsman\-ship, were determined to see their side\rquote s victory. Harry realized how much Professor McGonagall cared about beating Slytherin when she\lang3081  \lang1033 abstained from giving them homework in the week leading up to the match.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I think you\rquote ve got enough to be getting on with at the moment,\rdblquote  she said loftily. Nobody could quite believe their ears until she looked directly at Harry and Ron and said grimly, \ldblquote I\rquote ve become accustomed to seeing the Quidditch Cup in my study, boys, and I really don\rquote t want to have to hand it over to Professor Snape, so use the extra time to practice, won\rquote t you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Snape was no less obviously partisan: He had booked the Quid\-ditch pitch for Slytherin practice so often that the Gryffindors had difficulty getting on it to play. He was also turning a deaf ear to the many reports of Slytherin attempts to hex Gryffindor players in the corridors. When Alicia Spinnet turned up in the hospital wing with her eyebrows growing so thick and fast that they obscured her vision and obstructed her mouth, Snape insisted that she must have at\-tempted a Hair-Thickening Charm on herself and refused to listen to the fourteen eyewitnesses who insisted that they had seen the Slytherin Keeper, Miles Bletchley, hit her from behind with a jinx while she worked in the library.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry felt optimistic about Gryffindor\rquote s chances; they had, after all, never lost to Malfoy\rquote s team. Admittedly Ron was still not performing to Wood\rquote s standard, but he was working extremely hard to improve. His greatest weakness was a tendency to lose confidence when he made a blunder; if he let in one goal he became flustered and was therefore likely to miss more. On the other hand, Harry had seen Ron make some truly spectacular saves when he was on form: During one memorable practice, he had hung one-handed from his broom and kicked the Quaffle so hard away from the goal hoop that it soared the length of the pitch and through the center hoop at the other end. The rest of the team felt this save compared favorably with one made re\-cently by Barry Ryan, the Irish International Keeper, against Poland\rquote s top Chaser, Ladislaw Zamojski. Even Fred had said that Ron might\lang3081  \lang1033 yet make him and George proud, and that they were seriously consid\-ering admitting that he was related to them, something he assured Ron they had been trying to deny for four years.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The only thing really worrying Harry was how much Ron was al\-lowing the tactics of the Slytherin team to upset him before they even got onto the pitch. Harry, of course, had endured their snide com\-ments for more than four years, so whispers of, \ldblquote Hey, Potty, I heard Warrington\rquote s sworn to knock you off your broom on Saturday,\rdblquote  far from chilling his blood, made him laugh. \ldblquote Warrington\rquote s aim\rquote s so pa\-thetic I\rquote d be more worried if he was aiming for the person next to me,\rdblquote  he retorted, which made Ron and Hermione laugh and wiped the smirk off Pansy Parkinson\rquote s face.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But Ron had never endured a relentless campaign of insults, jeers, and intimidation. When Slytherins, some of them seventh years and consid\-erably larger than he was, muttered as they passed in the corridors, \ldblquote Got your bed booked in the hospital wing, Weasley?\rdblquote  he did not laugh, but turned a delicate shade of green. When Draco Malfoy imitated Ron dropping the Quaffle (which he did whenever they were within sight of each other), Ron\rquote s ears glowed red and his hands shook so badly that he was likely to drop whatever he was holding at the time too.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 October extinguished itself in a rush of howling winds and driving rain and November arrived, cold as frozen iron, with hard frosts every morning and icy drafts that bit at exposed hands and faces. The skies and the ceiling of the Great Hall turned a pale, pearly gray, the moun\-tains around Hogwarts became snowcapped, and the temperature in the castle dropped so far that many students wore their thick protec\-tive dragon skin gloves in the corridors between lessons.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The morning of the match dawned bright and cold. When Harry awoke he looked around at Ron\rquote s bed and saw him sitting bolt up\-right, his arms around his knees, staring fixedly into space.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You all right?\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron nodded but did not speak. Harry was reminded forcibly of the\lang3081  \lang1033 time that Ron had accidentally put a slug-vomiting charm on himself. He looked just as pale and sweaty as he had done then, not to men\-tion as reluctant to open his mouth.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You just need some breakfast,\rdblquote  Harry said bracingly. \ldblquote C\rquote mon.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The Great Hall was filling up fast when they arrived, the talk louder and the mood more exuberant than usual. As they passed the Slytherin table there was an upsurge of noise; Harry looked around and saw that nearly everyone there was wearing, in addition to the usual green-and-silver scarves and hats, silver badges in the shape of what seemed to be crowns. For some reason many of them waved at Ron, laughing uproariously. Harry tried to see what was written on the badges as he walked by, but he was too concerned to get Ron past their table quickly to linger long enough to read them.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They received a rousing welcome at the Gryffindor table, where everyone was wearing red and gold, but far from raising Ron\rquote s spirits the cheers seemed to sap the last of his morale; he collapsed onto the nearest bench looking as though he were facing his final meal.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I must\rquote ve been mental to do this,\rdblquote  he said in a croaky whisper. \ldblquote\i Mental.\i0\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Don\rquote t be thick,\rdblquote  said Harry firmly, passing him a choice of cereals. \ldblquote You\rquote re going to be fine. It\rquote s normal to be nervous.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m rubbish,\rdblquote  croaked Ron. \ldblquote I\rquote m lousy. I can\rquote t play to save my life. What was I thinking?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Get a grip,\rdblquote  said Harry sternly. \ldblquote Look at that save you made with your foot the other day, even Fred and George said it was brilliant \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron turned a tortured face to Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That was an accident,\rdblquote  he whispered miserably. \ldblquote I didn\rquote t mean to do it \emdash  I slipped off my broom when none of you were looking and I was trying to get back on and I kicked the Quaffle by accident.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well,\rdblquote  said Harry, recovering quickly from this unpleasant sur\-prise, \ldblquote a few more accidents like that and the game\rquote s in the bag, isn\rquote t it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione and Ginny sat down opposite them wearing red-and-gold scarves, gloves, and rosettes.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How\rquote re you feeling?\rdblquote  Ginny asked Ron, who was now staring into the dregs of milk at the bottom of his empty cereal bowl as though se\-riously considering attempting to drown himself in them.\lang3081\par
