\lang1033\ldblquote Well, I tried,\rdblquote  she said dully, sinking into a chair beside Harry. She pulled out her wand and gave it a complicated little wave so that hot air streamed out of the tip; she then pointed this at her robes, which began to steam as they dried out. \ldblquote He wasn\rquote t even there when I ar\-rived, I was knocking for at least half an hour. And then he came stumping out of the forest \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry groaned. The Forbidden Forest was teeming with the kind of creatures most likely to get Hagrid the sack. \ldblquote What\rquote s he keeping in there? Did he say?\rdblquote  asked Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Hermione miserably. \ldblquote He says he wants them to be a surprise. I tried to explain about Umbridge, but he just doesn\rquote t get it. He kept saying nobody in their right mind would rather study knarls than chimaeras \emdash  oh I don\rquote t think he\rquote s \i got\i0  a chimaera,\rdblquote  she added at the appalled look on Harry and Ron\rquote s faces, \ldblquote but that\rquote s not for lack of trying from what he said about how hard it is to get eggs. \'85 I don\rquote t know how many times I told him he\rquote d be better off following Grubbly-Plank\rquote s plan, I honestly don\rquote t think he listened to half of what I said. He\rquote s in a bit of a funny mood, you know. He still won\rquote t say how he got all those injuries. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hagrid\rquote s reappearance at the staff table at breakfast next day was not greeted by enthusiasm from all students. Some, like Fred, George, and Lee, roared with delight and sprinted up the aisle between the Gryffindor and Hufflepuff tables to wring Hagrid\rquote s enormous hand; others, like Parvati and Lavender, exchanged gloomy looks and shook their heads. Harry knew that many of them preferred Professor Grubbly-Plank\rquote s lessons, and the worst of it was that a very small, un\-biased part of him knew that they had good reason: Grubbly-Plank\rquote s idea of an interesting class was not one where there was a risk that somebody might have their head ripped off.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It was with a certain amount of apprehension that Harry, Ron, and Hermione headed down to Hagrid\rquote s on Tuesday, heavily muffled against the cold. Harry was worried, not only about what Hagrid\lang3081  \lang1033 might have decided to teach them, but also about how the rest of the class, particularly Malfoy and his cronies, would behave if Umbridge was watching them.\lang3081\par
