Harry was so relieved that she was taking him seriously that he did not hesitate, but jumped out of bed at once, pulled on his dressing gown, and pushed his glasses back onto his nose.\par
\ldblquote Weasley, you ought to come too,\rdblquote  said Professor McGonagall.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They followed Professor McGonagall past the silent figures of Neville, Dean, and Seamus, out of the dormitory, down the spiral stairs into the common room, through the portrait hole, and off along the Fat Lady\rquote s moonlit corridor. Harry felt as though the panic inside him might spill over at any moment; he wanted to run, to yell for Dumbledore. Mr. Weasley was bleeding as they walked along so se\-dately, and what if those fangs (Harry tried hard not to think \ldblquote my fangs\rdblquote ) had been poisonous? They passed Mrs. Norris, who turned her lamplike eyes upon them and hissed faintly, but Professor McGona\-gall said, \ldblquote Shoo!\rdblquote  Mrs. Norris slunk away into the shadows, and in a few minutes they had reached the stone gargoyle guarding the en\-trance to Dumbledore\rquote s office.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Fizzing Whizbee,\rdblquote  said Professor McGonagall.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The gargoyle sprang to life and leapt aside; the wall behind it split in two to reveal a stone staircase that was moving continuously up\-ward like a spiral escalator. The three of them stepped onto the mov\-ing stairs; the wall closed behind them with a thud, and they were moving upward in tight circles until they reached the highly polished oak door with the brass knocker shaped like a griffin.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Though it was now well past midnight, there were voices coming from inside the room, a positive babble of them. It sounded as though Dumbledore was entertaining at least a dozen people.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Professor McGonagall rapped three times with the griffin knocker, and the voices ceased abruptly as though someone had switched them all off. The door opened of its own accord and Professor McGonagall led Harry and Ron inside.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The room was in half darkness; the strange silver instruments standing on tables were silent and still rather than whirring and emit\-ting puffs of smoke as they usually did. The portraits of old headmas\-ters and headmistresses covering the walls were all snoozing in their frames. Behind the door, a magnificent red-and-gold bird the size of a swan dozed on its perch with its head under its wing.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, it\rquote s you, Professor McGonagall\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 and \'85 \i ah.\i0\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore was sitting in a high-backed chair behind his desk; he leaned forward into the pool of candlelight illuminating the papers laid out before him. He was wearing a magnificently embroidered purple-and-gold dressing gown over a snowy-white nightshirt, but seemed wide awake, his penetrating light-blue eyes fixed intently upon Professor McGonagall.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Professor Dumbledore, Potter has had a \'85 well, a nightmare,\rdblquote  said Professor McGonagall. \ldblquote He says \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It wasn\rquote t a nightmare,\rdblquote  said Harry quickly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Professor McGonagall looked around at Harry, frowning slightly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Very well, then, Potter, you tell the headmaster about it.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I \'85 well, I \i was\i0  asleep. \'85\rdblquote  said Harry and even in his terror and\lang3081  \lang1033 his desperation to make Dumbledore understand he felt slightly irri\-tated that the headmaster was not looking at him, but examining his own interlocked fingers. \ldblquote But it wasn\rquote t an ordinary dream \'85 it was real. \'85 I saw it happen. \'85\rdblquote  He took a deep breath, \ldblquote Ron\rquote s dad \emdash  Mr. Weasley \emdash  has been attacked by a giant snake.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The words seemed to reverberate in the air after he had said them, slightly ridiculous, even comic. There was a pause in which Dumble\-dore leaned back and stared meditatively at the ceiling. Ron looked from Harry to Dumbledore, white-faced and shocked.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How did you see this?\rdblquote  Dumbledore asked quietly, still not look\-ing at Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 I don\rquote t know,\rdblquote  said Harry, rather angrily \emdash  what did it matter? \ldblquote Inside my head, I suppose \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You misunderstand me,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, still in the same calm tone. \ldblquote I mean \'85 can you remember \emdash  er \emdash  where you were posi\-tioned as you watched this attack happen? Were you perhaps standing beside the victim, or else looking down on the scene from above?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 This was such a curious question that Harry gaped at Dumbledore; it was almost as though he knew \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I was the snake,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote I saw it all from the snake\rquote s point of view. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Nobody else spoke for a moment, then Dumbledore, now looking at Ron, who was still whey-faced, said in a new and sharper voice, \ldblquote Is Arthur seriously injured?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Yes,\i0\rdblquote  said Harry emphatically \emdash  why were they all so slow on the uptake, did they not realize how much a person bled when fangs that long pierced their side? And why could Dumbledore not do him the courtesy of looking at him?\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But Dumbledore stood up so quickly that Harry jumped, and ad\-dressed one of the old portraits hanging very near the ceiling.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Everard?\rdblquote  he said sharply. \ldblquote And you too, Dilys!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A\i  \i0 sallow-faced wizard with short, black bangs and an elderly witch\lang3081  \lang1033 with long silver ringlets in the frame beside him, both of whom seemed to have been in the deepest of sleeps, opened their eyes immediately.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You were listening?\rdblquote  said Dumbledore.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The wizard nodded, the witch said, \ldblquote Naturally.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The man has red hair and glasses,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote Everard, you will need to raise the alarm, make sure he is found by the right people \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Both nodded and moved sideways out of their frames, but instead of emerging in neighboring pictures (as usually happened at Hog\-warts), neither reappeared; one frame now contained nothing but a backdrop of dark curtain, the other a handsome leather armchair. Harry noticed that many of the other headmasters and mistresses on the walls, though snoring and drooling most convincingly, kept sneaking peeks at him under their eyelids, and he suddenly under\-stood who had been talking when they had knocked.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Everard and Dilys were two of Hogwarts\rquote s most celebrated Heads,\rdblquote  Dumbledore said, now sweeping around Harry, Ron, and Professor McGonagall and approaching the magnificent sleeping bird on his perch beside the door. \ldblquote Their renown is such that both have portraits hanging in other important Wizarding institutions. As they are free to move between their own portraits they can tell us what may be hap\-pening elsewhere. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But Mr. Weasley could be anywhere!\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Please sit down, all three of you,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, as though Harry had not spoken. \ldblquote Everard and Dilys may not be back for several minutes. \'85 Professor McGonagall, if you could draw up extra chairs \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Professor McGonagall pulled her wand from the pocket of her dressing gown and waved it; three chairs appeared out of thin air, straight-backed and wooden, quite unlike the comfortable chintz armchairs that Dumbledore had conjured back at Harry\rquote s hearing. Harry sat down, watching Dumbledore over his shoulder. Dumble\-dore was now stroking Fawkes\rquote s plumed golden head with one finger. The phoenix awoke immediately. He stretched his beautiful head high and observed Dumbledore through bright, dark eyes.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We will need,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore very quietly to the bird, \ldblquote a warning.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a flash of fire and the phoenix had gone.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore now swooped down upon one of the fragile silver in\-struments whose function Harry had never known, carried it over to his desk, sat down facing them again, and tapped it gently with the tip of his wand.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The instrument tinkled into life at once with rhythmic clinking noises. Tiny puffs of pale green smoke issued from the minuscule sil\-ver tube at the top. Dumbledore watched the smoke closely, his brow furrowed, and after a few seconds, the tiny puffs became a steady stream of smoke that thickened and coiled in the air. \'85 A serpent\rquote s head grew out of the end of it, opening its mouth wide. Harry won\-dered whether the instrument was confirming his story: He looked eagerly at Dumbledore for a sign that he was right, but Dumbledore did not look up.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Naturally, naturally,\rdblquote  murmured Dumbledore apparently to him\-self, still observing the stream of smoke without the slightest sign of surprise. \ldblquote But in essence divided?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry could make neither head nor tail of this question. The smoke serpent, however, split itself instantly into two snakes, both coiling and undulating in the dark air. With a look of grim satisfaction Dumbledore gave the instrument another gentle tap with his wand: The clinking noise slowed and died, and the smoke serpents grew faint, became a formless haze, and vanished.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore replaced the instrument upon its spindly little table; Harry saw many of the old headmasters in the portraits follow him with their eyes, then, realizing that Harry was watching them, hastily\lang3081  \lang1033 pretend to be sleeping again. Harry wanted to ask what the strange sil\-ver instrument was for, but before he could do so, there was a shout from the top of the wall to their right; the wizard called Everard had reappeared in his portrait, panting slightly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Dumbledore!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What news?\rdblquote  said Dumbledore at once.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I yelled until someone came running,\rdblquote  said the wizard, who was mopping his brow on the curtain behind him, \ldblquote said I\rquote d heard some\-thing moving downstairs \emdash  they weren\rquote t sure whether to believe me but went down to check \emdash  you know there are no portraits down there to watch from. Anyway, they carried him up a few minutes later. He doesn\rquote t look good, he\rquote s covered in blood, I ran along to Elfrida Cragg\rquote s portrait to get a good view as they left \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Good,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore as Ron made a convulsive movement, \ldblquote I take it Dilys will have seen him arrive, then \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And moments later, the silver-ringletted witch had reappeared in her picture too; she sank, coughing, into her armchair and said, \ldblquote Yes, they\rquote ve taken him to St. Mungo\rquote s, Dumbledore. \'85 They carried him past under my portrait. \'85 He looks bad. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Thank you,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. He looked around at Professor McGonagall.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Minerva, I need you to go and wake the other Weasley children.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Of course. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Professor McGonagall got up and moved swiftly to the door; Harry cast a sideways glance at Ron, who was now looking terrified.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And Dumbledore \emdash  what about Molly?\rdblquote  said Professor McGona\-gall, pausing at the door.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That will be a job for Fawkes when he has finished keeping a lookout for anybody approaching,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote But she may already know \'85 that excellent clock of hers \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry knew Dumbledore was referring to the clock that told, not the time, but the whereabouts and conditions of the various Weasley\lang3081  \lang1033 family members, and with a pang he thought that Mr. Weasley\rquote s hand must, even now, be pointing at \ldblquote mortal peril.\rdblquote  But it was very late. \'85 Mrs. Weasley was probably asleep, not watching the clock. \'85 And he felt cold as he remembered Mrs. Weasley\rquote s boggart turning into Mr. Weasley\rquote s lifeless body, his glasses askew, blood running down his face. \'85 But Mr. Weasley wasn\rquote t going to die. \'85 He couldn\rquote t. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore was now rummaging in a cupboard behind Harry and Ron. He emerged from it carrying a blackened old kettle, which he placed carefully upon his desk. He raised his wand and murmured \ldblquote\i Portus\i0\rdblquote ; for a moment the kettle trembled, glowing with an odd blue light, then it quivered to a rest, as solidly black as ever.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dumbledore marched over to another portrait, this time of a clever-looking wizard with a pointed beard, who had been painted wearing the Slytherin colors of green and silver and was apparently sleeping so deeply that he could not hear Dumbledore\rquote s voice when he attempted to rouse him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Phineas. \i Phineas.\i0\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And now the subjects of the portraits lining the room were no longer pretending to be asleep; they were shifting around in their frames, the better to watch what was happening. When the clever-looking wizard continued to feign sleep, some of them shouted his name too.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Phineas! \i Phineas\i0 ! PHINEAS!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He could not pretend any longer; he gave a theatrical jerk and opened his eyes wide.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Did someone call?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I need you to visit your other portrait again, Phineas,\rdblquote  said Dum\-bledore. \ldblquote I\rquote ve got another message.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Visit my other portrait?\rdblquote  said Phineas in a reedy voice, giving a long, fake yawn (his eyes traveling around the room and focusing upon Harry). \ldblquote Oh no, Dumbledore, I am too tired tonight. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Something about Phineas\rquote s voice was familiar to Harry. Where had\lang3081  \lang1033 he heard it before? But before he could think, the portraits on the sur\-rounding walls broke into a storm of protest.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Insubordination, sir!\rdblquote  roared a corpulent, red-nosed wizard, bran\-dishing his fists. \ldblquote Dereliction of duty!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We are honor-bound to give service to the present Headmaster of Hogwarts!\rdblquote  cried a frail-looking old wizard whom Harry recognized as Dumbledore\rquote s predecessor, Armando Dippet. \ldblquote Shame on you, Phineas!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Shall I persuade him, Dumbledore?\rdblquote  called a gimlet-eyed witch, raising an unusually thick wand that looked not unlike a birch rod.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, very \i well,\rdblquote  \i0 said the wizard called Phineas, eyeing this wand slightly apprehensively, \ldblquote though he may well have destroyed my pic\-ture by now, he\rquote s done most of the family \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sirius knows not to destroy your portrait,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, and Harry realized immediately where he had heard Phineas\rquote s voice before: issuing from the apparently empty frame in his bedroom in Grim\-mauld Place. \ldblquote You are to give him the message that Arthur Weasley has been gravely injured and that his wife, children, and Harry Potter will be arriving at his house shortly. Do you understand?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Arthur Weasley, injured, wife and children and Harry Potter coming to stay,\rdblquote  recited Phineas in a bored voice. \ldblquote Yes, yes \'85 very well. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He sloped away into the frame of the portrait and disappeared from view at the very moment that the study door opened again. Fred, George, and Ginny were ushered inside by Professor McGonagall, all three of them looking disheveled and shocked, still in their night things.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry \emdash  what\rquote s going on?\rdblquote  asked Ginny, who looked frightened. \ldblquote Professor McGonagall says you saw Dad hurt \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Your father has been injured in the course of his work for the Or\-der of the Phoenix,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore before Harry could speak. \ldblquote He has been taken to St. Mungo\rquote s Hospital for Magical Maladies and In\-juries. I am sending you back to Sirius\rquote s house, which is much more\lang3081  \lang1033 convenient for the hospital than the Burrow. You will meet your mother there.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How\rquote re we going?\rdblquote  asked Fred, looking shaken. \ldblquote Floo powder?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, \ldblquote Floo powder is not safe at the moment, the Network is being watched. You will be taking a Portkey.\rdblquote  He indi\-cated the old kettle lying innocently on his desk. \ldblquote We are just waiting for Phineas Nigellus to report back. \'85 I wish to be sure that the coast is clear before sending you \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a flash of flame in the very middle of the office, leaving behind a single golden feather that floated gently to the floor.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It is Fawkes\rquote s warning,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, catching the feather as it fell. \ldblquote She must know you\rquote re out of your beds. \'85 Minerva, go and head her off\lang3081  \lang1033\emdash  tell her any story \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Professor McGonagall was gone in a swish of tartan.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He says he\rquote ll be delighted,\rdblquote  said a bored voice behind Dumble\-dore; the wizard called Phineas had reappeared in front of his Slytherin banner. \ldblquote My great-great-grandson has always had odd taste in houseguests. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Come here, then,\rdblquote  Dumbledore said to Harry and the Weasleys. \ldblquote And quickly, before anyone else joins us \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry and the others gathered around Dumbledore\rquote s desk.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You have all used a Portkey before?\rdblquote  asked Dumbledore, and they nodded, each reaching out to touch some part of the blackened kettle. \ldblquote Good. On the count of three then \'85 one \'85 two \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It happened in a fraction of a second: In the infinitesimal pause be\-fore Dumbledore said \ldblquote three,\rdblquote  Harry looked up at him \emdash  they were very close together \emdash  and Dumbledore\rquote s clear blue gaze moved from the Portkey to Harry\rquote s face.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 At once, Harry\rquote s scar burned white-hot, as though the old wound had burst open again \emdash  and unbidden, unwanted, but terrifyingly strong, there rose within Harry a hatred so powerful he felt, for that\lang3081  \lang1033 instant, that he would like nothing better than to strike \emdash  to bite \emdash  to sink his fangs into the man before him \emdash\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\'85 \i three.\i0\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He felt a powerful jerk behind his navel, the ground vanished from beneath his feet, his hand was glued to the kettle; he was banging into the others as all sped forward in a swirl of colors and a rush of wind, the kettle pulling them onward and then \emdash\lang3081\par
\lang1033 His feet hit the ground so hard that his knees buckled, the kettle clattered to the ground and somewhere close at hand a voice said, \ldblquote Back again, the blood traitor brats, is it true their father\rquote s dying \'85 ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote OUT!\rdblquote  roared a second voice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry scrambled to his feet and looked around; they had arrived in the gloomy basement kitchen of number twelve, Grimmauld Place. The only sources of light were the fire and one guttering candle, which illuminated the remains of a solitary supper. Kreacher was dis\-appearing through the door to the hall, looking back at them malevo\-lently as he hitched up his loincloth; Sirius was hurrying toward them all, looking anxious. He was unshaven and still in his day clothes; there was also a slightly Mundungus-like whiff of stale drink about him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What\rquote s going on?\rdblquote  he said, stretching out a hand to help Ginny up. \ldblquote Phineas Nigellus said Arthur\rquote s been badly injured \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ask Harry,\rdblquote  said Fred.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, I want to hear this for myself,\rdblquote  said George.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The twins and Ginny were staring at him. Kreacher\rquote s footsteps had stopped on the stairs outside.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It was \emdash\rdblquote  Harry began; this was even worse than telling McGona\-gall and Dumbledore. \ldblquote I had a \emdash  a kind of\lang3081  \lang1033\emdash  vision. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And he told them all that he had seen, though he altered the story so that it sounded as though he had watched from the sidelines as the snake attacked, rather than from behind the snake\rquote s own eyes. \'85 Ron, who was still very white, gave him a fleeting look, but did not speak. When Harry had finished, Fred, George, and Ginny continued to stare at him for a moment. Harry did not know whether he was imagining it or not, but he fancied there was something accusatory in their looks. Well, if they were going to blame him for just seeing the attack, he was glad he had not told them that he had been inside the snake at the time. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Is Mum here?\rdblquote  said Fred, turning to Sirius.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote She probably doesn\rquote t even know what\rquote s happened yet,\rdblquote  said Sirius. \ldblquote The important thing was to get you away before Umbridge could in\-terfere. I expect Dumbledore\rquote s letting Molly know now.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We\rquote ve got to go to St. Mungo\rquote s,\rdblquote  said Ginny urgently. She looked around at her brothers; they were of course still in their pajamas. \ldblquote Sir\-ius, can you lend us cloaks or anything \emdash  ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hang on, you can\rquote t go tearing off to St. Mungo\rquote s!\rdblquote  said Sirius.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \rquote Course we can go to St. Mungo\rquote s if we want,\rdblquote  said Fred, with a mulish expression, \ldblquote he\rquote s our dad!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And how are you going to explain how you knew Arthur was at\-tacked before the hospital even let his wife know?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What does that matter?\rdblquote  said George hotly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It matters because we don\rquote t want to draw attention to the fact that Harry is having visions of things that are happening hundreds of miles away!\rdblquote  said Sirius angrily. \ldblquote Have you any idea what the Ministry would make of that information?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Fred and George looked as though they could not care less what the Ministry made of anything. Ron was still white-faced and silent. Ginny said, \ldblquote Somebody else could have told us. \'85 We could have heard it somewhere other than Harry. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Like who?\rdblquote  said Sirius impatiently. \ldblquote Listen, your dad\rquote s been hurt while on duty for the Order and the circumstances are fishy enough without his children knowing about it seconds after it happened, you could seriously damage the Order\rquote s \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We don\rquote t care about the dumb Order!\rdblquote  shouted Fred.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s our dad dying we\rquote re talking about!\rdblquote  yelled George.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Your father knew what he was getting into, and he won\rquote t thank you for messing things up for the Order!\rdblquote  said Sirius angrily in his turn. \ldblquote This is how it is \emdash  this is why you\rquote re not in the Order \emdash  you don\rquote t understand \emdash  there are things worth dying for!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Easy for you to say, stuck here!\rdblquote  bellowed Fred. \ldblquote I don\rquote t see you risking your neck!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The little color remaining in Sirius\rquote s face drained from it. He looked for a moment as though he would quite like to hit Fred, but when he spoke, it was in a voice of determined calm. \ldblquote I know it\rquote s hard, but we\rquote ve all got to act as though we don\rquote t know anything yet. We\rquote ve got to stay put, at least until we hear from your mother, all right?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Fred and George still looked mutinous. Ginny, however, took a few steps over to the nearest chair and sank into it. Harry looked at Ron, who made a funny movement somewhere between a nod and shrug, and they sat down too. The twins glared at Sirius for another minute, then took seats on either side of Ginny.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That\rquote s right,\rdblquote  said Sirius encouragingly, \ldblquote come on, let\rquote s all\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 let\rquote s all have a drink while we\rquote re waiting. \i Accio Butterbeer\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He raised his wand as he spoke and half a dozen bottles came flying toward them out of the pantry, skidded along the table, scattering the debris of Sirius\rquote s meal, and stopped neatly in front of the six of them. They all drank, and for a while the only sounds were those of the crack\-ling of the kitchen fire and the soft thud of their bottles on the table.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry was only drinking to have something to do with his hands. His stomach was full of horrible hot, bubbling guilt. They would not be here if it were not for him; they would all still be asleep in bed. And it was no good telling himself that by raising the alarm he had ensured that Mr. Weasley was found, because there was also the inescapable business of it being he who had attacked Mr. Weasley in the first place. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\i Don\rquote t be stupid, you haven\rquote t got fangs,\i0  he told himself, trying to keep calm, though the hand on his butterbeer bottle was shaking. \i You were lying in bed, you weren\rquote t attacking anyone. \'85\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\i But then, what just happened in Dumbledore\rquote s office\i0 ? he asked him\-self. \i I felt like I wanted to attack Dumbledore too. \'85\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033 He put the bottle down on the table a little harder than he meant to, so that it slopped over onto the table. No one took any notice. Then a burst of fire in midair illuminated the dirty plates in front of them and as they gave cries of shock, a scroll of parchment fell with a thud onto the table, accompanied by a single golden phoenix tail feather.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Fawkes!\rdblquote  said Sirius at once, snatching up the parchment. \ldblquote That\rquote s not Dumbledore\rquote s writing \emdash  it must be a message from your mother \emdash  here \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
