\lang1033\ldblquote Good haul this year,\rdblquote  he informed Harry through a cloud of pa\-per. \ldblquote Thanks for the Broom Compass, it\rquote s excellent, beats Hermi\-one\rquote s \emdash  she\rquote s got me a \i homework planner \i0\emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry sorted through his presents and found one with Hermione\rquote s handwriting on it. She had given him too a book that resembled a di\-ary, except that it said things like \ldblquote\i Do it today or later you\rquote ll pay\i0 !\rdblquote  every time he opened a page.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Sirius and Lupin had given Harry a set of excellent books entitled \i Practical Defensive Magic and Its Use Against the Dark Arts,\i0  which had superb, moving color illustrations of all the counterjinxes and hexes it described. Harry flicked through the first volume eagerly; he could see\lang3081  \lang1033 it was going to be highly useful in his plans for the D.A. Hagrid had sent a furry brown wallet that had fangs, which were presumably sup\-posed to be an antitheft device, but unfortunately prevented Harry putting any money in without getting his fingers ripped off. Tonks\rquote s present was a small, working model of a Firebolt, which Harry watched fly around the room, wishing he still had his full-size version; Ron had given him an enormous box of Every-Flavor Beans; Mr. and Mrs. Weasley the usual hand-knitted jumper and some mince pies; and Dobby, a truly dreadful painting that Harry suspected had been done by the elf himself. He had just turned it upside down to see whether it looked better that way when, with a loud \i crack,\i0  Fred and George Apparated at the foot of his bed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Merry Christmas,\rdblquote  said George. \ldblquote Don\rquote t go downstairs for a bit.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Why not?\rdblquote  said Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Mum\rquote s crying again,\rdblquote  said Fred heavily. \ldblquote Percy sent back his Christmas jumper.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Without a note,\rdblquote  added George. \ldblquote Hasn\rquote t asked how Dad is or vis\-ited him or anything. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We tried to comfort her,\rdblquote  said Fred, moving around the bed to look at Harry\rquote s portrait. \ldblquote Told her Percy\rquote s nothing more than a hu\-mongous pile of rat droppings \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  didn\rquote t work,\rdblquote  said George, helping himself to a Chocolate Frog. \ldblquote So Lupin took over. Best let him cheer her up before we go down for breakfast, I reckon.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What\rquote s that supposed to be anyway?\rdblquote  asked Fred, squinting at Dobby\rquote s painting. \ldblquote Looks like a gibbon with two black eyes.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s Harry!\rdblquote  said George, pointing at the back of the picture. \ldblquote Says so on the back!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Good likeness,\rdblquote  said Fred, grinning. Harry threw his new home\-work diary at him; it hit the wall opposite and fell to the floor where it said happily, \ldblquote\i If\lang3081  \lang1033 you\rquote ve dotted the i\rquote s and crossed the t\rquote s then you may do whatever you please\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They got up and dressed; they could hear various inhabitants of the house calling \ldblquote Merry Christmas\rdblquote  to each other. On their way down\-stairs they met Hermione. \ldblquote Thanks for the book, Harry!\rdblquote  she said happily. \ldblquote I\rquote ve been wanting that \i New Theory of Numerology\i0  for ages! And that perfume is really unusual, Ron.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No problem,\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote Who\rquote s that for anyway?\rdblquote  he added, nod\-ding at the neatly wrapped present she was carrying.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Kreacher,\rdblquote  said Hermione brightly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It had better not be clothes!\rdblquote  said Ron warningly. \ldblquote You know what Sirius said, Kreacher knows too much, we can\rquote t set him free!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It isn\rquote t clothes,\rdblquote  said Hermione, \ldblquote although if I had my way I\rquote d cer\-tainly give him something to wear other than that filthy old rag. No, it\rquote s a patchwork quilt, I thought it would brighten up his bedroom.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What bedroom?\rdblquote  said Harry, dropping his voice to a whisper as they were passing the portrait of Sirius\rquote s mother.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, Sirius says it\rquote s not so much a bedroom, more a kind of\lang3081  \lang1033\emdash  \i den,\i0\rdblquote  said Hermione. \ldblquote Apparently he sleeps under the boiler in that cupboard off the kitchen.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mrs. Weasley was the only person in the basement when they ar\-rived there. She was standing at the stove and sounded as though she had a bad head cold when she wished them Merry Christmas, and they all averted their eyes.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So, this is Kreacher\rquote s bedroom?\rdblquote  said Ron, strolling over to a dingy door in the corner opposite the pantry which Harry had never seen open.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Hermione, now sounding a little nervous. \ldblquote Er \'85 I think we\rquote d better knock \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron rapped the door with his knuckles but there was no reply.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He must be sneaking around upstairs,\rdblquote  he said, and without fur\-ther ado pulled open the door. \ldblquote\i Urgh.\i0\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry peered inside. Most of the cupboard was taken up with a very large and old-fashioned boiler, but in the foot\rquote s space underneath\lang3081  \lang1033 the pipes Kreacher had made himself something that looked like a nest. A jumble of assorted rags and smelly old blankets were piled on the floor and the small dent in the middle of it showed where Kreacher curled up to sleep every night. Here and there among the material were stale bread crusts and moldy old bits of cheese. In a far corner glinted small objects and coins that Harry guessed Kreacher had saved, magpielike, from Sirius\rquote s purge of the house, and he had also managed to retrieve the silver-framed family photographs that Sirius had thrown away over the summer. Their glass might be shat\-tered, but still the little black-and-white people inside them peered haughtily up at him, including \emdash  he felt a little jolt in his stomach \emdash  the dark, heavy-lidded woman whose trial he had witnessed in Dum\-bledore\rquote s Pensieve: Bellatrix Lestrange. By the looks of it, hers was Kreacher\rquote s favorite photograph; he had placed it to the fore of all the others and had mended the glass clumsily with Spellotape.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I think I\rquote ll just leave his present here,\rdblquote  said Hermione, laying the package neatly in the middle of the depression in the rags and blankets and closing the door quietly. \ldblquote He\rquote ll find it later, that\rquote ll be fine. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Come to think of it,\rdblquote  said Sirius, emerging from the pantry carry\-ing a large turkey as they closed the cupboard door, \ldblquote has anyone actually seen Kreacher lately?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I haven\rquote t seen him since the night we came back here,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote You were ordering him out of the kitchen.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah \'85\rdblquote  said Sirius, frowning. \ldblquote You know, I think that\rquote s the last time I saw him, too. \'85 He must be hiding upstairs somewhere. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He couldn\rquote t have left, could he?\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote I mean, when you said \lquote out,\rquote  maybe he thought you meant, get out of the house?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, no, house-elves can\rquote t leave unless they\rquote re given clothes, they\rquote re tied to their family\rquote s house,\rdblquote  said Sirius.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote They can leave the house if they really want to,\rdblquote  Harry contra\-dicted him. \ldblquote Dobby did, he left the Malfoys\rquote  to give me warnings two years ago. He had to punish himself afterward, but he still managed it.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Sirius looked slightly disconcerted for a moment, then said, \ldblquote I\rquote ll look for him later, I expect I\rquote ll find him upstairs crying his eyes out over my mother\rquote s old bloomers or something. \'85 Of course, he might have crawled into the airing cupboard and died. \'85 But I mustn\rquote t get my hopes up. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Fred, George, and Ron laughed; Hermione, however, looked reproachful.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Once they had had their Christmas lunch, the Weasleys and Harry and Hermione were planning to pay Mr. Weasley another visit, es\-corted by Mad-Eye and Lupin. Mundungus turned up in time for Christmas pudding and trifle, having managed to \ldblquote borrow\rdblquote  a car for the occasion, as the Underground did not run on Christmas Day. The car, which Harry doubted very much had been taken with the knowl\-edge or consent of its owner, had had a similar Enlarging Spell put upon it as the Weasleys\rquote  old Ford Anglia; although normally propor\-tioned outside, ten people with Mundungus driving were able to fit into it quite comfortably. Mrs. Weasley hesitated at the point of get\-ting inside; Harry knew that her disapproval of Mundungus was bat\-tling with her dislike of traveling without magic; finally the cold outside and her children\rquote s pleading triumphed, and she settled herself into the backseat between Fred and Bill with good grace.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The journey to St. Mungo\rquote s was quite quick, as there was very little traffic on the roads. A small trickle of witches and wizards were creep\-ing furtively up the otherwise deserted street to visit the hospital. Harry and the others got out of the car, and Mundungus drove off around the corner to wait for them; they strolled casually toward the window where the dummy in green nylon stood, then, one by one, stepped through the glass.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The reception area looked pleasantly festive: The crystal orbs that illuminated St. Mungo\rquote s had been turned to red and gold so that they became gigantic, glowing Christmas baubles; holly hung around every doorway, and shining white Christmas trees covered in magical snow\lang3081  \lang1033 and icicles glittered in every corner, each topped with a gleaming gold star. It was less crowded than the last time they had been there, al\-though halfway across the room Harry found himself shunted aside by a witch with a walnut jammed up her left nostril.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Family argument, eh?\rdblquote  smirked the blonde witch behind the desk. \ldblquote You\rquote re the third I\rquote ve seen today \'85 Spell Damage, fourth floor \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They found Mr. Weasley propped up in bed with the remains of his turkey dinner on a tray in his lap and a rather sheepish expression on his face.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Everything all right, Arthur?\rdblquote  asked Mrs. Weasley, after they had all greeted Mr. Weasley and handed over their presents.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Fine, fine,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, a little too heartily. \ldblquote You \emdash  er \emdash  haven\rquote t seen Healer Smethwyck, have you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley suspiciously, \ldblquote why?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Nothing, nothing,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley airily, starting to unwrap his pile of gifts. \ldblquote Well, everyone had a good day? What did you all get for Christmas? Oh, \i Harry\i0  \emdash  this is absolutely \i wonderful\lang3081\i0  \lang1033\emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 For he had just opened Harry\rquote s gift of fuse-wire and screwdrivers. Mrs. Weasley did not seem entirely satisfied with Mr. Weasley\rquote s an\-swer. As her husband leaned over to shake Harry\rquote s hand, she peered at the bandaging under his nightshirt.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Arthur,\rdblquote  she said, with a snap in her voice like a mousetrap, \ldblquote you\rquote ve had your bandages changed. Why have you had your ban\-dages changed a day early, Arthur? They told me they wouldn\rquote t need doing until tomorrow.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What?\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, looking rather frightened and pulling the bed covers higher up his chest. \ldblquote No, no \emdash  it\rquote s nothing \emdash  it\rquote s \emdash  I \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He seemed to deflate under Mrs. Weasley\rquote s piercing gaze.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well \emdash  now don\rquote t get upset, Molly, but Augustus Pye had an idea. \'85 He\rquote s the Trainee Healer, you know, lovely young chap and very interested in \'85 um \'85 complementary medicine. \'85 I mean,\lang3081  \lang1033 some of these old Muggle remedies \'85 well, they\rquote re called \i stitches,\i0  Molly, and they work very well on \emdash  on Muggle wounds \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Mrs. Weasley let out an ominous noise somewhere between a shriek and a snarl. Lupin strolled away from the bed and over to the werewolf, who had no visitors and was looking rather wistfully at the crowd around Mr. Weasley; Bill muttered something about getting himself a cup of tea and Fred and George leapt up to accompany him, grinning.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Do you mean to tell me,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley, her voice growing louder with every word and apparently unaware that her fellow visi\-tors were scurrying for cover, \ldblquote that you have been messing about with Muggle remedies?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Not messing about, Molly, dear,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley imploringly. \ldblquote It was just \emdash  just something Pye and I thought we\rquote d try \emdash  only, most unfortunately \emdash  well, with these particular kinds of wounds \emdash  it doesn\rquote t seem to work as well as we\rquote d hoped \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Meaning\i0 ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 well, I don\rquote t know whether you know what \emdash  what stitches are?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It sounds as though you\rquote ve been trying to sew your skin back to\-gether,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley with a snort of mirthless laughter, \ldblquote but even you, Arthur, wouldn\rquote t be \i that\i0  stupid \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I fancy a cup of tea too,\rdblquote  said Harry, jumping to his feet.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione, Ron, and Ginny almost sprinted to the door with him. As it swung closed behind them, they heard Mrs. Weasley shriek, \ldblquote WHAT DO YOU MEAN, THAT\rquote S THE GENERAL IDEA?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Typical Dad,\rdblquote  said Ginny, shaking her head as they set off up the corridor. \ldblquote Stitches \'85 I ask you \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, you know, they do work well on non-magical wounds,\rdblquote  said Hermione fairly. \ldblquote I suppose something in that snake\rquote s venom dissolves them or something. \'85 I wonder where the tearoom is?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Fifth floor,\rdblquote  said Harry, remembering the sign over the Welcome Witch\rquote s desk.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They walked along the corridor through a set of double doors and found a rickety staircase lined with more portraits of brutal-looking Healers. As they climbed it, the various Healers called out to them, di\-agnosing odd complaints and suggesting horrible remedies. Ron was seriously affronted when a medieval wizard called out that he clearly had a bad case of spattergroit.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And what\rquote s that supposed to be?\rdblquote  he asked angrily, as the Healer pursued him through six more portraits, shoving the occupants out of the way.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \rquote Tis a most grievous affliction of the skin, young master, that will leave you pockmarked and more gruesome even than you are now \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Watch who you\rquote re calling gruesome!\rdblquote  said Ron, his ears turning red.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The only remedy is to take the liver of a toad, bind it tight about your throat, stand naked by the full moon in a barrel of eels\rquote  eyes \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I have not got spattergroit!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But the unsightly blemishes upon your visage, young master \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote They\rquote re freckles!\rdblquote  said Ron furiously. \ldblquote Now get back in your own picture and leave me alone!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He rounded on the others, who were all keeping determinedly straight faces.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What floor\rquote s this?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I think it\rquote s the fifth,\rdblquote  said Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Nah, it\rquote s the fourth,\rdblquote  said Harry, \ldblquote one more \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But as he stepped onto the landing he came to an abrupt halt, star\-ing at the small window set into the double doors that marked the start of a corridor signposted SPELL DAMAGE. A man was peering out at them all with his nose pressed against the glass. He had wavy blond hair, bright blue eyes, and a broad vacant smile that revealed daz\-zlingly white teeth.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Blimey!\rdblquote  said Ron, also staring at the man.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh my goodness,\rdblquote  said Hermione suddenly, sounding breathless. \ldblquote Professor Lockhart!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Their ex-Defense Against the Dark Arts teacher pushed open the doors and moved toward them, wearing a long lilac dressing gown.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, hello there!\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote I expect you\rquote d like my autograph, would you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hasn\rquote t changed much, has he?\rdblquote  Harry muttered to Ginny, who grinned.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Er \emdash  how are you, Professor?\rdblquote  said Ron, sounding slightly guilty. It had been Ron\rquote s malfunctioning wand that had damaged Professor Lockhart\rquote s memory so badly that he had landed here in the first place, though, as Lockhart had been attempting to permanently wipe Harry and Ron\rquote s memories at the time, Harry\rquote s sympathy was limited.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m very well indeed, thank you!\rdblquote  said Lockhart exuberantly, pulling a rather battered peacock-feather quill from his pocket. \ldblquote Now, how many autographs would you like? I can do joined-up writing now, you know!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Er \emdash  we don\rquote t want any at the moment, thanks,\rdblquote  said Ron, rais\-ing his eyebrows at Harry, who asked, \ldblquote Professor, should you be wan\-dering around the corridors? Shouldn\rquote t you be in a ward?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The smile faded slowly from Lockhart\rquote s face. For a few moments he gazed intently at Harry, then he said, \ldblquote Haven\rquote t we met?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Er \'85 yeah, we have,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote You used to teach us at Hog\-warts, remember?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Teach?\rdblquote  repeated Lockhart, looking faintly unsettled. \ldblquote Me? Did I?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And then the smile reappeared upon his face so suddenly it was rather alarming. \ldblquote Taught you everything you know, I expect, did I? Well, how about those autographs, then? Shall we say a round dozen, you can give them to all your little friends then and nobody will be left out!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But just then a head poked out of a door at the far end of the cor\-ridor and a voice said, \ldblquote Gilderoy, you naughty boy, where have you wandered off to?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A motherly looking Healer wearing a tinsel wreath in her hair came bustling up the corridor, smiling warmly at Harry and the others.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh Gilderoy, you\rquote ve got visitors! How \i lovely,\i0  and on Christmas Day too! Do you know, he \i never\i0  gets visitors, poor lamb, and I can\rquote t think why, he\rquote s such a sweetie, aren\rquote t you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We\rquote re doing autographs!\rdblquote  Gilderoy told the Healer with another glittering smile. \ldblquote They want loads of them, won\rquote t take no for an an\-swer! I just hope we\rquote ve got enough photographs!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Listen to him,\rdblquote  said the Healer, taking Lockhart\rquote s arm and beam\-ing fondly at him as though he were a precocious two-year-old. \ldblquote He was rather well known a few years ago; we very much hope that this liking for giving autographs is a sign that his memory might be com\-ing back a little bit. Will you step this way? He\rquote s in a closed ward, you know, he must have slipped out while I was bringing in the Christmas presents, the door\rquote s usually kept locked \'85 not that he\rquote s dangerous! But,\rdblquote  she lowered her voice to a whisper, \ldblquote bit of a danger to himself, bless him. \'85 Doesn\rquote t know who he is, you see, wanders off and can\rquote t remember how to get back. \'85 It \i is\i0  nice of you to have come to see him \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Er,\rdblquote  said Ron, gesturing uselessly at the floor above, \ldblquote actually, we were just \emdash  er \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But the Healer was smiling expectantly at them, and Ron\rquote s feeble mutter of \ldblquote going to have a cup of tea\rdblquote  trailed away into nothingness. They looked at one another rather hopelessly and then followed Lock\-hart and his Healer along the corridor.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Let\rquote s not stay long,\rdblquote  Ron said quietly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The Healer pointed her wand at the door of the Janus Thickey ward and muttered \ldblquote\i Alohomora.\i0\rdblquote  The door swung open and she led\lang3081  \lang1033 the way inside, keeping a firm grasp on Gilderoy\rquote s arm until she had settled him into an armchair beside his bed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote This is our long-term resident ward,\rdblquote  she informed Harry, Ron, Hermione, and Ginny in a low voice. \ldblquote For permanent spell damage, you know. Of course, with intensive remedial potions and charms and a bit of luck, we can produce some improvement. \'85 Gilderoy does seem to be getting back some sense of himself, and we\rquote ve seen a real improvement in Mr. Bode, he seems to be regaining the power of speech very well, though he isn\rquote t speaking any language we recognize yet. \'85 Well, I must finish giving out the Christmas presents, I\rquote ll leave you all to chat. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry looked around; this ward bore unmistakable signs of being a permanent home to its residents. They had many more personal ef\-fects around their beds than in Mr. Weasley\rquote s ward; the wall around Gilderoy\rquote s headboard, for instance, was papered with pictures of him\-self, all beaming toothily and waving at the new arrivals. He had au\-tographed many of them to himself in disjointed, childish writing. The moment he had been deposited in his chair by the Healer, Gilderoy pulled a fresh stack of photographs toward him, seized a quill, and started signing them all feverishly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You can put them in envelopes,\rdblquote  he said to Ginny, throwing the signed pictures into her lap one by one as he finished them. \ldblquote I am not forgotten, you know, no, I still receive a very great deal of fan mail. \'85 Gladys Gudgeon writes \i weekly. \'85\i0  I just wish I knew \i why. \'85\i0\rdblquote  He paused, looking faintly puzzled, then beamed again and returned to his signing with renewed vigor. \ldblquote I suspect it is simply my good looks. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A sallow-skinned, mournful-looking wizard lay in the bed oppo\-site, staring at the ceiling; he was mumbling to himself and seemed quite unaware of anything around him. Two beds along was a woman whose entire head was covered in fur; Harry remembered something\lang3081  \lang1033 similar happening to Hermione during their second year, although fortunately the damage, in her case, had not been permanent. At the far end of the ward flowery curtains had been drawn around two beds to give the occupants and their visitors some privacy.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Here you are, Agnes,\rdblquote  said the Healer brightly to the furry-faced woman, handing her a small pile of Christmas presents. \ldblquote See, not for\-gotten, are you? And your son\rquote s sent an owl to say he\rquote s visiting tonight, so that\rquote s nice, isn\rquote t it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Agnes gave several loud barks.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And look, Broderick, you\rquote ve been sent a potted plant and a lovely calendar with a different fancy hippogriff for each month, they\rquote ll brighten things up, won\rquote t they?\rdblquote  said the Healer, bustling along to the mumbling man, setting a rather ugly plant with long, swaying tenta\-cles on the bedside cabinet and fixing the calendar to the wall with her wand. \ldblquote And \emdash  oh, Mrs. Longbottom, are you leaving already?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry\rquote s head spun round. The curtains had been drawn back from the two beds at the end of the ward and two visitors were walking back down the aisle between the beds: a formidable-looking old witch wearing a long green dress, a moth-eaten fox fur, and a pointed hat decorated with what was unmistakably a stuffed vulture and, trailing behind her looking thoroughly depressed \emdash  \i Neville.\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033 With a sudden rush of understanding, Harry realized who the people in the end beds must be. He cast around wildly for some means of distracting the others so that Neville could leave the ward unnoticed and unquestioned, but Ron had looked up at the sound of the name \ldblquote Longbottom\rdblquote  too, and before Harry could stop him had called, \ldblquote\i Neville\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Neville jumped and cowered as though a bullet had narrowly missed him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s us, Neville!\rdblquote  said Ron brightly, getting to his feet. \ldblquote Have you seen? Lockhart\rquote s here! Who\rquote ve you been visiting?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Friends of yours, Neville, dear?\rdblquote  said Neville\rquote s grandmother gra\-ciously, bearing down upon them all.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Neville looked as though he would rather be anywhere in the world but here. A dull purple flush was creeping up his plump face and he was not making eye contact with any of them.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ah, yes,\rdblquote  said his grandmother, looking closely at Harry and stick\-ing out a shriveled, clawlike hand for him to shake. \ldblquote Yes, yes, I know who you are, of course. Neville speaks most highly of you.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Er \emdash  thanks,\rdblquote  said Harry, shaking hands. Neville did not look at him, but stared at his own feet, the color deepening in his face all the while.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And you two are clearly Weasleys,\rdblquote  Mrs. Longbottom continued, proffering her hand regally to Ron and Ginny in turn. \ldblquote Yes, I know your parents \emdash  not well, of course \emdash  but fine people, fine people \'85 and you must be Hermione Granger?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione looked rather startled that Mrs. Longbottom knew her name, but shook hands all the same.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, Neville\rquote s told me all about you. Helped him out of a few sticky spots, haven\rquote t you? He\rquote s a good boy,\rdblquote  she said, casting a sternly appraising look down her rather bony nose at Neville, \ldblquote but he hasn\rquote t got his father\rquote s talent, I\rquote m afraid to say. \'85\rdblquote  And she jerked her head in the direction of the two beds at the end of the ward, so that the stuffed vulture on her hat trembled alarmingly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What?\rdblquote  said Ron, looking amazed (Harry wanted to stamp on Ron\rquote s foot, but that sort of thing was much harder to bring off unno\-ticed when you were wearing jeans rather than robes). \ldblquote Is that your \i dad\i0  down the end, Neville?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What\rquote s this?\rdblquote  said Mrs. Longbottom sharply. \ldblquote Haven\rquote t you told your friends about your parents, Neville?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Neville took a deep breath, looked up at the ceiling, and shook his head. Harry could not remember ever feeling sorrier for anyone,\lang3081  \lang1033 but he could not think of any way of helping Neville out of the situation.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, it\rquote s nothing to be ashamed of!\rdblquote  said Mrs. Longbottom an\-grily. \ldblquote You should be \i proud,\i0  Neville, \i proud\i0 ! They didn\rquote t give their health and their sanity so their only son would be ashamed of them, you know!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m not ashamed,\rdblquote  said Neville very faintly, still looking anywhere but at Harry and the others. Ron was now standing on tiptoe to look over at the inhabitants of the two beds.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, you\rquote ve got a funny way of showing it!\rdblquote  said Mrs. Longbot\-tom. \ldblquote My son and his wife,\rdblquote  she said, turning haughtily to Harry, Ron, Hermione, and Ginny, \ldblquote were tortured into insanity by You-Know-Who\rquote s followers.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione and Ginny both clapped their hands over their mouths. Ron stopped craning his neck to catch a glimpse of Neville\rquote s parents and looked mortified.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote They were Aurors, you know, and very well respected within the Wizarding community,\rdblquote  Mrs. Longbottom went on. \ldblquote Highly gifted, the pair of them. I \emdash  yes, Alice dear, what is it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Neville\rquote s mother had come edging down the ward in her nightdress. She no longer had the plump, happy-looking face Harry had seen in Moody\rquote s old photograph of the original Order of the Phoenix. Her face was thin and worn now, her eyes seemed overlarge, and her hair, which had turned white, was wispy and dead-looking. She did not seem to want to speak, or perhaps she was not able to, but she made timid motions toward Neville, holding something in her outstretched hand.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Again?\rdblquote  said Mrs. Longbottom, sounding slightly weary. \ldblquote Very well, Alice dear, very well \emdash  Neville, take it, whatever it is. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But Neville had already stretched out his hand, into which his mother dropped an empty Droobles Blowing Gum wrapper.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Very nice, dear,\rdblquote  said Neville\rquote s grandmother in a falsely cheery\lang3081  \lang1033 voice, patting his mother on the shoulder. But Neville said quietly, \ldblquote Thanks Mum.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 His mother tottered away, back up the ward, humming to herself. Neville looked around at the others, his expression defiant, as though daring them to laugh, but Harry did not think he\rquote d ever found any\-thing less funny in his life.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, we\rquote d better get back,\rdblquote  sighed Mrs. Longbottom, drawing on long green gloves. \ldblquote Very nice to have met you all. Neville, put that wrapper in the bin, she must have given you enough of them to paper your bedroom by now. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But as they left, Harry was sure he saw Neville slip the wrapper into his pocket.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The door closed behind them.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I never knew,\rdblquote  said Hermione, who looked tearful.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Nor did I,\rdblquote  said Ron rather hoarsely.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Nor me,\rdblquote  whispered Ginny.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They all looked at Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I did,\rdblquote  he said glumly. \ldblquote Dumbledore told me but I promised I wouldn\rquote t mention it\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 that\rquote s what Bellatrix Lestrange got sent to Azkaban for, using the Cruciatus Curse on Neville\rquote s parents until they lost their minds.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Bellatrix Lestrange did that?\rdblquote  whispered Hermione, horrified. \ldblquote That woman Kreacher\rquote s got a photo of in his den?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a long silence, broken by Lockhart\rquote s angry voice. \ldblquote Look, I didn\rquote t learn joined-up writing for nothing, you know!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\par
