Kreacher, it transpired, had been lurking in the attic. Sirius said he had found him up there, covered in dust, no doubt looking for more relics of the Black family to hide in his cupboard. Though Sirius seemed satisfied with this story, it made Harry uneasy. Kreacher seemed to be in a better mood on his reappearance, his bitter mutter\-ing had subsided somewhat, and he submitted to orders more docilely than usual, though once or twice Harry caught the house-elf staring avidly at him, always looking quickly away when he saw that Harry had noticed.\par
Harry did not mention his vague suspicions to Sirius, whose cheer\-fulness was evaporating fast now that Christmas was over. As the date of their departure back to Hogwarts drew nearer, he became more and more prone to what Mrs. Weasley called \ldblquote fits of the sullens,\rdblquote  in which he would become taciturn and grumpy, often withdrawing to Buck\-beak\rquote s room for hours at a time. His gloom seeped through the house, oozing under doorways like some noxious gas, so that all of them be\-came infected by it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry did not want to leave Sirius all alone again with only Kreacher\lang3081  \lang1033 for company. In fact, for the first time in his life, he was not looking forward to returning to Hogwarts. Going back to school would mean placing himself once again under the tyranny of Dolores Umbridge, who had no doubt managed to force through another dozen decrees in their absence. Then there was no Quidditch to look forward to now that he had been banned; there was every likelihood that their burden of homework would increase as the exams drew even nearer; Dumble\-dore remained as remote as ever; in fact, if it had not been for the D.A., Harry felt he might have gone to Sirius and begged him to let him leave Hogwarts and remain in Grimmauld Place.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Then, on the very last day of the holidays, something happened that made Harry positively dread his return to school.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry dear,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley, poking her head into his and Ron\rquote s bedroom, where the pair of them were playing wizard chess watched by Hermione, Ginny, and Crookshanks, \ldblquote could you come down to the kitchen? Professor Snape would like a word with you.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry did not immediately register what she had said; one of his castles was engaged in a violent tussle with a pawn of Ron\rquote s, and he was egging it on enthusiastically.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Squash him \emdash  \i squash him,\i0  he\rquote s only a pawn, you idiot \emdash  sorry, Mrs. Weasley, what did you say?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Professor Snape, dear. In the kitchen. He\rquote d like a word.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry\rquote s mouth fell open in horror. He looked around at Ron, Hermione, and Ginny, all of whom were gaping back at him. Crook\-shanks, whom Hermione had been restraining with difficulty for the past quarter of an hour, leapt gleefully upon the board and set the pieces running for cover, squealing at the top of their voices.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Snape?\rdblquote  said Harry blankly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Professor\i0  Snape, dear,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley reprovingly. \ldblquote Now come on, quickly, he says he can\rquote t stay long.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What\rquote s he want with you?\rdblquote  said Ron, looking unnerved as Mrs. Weasley withdrew from the room.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You haven\rquote t done anything, have you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No!\rdblquote  said Harry indignantly, racking his brains to think what he could have done that would make Snape pursue him to Grimmauld Place. Had his last piece of homework perhaps earned a\lang3081  \lang1033 T?\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He pushed open the kitchen door a minute or two later to find Sir\-ius and Snape both seated at the long kitchen table, glaring in oppo\-site directions. The silence between them was heavy with mutual dislike. A letter lay open on the table in front of Sirius.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Er,\rdblquote  said Harry to announce his presence.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Snape looked around at him, his face framed between curtains of greasy black hair.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sit down, Potter.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You know,\rdblquote  said Sirius loudly, leaning back on his rear chair legs and speaking to the ceiling, \ldblquote I think I\rquote d prefer it if you didn\rquote t give or\-ders here, Snape. It\rquote s my house, you see.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 An ugly flush suffused Snape\rquote s pallid face. Harry sat down in a chair beside Sirius, facing Snape across the table.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I was supposed to see you alone, Potter,\rdblquote  said Snape, the familiar sneer curling his mouth, \ldblquote but Black \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m his godfather,\rdblquote  said Sirius, louder than ever.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I am here on Dumbledore\rquote s orders,\rdblquote  said Snape, whose voice, by contrast, was becoming more and more quietly waspish, \ldblquote but by all means stay, Black, I know you like to feel\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 involved.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What\rquote s that supposed to mean?\rdblquote  said Sirius, letting his chair fall back onto all four legs with a loud bang.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Merely that I am sure you must feel \emdash  ah \emdash  frustrated by the fact that you can do nothing \i useful,\i0\rdblquote  Snape laid a delicate stress on the word, \ldblquote for the Order.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It was Sirius\rquote s turn to flush. Snape\rquote s lip curled in triumph as he turned to Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The headmaster has sent me to tell you, Potter, that it is his wish for you to study Occlumency this term.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Study what?\rdblquote  said Harry blankly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Snape\rquote s sneer became more pronounced.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Occlumency, Potter. The magical defense of the mind against ex\-ternal penetration. An obscure branch of magic, but a highly useful one.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry\rquote s heart began to pump very fast indeed. Defense against ex\-ternal penetration? But he was not being possessed, they had all agreed on that. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Why do I have to study Occlu \emdash  thing?\rdblquote  he blurted out.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Because the headmaster thinks it a good idea,\rdblquote  said Snape smoothly. \ldblquote You will receive private lessons once a week, but you will not tell anybody what you are doing, least of all Dolores Umbridge. You understand?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote Who\rquote s going to be teaching me?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Snape raised an eyebrow.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I am,\rdblquote  he said.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry had the horrible sensation that his insides were melting. Ex\-tra lessons with Snape \emdash  what on earth had he done to deserve this? He looked quickly around at Sirius for support.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Why can\rquote t Dumbledore teach Harry?\rdblquote  asked Sirius aggressively. \ldblquote Why you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I suppose because it is a headmaster\rquote s privilege to delegate less en\-joyable tasks,\rdblquote  said Snape silkily. \ldblquote I assure you I did not beg for the job.\rdblquote  He got to his feet. \ldblquote I will expect you at six o\rquote clock on Monday evening, Potter. My office. If anybody asks, you are taking Remedial Potions. Nobody who has seen you in my classes could deny you need them.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He turned to leave, his black traveling cloak billowing behind him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Wait a moment,\rdblquote  said Sirius, sitting up straighter in his chair.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Snape turned back to face them, sneering.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I am in rather a hurry, Black \'85 unlike you, I do not have unlim\-ited leisure time. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote ll get to the point, then,\rdblquote  said Sirius, standing up. He was rather taller than Snape who, Harry noticed, had balled his fist in the pocket of his cloak over what Harry was sure was the handle of his wand. \ldblquote If I hear you\rquote re using these Occlumency lessons to give Harry a hard time, you\rquote ll have me to answer to.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How touching,\rdblquote  Snape sneered. \ldblquote But surely you have noticed that Potter is very like his father?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, I have,\rdblquote  said Sirius proudly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well then, you\rquote ll know he\rquote s so arrogant that criticism simply bounces off him,\rdblquote  Snape said sleekly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Sirius pushed his chair roughly aside and strode around the table toward Snape, pulling out his wand as he went; Snape whipped out his own. They were squaring up to each other, Sirius looking livid, Snape calculating, his eyes darting from Sirius\rquote s wand tip to his face.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sirius!\rdblquote  said Harry loudly, but Sirius appeared not to hear him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote ve warned you, \i Snivellus,\i0\rdblquote\i  \i0 said Sirius, his face barely a foot from Snape\rquote s, \ldblquote I don\rquote t care if Dumbledore thinks you\rquote ve reformed, I know better \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, but why don\rquote t you tell him so?\rdblquote  whispered Snape. \ldblquote Or are you afraid he might not take the advice of a man who has been hiding in\-side his mother\rquote s house for six months very seriously?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Tell me, how is Lucius Malfoy these days? I expect he\rquote s delighted his lapdog\rquote s working at Hogwarts, isn\rquote t he?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Speaking of dogs,\rdblquote  said Snape softly, \ldblquote did you know that Lucius Malfoy recognized you last time you risked a little jaunt outside? Clever idea, Black, getting yourself seen on a safe station platform \'85 gave you a cast-iron excuse not to leave your hidey-hole in future, didn\rquote t it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Sirius raised his wand.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote NO!\rdblquote  Harry yelled, vaulting over the table and trying to get in be\-tween them, \ldblquote Sirius, don\rquote t \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Are you calling me a coward?\rdblquote  roared Sirius, trying to push Harry out of the way, but Harry would not budge.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Why, yes, I suppose I am,\rdblquote  said Snape.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry \emdash  get \emdash  out \emdash  of\lang3081  \lang1033\emdash  it!\rdblquote  snarled Sirius, pushing him out of the way with his free hand.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The kitchen door opened and the entire Weasley family, plus Hermione, came inside, all looking very happy, with Mr. Weasley walking proudly in their midst dressed in a pair of striped pajamas covered by a mackintosh.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Cured!\rdblquote  he announced brightly to the kitchen at large. \ldblquote Com\-pletely cured!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He and all the other Weasleys froze on the threshold, gazing at the scene in front of them, which was also suspended in mid-action, both Sirius and Snape looking toward the door with their wands pointing into each other\rquote s faces and Harry immobile between them, a hand stretched out to each of them, trying to force them apart.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Merlin\rquote s beard,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, the smile sliding off his face, \ldblquote what\rquote s going on here?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Both Sirius and Snape lowered their wands. Harry looked from one to the other. Each wore an expression of utmost contempt, yet the unexpected entrance of so many witnesses seemed to have brought them to their senses. Snape pocketed his wand and swept back across the kitchen, passing the Weasleys without comment. At the door he looked back.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Six o\rquote clock Monday evening, Potter.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He was gone. Sirius glared after him, his wand at his side.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But what\rquote s been going on?\rdblquote  asked Mr. Weasley again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Nothing, Arthur,\rdblquote  said Sirius, who was breathing heavily as though he had just run a long distance. \ldblquote Just a friendly little chat between two old school friends. \'85\rdblquote  With what looked like an enormous effort, he smiled. \ldblquote So \'85 you\rquote re cured? That\rquote s great news, really great. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, isn\rquote t it?\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley, leading her husband forward into a chair. \ldblquote Healer Smethwyck worked his magic in the end, found an antidote to whatever that snake\rquote s got in its fangs, and Arthur\rquote s learned his lesson about dabbling in Muggle medicine, \i haven\rquote t you, dear\i0 ?\rdblquote  she added, rather menacingly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, Molly dear,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley meekly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 That night\rquote s meal should have been a cheerful one with Mr. Weasley back amongst them; Harry could tell Sirius was trying to make it so, yet when his godfather was not forcing himself to laugh loudly at Fred and George\rquote s jokes or offering everyone more food, his face fell back into a moody, brooding expression. Harry was separated from him by Mundungus and Mad-Eye, who had dropped in to offer Mr. Weasley their congratulations; he wanted to talk to Sirius, to tell him that he should not listen to a word Snape said, that Snape was goading him deliberately and that the rest of them did not think Sir\-ius was a coward for doing as Dumbledore told him and remaining in Grimmauld Place, but he had no opportunity to do so, and wondered occasionally, eyeing the ugly look on Sirius\rquote s face, whether he would have dared to even if he had the chance. Instead he told Ron and Hermione under his voice about having to take Occlumency lessons with Snape.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Dumbledore wants to stop you having those dreams about Volde\-mort,\rdblquote  said Hermione at once. \ldblquote Well, you won\rquote t be sorry not to have them anymore, will you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Extra lessons with Snape?\rdblquote  said Ron, sounding aghast. \ldblquote I\rquote d rather have the nightmares!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They were to return to Hogwarts on the Knight Bus the following day, escorted once again by Tonks and Lupin, both of whom were eat\-ing breakfast in the kitchen when Harry, Ron, and Hermione arrived there next morning. The adults seemed to have been midway through a whispered conversation when the door opened; all of them looked around hastily and fell silent.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 After a hurried breakfast they pulled on jackets and scarves against the chilly gray January morning. Harry had an unpleasant constricted sensation in his chest; he did not want to say good-bye to Sirius. He had a bad feeling about this parting; he did not know when they would next see each other and felt that it was incumbent upon him to say something to Sirius to stop him doing anything stupid \emdash  Harry was worried that Snape\rquote s accusation of cowardice had stung Sirius so badly he might even now be planning some foolhardy trip beyond Grimmauld Place. Before he could think of what to say, however, Sir\-ius had beckoned him to his side.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I want you to take this,\rdblquote  he said quietly, thrusting a badly wrapped package roughly the size of a paperback book into Harry\rquote s hands.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What is it?\rdblquote  Harry asked.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote A way of letting me know if Snape\rquote s giving you a hard time. No, don\rquote t open it in here!\rdblquote  said Sirius, with a wary look at Mrs. Weasley, who was trying to persuade the twins to wear hand-knitted mittens. \ldblquote I doubt Molly would approve \emdash  but I want you to use it if you need me, all right?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Okay,\rdblquote  said Harry, stowing the package away in the inside pocket of his jacket, but he knew he would never use whatever it was. It would not be he, Harry, who lured Sirius from his place of safety, no matter how foully Snape treated him in their forthcoming Occlu\-mency classes.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Let\rquote s go, then,\rdblquote  said Sirius, clapping Harry on the shoulder and smiling grimly, and before Harry could say anything else, they were heading upstairs, stopping before the heavily chained and bolted front door, surrounded by Weasleys.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Good-bye, Harry, take care,\rdblquote  said Mrs. Weasley, hugging him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote See you Harry, and keep an eye out for snakes for me!\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley genially, shaking his hand.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Right \emdash  yeah,\rdblquote  said Harry distractedly. It was his last chance to tell Sirius to be careful; he turned, looked into his godfather\rquote s face and\lang3081  \lang1033 opened his mouth to speak, but before he could do so Sirius was giv\-ing him a brief, one-armed hug. He said gruffly, \ldblquote Look after yourself, Harry,\rdblquote  and next moment Harry found himself being shunted out into the icy winter air, with Tonks (today heavily disguised as a tall, tweedy woman with iron-gray hair) chivvying him down the steps.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The door of number twelve slammed shut behind them. They fol\-lowed Lupin down the front steps. As he reached the pavement, Harry looked around. Number twelve was shrinking rapidly as those on ei\-ther side of it stretched sideways, squeezing it out of sight; one blink later, it had gone.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Come on, the quicker we get on the bus the better,\rdblquote  said Tonks, and Harry thought there was nervousness in the glance she threw around the square. Lupin flung out his right arm.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 BANG.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A violently purple, triple-decker bus had appeared out of thin air in front of them, narrowly avoiding the nearest lamppost, which jumped backward out of its way.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A thin, pimply, jug-eared youth in a purple uniform leapt down onto the pavement and said, \ldblquote Welcome to the \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, yes, we know, thank you,\rdblquote  said Tonks swiftly. \ldblquote On, on, get on \emdash\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And she shoved Harry forward toward the steps, past the conduc\-tor, who goggled at Harry as he passed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \rquote Ere \emdash  it\rquote s \rquote Arry \emdash  !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote If you shout his name I will curse you into oblivion,\rdblquote  muttered Tonks menacingly, now shunting Ginny and Hermione forward.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote ve always wanted to go on this thing,\rdblquote  said Ron happily, joining Harry on board and looking around.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It had been evening the last time Harry had traveled by Knight Bus and its three decks had been full of brass bedsteads. Now, in the early morning, it was crammed with an assortment of mismatched chairs\lang3081  \lang1033 grouped haphazardly around windows. Some of these appeared to have fallen over when the bus stopped abruptly in Grimmauld Place; a few witches and wizards were still getting to their feet, grumbling, and somebody\rquote s shopping bag had slid the length of the bus; an un\-pleasant mixture of frog spawn, cockroaches, and custard creams was scattered all over the floor.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Looks like we\rquote ll have to split up,\rdblquote  said Tonics briskly, looking around for empty chairs. \ldblquote Fred, George, and Ginny, if you just take those seats at the back \'85 Remus can stay with you. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She, Harry, Ron, and Hermione proceeded up to the very top deck, where there were two chairs at the very front of the bus and two at the back. Stan Shunpike, the conductor, followed Harry and Ron eagerly to the back. Heads turned as Harry passed and when he sat down, he saw all the faces flick back to the front again.\lang3081\par
