\lang1033 This latest decree had been the subject of a great number of jokes among the students. Lee Jordan had pointed out to Umbridge that by the terms of the new rule she was not allowed to tell Fred and George off for playing Exploding Snap in the back of the class.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Exploding Snap\rquote s got nothing to do with Defense Against the Dark Arts, Professor! That\rquote s not information relating to your subject!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 When Harry next saw Lee, the back of his hand was bleeding rather badly. Harry recommended essence of murtlap.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry had thought that the breakout from Azkaban might have humbled Umbridge a little, that she might have been abashed at the catastrophe that had occurred right under her beloved Fudge\rquote s nose. It seemed, however, to have only intensified her furious desire to bring every aspect of life at Hogwarts under her personal control. She\lang3081  \lang1033 seemed determined at the very least to achieve a sacking before long, and the only question was whether it would be Professor Trelawney or Hagrid who went first.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Every single Divination and Care of Magical Creatures lesson was now conducted in the presence of Umbridge and her clipboard. She lurked by the fire in the heavily perfumed tower room, interrupting Professor Trelawney\rquote s increasingly hysterical talks with difficult ques\-tions about Ornithomancy and Heptomology, insisting that she pre\-dict students\rquote  answers before they gave them and demanding that she demonstrate her skill at the crystal ball, the tea leaves, and the rune stones in turn. Harry thought that Professor Trelawney might soon crack under the strain; several times he passed her in the corridors (in itself a very unusual occurrence as she generally remained in her tower room), muttering wildly to herself, wringing her hands, and shooting terrified glances over her shoulder, all the time giving off a powerful smell of cooking sherry. If he had not been so worried about Hagrid, he would have felt sorry for her \emdash  but if one of them was to be ousted out of a job, there could be only one choice for Harry as to who should remain.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Unfortunately, Harry could not see that Hagrid was putting up a better show than Trelawney. Though he seemed to be following Her\-mione\rquote s advice and had shown them nothing more frightening than a crup, a creature indistinguishable from a Jack Russell terrier except for its forked tail, since before Christmas, he also seemed to have lost his nerve. He was oddly distracted and jumpy in lessons, losing the thread of what he was saying while talking to the class, answering questions wrongly and glancing anxiously at Umbridge all the time. He was also more distant with Harry, Ron, and Hermione than he had ever been before, expressly forbidding them to visit him after dark.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote If she catches yeh, it\rquote ll be all of our necks on the line,\rdblquote  he told them flatly, and with no desire to do anything that jeopardized his job further, they abstained from walking down to his hut in the evenings.\lang3081  \lang1033 It seemed to Harry that Umbridge was steadily depriving him of everything that made his life at Hogwarts worth living: visits to Ha\-grid\rquote s house, letters from Sirius, his Firebolt, and Quidditch. He took his revenge the only way he had: redoubling his efforts for the D.A.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry was pleased to see that all of them, even Zacharias Smith, had been spurred to work harder than ever by the news that ten more Death Eaters were now on the loose, but in nobody was this improve\-ment more pronounced than in Neville. The news of his parents\rquote  at\-tacker\rquote s escape had wrought a strange and even slightly alarming change in him. He had not once mentioned his meeting with Harry, Ron, and Hermione on the closed ward in St. Mungo\rquote s, and taking their lead from him, they had kept quiet about it too. Nor had he said anything on the subject of Bellatrix and her fellow torturers\rquote  escape; in fact, he barely spoke during D.A. meetings anymore, but worked re\-lentlessly on every new jinx and countercurse Harry taught them, his plump face screwed up in concentration, apparently indifferent to in\-juries or accidents, working harder than anyone else in the room. He was improving so fast it was quite unnerving and when Harry taught them the Shield Charm, a means of deflecting minor jinxes so that they rebounded upon the attacker, only Hermione mastered the charm faster than Neville.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 In fact Harry would have given a great deal to be making as much progress at Occlumency as Neville was making during D.A. meetings. Harry\rquote s sessions with Snape, which had started badly enough, were not improving; on the contrary, Harry felt he was getting worse with every lesson.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Before he had started studying Occlumency, his scar had prickled occasionally, usually during the night, or else following one of those strange flashes of Voldemort\rquote s thoughts or moods that he experienced every now and then. Nowadays, however, his scar hardly ever stopped prickling, and he often felt lurches of annoyance or cheerfulness that were unrelated to what was happening to him at the time, which were\lang3081  \lang1033 always accompanied by a particularly painful twinge from his scar. He had the horrible impression that he was slowly turning into a kind of aerial that was tuned in to tiny fluctuations in Voldemort\rquote s mood, and he was sure he could date this increased sensitivity firmly from his first Occlumency lesson with Snape. What was more, he was now dream\-ing about walking down the corridor toward the entrance to the Department of Mysteries almost every night, dreams that always cul\-minated in him standing longingly in front of the plain black door.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Maybe it\rquote s a bit like an illness,\rdblquote  said Hermione, looking concerned when Harry confided in her and Ron. \ldblquote A fever or something. It has to get worse before it gets better.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s lessons with Snape that are making it worse,\rdblquote  said Harry flatly. \ldblquote I\rquote m getting sick of my scar hurting, and I\rquote m getting bored walking down that corridor every night.\rdblquote  He rubbed his forehead angrily. \ldblquote I just wish the door would open, I\rquote m sick of standing staring at it \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That\rquote s not funny,\rdblquote  said Hermione sharply. \ldblquote Dumbledore doesn\rquote t want you to have dreams about that corridor at all, or he wouldn\rquote t have asked Snape to teach you Occlumency. You\rquote re just going to have to work a bit harder in your lessons.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I am working!\rdblquote  said Harry, nettled. \ldblquote You try it sometime, Snape trying to get inside your head, it\rquote s not a bundle of laughs, you know!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Maybe \'85\rdblquote  said Ron slowly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Maybe what?\rdblquote  said Hermione rather snappishly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Maybe it\rquote s not Harry\rquote s fault he can\rquote t close his mind,\rdblquote  said Ron darkly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What do you mean?\rdblquote  said Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, maybe Snape isn\rquote t really trying to help Harry. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry and Hermione stared at him. Ron looked darkly and mean\-ingfully from one to the other.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Maybe,\rdblquote  he said again in a lower voice, \ldblquote he\rquote s actually trying to open Harry\rquote s mind a bit wider \'85 make it easier for You-Know \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Shut up, Ron,\rdblquote  said Hermione angrily. \ldblquote How many times have\lang3081  \lang1033 you suspected Snape, and when have you \i ever\i0  been right? Dumble\-dore trusts him, he works for the Order, that ought to be enough.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He used to be a Death Eater,\rdblquote  said Ron stubbornly. \ldblquote And we\rquote ve never seen proof that he \i really\i0  swapped sides. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Dumbledore trusts him,\rdblquote  Hermione repeated. \ldblquote And if we can\rquote t trust Dumbledore, we can\rquote t trust anyone.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
