\lang1033 And she hurried out of the Great Hall, the letter clutched in one hand and a piece of uneaten toast in the other.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Are you coming?\rdblquote  Harry asked Ron, but he shook his head, look\-ing glum.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I can\rquote t come into Hogsmeade at all, Angelina wants a full day\rquote s training. Like it\rquote s going to help \emdash  we\rquote re the worst team I\rquote ve ever seen. You should see Sloper and Kirke, they\rquote re pathetic, even worse than I am.\rdblquote  He heaved a great sigh. \ldblquote I dunno why Angelina won\rquote t just let me resign. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s because you\rquote re good when you\rquote re on form, that\rquote s why,\rdblquote  said Harry irritably.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He found it very hard to be sympathetic to Ron\rquote s plight when he himself would have given almost anything to be playing in the forth\-coming match against Hufflepuff. Ron seemed to notice Harry\rquote s tone, because he did not mention Quidditch again during breakfast, and there was a slight frostiness in the way they said good-bye to each other shortly afterward. Ron departed for the Quidditch pitch and Harry, after attempting to flatten his hair while staring at his reflection in the back of a teaspoon, proceeded alone to the entrance hall to meet Cho, feeling very apprehensive and wondering what on earth they were going to talk about.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She was waiting for him a little to the side of the oak front doors, looking very pretty with her hair tied back in a long ponytail. Harry\rquote s feet seemed to be too big for his body as he walked toward her, and he was suddenly horribly aware of his arms and how stupid they looked swinging at his sides.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hi,\rdblquote  said Cho slightly breathlessly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hi,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They stared at each other for a moment, then Harry said, \ldblquote Well \emdash  er \emdash  shall we go, then?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh \emdash  yes \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They joined the queue of people being signed out by Filch, occa\-sionally catching each other\rquote s eye and grinning shiftily, but not talking to each other. Harry was relieved when they reached the fresh air, find\-ing it easier to walk along in silence than just stand there looking awk\-ward. It was a fresh, breezy sort of day and as they passed the Quidditch stadium, Harry glimpsed Ron and Ginny skimming over the stands and felt a horrible pang that he was not up there with them. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You really miss it, don\rquote t you?\rdblquote  said Cho.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He looked around and saw her watching him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah,\rdblquote  sighed Harry. \ldblquote I do.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Remember the first time we played against each other, in the third year?\rdblquote  she asked him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah,\rdblquote  said Harry, grinning. \ldblquote You kept blocking me.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And Wood told you not to be a gentleman and knock me off my broom if you had to,\rdblquote  said Cho, smiling reminiscently. \ldblquote I heard he got taken on by Pride of Portree, is that right?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Nah, it was Puddlemere United, I saw him at the World Cup last year.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, I saw you there too, remember? We were on the same camp\-site. It was really good, wasn\rquote t it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The subject of the Quidditch World Cup carried them all the way down the drive and out through the gates. Harry could hardly believe how easy it was to talk to her, no more difficult, in fact, than talking to Ron and Hermione, and he was just starting to feel confident and cheerful when a large gang of Slytherin girls passed them, including Pansy Parkinson.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Potter and Chang!\rdblquote  screeched Pansy to a chorus of snide giggles. \ldblquote Urgh, Chang, I don\rquote t think much of your taste. \'85 At least Diggory was good-looking!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They sped up, talking and shrieking in a pointed fashion with many exaggerated glances back at Harry and Cho, leaving an embar\-rassed silence in their wake. Harry could think of nothing else to say about Quidditch, and Cho, slightly flushed, was watching her feet.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So \'85 where d\rquote you want to go?\rdblquote  Harry asked as they entered Hogsmeade. The High Street was full of students ambling up and down, peering into the shop windows and messing about together on the pavements.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh \'85 I don\rquote t mind,\rdblquote  said Cho, shrugging. \ldblquote Um \'85 shall we just have a look in the shops or something?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They wandered toward Dervish and Banges. A large poster had been stuck up in the window and a few Hogsmeaders were looking at it. They moved aside when Harry and Cho approached and Harry found himself staring once more at the ten pictures of the escaped Death Eaters. The poster (\ldblquote By Order of the Ministry of Magic\rdblquote ) of\-fered a thousand-Galleon reward to any witch or wizard with infor\-mation relating to the recapture of any of the convicts pictured.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s funny, isn\rquote t it,\rdblquote  said Cho in a low voice, also gazing up at the pictures of the Death Eaters. \ldblquote Remember when that Sirius Black es\-caped, and there were dementors all over Hogsmeade looking for him? And now ten Death Eaters are on the loose and there aren\rquote t de-mentors anywhere. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah,\rdblquote  said Harry, tearing his eyes away from Bellatrix Lestrange\rquote s face to glance up and down the High Street. \ldblquote Yeah, it is weird. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He was not sorry that there were no dementors nearby, but now he came to think of it, their absence was highly significant. They had not only let the Death Eaters escape, they were not bothering to look for them. \'85 It looked as though they really were outside Ministry con\-trol now.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The ten escaped Death Eaters were staring out of every shop window he and Cho passed. It started to rain as they passed Scrivenshaft\rquote s; cold, heavy drops of water kept hitting Harry\rquote s face and the back of his neck.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Um \'85 d\rquote you want to get a coffee?\rdblquote  said Cho tentatively, as the rain began to fall more heavily.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, all right,\rdblquote  said Harry, looking around. \ldblquote Where \emdash  ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, there\rquote s a really nice place just up here, haven\rquote t you ever been to Madam Puddifoot\rquote s?\rdblquote  she said brightly, and she led him up a side road and into a small tea shop that Harry had never noticed before. It was a cramped, steamy little place where everything seemed to have been decorated with frills or bows. Harry was reminded unpleasantly of Umbridge\rquote s office.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Cute, isn\rquote t it?\rdblquote  said Cho happily.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Er \'85 yeah,\rdblquote  said Harry untruthfully.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Look, she\rquote s decorated it for Valentine\rquote s Day!\rdblquote  said Cho, indicating a number of golden cherubs that were hovering over each of the small, circular tables, occasionally throwing pink confetti over the occupants.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Aaah \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They sat down at the last remaining table, which was situated in the steamy window. Roger Davies, the Ravenclaw Quidditch Captain, was sitting about a foot and a half away with a pretty blonde girl. They were holding hands. The sight made Harry feel uncomfortable, par\-ticularly when, looking around the tea shop, he saw that it was full of nothing but couples, all of them holding hands. Perhaps Cho would expect him to hold \i her\i0  hand.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What can I get you, m\rquote dears?\rdblquote  said Madam Puddifoot, a very stout woman with a shiny black bun, squeezing between their table and Roger Davies\rquote s with great difficulty.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Two coffees, please,\rdblquote  said Cho.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 In the time it took for their coffees to arrive, Roger Davies and his girlfriend started kissing over their sugar bowl. Harry wished they wouldn\rquote t; he felt that Davies was setting a standard with which Cho\lang3081  \lang1033 would soon expect him to compete. He felt his face growing hot and tried staring out of the window, but it was so steamed up he could not see the street outside. To postpone the moment when he had to look at Cho he stared up at the ceiling as though examining the paintwork and received a handful of confetti in the face from their hovering cherub.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 After a few more painful minutes Cho mentioned Umbridge; Harry seized on the subject with relief and they passed a few happy moments abusing her, but the subject had already been so thoroughly canvassed during D.A. meetings it did not last very long. Silence fell again. Harry was very conscious of the slurping noises coming from the table next door and cast wildly around for something else to say.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Er \'85 listen, d\rquote you want to come with me to the Three Broom\-sticks at lunchtime? I\rquote m meeting Hermione Granger there.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Cho raised her eyebrows.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote re meeting Hermione Granger? Today?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah. Well, she asked me to, so I thought I would. D\rquote you want to come with me? She said it wouldn\rquote t matter if you did.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh \'85 well\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 that was nice of her.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But Cho did not sound as though she thought it was nice at all; on the contrary, her tone was cold and all of a sudden she looked rather forbidding.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A few more minutes passed in total silence, Harry drinking his cof\-fee so fast that he would soon need a fresh cup. Next door, Roger Davies and his girlfriend seemed glued together by the lips.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Cho\rquote s hand was lying on the table beside her coffee, and Harry was feeling a mounting pressure to take hold of it. \i Just do it,\i0  he told him\-self, as a fount of mingled panic and excitement surged up inside his chest. \i Just reach out and grab it. \'85\i0  Amazing how much more difficult it was to extend his arm twelve inches and touch her hand than to snatch a speeding Snitch from midair \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But just as he moved his hand forward, Cho took hers off the table.\lang3081  \lang1033 She was now watching Roger Davies kissing his girlfriend with a mildly interested expression.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He asked me out, you know,\rdblquote  she said in a quiet voice. \ldblquote A couple of weeks ago. Roger. I turned him down, though.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry, who had grabbed the sugar bowl to excuse his sudden lung\-ing movement across the table, could not think why she was telling him this. If she wished she were sitting at the table next door being heartily kissed by Roger Davies, why had she agreed to come out with him?\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He said nothing. Their cherub threw another handful of confetti over them; some of it landed in the last cold dregs of coffee Harry had been about to drink.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I came in here with Cedric last year,\rdblquote  said Cho.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 In the second or so it took for him to take in what she had said, Harry\rquote s insides had become glacial. He could not believe she wanted to talk about Cedric now, while kissing couples surrounded them and a cherub floated over their heads.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Cho\rquote s voice was rather higher when she spoke again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote ve been meaning to ask you for ages. \'85 Did Cedric \emdash  did he m-m-mention me at all before he died?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 This was the very last subject on earth Harry wanted to discuss, and least of all with Cho.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well \emdash  no \emdash\rdblquote  he said quietly. \ldblquote There \emdash  there wasn\rquote t time for him to say anything. Erm \'85 so \'85 d\rquote you \'85 d\rquote you get to see a lot of Quidditch in the holidays? You support the Tornados, right?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 His voice sounded falsely bright and cheery. To his horror, he saw that her eyes were swimming with tears again, just as they had been af\-ter the last D.A. meeting before Christmas.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Look,\rdblquote  he said desperately, leaning in so that nobody else could overhear, \ldblquote let\rquote s not talk about Cedric right now. \'85 Let\rquote s talk about something else. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But this, apparently, was quite the wrong thing to say.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I thought,\rdblquote  she said, tears spattering down onto the table. \ldblquote I thought \i you\rquote d\i0  u-u-understand! I \i need\i0  to talk about it! Surely you n-need to talk about it t-too! I mean, you saw it happen, d-didn\rquote t you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Everything was going nightmarishly wrong; Roger Davies\rquote  girl\-friend had even unglued herself to look around at Cho crying.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well \emdash  I have talked about it,\rdblquote  Harry said in a whisper, \ldblquote to Ron and Hermione, but \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, you\rquote ll talk to Hermione Granger!\rdblquote  she said shrilly, her face now shining with tears, and several more kissing couples broke apart to stare. \ldblquote But you won\rquote t talk to me! P-perhaps it would be best if we just\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 just p-paid and you went and met up with Hermione G-Granger, like you obviously want to!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry stared at her, utterly bewildered, as she seized a frilly napkin and dabbed at her shining face with it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Cho?\rdblquote  he said weakly, wishing Roger would seize his girlfriend and start kissing her again to stop her goggling at him and Cho.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Go on, leave!\rdblquote  she said, now crying into the napkin. \ldblquote I don\rquote t know why you asked me out in the first place if you\rquote re going to make arrangements to meet other girls right after me. \'85 How many are you meeting after Hermione?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
