\lang1033 By \ldblquote they\rdblquote  he meant Dumbledore. He got back into bed and rolled over onto his side with his back to Ron and after a while he heard Ron\rquote s mattress creak as he lay back down too. His scar began to burn; he bit hard on his pillow to stop himself making a noise. Somewhere, he knew, Avery was being punished. \'85\lang3081\par
\par
\lang1033 Harry and Ron waited until break next morning to tell Hermione ex\-actly what had happened. They wanted to be absolutely sure they could not be overheard. Standing in their usual corner of the cool and\lang3081  \lang1033 breezy courtyard, Harry told her every detail of the dream he could remember. When he had finished, she said nothing at all for a few moments, but stared with a kind of painful intensity at Fred and George, who were both headless and selling their magical hats from under their cloaks on the other side of the yard.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So that\rquote s why they killed him,\rdblquote  she said quietly, withdrawing her gaze from Fred and George at last. \ldblquote When Bode tried to steal this weapon, something funny happened to him. I think there must be defensive spells on it, or around it, to stop people from touching it. That\rquote s why he was in St. Mungo\rquote s, his brain had gone all funny and he couldn\rquote t talk. But remember what the Healer told us? He was recov\-ering. And they couldn\rquote t risk him getting better, could they? I mean, the shock of whatever happened when he touched that weapon prob\-ably made the Imperius Curse lift. Once he\rquote d got his voice back, he\rquote d explain what he\rquote d been doing, wouldn\rquote t he? They would have known he\rquote d been sent to steal the weapon. Of course, it would have been easy for Lucius Malfoy to put the curse on him. Never out of the Ministry, is he?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He was even hanging around that day I had my hearing,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote In the \emdash  hang on \'85\rdblquote  he said slowly. \ldblquote He was in the De\-partment of Mysteries corridor that day! Your dad said he was proba\-bly trying to sneak down and find out what happened in my hearing, but what if\lang3081  \lang1033\emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sturgis,\rdblquote  gasped Hermione, looking thunderstruck.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sorry?\rdblquote  said Ron, looking bewildered.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sturgis Podmore,\rdblquote  said Hermione, breathlessly. \ldblquote Arrested for try\-ing to get through a door. Lucius Malfoy got him too. I bet he did it the day you saw him there, Harry. Sturgis had Moody\rquote s Invisibility Cloak, right? So what if he was standing guard by the door, invisible, and Malfoy heard him move, or guessed he was there, or just did the Imperius Curse on the off chance that a guard was there? So when Sturgis next had an opportunity \emdash  probably when it was his turn on\lang3081  \lang1033 guard duty again \emdash  he tried to get into the department to steal the weapon for Voldemort \emdash  Ron, be quiet \emdash  but he got caught and sent to Azkaban. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She gazed at Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And now Rookwood\rquote s told Voldemort how to get the weapon?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I didn\rquote t hear all the conversation, but that\rquote s what it sounded like,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote Rookwood used to work there. \'85 Maybe Voldemort\rquote ll send Rookwood to do it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione nodded, apparently still lost in thought. Then, quite abruptly, she said, \ldblquote But you shouldn\rquote t have seen this at all, Harry.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What?\rdblquote  he said, taken aback.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote re supposed to be learning how to close your mind to this sort of thing,\rdblquote  said Hermione, suddenly stern.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I know I am,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote But \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, I think we should just try and forget what you saw,\rdblquote  said Hermione firmly. \ldblquote And you ought to put in a bit more effort on your Occlumency from now on.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry was so angry with her that he did not talk to her for the rest of the day, which proved to be another bad one. When people were not discussing the escaped Death Eaters in the corridors today, they were laughing at Gryffindor\rquote s abysmal performance in their match against Hufflepuff; the Slytherins were singing \ldblquote Weasley Is Our King\rdblquote  so loudly and frequently that by sundown Filch had banned it from the corridors out of sheer irritation.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The week did not improve as it progressed: Harry received two more D\rquote s in Potions, was still on tenterhooks that Hagrid might get the sack, and could not stop himself from dwelling on the dream in which he had seen Voldemort, though he did not bring it up with Ron and Hermione again because he did not want another telling-off from Hermione. He wished very much that he could have talked to Sirius about it, but that was out of the question, so he tried to push the mat\-ter to the back of his mind.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Unfortunately, the back of his mind was no longer the secure place it had once been.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Get up, Potter.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A couple of weeks after his dream of Rookwood, Harry was to be found, yet again, kneeling on the floor of Snape\rquote s office, trying to clear his head. He had just been forced, yet again, to relive a stream of very early memories he had not even realized he still had, most of them concerning humiliations Dudley and his gang had inflicted upon him in primary school.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That last memory,\rdblquote  said Snape. \ldblquote What was it?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t know,\rdblquote  said Harry, getting wearily to his feet. He was find\-ing it increasingly difficult to disentangle separate memories from the rush of images and sound that Snape kept calling forth. \ldblquote You mean the one where my cousin tried to make me stand in the toilet?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Snape softly. \ldblquote I mean the one concerning a man kneel\-ing in the middle of a darkened room. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s \'85 nothing,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Snape\rquote s dark eyes bored into Harry\rquote s. Remembering what Snape had said about eye contact being crucial to Legilimency, Harry blinked and looked away.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How do that man and that room come to be inside your head, Potter?\rdblquote  said Snape.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It \emdash\rdblquote  said Harry, looking everywhere but at Snape, \ldblquote it was \emdash  just a dream I had.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
