\lang1033 There was a pause during which Harry stared fixedly at a large dead frog suspended in a purple liquid in its jar.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You do know why we are here, don\rquote t you, Potter?\rdblquote  said Snape in a low, dangerous voice. \ldblquote You do know why I am giving up my evenings to this tedious job?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Harry stiffly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Remind me why we are here, Potter.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So I can learn Occlumency,\rdblquote  said Harry, now glaring at a dead eel.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Correct, Potter. And dim though you may be\rdblquote  \emdash  Harry looked back at Snape, hating him \emdash  \ldblquote I would have thought that after two months\rquote  worth of lessons you might have made some progress. How many other dreams about the Dark Lord have you had?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Just that one,\rdblquote  lied Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Perhaps,\rdblquote  said Snape, his dark, cold eyes narrowing slightly, \ldblquote per\-haps you actually enjoy having these visions and dreams, Potter. Maybe they make you feel special \emdash  important?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, they don\rquote t,\rdblquote  said Harry, his jaw set and his fingers clenched tightly around the handle of his wand.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That is just as well, Potter,\rdblquote  said Snape coldly, \ldblquote because you are neither special nor important, and it is not up to you to find out what the Dark Lord is saying to his Death Eaters.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No \emdash  that\rquote s your job, isn\rquote t it?\rdblquote  Harry shot at him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He had not meant to say it; it had burst out of him in temper. For a long moment they stared at each other, Harry convinced he had gone too far. But there was a curious, almost satisfied expression on Snape\rquote s face when he answered.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, Potter,\rdblquote  he said, his eyes glinting. \ldblquote That is my job. Now, if you are ready, we will start again. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He raised his wand. \ldblquote One \emdash  two \emdash  three \emdash  \i Legilimens\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A hundred dementors were swooping toward Harry across the lake in the grounds. \'85 He screwed up his face in concentration. \'85 They were coming closer. \'85 He could see the dark holes beneath their hoods \'85 yet he could also see Snape standing in front of him, his eyes fixed upon Harry\rquote s face, muttering under his breath. \'85 And somehow, Snape was growing clearer, and the dementors were grow\-ing fainter \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry raised his own wand.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Protego\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Snape staggered; his wand flew upward, away from Harry \emdash  and\lang3081  \lang1033 suddenly Harry\rquote s mind was teeming with memories that were not his \emdash  a hook-nosed man was shouting at a cowering woman, while a small dark-haired boy cried in a corner. \'85 A greasy-haired teenager sat alone in a dark bedroom, pointing his wand at the ceiling, shoot\-ing down flies. \'85 A girl was laughing as a scrawny boy tried to mount a bucking broomstick \emdash\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote ENOUGH!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry felt as though he had been pushed hard in the chest; he took several staggering steps backward, hit some of the shelves covering Snape\rquote s walls and heard something crack. Snape was shaking slightly, very white in the face.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The back of Harry\rquote s robes were damp. One of the jars behind him had broken when he fell against it; the pickled slimy thing within was swirling in its draining potion.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Reparo\i0 !\rdblquote  hissed Snape, and the jar sealed itself once more. \ldblquote Well, Potter \'85 that was certainly an improvement. \'85\rdblquote  Panting slightly, Snape straightened the Pensieve in which he had again stored some of his thoughts before starting the lesson, almost as though checking that they were still there. \ldblquote I don\rquote t remember telling you to use a Shield Charm \'85 but there is no doubt that it was effective. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry did not speak; he felt that to say anything might be danger\-ous. He was sure he had just broken into Snape\rquote s memories, that he had just seen scenes from Snape\rquote s childhood, and it was unnerving to think that the crying little boy who had watched his parents shouting was ac\-tually standing in front of him with such loathing in his eyes. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Let\rquote s try again, shall we?\rdblquote  said Snape.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry felt a thrill of dread: He was about to pay for what had just happened, he was sure of it. They moved back into position with the desk between them, Harry feeling he was going to find it much harder to empty his mind this time. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote On the count of three, then,\rdblquote  said Snape, raising his wand once more. \ldblquote One \emdash  two \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry did not have time to gather himself together and attempt to clear his mind, for Snape had already cried \ldblquote\i Legilimens\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He was hurtling along the corridor toward the Department of Mys\-teries, past the blank stone walls, past the torches \emdash  the plain black door was growing ever larger; he was moving so fast he was going to collide with it, he was feet from it and he could see that chink of faint blue light again \emdash\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The door had flown open! He was through it at last, inside a black-walled, black-floored circular room lit with blue-flamed candles, and there were more doors all around him \emdash  he needed to go on \emdash  but which door ought he to take \emdash  ?\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote POTTER!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry opened his eyes. He was flat on his back again with no memory of having gotten there; he was also panting as though he re\-ally had run the length of the Department of Mysteries corridor, really had sprinted through the black door and found the circular room. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Explain yourself!\rdblquote  said Snape, who was standing over him, look\-ing furious.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I \'85 dunno what happened,\rdblquote  said Harry truthfully, standing up. There was a lump on the back of his head from where he had hit the ground and he felt feverish. \ldblquote I\rquote ve never seen that before. I mean, I told you, I\rquote ve dreamed about the door \'85 but it\rquote s never opened before. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You are not working hard enough!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 For some reason, Snape seemed even angrier than he had done two minutes before, when Harry had seen into his own memories.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You are lazy and sloppy, Potter, it is small wonder that the Dark Lord \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Can you tell me something, \i sir\i0 ?\rdblquote  said Harry, firing up again. \ldblquote Why do you call Voldemort the Dark Lord, I\rquote ve only ever heard Death Eaters call him that \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Snape opened his mouth in a snarl \emdash  and a woman screamed from somewhere outside the room.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Snape\rquote s head jerked upward; he was gazing at the ceiling.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What the \emdash  ?\rdblquote  he muttered.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry could hear a muffled commotion coming from what he thought might be the entrance hall. Snape looked around at him, frowning.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Did you see anything unusual on your way down here, Potter?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry shook his head. Somewhere above them, the woman screamed again. Snape strode to his office door, his wand still held at the ready, and swept out of sight. Harry hesitated for a moment, then followed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The screams were indeed coming from the entrance hall; they grew louder as Harry ran toward the stone steps leading up from the dun\-geons. When he reached the top he found the entrance hall packed. Students had come flooding out of the Great Hall, where dinner was still in progress, to see what was going on. Others had crammed them\-selves onto the marble staircase. Harry pushed forward through a knot of tall Slytherins and saw that the onlookers had formed a great ring, some of them looking shocked, others even frightened. Professor McGonagall was directly opposite Harry on the other side of the hall; she looked as though what she was watching made her feel faintly sick.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Professor Trelawney was standing in the middle of the entrance hall with her wand in one hand and an empty sherry bottle in the other, looking utterly mad. Her hair was sticking up on end, her glasses were lopsided so that one eye was magnified more than the other; her in\-numerable shawls and scarves were trailing haphazardly from her shoulders, giving the impression that she was falling apart at the seams. Two large trunks lay on the floor beside her, one of them up\-side down; it looked very much as though it had been thrown down the stairs after her. Professor Trelawney was staring, apparently terri\-fied, at something Harry could not see but that seemed to be standing at the foot of the stairs.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No!\rdblquote  she shrieked. \ldblquote NO! This cannot be happening. \'85 It cannot \'85 I refuse to accept it!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You didn\rquote t realize this was coming?\rdblquote  said a high girlish voice, sounding callously amused, and Harry, moving slightly to his right, saw that Trelawney\rquote s terrifying vision was nothing other than Professor Umbridge. \ldblquote Incapable though you are of predicting even tomorrow\rquote s weather, you must surely have realized that your pitiful performance during my inspections, and lack of any improvement, would make it inevitable you would be sacked?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You c-can\rquote t!\rdblquote  howled Professor Trelawney, tears streaming down her face from behind her enormous lenses, \ldblquote you c-can\rquote t sack me! I\rquote ve b-been here sixteen years! H-Hogwarts is m-my h-home!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It \i was\i0  your home,\rdblquote  said Professor Umbridge, and Harry was re\-volted to see the enjoyment stretching her toadlike face as she watched Professor Trelawney sink, sobbing uncontrollably, onto one of her trunks, \ldblquote until an hour ago, when the Minister of Magic countersigned the order for your dismissal. Now kindly remove yourself from this hall. You are embarrassing us.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But she stood and watched, with an expression of gloating enjoy\-ment, as Professor Trelawney shuddered and moaned, rocking back\-ward and forward on her trunk in paroxysms of grief. Harry heard a sob to his left and looked around. Lavender and Parvati were both cry\-ing silently, their arms around each other. Then he heard footsteps. Professor McGonagall had broken away from the spectators, marched straight up to Professor Trelawney and was patting her firmly on the back while withdrawing a large handkerchief from within her robes.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote There, there, Sibyll\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 Calm down. \'85 Blow your nose on this. \'85 It\rquote s not as bad as you think, now. \'85 You are not going to have to leave Hogwarts. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh really, Professor McGonagall?\rdblquote  said Umbridge in a deadly voice, taking a few steps forward. \ldblquote And your authority for that state\-ment is \'85 ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That would be mine,\rdblquote  said a deep voice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The oak front doors had swung open. Students beside them scut\-tled out of the way as Dumbledore appeared in the entrance. What he had been doing out in the grounds Harry could not imagine, but there was something impressive about the sight of him framed in the doorway against an oddly misty night. Leaving the doors wide behind him, he strode forward through the circle of onlookers toward the place where Professor Trelawney sat, tearstained and trembling, upon her trunk, Professor McGonagall alongside her.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yours, Professor Dumbledore?\rdblquote  said Umbridge with a singularly unpleasant little laugh. \ldblquote I\rquote m afraid you do not understand the posi\-tion. I have here\rdblquote  \emdash  she pulled a parchment scroll from within her robes \emdash  \ldblquote an Order of Dismissal signed by myself and the Minister of Magic. Under the terms of Educational Decree Number Twenty-three, the High Inquisitor of Hogwarts has the power to inspect, place upon probation, and sack any teacher she \emdash  that is to say, I \emdash  feel is not performing up to the standard required by the Ministry of Magic. I have decided that Professor Trelawney is not up to scratch. I have dis\-missed her.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 To Harry\rquote s very great surprise, Dumbledore continued to smile. He looked down at Professor Trelawney, who was still sobbing and chok\-ing on her trunk, and said, \ldblquote You are quite right, of course, Professor Umbridge. As High Inquisitor you have every right to dismiss my teachers. You do not, however, have the authority to send them away from the castle. I am afraid,\rdblquote  he went on, with a courteous little bow, \ldblquote that the power to do that still resides with the headmaster, and it is my wish that Professor Trelawney continue to live at Hogwarts.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 At this, Professor Trelawney gave a wild little laugh in which a hic\-cup was barely hidden.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No \emdash  no, I\rquote ll g-go, Dumbledore! I sh-shall l-leave Hogwarts and s-seek my fortune elsewhere \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore sharply. \ldblquote It is my wish that you remain, Sibyll.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He turned to Professor McGonagall.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Might I ask you to escort Sibyll back upstairs, Professor McGonagall?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Of course,\rdblquote  said McGonagall. \ldblquote Up you get, Sibyll. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Professor Sprout came hurrying forward out of the crowd and grabbed Professor Trelawney\rquote s other arm. Together they guided her past Umbridge and up the marble stairs. Professor Flitwick went scur\-rying after them, his wand held out before him; he squeaked, \ldblquote\i Loco\-motor trunks\i0 !\rdblquote  and Professor Trelawney\rquote s luggage rose into the air and proceeded up the staircase after her, Professor Flitwick bringing up the rear.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Professor Umbridge was standing stock-still, staring at Dumble\-dore, who continued to smile benignly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And what,\rdblquote  she said in a whisper that nevertheless carried all around the entrance hall, \ldblquote are you going to do with her once I appoint a new Divination teacher who needs her lodgings?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, that won\rquote t be a problem,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore pleasantly. \ldblquote You see, I have already found us a new Divination teacher, and he will pre\-fer lodgings on the ground floor.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote ve found \emdash  ?\rdblquote  said Umbridge shrilly. \ldblquote\i You\rquote ve\i0  found? Might I remind you, Dumbledore, that under Educational Decree Twenty-two \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  the Ministry has the right to appoint a suitable candidate if\lang3081  \lang1033\emdash  and only if\lang3081  \lang1033\emdash  the headmaster is unable to find one,\rdblquote  said Dumble\-dore. \ldblquote And I am happy to say that on this occasion I have succeeded. May I introduce you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He turned to face the open front doors, through which night mist was now drifting. Harry heard hooves. There was a shocked murmur around the hall and those nearest the doors hastily moved even farther\lang3081  \lang1033 backward, some of them tripping over in their haste to clear a path for the newcomer.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Through the mist came a face Harry had seen once before on a dark, dangerous night in the Forbidden Forest: white-blond hair and astonishingly blue eyes, the head and torso of a man joined to the palomino body of a horse.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote This is Firenze,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore happily to a thunderstruck Umbridge. \ldblquote I think you\rquote ll find him suitable.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
