\lang1033\ldblquote Not very good, poor thing,\rdblquote  said Lavender sympathetically. \ldblquote She\lang3081  \lang1033 was crying and saying she\rquote d rather leave the castle forever than stay here if Umbridge is still here, and I don\rquote t blame her. Umbridge was horrible to her, wasn\rquote t she?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote ve got a feeling Umbridge has only just started being horrible,\rdblquote  said Hermione darkly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Impossible,\rdblquote  said Ron, who was tucking into a large plate of eggs and bacon. \ldblquote She can\rquote t get any worse than she\rquote s been already.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You mark my words, she\rquote s going to want revenge on Dumbledore for appointing a new teacher without consulting her,\rdblquote  said Hermione, closing the newspaper. \ldblquote Especially another part-human. You saw the look on her face when she saw Firenze. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 After breakfast Hermione departed for her Arithmancy class and Harry and Ron followed Parvati and Lavender into the entrance hall, heading for Divination.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Aren\rquote t we going up to North Tower?\rdblquote  asked Ron, looking puzzled, as Parvati bypassed the marble staircase.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Parvati looked scornfully over her shoulder at him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How d\rquote you expect Firenze to climb that ladder? We\rquote re in class\-room eleven now, it was on the notice board yesterday.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Classroom eleven was situated in the ground-floor corridor leading off the entrance hall on the opposite side to the Great Hall. Harry knew it to be one of those classrooms that were never used regularly, and that it therefore had the slightly neglected feeling of a cupboard or storeroom. When he entered it right behind Ron, and found him\-self right in the middle of a forest clearing, he was therefore momen\-tarily stunned.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What the \emdash  ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The classroom floor had become springily mossy and trees were growing out of it; their leafy branches fanned across the ceiling and windows, so that the room was full of slanting shafts of soft, dappled, green light. The students who had already arrived were sitting on the earthy floor with their backs resting against tree trunks or boulders,\lang3081  \lang1033 arms wrapped around their knees or folded tightly across their chests, looking rather nervous. In the middle of the room, where there were no trees, stood Firenze.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry Potter,\rdblquote  he said, holding out a hand when Harry entered.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Er \emdash  hi,\rdblquote  said Harry, shaking hands with the centaur, who sur\-veyed him unblinkingly through those astonishingly blue eyes but did not smile. \ldblquote Er \emdash  good to see you \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And you,\rdblquote  said the centaur, inclining his white-blond head. \ldblquote It was foretold that we would meet again.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry noticed that there was the shadow of a hoof-shaped bruise on Firenze\rquote s chest. As he turned to join the rest of the class upon the floor, he saw that they were all looking at him with awe, apparently deeply impressed that he was on speaking terms with Firenze, whom they seemed to find intimidating.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 When the door was closed and the last student had sat down upon a tree stump beside the wastepaper basket, Firenze gestured around the room.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Professor Dumbledore has kindly arranged this classroom for us,\rdblquote  said Firenze, when everyone had settled down, \ldblquote in imitation of my natural habitat. I would have preferred to teach you in the Forbidden Forest, which was \emdash  until Monday \emdash  my home \'85 but this is not possible.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Please \emdash  er \emdash  sir \emdash\rdblquote  said Parvati breathlessly, raising her hand, \ldblquote why not? We\rquote ve been in there with Hagrid, we\rquote re not frightened!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It is not a question of your bravery,\rdblquote  said Firenze, \ldblquote but of my po\-sition. I can no longer return to the forest. My herd has banished me.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Herd?\rdblquote  said Lavender in a confused voice, and Harry knew she was thinking of cows. \ldblquote What \emdash  oh!\rdblquote  Comprehension dawned on her face. \ldblquote There are \i more of\lang3081  \lang1033 you\i0 ?\rdblquote  she said, stunned.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Did Hagrid breed you, like the thestrals?\rdblquote  asked Dean eagerly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Firenze turned his head very slowly to face Dean, who seemed to realize at once that he had said something very offensive.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I didn\rquote t \emdash  I meant \emdash  sorry,\rdblquote  he finished in a hushed voice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Centaurs are not the servants or playthings of humans,\rdblquote  said Firenze quietly. There was a pause, then Parvati raised her hand again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Please, sir \'85 why have the other centaurs banished you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Because I have agreed to work for Professor Dumbledore,\rdblquote  said Firenze. \ldblquote They see this as a betrayal of our kind.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry remembered how, nearly four years ago, the centaur Bane had shouted at Firenze for allowing Harry to ride to safety upon his back, calling him a \ldblquote common mule.\rdblquote  He wondered whether it had been Bane who had kicked Firenze in the chest.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Let us begin,\rdblquote  said Firenze. He swished his long palomino tail, raised his hand toward the leafy canopy overhead then lowered it slowly, and as he did so, the light in the room dimmed, so that they now seemed to be sitting in a forest clearing by twilight, and stars emerged upon the ceiling. There were \i oohs\i0  and gasps, and Ron said audibly, \ldblquote Blimey!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Lie back upon the floor,\rdblquote  said Firenze in his calm voice, \ldblquote and ob\-serve the heavens. Here is written, for those who can see, the fortune of our races.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry stretched out on his back and gazed upward at the ceiling. A twinkling red star winked at him from overhead.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I know that you have learned the names of the planets and their moons in Astronomy,\rdblquote  said Firenze\rquote s calm voice, \ldblquote and that you have mapped the stars\rquote  progress through the heavens. Centaurs have unrav\-eled the mysteries of these movements over centuries. Our findings teach us that the future may be glimpsed in the sky above us. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Professor Trelawney did Astrology with us!\rdblquote  said Parvati excitedly, raising her hand in front of her so that it stuck up in the air as she lay on her back. \ldblquote Mars causes accidents and burns and things like that, and when it makes an angle to Saturn, like now\rdblquote  \emdash  she drew a right angle in the air above her \emdash  \ldblquote that means that people need to be extra careful when handling hot things \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That,\rdblquote  said Firenze calmly, \ldblquote is human nonsense.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Parvati\rquote s hand fell limply to her side.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Trivial hurts, tiny human accidents,\rdblquote  said Firenze, as his hooves thudded over the mossy floor. \ldblquote These are of no more significance than the scurryings of ants to the wide universe, and are unaffected by planetary movements.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Professor Trelawney \emdash\rdblquote  began Parvati, in a hurt and indignant voice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  is a human,\rdblquote  said Firenze simply. \ldblquote And is therefore blinkered and fettered by the limitations of your kind.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry turned his head very slightly to look at Parvati. She looked very offended, as did several of the people surrounding her.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sibyll Trelawney may have Seen, I do not know,\rdblquote  continued Firenze, and Harry heard the swishing of his tail again as he walked up and down before them, \ldblquote but she wastes her time, in the main, on the self-flattering nonsense humans call fortune-telling. I, however, am here to explain the wisdom of centaurs, which is impersonal and im\-partial. We watch the skies for the great tides of evil or change that are sometimes marked there. It may take ten years to be sure of what we are seeing.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Firenze pointed to the red star directly above Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote In the past decade, the indications have been that Wizard-kind is living through nothing more than a brief calm between two wars. Mars, bringer of battle, shines brightly above us, suggesting that the fight must break out again soon. How soon, centaurs may attempt to divine by the burning of certain herbs and leaves, by the observation of fume and flame. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It was the most unusual lesson Harry had ever attended. They did indeed burn sage and mallowsweet there on the classroom floor, and Firenze told them to look for certain shapes and symbols in the pun\-gent fumes, but he seemed perfectly unconcerned that not one of them could see any of the signs he described, telling them that humans\lang3081  \lang1033 were hardly ever good at this, that it took centaurs years and years to become competent, and finished by telling them that it was foolish to put too much faith in such things anyway, because even centaurs sometimes read them wrongly. He was nothing like any human teacher Harry had ever had. His priority did not seem to be to teach them what he knew, but rather to impress upon them that nothing, not even centaurs\rquote  knowledge, was foolproof.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He\rquote s not very definite on anything, is he?\rdblquote  said Ron in a low voice, as they put out their mallowsweet fire. \ldblquote I mean, I could do with a few more details about this war we\rquote re about to have, couldn\rquote t you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The bell rang right outside the classroom door and everyone jumped; Harry had completely forgotten that they were still inside the castle, quite convinced that he was really in the forest. The class filed out, looking slightly perplexed; Harry and Ron were on the point of following them when Firenze called, \ldblquote Harry Potter, a word, please.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry turned. The centaur advanced a little toward him. Ron hesitated.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You may stay,\rdblquote  Firenze told him. \ldblquote But close the door, please.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron hastened to obey.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry Potter, you are a friend of Hagrid\rquote s, are you not?\rdblquote  said the centaur.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Then give him a warning from me. His attempt is not working. He would do better to abandon it.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote His attempt is not working?\rdblquote  Harry repeated blankly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And he would do better to abandon it,\rdblquote  said Firenze, nodding. \ldblquote I would warn Hagrid myself, but I am banished \emdash  it would be unwise for me to go too near the forest now \emdash  Hagrid has troubles enough, without a centaurs\rquote  battle.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But \emdash  what\rquote s Hagrid attempting to do?\rdblquote  said Harry nervously.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Firenze looked at Harry impassively.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hagrid has recently rendered me a great service,\rdblquote  said Firenze,\lang3081  \lang1033\ldblquote and he has long since earned my respect for the care he shows all liv\-ing creatures. I shall not betray his secret. But he must be brought to his senses. The attempt is not working. Tell him, Harry Potter. Good day to you.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\par
\lang1033 The happiness Harry had felt in the aftermath of \i The Quibbler\i0  inter\-view had long since evaporated. As a dull March blurred into a squally April, his life seemed to have become one long series of worries and problems again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Umbridge had continued attending all Care of Magical Creatures lessons, so it had been very difficult to deliver Firenze\rquote s warning to Ha\-grid. At last Harry had managed it by pretending he had lost his copy of \i Fantastic Beasts and Where to Find Them\i0  and doubling back after class one day. When he passed on Firenze\rquote s message, Hagrid gazed at him for a moment through his puffy, blackened eyes, apparently taken aback. Then he seemed to pull himself together.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Nice bloke, Firenze,\rdblquote  he said gruffly, \ldblquote but he don\rquote  know what he\rquote s talkin\rquote  abou\rquote  on this. The attemp\rquote s comin\rquote  on fine.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hagrid, what\rquote re you up to?\rdblquote  asked Harry seriously. \ldblquote Because you\rquote ve got to be careful, Umbridge has already sacked Trelawney and if you ask me, she\rquote s on a roll. If you\rquote re doing anything you shouldn\rquote t be\lang3081  \lang1033\emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote There\rquote s things more importan\rquote  than keepin\rquote  a job,\rdblquote  said Hagrid, though his hands shook slightly as he said this and a basin full of knarl droppings crashed to the floor. \ldblquote Don\rquote  worry abou\rquote  me, Harry, jus\rquote  get along now, there\rquote s a good lad. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry had no choice but to leave Hagrid mopping up the dung all over his floor, but he felt thoroughly dispirited as he trudged back up to the castle.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Meanwhile, as the teachers and Hermione persisted in reminding them, the O.W.L.s were drawing ever nearer. All the fifth years were suffering from stress to some degree, but Hannah Abbott became the\lang3081  \lang1033 first to receive a Calming Draught from Madam Pomfrey after she burst into tears during Herbology and sobbed that she was too stupid to take exams and wanted to leave school now.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 If it had not been for the D.A. lessons, Harry thought he would have been extremely unhappy. He sometimes felt that he was living for the hours he spent in the Room of Requirement, working hard but thoroughly enjoying himself at the same time, swelling with pride as he looked around at his fellow D.A. members and saw how far they had come. Indeed, Harry sometimes wondered how Umbridge was going to react when all the members of the D.A. received \ldblquote Outstand\-ing\rdblquote  in their Defense Against the Dark Arts O.W.L.s.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They had finally started work on Patronuses, which everybody had been very keen to practice, though as Harry kept reminding them, producing a Patronus in the middle of a brightly lit classroom when they were not under threat was very different to producing it when confronted by something like a dementor.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, don\rquote t be such a killjoy,\rdblquote  said Cho brightly, watching her sil\-very swan-shaped Patronus soar around the Room of Requirement during their last lesson before Easter. \ldblquote They\rquote re so pretty!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote They\rquote re not supposed to be pretty, they\rquote re supposed to protect you,\rdblquote  said Harry patiently. \ldblquote What we really need is a boggart or some\-thing; that\rquote s how I learned, I had to conjure a Patronus while the bog\-gart was pretending to be a dementor \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But that would be really scary!\rdblquote  said Lavender, who was shooting puffs of silver vapor out of the end of her wand. \ldblquote And I still \emdash  can\rquote t \emdash  do it!\rdblquote  she added angrily.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Neville was having trouble too. His face was screwed up in concen\-tration, but only feeble wisps of silver smoke issued from his wand tip.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote ve got to think of something happy,\rdblquote  Harry reminded him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m trying,\rdblquote  said Neville miserably, who was trying so hard his round face was actually shining with sweat.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry, I think I\rquote m doing it!\rdblquote  yelled Seamus, who had been\lang3081  \lang1033 brought along to his first ever D.A. meeting by Dean. \ldblquote Look \emdash  ah \emdash  it\rquote s gone. \'85 But it was definitely something hairy, Harry!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione\rquote s Patronus, a shining silver otter, was gamboling around her.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote They \i are\i0  sort of nice, aren\rquote t they?\rdblquote  she said, looking at it fondly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The door of the Room of Requirement opened and then closed again; Harry looked around to see who had entered, but there did not seem to be anybody there. It was a few moments before he realized that the people close to the door had fallen silent. Next thing he knew, something was tugging at his robes somewhere near the knee. He looked down and saw, to his very great astonishment, Dobby the house-elf peering up at him from beneath his usual eight hats.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hi, Dobby!\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote What are you \emdash  what\rquote s wrong?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 For the elf\rquote s eyes were wide with terror and he was shaking. The members of the D.A. closest to Harry had fallen silent now: Every\-body in the room was watching Dobby. The few Patronuses people had managed to conjure faded away into silver mist, leaving the room looking much darker than before.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry Potter, sir \'85\rdblquote  squeaked the elf, trembling from head to foot, \ldblquote Harry Potter, sir \'85 Dobby has come to warn you \'85 but the house-elves have been warned not to tell\lang3081  \lang1033\'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He ran headfirst at the wall: Harry, who had some experience of Dobby\rquote s habits of self-punishment, made to seize him, but Dobby merely bounced off the stone, cushioned by his eight hats. Hermione and a few of the other girls let out squeaks of fear and sympathy.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What\rquote s happened, Dobby?\rdblquote  Harry asked, grabbing the elf\rquote s tiny arm and holding him away from anything with which he might seek to hurt himself.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry Potter \'85 she \'85 she \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dobby hit himself hard on the nose with his free fist: Harry seized that too.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Who\rquote s \lquote she,\rquote  Dobby?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But he thought he knew \emdash  surely only one \ldblquote she\rdblquote  could induce such fear in Dobby? The elf looked up at him, slightly cross-eyed, and mouthed wordlessly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Umbridge?\rdblquote  asked Harry, horrified.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dobby nodded, then tried to bang his head off Harry\rquote s knees; Harry held him at bay.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What about her? Dobby \emdash  she hasn\rquote t found out about this \emdash  about us \emdash  about the D.A.?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He read the answer in the elf\rquote s stricken face. His hands held fast by Harry, the elf tried to kick himself and fell to the floor.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Is she coming?\rdblquote  Harry asked quietly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dobby let out a howl, and began beating his bare feet hard on the floor. \ldblquote Yes, Harry Potter, yes!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry straightened up and looked around at the motionless, terri\-fied people gazing at the thrashing elf.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote WHAT ARE YOU WAITING FOR?\rdblquote  Harry bellowed. \ldblquote RUN!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They all pelted toward the exit at once, forming a scrum at the door, then people burst through; Harry could hear them sprinting along the corridors and hoped they had the sense not to try and make it all the way to their dormitories. It was only ten to nine, if they just took refuge in the library or the Owlery, which were both nearer \emdash\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry, come on!\rdblquote  shrieked Hermione from the center of the knot of people now fighting to get out.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He scooped up Dobby, who was still attempting to do himself seri\-ous injury, and ran with the elf in his arms to join the back of the queue.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Dobby \emdash  this is an order \emdash  get back down to the kitchen with the other elves, and if she asks you whether you warned me, lie and say no!\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote And I forbid you to hurt yourself!\rdblquote  he added, drop\-ping the elf as he made it over the threshold at last and slamming the door behind him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Thank you, Harry Potter!\rdblquote  squeaked Dobby, and he streaked off.\lang3081  \lang1033 Harry glanced left and right, the others were all moving so fast that he caught only glimpses of flying heels at either end of the corridor be\-fore they vanished. He started to run right; there was a boys\rquote  bath\-room up ahead, he could pretend he\rquote d been in there all the time if he could just reach it \emdash\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote AAARGH!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Something caught him around the ankles and he fell spectacularly, skidding along on his front for six feet before coming to a halt. Some\-one behind him was laughing. He rolled over onto his back and saw Malfoy concealed in a niche beneath an ugly dragon-shaped vase.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Trip Jinx, Potter!\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote Hey, Professor \emdash  PROFESSOR! I\rquote ve got one!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Umbridge came bustling around the far corner, breathless but wearing a delighted smile.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s him!\rdblquote  she said jubilantly at the sight of Harry on the floor. \ldblquote Ex\-cellent, Draco, excellent, oh, very good \emdash  fifty points to Slytherin! I\rquote ll take him from here. \'85 Stand up, Potter!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry got to his feet, glaring at the pair of them. He had never seen Umbridge looking so happy. She seized his arm in a vicelike grip and turned, beaming broadly, to Malfoy. \ldblquote You hop along and see if you can round up anymore of them, Draco,\rdblquote  she said. \ldblquote Tell the others to look in the library \emdash  anybody out of breath \emdash  check the bathrooms, Miss Parkinson can do the girls\rquote  ones \emdash  off you go \emdash  and you,\rdblquote  she added in her softest, most dangerous voice, as Malfoy walked away. \ldblquote You can come with me to the headmaster\rquote s office, Potter.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They were at the stone gargoyle within minutes. Harry wondered how many of the others had been caught. He thought of Ron \emdash  Mrs. Weasley would kill him \emdash  and of how Hermione would feel if she was expelled before she could take her O.W.L.s. And it had been Sea\-mus\rquote s very first meeting \'85 and Neville had been getting so good. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Fizzing Whizbee,\rdblquote  sang Umbridge, and the stone gargoyle jumped aside, the wall behind split open, and they ascended the moving stone\lang3081  \lang1033 staircase. They reached the polished door with the griffin knocker, but Umbridge did not bother to knock, she strode straight inside, still holding tight to Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The office was full of people. Dumbledore was sitting behind his desk, his expression serene, the tips of his long fingers together. Pro\-fessor McGonagall stood rigidly beside him, her face extremely tense. Cornelius Fudge, Minister of Magic, was rocking backward and for\-ward on his toes beside the fire, apparently immensely pleased with the situation. Kingsley Shacklebolt and a tough-looking wizard Harry did not recognize with very short, wiry hair were positioned on either side of the door like guards, and the freckled, bespectacled form of Percy Weasley hovered excitedly beside the wall, a quill and a heavy scroll of parchment in his hands, apparently poised to take notes.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The portraits of old headmasters and mistresses were not sham\-ming sleep tonight. All of them were watching what was happening below, alert and serious. As Harry entered, a few flitted into neigh\-boring frames and whispered urgently into their neighbors\rquote  ears.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry pulled himself free of Umbridge\rquote s grasp as the door swung shut behind them. Cornelius Fudge was glaring at him with a kind of vicious satisfaction upon his face.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote Well, well, well\lang3081  \lang1033\'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry replied with the dirtiest look he could muster. His heart drummed madly inside him, but his brain was oddly cool and clear.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He was heading back to Gryffindor Tower,\rdblquote  said Umbridge. There was an indecent excitement in her voice, the same callous pleasure Harry had heard as she watched Professor Trelawney dissolving with misery in the entrance hall. \ldblquote The Malfoy boy cornered him.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Did he, did he?\rdblquote  said Fudge appreciatively. \ldblquote I must remember to tell Lucius. Well, Potter \'85 I expect you know why you are here?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry fully intended to respond with a defiant \ldblquote yes\rdblquote : His mouth had opened and the word was half formed when he caught sight of\lang3081  \lang1033 Dumbledore\rquote s face. Dumbledore was not looking directly at Harry; his eyes were fixed upon a point just over his shoulder, but as Harry stared at him, he shook his head a fraction of an inch to each side.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry changed direction mid-word.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeh \emdash  no.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I beg your pardon?\rdblquote  said Fudge.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Harry, firmly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You \i don\rquote t\i0  know why you are here?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, I don\rquote t,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Fudge looked incredulously from Harry to Professor Umbridge; Harry took advantage of his momentary inattention to steal another quick look at Dumbledore, who gave the carpet the tiniest of nods and the shadow of a wink.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So you have no idea,\rdblquote  said Fudge in a voice positively sagging with sarcasm, \ldblquote why Professor Umbridge has brought you to this office? You are not aware that you have broken any school rules?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote School rules?\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote No.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Or Ministry decrees?\rdblquote  amended Fudge angrily.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Not that I\rquote m aware of,\rdblquote  said Harry blandly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 His heart was still hammering very fast. It was almost worth telling these lies to watch Fudge\rquote s blood pressure rising, but he could not see how on earth he would get away with them. If somebody had tipped off Umbridge about the D.A. then he, the leader, might as well be packing his trunk right now.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So it\rquote s news to you, is it,\rdblquote  said Fudge, his voice now thick with anger, \ldblquote that an illegal student organization has been discovered within this school?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
