\lang1033\ldblquote Guilty conscience, eh?\rdblquote  he wheezed. \ldblquote Follow me. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry glanced back at Ron and Hermione, who were both looking worried. He shrugged and followed Filch back into the entrance hall, against the tide of hungry students.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Filch seemed to be in an extremely good mood; he hummed creak\-ily under his breath as they climbed the marble staircase. As they reached the first landing he said, \ldblquote Things are changing around here, Potter.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote ve noticed,\rdblquote  said Harry coldly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yerse \'85 I\rquote ve been telling Dumbledore for years and years he\rquote s too soft with you all,\rdblquote  said Filch, chuckling nastily. \ldblquote You filthy little beasts would never have dropped Stinkpellets if you\rquote d known I had it in my power to whip you raw, would you, now? Nobody would have thought of throwing Fanged Frisbees down the corridors if I could\rquote ve strung you up by the ankles in my office, would they? But when Edu\-cational Decree Twenty-nine comes in, Potter, I\rquote ll be allowed to do\lang3081  \lang1033 them things. \'85 \i And\i0  she\rquote s asked the Minister to sign an order for the expulsion of Peeves. \'85 Oh, things are going to be very different around here with \i her\i0  in charge. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Umbridge had obviously gone to some lengths to get Filch on her side, Harry thought, and the worst of it was that he would probably prove an important weapon; his knowledge of the school\rquote s secret pas\-sageways and hiding places was probably second only to the Weasley twins.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Here we are,\rdblquote  he said, leering down at Harry as he rapped three times upon Professor Umbridge\rquote s door and pushed it open. \ldblquote The Pot\-ter boy to see you, ma\rquote am.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Umbridge\rquote s office, so very familiar to Harry from his many deten\-tions, was the same as usual except for the large wooden block lying across the front of her desk on which golden letters spelled the word HEADMISTRESS; also his Firebolt, and Fred\rquote s and George\rquote s Clean-sweeps, which he saw with a pang were now chained and padlocked to a stout iron peg in the wall behind the desk. Umbridge was sitting be\-hind the desk, busily scribbling upon some of her pink parchment, but looked up and smiled widely at their entrance.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Thank you, Argus,\rdblquote  she said sweetly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Not at all, ma\rquote am, not at all,\rdblquote  said Filch, bowing as low as his rheumatism would permit, and exiting backward.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sit,\rdblquote  said Umbridge curtly, pointing toward a chair, and Harry sat. She continued to scribble for a few moments. He watched some of the foul kittens gamboling around the plates over her head, wondering what fresh horror she had in store for him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well now,\rdblquote  she said finally, setting down her quill and looking like a toad about to swallow a particularly juicy fly. \ldblquote What would you like to drink?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What?\rdblquote  said Harry, quite sure he had misheard her.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote To drink, Mr. Potter,\rdblquote  she said, smiling still more widely. \ldblquote Tea? Coffee? Pumpkin juice?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 As she named each drink, she gave her short wand a wave, and a cup or glass of it appeared upon her desk.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Nothing, thank you,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I wish you to have a drink with me,\rdblquote  she said, her voice becoming more dangerously sweet. \ldblquote Choose one.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Fine \'85 tea then,\rdblquote  said Harry, shrugging.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She got up and made quite a performance of adding milk with her back to him. She then bustled around the desk with it, smiling in sin\-isterly sweet fashion.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote There,\rdblquote  she said, handing it to him. \ldblquote Drink it before it gets cold, won\rquote t you? Well, now, Mr. Potter \'85 I thought we ought to have a lit\-tle chat, after the distressing events of last night.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He said nothing. She settled herself back into her seat and waited. When several long moments had passed in silence, she said gaily, \ldblquote You\rquote re not drinking up!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He raised the cup to his lips and then, just as suddenly, lowered it. One of the horrible painted kittens behind Umbridge had great round blue eyes just like Mad-Eye Moody\rquote s magical one, and it had just oc\-curred to Harry what Mad-Eye would say if he ever heard that Harry had drunk anything offered by a known enemy.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What\rquote s the matter?\rdblquote  said Umbridge, who was still watching him. \ldblquote Do you want sugar?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He raised the cup to his lips again and pretended to take a sip, though keeping his mouth tightly closed. Umbridge\rquote s smile widened.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Good,\rdblquote  she whispered. \ldblquote Very good. Now then \'85\rdblquote  She leaned forward a little. \ldblquote\i Where is Albus Dumbledore\i0 ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No idea,\rdblquote  said Harry promptly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Drink up, drink up,\rdblquote  she said, still smiling. \ldblquote Now, Mr. Potter, let us not play childish games. I know that you know where he has gone. You and Dumbledore have been in this together from the beginning. Consider your position, Mr. Potter. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t know where he is.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry pretended to drink again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Very well,\rdblquote  said Umbridge, looking displeased. \ldblquote In that case, you will kindly tell me the whereabouts of Sirius Black.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry\rquote s stomach turned over and his hand holding the teacup shook so that the cup rattled in its saucer. He tilted the cup to his mouth with his lips pressed together, so that some of the hot liquid trickled down onto his robes.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t know,\rdblquote  he said a little too quickly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Mr. Potter,\rdblquote  said Umbridge, \ldblquote let me remind you that it was I who almost caught the criminal Black in the Gryffindor fire in October. I know perfectly well it was you he was meeting and if I had had any proof neither of you would be at large today, I promise you. I repeat, Mr. Potter \'85 Where is Sirius Black?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No idea,\rdblquote  said Harry loudly. \ldblquote Haven\rquote t got a clue.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They stared at each other so long that Harry felt his eyes watering. Then she stood up.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Very well, Potter, I will take your word for it this time, but be warned: The might of the Ministry stands behind me. All channels of communication in and out of this school are being monitored. A Floo Network Regulator is keeping watch over every fire in Hogwarts \emdash  except my own, of course. My Inquisitorial Squad is opening and reading all owl post entering and leaving the castle. And Mr. Filch is observing all secret passages in and out of the castle. If I find a shred of evidence \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\i BOOM!\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033 The very floor of the office shook; Umbridge slipped sideways, clutching her desk for support, looking shocked.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What was \emdash  ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She was gazing toward the door; Harry took the opportunity to empty his almost full cup of tea into the nearest vase of dried flowers. He could hear people running and screaming several floors below.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Back to lunch with you, Potter!\rdblquote  cried Umbridge, raising her wand and dashing out of the office. Harry gave her a few seconds\rquote  start then hurried after her to see what the source of all the uproar was.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It was not difficult to find. One floor down, pandemonium reigned. Somebody (and Harry had a very shrewd idea who) had set off what seemed to be an enormous crate of enchanted fireworks.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dragons comprised entirely of green-and-gold sparks were soaring up and down the corridors, emitting loud fiery blasts and bangs as they went. Shocking-pink Catherine wheels five feet in diameter were whizzing lethally through the air like so many flying saucers. Rockets with long tails of brilliant silver stars were ricocheting off the walls. Sparklers were writing swearwords in midair of their own accord. Fire\-crackers were exploding like mines everywhere Harry looked, and in\-stead of burning themselves out, fading from sight, or fizzling to a halt, these pyrotechnical miracles seemed to be gaining in energy and momentum the longer he watched.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Filch and Umbridge were standing, apparently transfixed with hor\-ror, halfway down the stairs. As Harry watched, one of the larger Catherine wheels seemed to decide that what it needed was more room to maneuver; it whirled toward Umbridge and Filch with a sin\-ister \i wheeeeeeeeee.\i0  Both adults yelled with fright and ducked and it soared straight out of the window behind them and off across the grounds. Meanwhile, several of the dragons and a large purple bat that was smoking ominously took advantage of the open door at the end of the corridor to escape toward the second floor.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hurry, Filch, hurry!\rdblquote  shrieked Umbridge. \ldblquote They\rquote ll be all over the school unless we do something \emdash  \i Stupefy\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A jet of red light shot out of the end of her wand and hit one of the rockets. Instead of freezing in midair, it exploded with such force that it blasted a hole in a painting of a soppy-looking witch in the middle of a meadow \emdash  she ran for it just in time, reappearing seconds later\lang3081  \lang1033 squashed into the painting next door, where a couple of wizards play\-ing cards stood up hastily to make room for her.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Don\rquote t Stun them, Filch!\rdblquote  shouted Umbridge angrily, for all the world as though it had been his suggestion.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Right you are, Headmistress!\rdblquote  wheezed Filch, who was a Squib and could no more have Stunned the fireworks than swallowed them. He dashed to a nearby cupboard, pulled out a broom, and began swat\-ting at the fireworks in midair; within seconds the head of the broom was ablaze.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry had seen enough. Laughing, he ducked down low, ran to a door he knew was concealed behind a tapestry a little way along the corridor and slipped through it to find Fred and George hiding just behind it, listening to Umbridge\rquote s and Filch\rquote s yells and quaking with suppressed mirth.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Impressive,\rdblquote  Harry said quietly, grinning. \ldblquote Very impressive \'85 You\rquote ll put Dr. Filibuster out of business, no problem. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Cheers,\rdblquote  whispered George, wiping tears of laughter from his face. \ldblquote Oh, I hope she tries Vanishing them next. \'85 They multiply by ten every time you try. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The fireworks continued to burn and to spread all over the school that afternoon. Though they caused plenty of disruption, particularly the firecrackers, the other teachers did not seem to mind them very much.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Dear, dear,\rdblquote  said Professor McGonagall sardonically, as one of the dragons soared around her classroom, emitting loud bangs and exhal\-ing flame. \ldblquote Miss Brown, would you mind running along to the head\-mistress and informing her that we have an escaped firework in our classroom?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The upshot of it all was that Professor Umbridge spent her first af\-ternoon as headmistress running all over the school answering the summonses of the other teachers, none of whom seemed able to rid\lang3081  \lang1033 their rooms of the fireworks without her. When the final bell rang and the students were heading back to Gryffindor Tower with their bags, Harry saw, with immense satisfaction, a disheveled and soot-blackened Umbridge tottering sweaty-faced from Professor Flitwick\rquote s classroom.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Thank you so much, Professor!\rdblquote  said Professor Flitwick in his squeaky little voice. \ldblquote I could have got rid of the sparklers myself, of course, but I wasn\rquote t sure whether I had the \i authority. \'85\i0\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Beaming, he closed his classroom door in her snarling face.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Fred and George were heroes that night in the Gryffindor common room. Even Hermione fought her way through the excited crowd around them to congratulate them.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote They were wonderful fireworks,\rdblquote  she said admiringly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Thanks,\rdblquote  said George, looking both surprised and pleased. \ldblquote Weasleys\rquote  Wildfire Whiz-Bangs. Only thing is, we used our whole stock, we\rquote re going to have to start again from scratch now. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It was worth it, though,\rdblquote  said Fred, who was taking orders from clamoring Gryffindors. \ldblquote If you want to add your name to the waiting list, Hermione, it\rquote s five Galleons for your Basic Blaze box and twenty for the Deflagration Deluxe. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione returned to the table where Harry and Ron were sitting staring at their schoolbags as though hoping their homework might spring out of it and start doing itself.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, why don\rquote t we have a night off?\rdblquote  said Hermione brightly, as a silver-tailed Weasley rocket zoomed past the window. \ldblquote After all, the Easter holidays start on Friday, we\rquote ll have plenty of time then. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Are you feeling all right?\rdblquote  Ron asked, staring at her in disbelief.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Now you mention it,\rdblquote  said Hermione happily, \ldblquote d\rquote you know \'85 I think I\rquote m feeling a bit\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 \i rebellious.\i0\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry could still hear the distant \i bangs\i0  of escaped firecrackers when he and Ron went up to bed an hour later, and as he got undressed a sparkler floated past the tower, still resolutely spelling out the word POO.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He got into bed, yawning. With his glasses off, the occasional fire-work still passing the window became blurred, looking like sparkling clouds, beautiful and mysterious against the black sky. He turned onto his side, wondering how Umbridge was feeling about her first day in Dumbledore\rquote s job, and how Fudge would react when he heard that the school had spent most of the day in a state of advanced dis\-ruption. \'85 Smiling to himself, he closed his eyes. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The whizzes and bangs of escaped fireworks in the grounds seemed to be growing more distant\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 or perhaps he, Harry, was simply speeding away from them. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He had fallen right into the corridor leading to the Department of Mysteries. He was speeding toward the plain black door. \'85 \i Let it open. \'85 Let it open. \'85\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033 It did. He was inside the circular room lined with doors. \'85 He crossed it, placed his hand upon an identical door, and it swung inward. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Now he was in a long, rectangular room full of an odd, mechanical clicking. There were dancing flecks of light on the walls but he did not pause to investigate. \'85 He had to go on. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a door at the far end. \'85 It too opened at his touch. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And now he was in a dimly lit room as high and wide as a church, full of nothing but rows and rows of towering shelves, each laden with small, dusty, spun-glass spheres. \'85 Now Harry\rquote s heart was beating fast with excitement. \'85 He knew where to go. \'85 He ran forward, but his footsteps made no noise in the enormous, deserted room. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was something in this room he wanted very, very much. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Something he wanted. \'85 or somebody else wanted. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 His scar was hurting. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\i BANG! \i0 Harry awoke instantly, confused and angry. The dark dor\-mitory was full of the sound of laughter.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Cool!\rdblquote  said Seamus, who was silhouetted against the window.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I think one of those Catherine wheels hit a rocket and it\rquote s like they mated, come and see!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry heard Ron and Dean scramble out of bed for a better look. He lay quite still and silent while the pain in his scar subsided and dis\-appointment washed over him. He felt as though a wonderful treat had been snatched from him at the very last moment. \'85 He had got so close that time. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Glittering, pink-and-silver winged piglets were now soaring past the windows of Gryffindor Tower. Harry lay and listened to the ap\-preciative whoops of Gryffindors in the dormitories below them. His stomach gave a sickening jolt as he remembered that he had Occlu\-mency the following evening. \'85\lang3081\par
\par
\lang1033 Harry spent the whole of the next day dreading what Snape was going to say if he found out how much farther into the Department of Mys\-teries he had penetrated during his last dream. With a surge of guilt he realized that he had not practiced Occlumency once since their last lesson: There had been too much going on since Dumbledore had left. He was sure he would not have been able to empty his mind even if he had tried. He doubted, however, whether Snape would accept that excuse. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He attempted a little last-minute practice during classes that day, but it was no good, Hermione kept asking him what was wrong whenever he fell silent trying to rid himself of all thought and emo\-tion and, after all, the best moment to empty his brain was not while teachers were firing review questions at the class.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Resigned to the worst, he set off for Snape\rquote s office after dinner. Halfway across the entrance hall, however, Cho came hurrying up to him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Over here,\rdblquote  said Harry, glad of a reason to postpone his meeting with Snape and beckoning her across to the corner of the entrance hall where the giant hourglasses stood. Gryffindor\rquote s was now almost\lang3081  \lang1033 empty. \ldblquote Are you okay? Umbridge hasn\rquote t been asking you about the D.A., has she?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh no,\rdblquote  said Cho hurriedly. \ldblquote No, it was only\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 Well, I just wanted to say\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 Harry, I never dreamed Marietta would tell. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, well,\rdblquote  said Harry moodily. He did feel Cho might have cho\-sen her friends a bit more carefully. It was small consolation that the last he had heard, Marietta was still up in the hospital wing and Madam Pomfrey had not been able to make the slightest improve\-ment to her pimples.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote She\rquote s a lovely person really,\rdblquote  said Cho. \ldblquote She just made a mistake \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry looked at her incredulously.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i A lovely person who made a mistake\i0 ? She sold us all out, including you!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 we all got away, didn\rquote t we?\rdblquote  said Cho pleadingly. \ldblquote You know, her mum works for the Ministry, it\rquote s really difficult for her \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ron\rquote s dad works for the Ministry too!\rdblquote  Harry said furiously. \ldblquote And in case you hadn\rquote t noticed, he hasn\rquote t got \lquote sneak\rquote  written across \i his \i0 face \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That was a really horrible trick of Hermione Granger\rquote s,\rdblquote  said Cho fiercely. \ldblquote She should have told us she\rquote d jinxed that list \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I think it was a brilliant idea,\rdblquote  said Harry coldly. Cho flushed and her eyes grew brighter.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh yes, I forgot \emdash  of course, if it was darling \i Hermione\rquote s\i0  idea \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Don\rquote t start crying again,\rdblquote  said Harry warningly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I wasn\rquote t going to!\rdblquote  she shouted.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah \'85 well\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 good,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote I\rquote ve got enough to cope with at the moment.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Go and cope with it then!\rdblquote  she said furiously, turning on her heel and stalking off.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Fuming, Harry descended the stairs to Snape\rquote s dungeon, and though he knew from experience how much easier it would be for\lang3081  \lang1033 Snape to penetrate his mind if he arrived angry and resentful, he suc\-ceeded in nothing but thinking of a few more good things he should have said to Cho about Marietta before reaching the dungeon door.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote re late, Potter,\rdblquote  said Snape coldly, as Harry closed the door be\-hind him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Snape was standing with his back to Harry, removing, as usual, cer\-tain of his thoughts and placing them carefully in Dumbledore\rquote s Pen\-sieve. He dropped the last silvery strand into the stone basin and turned to face Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote Have you been practicing?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  Harry lied, looking carefully at one of the legs of Snape\rquote s desk.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, we\rquote ll soon find out, won\rquote t we?\rdblquote  said Snape smoothly. \ldblquote Wand out, Potter.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry moved into his usual position, facing Snape with the desk between them. His heart was pumping fast with anger at Cho and anxiety about how much Snape was about to extract from his mind.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote On the count of three then,\rdblquote  said Snape lazily. \ldblquote One \emdash  two \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Snape\rquote s office door banged open and Draco Malfoy sped in.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Professor Snape, sir \emdash  oh \emdash  sorry \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Malfoy was looking at Snape and Harry in some surprise.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s all right, Draco,\rdblquote  said Snape, lowering his wand. \ldblquote Potter is here for a little Remedial Potions.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry had not seen Malfoy look so gleeful since Umbridge had turned up to inspect Hagrid.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I didn\rquote t know,\rdblquote  he said, leering at Harry, who knew his face was burning. He would have given a great deal to be able to shout the truth at Malfoy \emdash  or, even better, to hit him with a good curse.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, Draco, what is it?\rdblquote  asked Snape.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s Professor Umbridge, sir \emdash  she needs your help,\rdblquote  said Malfoy. \ldblquote They\rquote ve found Montague, sir. He\rquote s turned up jammed inside a toilet on the fourth floor.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How did he get in there?\rdblquote  demanded Snape.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t know, sir, he\rquote s a bit confused. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Very well, very well \emdash  Potter,\rdblquote  said Snape, \ldblquote we shall resume this lesson tomorrow evening instead.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He turned and swept from his office. Malfoy mouthed \ldblquote\i Remedial Potions\i0 ?\rdblquote  at Harry behind Snape\rquote s back before following him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Seething, Harry replaced his wand inside his robes and made to leave the room. At least he had twenty-four more hours in which to practice; he knew he ought to feel grateful for the narrow escape, though it was hard that it came at the expense of Malfoy telling the whole school that he needed Remedial Potions. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He was at the office door when he saw it: a patch of shivering light dancing on the door frame. He stopped, looking at it, reminded of something. \'85 Then he remembered: It was a little like the lights he had seen in his dream last night, the lights in the second room he had walked through on his journey through the Department of Mysteries.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He turned around. The light was coming from the Pensieve sitting on Snape\rquote s desk. The silver-white contents were ebbing and swirling within. Snape\rquote s thoughts \'85 things he did not want Harry to see if he broke through Snape\rquote s defenses accidentally. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry gazed at the Pensieve, curiosity welling inside him. \'85 What was it that Snape was so keen to hide from Harry?\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The silvery lights shivered on the wall. \'85 Harry took two steps to\-ward the desk, thinking hard. Could it possibly be information about the Department of Mysteries that Snape was determined to keep from him?\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry looked over his shoulder, his heart now pumping harder and faster than ever. How long would it take Snape to release Montague from the toilet? Would he come straight back to his office afterward, or accompany Montague to the hospital wing? Surely the latter \'85 Montague was Captain of the Slytherin Quidditch team, Snape would want to make sure he was all right. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry walked the remaining few feet to the Pensieve and stood over it, gazing into its depths. He hesitated, listening, then pulled out his wand again. The office and the corridor beyond were completely silent. He gave the contents of the Pensieve a small prod with the end of his wand.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The silvery stuff within began to swirl very fast. Harry leaned for\-ward over it and saw that it had become transparent. He was, once again, looking down into a room as though through a circular win\-dow in the ceiling. \'85 In fact, unless he was much mistaken, he was looking down upon the Great Hall. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 His breath was actually fogging the surface of Snape\rquote s thoughts. \'85 His brain seemed to be in limbo. \'85 It would be insane to do the thing that he was so strongly tempted to do. \'85 He was trembling. \'85 Snape could be back at any moment\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 but Harry thought of Cho\rquote s anger, of Malfoy\rquote s jeering face, and a reckless daring seized him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He took a great gulp of breath and plunged his face into the surface of Snape\rquote s thoughts. At once, the floor of the office lurched, tipping Harry headfirst into the Pensieve. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He was falling through cold blackness, spinning furiously as he went, and then \emdash\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He was standing in the middle of the Great Hall, but the four House tables were gone. Instead there were more than a hundred smaller tables, all facing the same way, at each of which sat a student, head bent low, scribbling on a roll of parchment. The only sound was the scratching of quills and the occasional rustle as somebody adjusted their parchment. It was clearly exam time.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Sunshine was streaming through the high windows onto the bent heads, which shone chestnut and copper and gold in the bright light. Harry looked around carefully. Snape had to be here somewhere. \'85 This was \i his\i0  memory. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And there he was, at a table right behind Harry. Harry stared. Snape-the-teenager had a stringy, pallid look about him, like a plant\lang3081  \lang1033 kept in the dark. His hair was lank and greasy and was flopping onto the table, his hooked nose barely half an inch from the surface of the parchment as he scribbled. Harry moved around behind Snape and read the heading of the examination paper:\par
\par
\pard\qc DEFENSE AGAINST THE DARK ARTS\lang3081  \emdash\par
\lang1033 ORDINARY WIZARDING LEVEL\lang3081\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\qj\lang1033\par
So Snape had to be fifteen or sixteen, around Harry\rquote s own age. His hand was flying across the parchment; he had written at least a foot more than his closest neighbors, and yet his writing was minuscule and cramped.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Five more minutes!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The voice made Harry jump; turning, he saw the top of Professor Flitwick\rquote s head moving between the desks a short distance away. Pro\-fessor Flitwick was walking past a boy with untidy black hair \'85 very untidy black hair. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry moved so quickly that, had he been solid, he would have knocked desks flying. Instead he seemed to slide, dreamlike, across two aisles and up a third. The back of the black-haired boy\rquote s head drew nearer and nearer. \'85 He was straightening up now, putting down his quill, pulling his roll of parchment toward him so as to reread what he had written. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry stopped in front of the desk and gazed down at his fifteen-year-old father.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Excitement exploded in the pit of his stomach: It was as though he was looking at himself but with deliberate mistakes. James\rquote s eyes were hazel, his nose was slightly longer than Harry\rquote s, and there was no scar on his forehead, but they had the same thin face, same mouth, same eyebrows. James\rquote s hair stuck up at the back exactly as Harry\rquote s did, his hands could have been Harry\rquote s, and Harry could tell that when James stood up, they would be within an inch of each other\rquote s heights.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 James yawned hugely and rumpled up his hair, making it even\lang3081  \lang1033 messier than it had been. Then, with a glance toward Professor Flitwick, he turned in his seat and grinned at a boy sitting four seats behind him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 With another shock of excitement, Harry saw Sirius give James the thumbs-up. Sirius was lounging in his chair at his ease, tilting it back on two legs. He was very good-looking; his dark hair fell into his eyes with a sort of casual elegance neither James\rquote s nor Harry\rquote s could ever have achieved, and a girl sitting behind him was eyeing him hopefully, though he didn\rquote t seem to have noticed. And two seats along from this girl \emdash  Harry\rquote s stomach gave another pleasurable squirm \emdash  was Re\-mus Lupin. He looked rather pale and peaky (was the full moon ap\-proaching?) and was absorbed in the exam: As he reread his answers he scratched his chin with the end of his quill, frowning slightly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 So that meant Wormtail had to be around here somewhere too \'85 and sure enough, Harry spotted him within seconds: a small, mousy-haired boy with a pointed nose. Wormtail looked anxious; he was chewing his fingernails, staring down at his paper, scuffing the ground with his toes. Every now and then he glanced hopefully at his neigh\-bor\rquote s paper. Harry stared at Wormtail for a moment, then back at James, who was now doodling on a bit of scrap parchment. He had drawn a Snitch and was now tracing the letters L. E. What did they stand for?\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Quills down, please!\rdblquote  squeaked Professor Flitwick. \ldblquote That means you too, Stebbins! Please remain seated while I collect your parch\-ment! \i Accio\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 More than a hundred rolls of parchment zoomed into the air and into Professor Flitwick\rquote s outstretched arms, knocking him backward off his feet. Several people laughed. A couple of students at the front desks got up, took hold of Professor Flitwick beneath the elbows, and lifted him onto his feet again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Thank you \'85 thank you,\rdblquote  panted Professor Flitwick. \ldblquote Very well, everybody, you\rquote re free to go!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry looked down at his father, who had hastily crossed out the L. E. he had been embellishing, jumped to his feet, stuffed his quill and the exam question paper into his bag, which he slung over his back, and stood waiting for Sirius to join him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry looked around and glimpsed Snape a short way away, mov\-ing between the tables toward the doors into the entrance hall, still absorbed in his own examination paper. Round-shouldered yet angu\-lar, he walked in a twitchy manner that recalled a spider, his oily hair swinging about his face.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A gang of chattering girls separated Snape from James and Sirius, and by planting himself in the midst of this group, Harry managed to keep Snape in sight while straining his ears to catch the voices of James and his friends.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Did you like question ten, Moony?\rdblquote  asked Sirius as they emerged into the entrance hall.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Loved it,\rdblquote  said Lupin briskly. \ldblquote  \lquote Give five signs that identify the werewolf.\rquote  Excellent question.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote D\rquote you think you managed to get all the signs?\rdblquote  said James in tones of mock concern.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Think I did,\rdblquote  said Lupin seriously, as they joined the crowd throng\-ing around the front doors eager to get out into the sunlit grounds. \ldblquote One: He\rquote s sitting on my chair. Two: He\rquote s wearing my clothes. Three: His name\rquote s Remus Lupin \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Wormtail was the only one who didn\rquote t laugh.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I got the snout shape, the pupils of the eyes, and the tufted tail,\rdblquote  he said anxiously, \ldblquote but I couldn\rquote t think what else \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How thick are you, Wormtail?\rdblquote  said James impatiently. \ldblquote You run round with a werewolf once a month \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Keep your voice down,\rdblquote  implored Lupin.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry looked anxiously behind him again. Snape remained close by, still buried in his examination questions; but this was Snape\rquote s memory, and Harry was sure that if Snape chose to wander off in a\lang3081  \lang1033 different direction once outside in the grounds, he, Harry, would not be able to follow James any farther. To his intense relief, however, when James and his three friends strode off down the lawn toward the lake, Snape followed, still poring over the paper and apparently with no fixed idea of where he was going. By jogging a little ahead of him, Harry managed to maintain a close watch on James and the others.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, I thought that paper was a piece of cake,\rdblquote  he heard Sirius say. \ldblquote I\rquote ll be surprised if I don\rquote t get Outstanding on it at least.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Me too,\rdblquote  said James. He put his hand in his pocket and took out a struggling Golden Snitch.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Where\rquote d you get that?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Nicked it,\rdblquote  said James casually. He started playing with the Snitch, allowing it to fly as much as a foot away and seizing it again; his re\-flexes were excellent. Wormtail watched him in awe.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They stopped in the shade of the very same beech tree on the edge of the lake where Harry, Ron, and Hermione had spent a Sunday fin\-ishing their homework, and threw themselves down on the grass.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry looked over his shoulder yet again and saw, to his delight, that Snape had settled himself on the grass in the dense shadows of a clump of bushes. He was as deeply immersed in the O.W.L. paper as ever, which left Harry free to sit down on the grass between the beech and the bushes and watch the foursome under the tree.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The sunlight was dazzling on the smooth surface of the lake, on the bank of which the group of laughing girls who had just left the Great Hall were sitting with shoes and socks off, cooling their feet in the water.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Lupin had pulled out a book and was reading. Sirius stared around at the students milling over the grass, looking rather haughty and bored, but very handsomely so. James was still playing with the Snitch, letting it zoom farther and farther away, almost escaping but always grabbed at the last second. Wormtail was watching him with his mouth open. Every time James made a particularly difficult catch,\lang3081  \lang1033 Wormtail gasped and applauded. After five minutes of this, Harry wondered why James didn\rquote t tell Wormtail to get a grip on himself, but James seemed to be enjoying the attention. Harry noticed his father had a habit of rumpling up his hair as though to make sure it did not get too tidy, and also that he kept looking over at the girls by the wa\-ter\rquote s edge.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Put that away, will you?\rdblquote  said Sirius finally, as James made a fine catch and Wormtail let out a cheer. \ldblquote Before Wormtail wets himself from excitement.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Wormtail turned slightly pink but James grinned.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote If it bothers you,\rdblquote  he said, stuffing the Snitch back in his pocket. Harry had the distinct impression that Sirius was the only one for whom James would have stopped showing off.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m bored,\rdblquote  said Sirius. \ldblquote Wish it was full moon.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You might,\rdblquote  said Lupin darkly from behind his book. \ldblquote We\rquote ve still got Transfiguration, if you\rquote re bored you could test me. \'85 Here.\rdblquote  He held out his book.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Sirius snorted. \ldblquote I don\rquote t need to look at that rubbish, I know it all.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote This\rquote ll liven you up, Padfoot,\rdblquote  said James quietly. \ldblquote Look who it is. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Sirius\rquote s head turned. He had become very still, like a dog that has scented a rabbit.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Excellent,\rdblquote  he said softly. \ldblquote\i Snivellus.\i0\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry turned to see what Sirius was looking at.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Snape was on his feet again, and was stowing the O.W.L. paper in his bag. As he emerged from the shadows of the bushes and set off across the grass, Sirius and James stood up. Lupin and Wormtail re\-mained sitting: Lupin was still staring down at his book, though his eyes were not moving and a faint frown line had appeared between his eyebrows. Wormtail was looking from Sirius and James to Snape with a look of avid anticipation on his face.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote All right, Snivellus?\rdblquote  said James loudly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Snape reacted so fast it was as though he had been expecting an at\-tack: Dropping his bag, he plunged his hand inside his robes, and his wand was halfway into the air when James shouted, \ldblquote\i Expelliarmus\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Snape\rquote s wand flew twelve feet into the air and fell with a little thud in the grass behind him. Sirius let out a bark of laughter.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Impedimenta\i0 !\rdblquote  he said, pointing his wand at Snape, who was knocked off his feet, halfway through a dive toward his own fallen wand.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Students all around had turned to watch. Some of them had gotten to their feet and were edging nearer to watch. Some looked apprehen\-sive, others entertained.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Snape lay panting on the ground. James and Sirius advanced on him, wands up, James glancing over his shoulder at the girls at the wa\-ter\rquote s edge as he went. Wormtail was on his feet now, watching hun\-grily, edging around Lupin to get a clearer view.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How\rquote d the exam go, Snivelly?\rdblquote  said James.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I was watching him, his nose was touching the parchment,\rdblquote  said Sirius viciously. \ldblquote There\rquote ll be great grease marks all over it, they won\rquote t be able to read a word.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Several people watching laughed; Snape was clearly unpopular. Wormtail sniggered shrilly. Snape was trying to get up, but the jinx was still operating on him; he was struggling, as though bound by in\-visible ropes.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You \emdash  wait,\rdblquote  he panted, staring up at James with an expression of purest loathing. \ldblquote You \emdash  wait. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Wait for what?\rdblquote  said Sirius coolly. \ldblquote What\rquote re you going to do, Sniv\-elly, wipe your nose on us?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Snape let out a stream of mixed swearwords and hexes, but his wand being ten feet away nothing happened.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Wash out your mouth,\rdblquote  said James coldly. \ldblquote\i Scourgify\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Pink soap bubbles streamed from Snape\rquote s mouth at once; the froth was covering his lips, making him gag, choking him \emdash\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Leave him ALONE!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 James and Sirius looked around. James\rquote s free hand jumped to his hair again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It was one of the girls from the lake edge. She had thick, dark red hair that fell to her shoulders and startlingly green almond-shaped eyes \emdash  Harry\rquote s eyes.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry\rquote s mother \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote All right, Evans?\rdblquote  said James, and the tone of his voice was sud\-denly pleasant, deeper, more mature.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Leave him alone,\rdblquote  Lily repeated. She was looking at James with every sign of great dislike. \ldblquote What\rquote s he done to you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well,\rdblquote  said James, appearing to deliberate the point, \ldblquote it\rquote s more the fact that he \i exists,\i0  if you know what I mean. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Many of the surrounding watchers laughed, Sirius and Wormtail included, but Lupin, still apparently intent on his book, didn\rquote t, and neither did Lily.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You think you\rquote re funny,\rdblquote  she said coldly. \ldblquote But you\rquote re just an arro\-gant, bullying toerag, Potter. Leave him \i alone.\i0\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I will if you go out with me, Evans,\rdblquote  said James quickly. \ldblquote Go on \'85 Go out with me, and I\rquote ll never lay a wand on old Snivelly again.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Behind him, the Impediment Jinx was wearing off. Snape was be\-ginning to inch toward his fallen wand, spitting out soapsuds as he crawled.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I wouldn\rquote t go out with you if it was a choice between you and the giant squid,\rdblquote  said Lily.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Bad luck, Prongs,\rdblquote  said Sirius briskly, turning back to Snape. \ldblquote OY!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But too late; Snape had directed his wand straight at James; there was a flash of light and a gash appeared on the side of James\rquote s face, spattering his robes with blood. James whirled about; a second flash of light later, Snape was hanging upside down in the air, his robes falling over his head to reveal skinny, pallid legs and a pair of graying underpants.\lang3081\par
