The story of Fred and George\rquote s flight to freedom was retold so of\-ten over the next few days that Harry could tell it would soon become the stuff of Hogwarts legend. Within a week, even those who had been eyewitnesses were half-convinced that they had seen the twins dive-bomb Umbridge on their brooms, pelting her with Dung\-bombs before zooming out of the doors. In the immediate aftermath of their departure there was a great wave of talk about copying them, so that Harry frequently heard students saying things like, \ldblquote Honestly, some days I just feel like jumping on my broom and leaving this place,\rdblquote  or else, \ldblquote One more lesson like that and I might just do a Weasley. \'85\rdblquote\par
Fred and George had made sure that nobody was likely to forget them very soon. For one thing, they had not left instructions on how to remove the swamp that now filled the corridor on the fifth floor of the east wing. Umbridge and Filch had been observed trying different means of removing it but without success. Eventually the area was roped off and Filch, gnashing his teeth furiously, was given the task of punting students across it to their classrooms. Harry was certain that\lang3081  \lang1033 teachers like McGonagall or Flitwick could have removed the swamp in an instant, but just as in the case of Fred and George\rquote s Wildfire Whiz-Bangs, they seemed to prefer to watch Umbridge struggle.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Then there were the two large broom-shaped holes in Umbridge\rquote s office door, through which Fred and George\rquote s Cleansweeps had smashed to rejoin their masters. Filch fitted a new door and removed Harry\rquote s Firebolt to the dungeons where, it was rumored, Umbridge had set an armed security troll to guard it. However, her troubles were far from over.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Inspired by Fred and George\rquote s example, a great number of students were now vying for the newly vacant positions of Troublemakers-in-Chief. In spite of the new door, somebody managed to slip a hairy-snouted niffler into Umbridge\rquote s office, which promptly tore the place apart in its search for shiny objects, leapt on Umbridge on her reen-trance, and tried to gnaw the rings off her stubby fingers. Dungbombs and Stinkpellets were dropped so frequently in the corridors that it be\-came the new fashion for students to perform Bubble-Head Charms on themselves before leaving lessons, which ensured them a supply of fresh clean air, even though it gave them all the peculiar appearance of wearing upside-down goldfish bowls on their heads.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Filch prowled the corridors with a horsewhip ready in his hands, desperate to catch miscreants, but the problem was that there were now so many of them that he did not know which way to turn. The Inquisitorial Squad were attempting to help him, but odd things kept happening to its members. Warrington of the Slytherin Quidditch team reported to the hospital wing with a horrible skin complaint that made him look as though he had been coated in cornflakes. Pansy Parkinson, to Hermione\rquote s delight, missed all her lessons the following day, as she had sprouted antlers.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Meanwhile it became clear just how many Skiving Snackboxes Fred and George had managed to sell before leaving Hogwarts. Umbridge only had to enter her classroom for the students assembled there to\lang3081  \lang1033 faint, vomit, develop dangerous fevers, or else spout blood from both nostrils. Shrieking with rage and frustration she attempted to trace the mysterious symptoms to their source, but the students told her stub\-bornly they were suffering \ldblquote Umbridge-itis.\rdblquote  After putting four succes\-sive classes in detention and failing to discover their secret she was forced to give up and allow the bleeding, swooning, sweating, and vomiting students to leave her classes in droves.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But not even the users of the Snackboxes could compete with that master of chaos, Peeves, who seemed to have taken Fred\rquote s parting words deeply to heart. Cackling madly, he soared through the school, upending tables, bursting out of blackboards, and toppling statues and vases. Twice he shut Mrs. Norris inside suits of armor, from which she was rescued, yowling loudly, by the furious caretaker. He smashed lanterns and snuffed out candles, juggled burning torches over the heads of screaming students, caused neatly stacked piles of parchment to topple into fires or out of windows, flooded the second floor when he pulled off all the taps in the bathrooms, dropped a bag of tarantu\-las in the middle of the Great Hall during breakfast and, whenever he fancied a break, spent hours at a time floating along after Umbridge and blowing loud raspberries every time she spoke.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 None of the staff but Filch seemed to be stirring themselves to help her. Indeed, a week after Fred and George\rquote s departure Harry witnessed Professor McGonagall walking right past Peeves, who was deter\-minedly loosening a crystal chandelier, and could have sworn he heard her tell the poltergeist out of the corner of her mouth, \ldblquote It unscrews the other way.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 To cap matters, Montague had still not recovered from his sojourn in the toilet. He remained confused and disorientated and his parents were to be observed one Tuesday morning striding up the front drive, looking extremely angry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Should we say something?\rdblquote  said Hermione in a worried voice, pressing her cheek against the Charms window so that she could see\lang3081  \lang1033 Mr. and Mrs. Montague marching inside. \ldblquote About what happened to him? In case it helps Madam Pomfrey cure him?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \rquote Course not, he\rquote ll recover,\rdblquote  said Ron indifferently.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Anyway, more trouble for Umbridge, isn\rquote t it?\rdblquote  said Harry in a sat\-isfied voice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He and Ron both tapped the teacups they were supposed to be charming with their wands. Harry\rquote s spouted four very short legs that would not reach the desk and wriggled pointlessly in midair. Ron\rquote s grew four very thin spindly legs that hoisted the cup off the desk with great difficulty, trembled for a few seconds, then folded, causing the cup to crack into two.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Reparo\i0 !\rdblquote  said Hermione quickly, mending Ron\rquote s cup with a wave of her wand. \ldblquote That\rquote s all very well, but what if Montague\rquote s perma\-nently injured?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Who cares?\rdblquote  said Ron irritably, while his teacup stood drunkenly again, trembling violently at the knees. \ldblquote Montague shouldn\rquote t have tried to take all those points from Gryffindor, should he? If you want to worry about anyone, Hermione, worry about me!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You?\rdblquote  she said, catching her teacup as it scampered happily away across the desk on four sturdy little willow-patterned legs and replac\-ing it in front of her. \ldblquote Why should I be worried about you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote When Mum\rquote s next letter finally gets through Umbridge\rquote s screen\-ing process,\rdblquote  said Ron bitterly, now holding his cup up while its frail legs tried feebly to support its weight, \ldblquote I\rquote m going to be in deep trou\-ble. I wouldn\rquote t be surprised if she\rquote s sent a Howler again.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But\lang3081  \lang1033\emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote ll be my fault Fred and George left, you wait,\rdblquote  said Ron darkly. \ldblquote She\rquote ll say I should\rquote ve stopped them leaving, I should\rquote ve grabbed the ends of their brooms and hung on or something. \'85 Yeah, it\rquote ll be all my fault. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, if she \i does\i0  say that it\rquote ll be very unfair, you couldn\rquote t have done anything! But I\rquote m sure she won\rquote t, I mean, if it\rquote s really true they\rquote ve got\lang3081  \lang1033 premises in Diagon Alley now, they must have been planning this for ages. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, but that\rquote s another thing, how did they get premises?\rdblquote  said Ron, hitting his teacup so hard with his wand that its legs collapsed again and it lay twitching before him. \ldblquote It\rquote s a bit dodgy, isn\rquote t it? They\rquote ll need loads of Galleons to afford the rent on a place in Diagon Alley, she\rquote ll want to know what they\rquote ve been up to, to get their hands on that sort of gold. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, yes, that occurred to me too,\rdblquote  said Hermione, allowing her teacup to jog in neat little circles around Harry\rquote s, whose stubby little legs were still unable to touch the desktop. \ldblquote I\rquote ve been wondering whether Mundungus has persuaded them to sell stolen goods or something awful. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He hasn\rquote t,\rdblquote  said Harry curtly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How do you know?\rdblquote  said Ron and Hermione together.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Because \emdash\rdblquote  Harry hesitated, but the moment to confess finally seemed to have come. There was no good to be gained in keeping silent if it meant anyone suspected that Fred and George were crimi\-nals. \ldblquote Because they got the gold from me. I gave them my Triwizard winnings last June.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a shocked silence, then Hermione\rquote s teacup jogged right over the edge of the desk and smashed on the floor.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, Harry, you \i didn\rquote t\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\i  \lang1033\i0 she said.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, I did,\rdblquote  said Harry mutinously. \ldblquote And I don\rquote t regret it either \emdash  I didn\rquote t need the gold, and they\rquote ll be great at a joke shop. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But this is excellent!\rdblquote  said Ron, looking thrilled. \ldblquote It\rquote s all your fault, Harry \emdash  Mum can\rquote t blame me at all! Can I tell her?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, I suppose you\rquote d better,\rdblquote  said Harry dully. \ldblquote  \rquote Specially if she thinks they\rquote re receiving stolen cauldrons or something. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione said nothing at all for the rest of the lesson, but Harry had a shrewd suspicion that her self-restraint was bound to crack before long. Sure enough, once they had left the castle for break and were standing around in the weak May sunshine, she fixed Harry with a beady eye and opened her mouth with a determined air.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry interrupted her before she had even started.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s no good nagging me, it\rquote s done,\rdblquote  he said firmly. \ldblquote Fred and George have got the gold \emdash  spent a good bit of it too, by the sounds of it \emdash  and I can\rquote t get it back from them and I don\rquote t want to. So save your breath, Hermione.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I wasn\rquote t going to say anything about Fred and George!\rdblquote  she said in an injured voice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron snorted disbelievingly and Hermione threw him a very dirty look.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No, I wasn\rquote t!\rdblquote  she said angrily. \ldblquote As a matter of fact, I was going to ask Harry when he\rquote s going to go back to Snape and ask for Occlu\-mency lessons again!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry\rquote s heart sank. Once they had exhausted the subject of Fred and George\rquote s dramatic departure, which admittedly had taken many hours, Ron and Hermione had wanted to hear news of Sirius. As Harry had not confided in them the reason he had wanted to talk to Sirius in the first place, it had been hard to think of things to tell them. He had ended up saying to them truthfully that Sirius wanted Harry to resume Occlumency lessons. He had been regretting this ever since; Hermione would not let the subject drop and kept revert\-ing to it when Harry least expected it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You can\rquote t tell me you\rquote ve stopped having funny dreams,\rdblquote  Hermione said now, \ldblquote because Ron told me last night you were muttering in your sleep again. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry threw Ron a furious look. Ron had the grace to look ashamed of himself.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You were only muttering a bit,\rdblquote  he mumbled apologetically. \ldblquote Something about \lquote just a bit farther.\rquote  \rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I dreamed I was watching you lot play Quidditch,\rdblquote  Harry lied brutally. \ldblquote I was trying to get you to stretch out a bit farther to grab the Quaffle.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Ron\rquote s ears went red. Harry felt a kind of vindictive pleasure: He had not, of course, dreamed anything of the sort.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Last night he had once again made the journey along the Depart\-ment of Mysteries corridor. He had passed through the circular room, then the room full of clicking and dancing light, until he found him\-self again inside that cavernous room full of shelves on which were ranged dusty glass spheres. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He had hurried straight toward row number ninety-seven, turned left, and ran along it. \'85 It had probably been then that he had spo\-ken aloud. \'85 \i Just a bit farther\lang3081\i0  \lang1033\'85 for he could feel his conscious self struggling to wake \'85 and before he had reached the end of the row, he had found himself lying in bed again, gazing up at the canopy of his four-poster.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You are \i trying\i0  to block your mind, aren\rquote t you?\rdblquote  said Hermione, look\-ing beadily at Harry. \ldblquote You are keeping going with your Occlumency?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Of course I am,\rdblquote  said Harry, trying to sound as though this ques\-tion was insulting, but not quite meeting her eye. The truth was that he was so intensely curious about what was hidden in that room full of dusty orbs that he was quite keen for the dreams to continue.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The problem was that with just under a month to go until the ex\-ams and every free moment devoted to studying, his mind seemed saturated with information when he went to bed so that he found it very difficult to get to sleep at all. When he did, his overwrought brain presented him most nights with stupid dreams about the exams. He also suspected that part of his mind \emdash  the part that often spoke in Hermione\rquote s voice \emdash  now felt guilty on the occasions it strayed down that corridor ending in the black door, and sought to wake him before he could reach journey\rquote s end.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You know,\rdblquote  said Ron, whose ears were still flaming red, \ldblquote if Mon\-tague doesn\rquote t recover before Slytherin play Hufflepuff, we might be in with a chance of winning the Cup.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, I s\rquote pose so,\rdblquote  said Harry, glad of a change of subject.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I mean, we\rquote ve won one, lost one \emdash  if Slytherin lose to Hufflepuff next Saturday \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, that\rquote s right,\rdblquote  said Harry, losing track of what he was agree\-ing to: Cho Chang had just walked across the courtyard, deter\-minedly not looking at him.\lang3081\par
