\lang1033 When they reached the top of the Astronomy Tower at eleven o\rquote clock they found a perfect night for stargazing, cloudless and still. The grounds were bathed in silvery moonlight, and there was a slight chill in the air. Each of them set up his or her telescope and, when Professor Marchbanks gave the word, proceeded to fill in the blank star chart he or she had been given.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Professors Marchbanks and Tofty strolled among them, watching as they entered the precise positions of the stars and planets they were observing. All was quiet except for the rustle of parchment, the occa\-sional creak of a telescope as it was adjusted on its stand, and the scrib\-bling of many quills. Half an hour passed, then an hour; the little squares of reflected gold light flickering on the ground below started to vanish as lights in the castle windows were extinguished.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 As Harry completed the constellation Orion on his chart, however, the front doors of the castle opened directly below the parapet where he was standing, so that light spilled down the stone steps a little way across the lawn. Harry glanced down as he made a slight adjustment\lang3081  \lang1033 to the position of his telescope and saw five or six elongated shadows moving over the brightly lit grass before the doors swung shut and the lawn became a sea of darkness once more.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry put his eye back to his telescope and refocused it, now ex\-amining Venus. He looked down at his chart to enter the planet there, but something distracted him. Pausing with his quill suspended over the parchment, he squinted down into the shadowy grounds and saw half a dozen figures walking over the lawn. If they had not been mov\-ing, and the moonlight had not been gilding the tops of their heads, they would have been indistinguishable from the dark ground on which they stood. Even at this distance, Harry had a funny feeling that he recognized the walk of the squattest among them, who seemed to be leading the group.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He could not think why Umbridge would be taking a stroll outside past midnight, much less accompanied by five others. Then some\-body coughed behind him, and he remembered that he was halfway through an exam. He had quite forgotten Venus\rquote s position \emdash  jam\-ming his eye to his telescope, he found it again and was again on the point of entering it on his chart when, alert for any odd sound, he heard a distant knock that echoed through the deserted grounds, fol\-lowed immediately by the muffled barking of a large dog.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He looked up, his heart hammering. There were lights on in Ha\-grid\rquote s windows and the people he had observed crossing the lawn were now silhouetted against them. The door opened and he distinctly saw six tiny but sharply defined figures walk over the threshold. The door closed again and there was silence.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry felt very uneasy. He glanced around to see whether Ron or Hermione had noticed what he had, but Professor Marchbanks came walking behind him at that moment, and not wanting to appear as though he was sneaking looks at anyone else\rquote s work, he hastily bent over his star chart and pretended to be adding notes to it while really\lang3081  \lang1033 peering over the top of the parapet toward Hagrid\rquote s cabin. Figures were now moving across the cabin windows, temporarily blocking the light.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He could feel Professor Marchbanks\rquote s eyes on the back of his neck and pressed his eye again to his telescope, staring up at the moon though he had marked its position an hour ago, but as Professor Marchbanks moved on he heard a roar from the distant cabin that echoed through the darkness right to the top of the Astronomy Tower. Several of the people around Harry ducked out from behind their telescopes and peered instead in the direction of Hagrid\rquote s cabin.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Professor Tofty gave another dry little cough.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Try and concentrate, now, boys and girls,\rdblquote  he said softly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Most people returned to their telescopes. Harry looked to his left. Hermione was gazing transfixed at Hagrid\rquote s.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ahem \emdash  twenty minutes to go,\rdblquote  said Professor Tofty.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione jumped and returned at once to her star chart; Harry looked down at his own and noticed that he had mislabelled Venus as Mars. He bent to correct it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a loud \i BANG \i0 from the grounds. Several people said \ldblquote Ouch!\rdblquote  as they poked themselves in the face with the ends of their telescopes, hastening to see what was going on below.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hagrid\rquote s door had burst open and by the light flooding out of the cabin they saw him quite clearly, a massive figure roaring and bran\-dishing his fists, surrounded by six people, all of whom, judging by the tiny threads of red light they were casting in his direction, seemed to be attempting to Stun him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No!\rdblquote  cried Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote My dear!\rdblquote  said Professor Tofty in a scandalized voice. \ldblquote This is an examination!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But nobody was paying the slightest attention to their star charts anymore: Jets of red light were still flying beside Hagrid\rquote s cabin, yet somehow they seemed to be bouncing off him. He was still upright\lang3081  \lang1033 and still, as far as Harry could see, fighting. Cries and yells echoed across the grounds; a man yelled, \ldblquote Be reasonable, Hagrid!\rdblquote  and Hagrid roared, \ldblquote Reasonable be damned, yeh won\rquote  take me like this, Dawlish!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry could see the tiny outline of Fang, attempting to defend Ha\-grid, leaping at the wizards surrounding him until a Stunning Spell caught him and he fell to the ground. Hagrid gave a howl of fury, lifted the culprit bodily from the ground, and threw him: The man flew what looked like ten feet and did not get up again. Hermione gasped, both hands over her mouth; Harry looked around at Ron and saw that he too was looking scared. None of them had ever seen Ha\-grid in a real temper before. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Look!\rdblquote  squealed Parvati, who was leaning over the parapet and pointing to the foot of the castle where the front doors seemed to have opened again; more light had spilled out onto the dark lawn and a sin\-gle long black shadow was now rippling across the lawn.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Now, really!\rdblquote  said Professor Tofty anxiously. \ldblquote Only sixteen min\-utes left, you know!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But nobody paid him the slightest attention: They were watching the person now sprinting toward the battle beside Hagrid\rquote s cabin.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How dare you!\rdblquote  the figure shouted as she ran. \ldblquote How \i dare\i0  you!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s McGonagall!\rdblquote  whispered Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Leave him alone! \i Alone,\i0  I say!\rdblquote  said Professor McGonagall\rquote s voice through the darkness. \ldblquote On what grounds are you attacking him? He has done nothing, nothing to warrant such \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione, Parvati, and Lavender all screamed. No fewer than four Stunners had shot from the figures around the cabin toward Professor McGonagall. Halfway between cabin and castle the red beams col\-lided with her. For a moment she looked luminous, illuminated by an eerie red glow, then was lifted right off her feet, landed hard on her back, and moved no more.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Galloping gargoyles!\rdblquote  shouted Professor Tofty, who seemed to\lang3081  \lang1033 have forgotten the exam completely. \ldblquote Not so much as a warning! Out\-rageous behavior!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote COWARDS!\rdblquote  bellowed Hagrid, his voice carrying clearly to the top of the tower, and several lights flickered back on inside the castle. \ldblquote RUDDY COWARDS! HAVE SOME O\rquote  THAT \emdash  AN\rquote  THAT \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh my \emdash\rdblquote  gasped Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hagrid took two massive swipes at his closest attackers; judging by their immediate collapse, they had been knocked cold. Harry saw him double over and thought for a moment that he had finally been over\-come by a spell, but on the contrary, next moment Hagrid was stand\-ing again with what appeared to be a sack on his back \emdash  then Harry realized that Fang\rquote s limp body was draped around his shoulders.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Get him, get him!\rdblquote  screamed Umbridge, but her remaining helper seemed highly reluctant to go within reach of Hagrid\rquote s fists. Indeed, he was backing away so fast he tripped over one of his unconscious colleagues and fell over. Hagrid had turned and begun to run with Fang still hung around his neck; Umbridge sent one last Stunning Spell after him but it missed, and Hagrid, running full-pelt toward the distant gates, disappeared into the darkness.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was a long minute\rquote s quivering silence, everybody gazing openmouthed into the grounds. Then Professor Tofty\rquote s voice said fee\-bly, \ldblquote Um \'85 five minutes to go, everybody \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Though he had only filled in two-thirds of his chart, Harry was desperate for the end of the exam. When it came at last he, Ron, and Hermione forced their telescopes haphazardly back into their holders and dashed back down the spiral staircase. None of the students were going to bed \emdash  they were all talking loudly and excitedly at the foot of the stairs about what they had witnessed.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That evil woman!\rdblquote  gasped Hermione, who seemed to be having difficulty talking due to rage. \ldblquote Trying to sneak up on Hagrid in the dead of night!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote She clearly wanted to avoid another scene like Trelawney\rquote s,\rdblquote  said Ernie Macmillan sagely, squeezing over to join them.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hagrid did well, didn\rquote t he?\rdblquote  said Ron, who looked more alarmed than impressed. \ldblquote How come all the spells bounced off him?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote ll be his giant blood,\rdblquote  said Hermione shakily. \ldblquote It\rquote s very hard to Stun a giant, they\rquote re like trolls, really tough. \'85 But poor Professor McGonagall. \'85 Four Stunners straight in the chest, and she\rquote s not ex\-actly young, is she?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Dreadful, dreadful,\rdblquote  said Ernie, shaking his head pompously. \ldblquote Well, I\rquote m off to bed. \'85 \rquote Night, all\lang3081  \lang1033\'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 People around them were drifting away, still talking excitedly about what they had just seen.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote At least they didn\rquote t get to take Hagrid off to Azkaban,\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote I \rquote spect he\rquote s gone to join Dumbledore, hasn\rquote t he?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I suppose so,\rdblquote  said Hermione, who looked tearful. \ldblquote Oh, this is aw\-ful, I really thought Dumbledore would be back before long, but now we\rquote ve lost Hagrid too. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They traipsed back to the Gryffindor common room to find it full. The commotion out in the grounds had woken several people, who had hastened to rouse their friends. Seamus and Dean, who had ar\-rived ahead of Harry, Ron, and Hermione, were now telling everyone what they had heard from the top of the Astronomy Tower.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But why sack Hagrid now?\rdblquote  asked Angelina Johnson, shaking her head. \ldblquote It\rquote s not like Trelawney, he\rquote s been teaching much better than usual this year!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Umbridge hates part-humans,\rdblquote  said Hermione bitterly, flopping down into an armchair. \ldblquote She was always going to try and get Hagrid out.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And she thought Hagrid was putting nifflers in her office,\rdblquote  piped up Katie Bell.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh blimey,\rdblquote  said Lee Jordan, covering his mouth. \ldblquote It\rquote s me\rquote s been\lang3081  \lang1033 putting the nifflers in her office, Fred and George left me a couple, I\rquote ve been levitating them in through her window. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote She\rquote d have sacked him anyway,\rdblquote  said Dean. \ldblquote He was too close to Dumbledore.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That\rquote s true,\rdblquote  said Harry, sinking into an armchair beside Her\-mione\rquote s.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I just hope Professor McGonagall\rquote s all right,\rdblquote  said Lavender tearfully.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote They carried her back up to the castle, we watched through the dor\-mitory window,\rdblquote  said Colin Creevey \ldblquote She didn\rquote t look very well. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Madam Pomfrey will sort her out,\rdblquote  said Alicia Spinnet firmly. \ldblquote She\rquote s never failed yet.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 It was nearly four in the morning before the common room cleared. Harry felt wide awake \emdash  the image of Hagrid sprinting away into the dark was haunting him. He was so angry with Umbridge he could not think of a punishment bad enough for her, though Ron\rquote s suggestion of having her fed to a box of starving Blast-Ended Skrewts had its merits. He fell asleep contemplating hideous revenges and arose from bed three hours later feeling distinctly unrested.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Their final exam, History of Magic, was not to take place until that afternoon. Harry would very much have liked to go back to bed after breakfast, but he had been counting on the morning for a spot of last-minute studying, so instead he sat with his head in his hands by the common room window, trying hard not to doze off as he read through some of the notes stacked three-and-a-half feet high that Hermione had lent him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The fifth years entered the Great Hall at two o\rquote clock and took their places in front of their overturned examination papers. Harry felt ex\-hausted. He just wanted this to be over so that he could go and sleep. Then tomorrow, he and Ron were going to go down to the Quidditch pitch \emdash  he was going to have a fly on Ron\rquote s broom and savor their freedom from studying. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Turn over your papers,\rdblquote  said Professor Marchbanks from the front of the Hall, flicking over the giant hourglass. \ldblquote You may begin. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry stared fixedly at the first question. It was several seconds be\-fore it occurred to him that he had not taken in a word of it; there was a wasp buzzing distractingly against one of the high windows. Slowly, tortuously, he began to write an answer.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He was finding it very difficult to remember names and kept con\-fusing dates. He simply skipped question four: \i In your opinion, did wand legislation contribute to, or lead to better control of, goblin riots of the eighteenth century\i0 ? thinking that he would go back to it if he had time at the end. He had a stab at question five: \i How was the Statute of Secrecy breached in 1749 and what measures were introduced to prevent a recurrence\i0 ? but had a nagging suspicion that he had missed several im\-portant points. He had a feeling vampires had come into the story somewhere. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He looked ahead for a question he could definitely answer and his eyes alighted upon number ten.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\i Describe the circumstances that led to the Formation of the Interna\-tional Confederation of Wizards and explain why the warlocks of Liecht\-enstein refused to join.\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\i I know this,\i0  Harry thought, though his brain felt torpid and slack. He could visualize a heading, in Hermione\rquote s handwriting: \i The Forma\-tion of the International Confederation of Wizards\'85\i0  He had read these notes only this morning. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He began to write, looking up now and again to check the large hourglass on the desk beside Professor Marchbanks. He was sitting right behind Parvati Patil, whose long dark hair fell below the back of her chair. Once or twice he found himself staring at the tiny golden lights that glistened in it when she moved her head very slightly and had to give his own head a little shake to clear it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\'85 \i the first Supreme Mugwump of the International Confederation\lang3081\i0  \lang1033\i of Wizards was Pierre Bonaccord, but his appointment was contested by the Wizarding community of Liechtenstein, because \i0\emdash\lang3081\par
\lang1033 All around Harry quills were scratching on parchment like scurry\-ing, burrowing rats. The sun was very hot on the back of his head. What was it that Bonaccord had done to offend the wizards of Liecht\-enstein? Harry had a feeling it had something to do with trolls. \'85 He gazed blankly at the back of Parvati\rquote s head again. If he could only perform Legilimency and open a window in the back of her head and see what it was about trolls that had caused the breach between Pierre Bonaccord and Liechtenstein. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry closed his eyes and buried his face in his hands, so that the glowing red of his eyelids grew dark and cool. Bonaccord had wanted to stop troll-hunting and give the trolls rights \'85 but Liechtenstein was having problems with a tribe of particularly vicious mountain trolls. \'85 That was it. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He opened his eyes; they stung and watered at the sight of the blaz\-ing-white parchment. Slowly he wrote two lines about the trolls then read through what he had done so far. It did not seem very informa\-tive or detailed, yet he was sure Hermione\rquote s notes on the confedera\-tion had gone on for pages and pages. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He closed his eyes again, trying to see them, trying to remember. \'85 The confederation had met for the first time in France, yes, he had written that already. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Goblins had tried to attend and been ousted. \'85 He had written that too. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And nobody from Liechtenstein had wanted to come \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\i Think,\i0  he told himself, his face in his hands, while all around him quills scratched out never-ending answers and the sand trickled through the hourglass at the front. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He was walking along the cool, dark corridor to the Department of Mysteries again, walking with a firm and purposeful tread, breaking\lang3081  \lang1033 occasionally into a run, determined to reach his destination at last. \'85 The black door swung open for him as usual, and here he was in the circular room with its many doors. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Straight across the stone floor and through the second door \'85 patches of dancing light on the walls and floor and that odd mechan\-ical clicking, but no time to explore, he must hurry. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He jogged the last few feet to the third door, which swung open just like the others. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Once again he was in the cathedral-sized room full of shelves and glass spheres. \'85 His heart was beating very fast now. \'85 He was go\-ing to get there this time. \'85 When he reached number ninety-seven he turned left and hurried along the aisle between two rows. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But there was a shape on the floor at the very end, a black shape moving upon the floor like a wounded animal. \'85 Harry\rquote s stomach contracted with fear \'85 with excitement. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A voice issued from his own mouth, a high, cold voice empty of any human kindness, \ldblquote Take it for me. \'85 Lift it down, now. \'85 I cannot touch it\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 but you can. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The black shape upon the floor shifted a little. Harry saw a long-fingered white hand clutching a wand rise on the end of his own arm \'85 heard the high, cold voice say, \ldblquote\i Crucio\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The man on the floor let out a scream of pain, attempted to stand but fell back, writhing. Harry was laughing. He raised his wand, the curse lifted, and the figure groaned and became motionless.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Lord Voldemort is waiting. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Very slowly, his arms trembling, the man on the ground raised his shoulders a few inches and lifted his head. His face was bloodstained and gaunt, twisted in pain yet rigid with defiance. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You\rquote ll have to kill me,\rdblquote  whispered Sirius.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Undoubtedly I shall in the end,\rdblquote  said the cold voice. \ldblquote But you will fetch it for me first, Black. \'85 You think you have felt pain thus far?\lang3081  \lang1033 Think again. \'85 We have hours ahead of us and nobody to hear you scream. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 But somebody screamed as Voldemort lowered his wand again; somebody yelled and fell sideways off a hot desk onto the cold stone floor. Harry hit the ground and awoke, still yelling, his scar on fire, as the Great Hall erupted all around him.\lang3081\par
