\lang1033\ldblquote Visitor to the Ministry, you are required to submit to a search and present your wand for registration at the security desk, which is lo\-cated at the far end of the Atrium.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Fine!\rdblquote  Harry said loudly, as his scar gave another throb. \ldblquote Now can we \i move\i0 ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The floor of the telephone box shuddered and the pavement rose up past the glass windows of the telephone box. The scavenging thes\-trals were sliding out of sight, blackness closed over their heads, and with a dull grinding noise they sank down into the depths of the Min\-istry of Magic.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 A chink of soft golden light hit their feet and, widening, rose up their bodies. Harry bent his knees and held his wand as ready as he could in such cramped conditions, peering through the glass to see whether anybody was waiting for them in the Atrium, but it seemed to be completely empty. The light was dimmer than it had been by day. There were no fires burning under the mantelpieces set into the\lang3081  \lang1033 walls, but he saw as the lift slid smoothly to a halt that golden symbols continued to twist sinuously in the dark blue ceiling.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote The Ministry of Magic wishes you a pleasant evening,\rdblquote  said the woman\rquote s voice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The door of the telephone box burst open; Harry toppled out of it, followed by Neville and Luna. The only sound in the Atrium was the steady rush of water from the golden fountain, where jets from the wands of the witch and wizard, the point of the centaur\rquote s arrow, the tip of the goblin\rquote s hat, and the house-elf\rquote s ears continued to gush into the surrounding pool.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Come on,\rdblquote  said Harry quietly and the six of them sprinted off down the hall, Harry in the lead, past the fountain, toward the desk where the security man who had weighed Harry\rquote s wand had sat and which was now deserted.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry felt sure that there ought to be a security person there, sure that their absence was an ominous sign, and his feeling of foreboding increased as they passed through the golden gates to the lifts. He pressed the nearest down button and a lift clattered into sight almost immediately, the golden grilles slid apart with a great, echoing clank\-ing, and they dashed inside. Harry stabbed the number nine button, the grilles closed with a bang, and the lift began to descend, jangling and rattling. Harry had not realized how noisy the lifts were on the day that he had come with Mr. Weasley \emdash  he was sure that the din would raise every security person within the building, yet when the lift halted, the cool female voice said, \ldblquote Department of Mysteries,\rdblquote  and the grilles slid open again, they stepped out into the corridor where nothing was moving but the nearest torches, flickering in the rush of air from the lift.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry turned toward the plain black door. After months and months of dreaming about it, he was here at last. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Let\rquote s go,\rdblquote  he whispered, and he led the way down the corridor, Luna right behind him, gazing around with her mouth slightly open.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Okay, listen,\rdblquote  said Harry, stopping again within six feet of the door. \ldblquote Maybe \'85 maybe a couple of people should stay here as a \emdash  as a lookout, and \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And how\rquote re we going to let you know something\rquote s coming?\rdblquote  asked Ginny, her eyebrows raised. \ldblquote You could be miles away.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We\rquote re coming with you, Harry,\rdblquote  said Neville.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Let\rquote s get on with it,\rdblquote  said Ron firmly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry still did not want to take them all with him, but it seemed he had no choice. He turned to face the door and walked forward. Just as it had in his dream, it swung open and he marched forward, leading the others over the threshold.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They were standing in a large, circular room. Everything in here was black including the floor and ceiling \emdash  identical, unmarked, handle-less black doors were set at intervals all around the black walls, interspersed with branches of candles whose flames burned blue, their cool, shimmering light reflected in the shining marble floor so that it looked as though there was dark water underfoot.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Someone shut the door,\rdblquote  Harry muttered.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He regretted giving this order the moment Neville had obeyed it. Without the long chink of light from the torch-lit corridor behind them, the place became so dark that for a moment the only things they could see were the bunches of shivering blue flames on the walls and their ghostly reflections in the floor below.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 In his dream, Harry had always walked purposefully across this room to the door immediately opposite the entrance and walked on. But there were around a dozen doors here. Just as he was gazing ahead at the doors opposite him, trying to decide which was the right one, there was a great rumbling noise and the candles began to move side\-ways. The circular wall was rotating.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Hermione grabbed Harry\rquote s arm as though frightened the floor might move too, but it did not. For a few seconds the blue flames around them were blurred to resemble neon lines as the wall sped\lang3081  \lang1033 around and then, quite as suddenly as it had started, the rumbling stopped and everything became stationary once again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry\rquote s eyes had blue streaks burned into them; it was all he could see.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What was that about?\rdblquote  whispered Ron fearfully.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I think it was to stop us knowing which door we came in from,\rdblquote  said Ginny in a hushed voice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry realized at once that she was right: He could no sooner have picked the exit from the other doors than located an ant upon the jet-black floor. Meanwhile, the door through which they needed to pro\-ceed could be any of the dozen surrounding them.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How\rquote re we going to get back out?\rdblquote  said Neville uncomfortably.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well, that doesn\rquote t matter now,\rdblquote  said Harry forcefully, blinking to try and erase the blue lines from his vision, and clutching his wand tighter than ever. \ldblquote We won\rquote t need to get out till we\rquote ve found Sirius \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Don\rquote t go calling for him, though!\rdblquote  Hermione said urgently, but Harry had never needed her advice less; his instinct was to keep as quiet as possible for the time being.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Where do we go, then, Harry?\rdblquote  Ron asked.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t \emdash\rdblquote  Harry began. He swallowed. \ldblquote In the dreams I went through the door at the end of the corridor from the lifts into a dark room \emdash  that\rquote s this one \emdash  and then I went through another door into a room that kind of\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 glitters. We should try a few doors,\rdblquote  he said hastily. \ldblquote I\rquote ll know the right way when I see it. C\rquote mon.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He marched straight at the door now facing him, the others follow\-ing close behind him, set his left hand against its cool, shining surface, raised his wand, ready to strike the moment it opened, and pushed. It swung open easily.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 After the darkness of the first room, the lamps hanging low on golden chains from this ceiling gave the impression that this long rec\-tangular room was much brighter, though there were no glittering, shimmering lights such as Harry had seen in his dreams. The place\lang3081  \lang1033 was quite empty except for a few desks and, in the very middle of the room, an enormous glass tank of deep-green water, big enough for all of them to swim in, which contained a number of pearly white objects that were drifting around lazily in the liquid.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What\rquote re those things?\rdblquote  whispered Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Dunno,\rdblquote  said Harry.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Are they fish?\rdblquote  breathed Ginny.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Aquavirius maggots!\rdblquote  said Luna excitedly. \ldblquote Dad said the Ministry were breeding \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Hermione. She sounded odd. She moved forward to look through the side of the tank. \ldblquote They\rquote re brains.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Brains\i0 ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes \'85 I wonder what they\rquote re doing with them?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry joined her at the tank. Sure enough, there could be no mis\-take now that he saw them at close quarters. Glimmering eerily they drifted in and out of sight in the depths of the green water, looking something like slimy cauliflowers.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Let\rquote s get out of here,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote This isn\rquote t right, we need to try another door \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote There are doors here too,\rdblquote  said Ron, pointing around the walls. Harry\rquote s heart sank; how big was this place?\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote In my dream I went through that dark room into the second one,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote I think we should go back and try from there.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 So they hurried back into the dark, circular room; the ghostly shapes of the brains were now swimming before Harry\rquote s eyes instead of the blue candle flames.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Wait!\rdblquote  said Hermione sharply, as Luna made to close the door of the brain room behind them. \ldblquote\i Flagrate\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She drew with her wand in midair and a fiery \lang3081 X \lang1033 appeared on the door. No sooner had the door clicked shut behind them than there was a great rumbling, and once again the wall began to revolve very fast, but now there was a great red-gold blur in amongst the faint blue,\lang3081  \lang1033 and when all became still again, the fiery cross still burned, showing the door they had already tried.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Good thinking,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote Okay, let\rquote s try this one \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Again he strode directly at the door facing him and pushed it open, his wand still raised, the others at his heels.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 This room was larger than the last, dimly lit and rectangular, and the center of it was sunken, forming a great stone pit some twenty feet be\-low them. They were standing on the topmost tier of what seemed to be stone benches running all around the room and descending in steep steps like an amphitheater, or the courtroom in which Harry had been tried by the Wizengamot. Instead of a chained chair, however, there was a raised stone dais in the center of the lowered floor, and upon this dais stood a stone archway that looked so ancient, cracked, and crumbling that Harry was amazed the thing was still standing. Unsupported by any surrounding wall, the archway was hung with a tattered black cur\-tain or veil which, despite the complete stillness of the cold surround\-ing air, was fluttering very slightly as though it had just been touched.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Who\rquote s there?\rdblquote  said Harry, jumping down onto the bench below. There was no answering voice, but the veil continued to flutter and sway.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Careful!\rdblquote  whispered Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry scrambled down the benches one by one until he reached the stone bottom of the sunken pit. His footsteps echoed loudly as he walked slowly toward the dais. The pointed archway looked much taller from where he stood now than when he had been looking down on it from above. Still the veil swayed gently, as though somebody had just passed through it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sirius?\rdblquote  Harry spoke again, but much more quietly now that he was nearer.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He had the strangest feeling that there was someone standing right behind the veil on the other side of the archway. Gripping his wand very tightly, he edged around the dais, but there was nobody there. All that could be seen was the other side of the tattered black veil.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Let\rquote s go,\rdblquote  called Hermione from halfway up the stone steps. \ldblquote This isn\rquote t right, Harry, come on, let\rquote s go. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She sounded scared, much more scared than she had in the room where the brains swam, yet Harry thought the archway had a kind of beauty about it, old though it was. The gently rippling veil intrigued him; he felt a very strong inclination to climb up on the dais and walk through it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry, let\rquote s go, okay?\rdblquote  said Hermione more forcefully.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Okay,\rdblquote  he said, but he did not move. He had just heard some\-thing. There were faint whispering, murmuring noises coming from the other side of the veil.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What are you saying?\rdblquote  he said very loudly, so that the words echoed all around the surrounding stone benches.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Nobody\rquote s talking, Harry!\rdblquote  said Hermione, now moving over to him.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Someone\rquote s whispering behind there,\rdblquote  he said, moving out of her reach and continuing to frown at the veil. \ldblquote Is that you, Ron?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I\rquote m here, mate,\rdblquote  said Ron, appearing around the side of the arch\-way.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Can\rquote t anyone else hear it?\rdblquote  Harry demanded, for the whispering and murmuring was becoming louder; without really meaning to put it there, he found his foot was on the dais.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I can hear them too,\rdblquote  breathed Luna, joining them around the side of the archway and gazing at the swaying veil. \ldblquote There are people \i in there\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What do you mean, \lquote\i in there\i0\rquote ?\rdblquote  demanded Hermione, jumping down from the bottom step and sounding much angrier than the oc\-casion warranted. \ldblquote There isn\rquote t any \lquote\i in there,\i0\rquote  it\rquote s just an archway, there\rquote s no room for anybody to be there \emdash  Harry, stop it, come away \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 She grabbed his arm and pulled, but he resisted.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry, we are supposed to be here for Sirius!\rdblquote  she said in a high-pitched, strained voice.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sirius,\rdblquote  Harry repeated, still gazing, mesmerized, at the continu\-ously swaying veil. \ldblquote Yeah \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And then something slid back into place in his brain: Sirius, cap\-tured, bound, and tortured, and he was staring at this archway. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He took several paces back from the dais and wrenched his eyes from the veil.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Let\rquote s go,\rdblquote  he said.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That\rquote s what I\rquote ve been trying to \emdash  well, come on, then!\rdblquote  said Hermione, and she led the way back around the dais. On the other side, Ginny and Neville were staring, apparently entranced, at the veil too. Without speaking, Hermione took hold of Ginny\rquote s arm, Ron Neville\rquote s, and they marched them firmly back to the lowest stone bench and clambered all the way back up to the door.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What d\rquote you reckon that arch was?\rdblquote  Harry asked Hermione as they regained the dark circular room.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I don\rquote t know, but whatever it was, it was dangerous,\rdblquote  she said firmly, again inscribing a fiery cross upon the door.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Once more the wall spun and became still again. Harry approached a door at random and pushed. It did not move.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What\rquote s wrong?\rdblquote  said Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s \'85 locked \'85\rdblquote  said Harry, throwing his weight at the door, but it did not budge.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote This is it, then, isn\rquote t it?\rdblquote  said Ron excitedly, joining Harry in the attempt to force the door open. \ldblquote Bound to be!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Get out of the way!\rdblquote  said Hermione sharply. She pointed her wand at the place where a lock would have been on an ordinary door and said, \ldblquote\i Alohomora\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Nothing happened.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Sirius\rquote s knife!\rdblquote  said Harry, and he pulled it out from inside his robes and slid it into the crack between the door and the wall. The others all watched eagerly as he ran it from top to bottom, withdrew it, and then flung his shoulder again at the door. It remained as firmly\lang3081  \lang1033 shut as ever. What was more, when Harry looked down at the knife, he saw that the blade had melted.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Right, we\rquote re leaving that room,\rdblquote  said Hermione decisively.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But what if that\rquote s the one?\rdblquote  said Ron, staring at it with a mixture of apprehension and longing.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It can\rquote t be, Harry could get through all the doors in his dream,\rdblquote  said Hermione, marking the door with another fiery cross as Harry re\-placed the now-useless handle of Sirius\rquote s knife in his pocket.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You know what could be in there?\rdblquote  said Luna eagerly, as the wall started to spin yet again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Something blibbering, no doubt,\rdblquote  said Hermione under her breath, and Neville gave a nervous little laugh.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 The wall slid back to a halt and Harry, with a feeling of increasing desperation, pushed the next door open.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i This is it\i0 !\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He knew it at once by the beautiful, dancing, diamond-sparkling light. As Harry\rquote s eyes became more accustomed to the brilliant glare he saw clocks gleaming from every surface, large and small, grandfa\-ther and carriage, hanging in spaces between the bookcases or stand\-ing on desks ranging the length of the room, so that a busy, relentless ticking filled the place like thousands of minuscule, marching foot\-steps. The source of the dancing, diamond-bright light was a towering crystal bell jar that stood at the far end of the room.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote This way!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry\rquote s heart was pumping frantically now that he knew they were on the right track. He led the way forward down the narrow space be\-tween the lines of the desks, heading, as he had done in his dream, for the source of the light, the crystal bell jar quite as tall as he was that stood on a desk and appeared to be full of a billowing, glittering wind.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh \i look\i0 !\rdblquote  said Ginny, as they drew nearer, pointing at the very heart of the bell jar.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Drifting along in the sparkling current inside was a tiny, jewel-bright egg. As it rose in the jar it cracked open and a hummingbird emerged, which was carried to the very top of the jar, but as it fell on the draft, its feathers became bedraggled and damp again, and by the time it had been borne back to the bottom of the jar it had been en\-closed once more in its egg.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Keep going!\rdblquote  said Harry sharply, because Ginny showed signs of wanting to stop and watch the egg\rquote s progress back into a bird.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You dawdled enough by that old arch!\rdblquote  she said crossly, but fol\-lowed him past the bell jar to the only door behind it.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote This is it,\rdblquote  Harry said again, and his heart was now pumping so hard and fast he felt it must interfere with his speech. \ldblquote It\rquote s through here \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He glanced around at them all. They had their wands out and looked suddenly serious and anxious. He looked back at the door and pushed. It swung open.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They were there, they had found the place: high as a church and full of nothing but towering shelves covered in small, dusty, glass orbs. They glimmered dully in the light issuing from more candle brackets set at intervals along the shelves. Like those in the circular room be\-hind them, their flames were burning blue. The room was very cold.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry edged forward and peered down one of the shadowy aisles between two rows of shelves. He could not hear anything nor see the slightest sign of movement.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote You said it was row ninety-seven,\rdblquote  whispered Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah,\rdblquote  breathed Harry, looking up at the end of the closest row. Beneath the branch of blue-glowing candles protruding from it glim\-mered the silver figure 53.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We need to go right, I think,\rdblquote  whispered Hermione, squinting to the next row. \ldblquote Yes \'85 that\rquote s fifty-four. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Keep your wands out,\rdblquote  Harry said softly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They crept forward, staring behind them as they went on down the\lang3081  \lang1033 long alleys of shelves, the farther ends of which were in near total darkness. Tiny, yellowing labels had been stuck beneath each glass orb on the shelf. Some of them had a weird, liquid glow; others were as dull and dark within as blown lightbulbs.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They passed row eighty-four \'85 eighty-five \'85 Harry was listen\-ing hard for the slightest sound of movement, but Sirius might be gagged now, or else unconscious \'85 \i or,\i0  said an unbidden voice inside his head, \i he might already be dead. \'85\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\i I\rquote d have felt it,\i0  he told himself, his heart now hammering against his Adam\rquote s apple. \i I\rquote d already know. \'85\lang3081\i0\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ninety-seven!\rdblquote  whispered Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They stood grouped around the end of the row, gazing down the alley beside it. There was nobody there.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He\rquote s right down at the end,\rdblquote  said Harry, whose mouth had be\-come slightly dry. \ldblquote You can\rquote t see properly from here. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 And he led them forward, between the towering rows of glass balls, some of which glowed softly as they passed. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He should be near here,\rdblquote  whispered Harry, convinced that every step was going to bring the ragged form of Sirius into view upon the darkened floor. \ldblquote Anywhere here \'85 really close \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry?\rdblquote  said Hermione tentatively, but he did not want to re\-spond. His mouth was very dry now.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Somewhere about\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 here \'85\rdblquote  he said.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 They had reached the end of the row and emerged into more dim candlelight. There was nobody there at all. All was echoing, dusty silence.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He might be \'85\rdblquote  Harry whispered hoarsely, peering down the alley next door. \ldblquote Or maybe \'85\rdblquote  He hurried to look down the one beyond that.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry?\rdblquote  said Hermione again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What?\rdblquote  he snarled.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I \'85 I don\rquote t think Sirius is here.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Nobody spoke. Harry did not want to look at any of them. He felt sick. He did not understand why Sirius was not here. He had to be here. This was where he, Harry, had seen him. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He ran up the space at the end of the rows, staring down them. Empty aisle after empty aisle flickered past. He ran the other way, back past his staring companions. There was no sign of Sirius any\-where, nor any hint of a struggle.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry?\rdblquote  Ron called.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He did not want to hear what Ron had to say, did not want to hear Ron tell him he had been stupid, or suggest that they ought to go back to Hogwarts. But the heat was rising in his face and he felt as though he would like to skulk down here in the darkness for a long while be\-fore facing the brightness of the Atrium above and the others\rquote  accus\-ing stares. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Have you seen this?\rdblquote  said Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What?\rdblquote  said Harry, but eagerly this time \emdash  it had to be a sign that Sirius had been there, a clue \emdash  he strode back to where they were all standing, a little way down row ninety-seven, but found nothing ex\-cept Ron staring at one of the dusty glass spheres on the shelves.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What?\rdblquote  Harry repeated glumly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It\rquote s \emdash  it\rquote s got your name on,\rdblquote  said Ron.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry moved a little closer. Ron was pointing at one of the small glass spheres that glowed with a dull inner light, though it was very dusty and appeared not to have been touched for many years.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote My name?\rdblquote  said Harry blankly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He stepped forward. Not as tall as Ron, he had to crane his neck to read the yellowish label affixed to the shelf right beneath the dusty glass ball. In spidery writing was written a date of some sixteen years previously, and below that:\par
\lang3081\par
\pard\qc\lang1033\i S.P.T. to A.P.W.B.D.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Dark Lord\par
and (?) Harry Potter\par
