\lang1033\ldblquote You are forgetting the next part of the prophecy, the final identi\-fying feature of the boy who could vanquish Voldemort. \'85 Volde\-mort himself would \lquote mark him as his equal.\rquote  And so he did, Harry. He chose you, not Neville. He gave you the scar that has proved both blessing and curse.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But he might have chosen wrong!\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote He might have marked the wrong person!\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He chose the boy he thought most likely to be a danger to him,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore. \ldblquote And notice this, Harry. He chose, not the pureblood (which, according to his creed, is the only kind of wizard worth being or knowing), but the half-blood, like himself. He saw himself in you be\-fore he had ever seen you, and in marking you with that scar, he did not kill you, as he intended, but gave you powers, and a future, which have fitted you to escape him not once, but four times so far \emdash  something that neither your parents, nor Neville\rquote s parents, ever achieved.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Why did he do it, then?\rdblquote  said Harry, who felt numb and cold. \ldblquote Why did he try and kill me as a baby? He should have waited to see whether Neville or I looked more dangerous when we were older and tried to kill whoever it was then \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote That might, indeed, have been the more practical course,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore, \ldblquote except that Voldemort\rquote s information about the prophecy was incomplete. The Hog\rquote s Head Inn, which Sibyll chose for its cheapness, has long attracted, shall we say, a more interesting clientele than the Three Broomsticks. As you and your friends found out to your cost, and I to mine that night, it is a place where it is never safe to assume you are not being overheard. Of course, I had not dreamed, when I set out to meet Sibyll Trelawney, that I would hear anything worth overhearing. My \emdash  our \emdash  one stroke of good for\-tune was that the eavesdropper was detected only a short way into the prophecy and thrown from the building.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So he only heard \'85 ?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote He heard only the first part, the part foretelling the birth of a boy in July to parents who had thrice defied Voldemort. Consequently, he could not warn his master that to attack you would be to risk trans\-ferring power to you \emdash  again marking you as his equal. So Voldemort never knew that there might be danger in attacking you, that it might be wise to wait or to learn more. He did not know that you would have \lquote power the Dark Lord knows not\rquote  \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote But I don\rquote t!\rdblquote  said Harry in a strangled voice. \ldblquote I haven\rquote t any powers he hasn\rquote t got, I couldn\rquote t fight the way he did tonight, I can\rquote t possess people or \emdash  or kill them \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote There is a room in the Department of Mysteries,\rdblquote  interrupted Dumbledore, \ldblquote that is kept locked at all times. It contains a force that is at once more wonderful and more terrible than death, than human intelligence, than forces of nature. It is also, perhaps, the most myste\-rious of the many subjects for study that reside there. It is the power held within that room that you possess in such quantities and which\lang3081  \lang1033 Voldemort has not at all. That power took you to save Sirius tonight. That power also saved you from possession by Voldemort, because he could not bear to reside in a body so full of the force he detests. In the end, it mattered not that you could not close your mind. It was your heart that saved you.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry closed his eyes. If he had not gone to save Sirius, Sirius would not have died. \'85 More to stave off the moment when he would have to think of Sirius again, Harry asked, without caring much about the answer, \ldblquote The end of the prophecy \'85 it was some\-thing about\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 \lquote\i neither can live. \'85\lang3081\i0\rquote  \rdblquote\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \lquote\'85\i  while the other survives,\i0\rquote  \rdblquote\i  \i0 said Dumbledore.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote So,\rdblquote  said Harry, dredging up the words from what felt like a deep well of despair inside him, \ldblquote so does that mean that\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 that one of us has got to kill the other one \'85 in the end?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 For a long time, neither of them spoke. Somewhere far beyond the office walls, Harry could hear the sound of voices, students heading down to the Great Hall for an early breakfast, perhaps. It seemed im\-possible that there could be people in the world who still desired food, who laughed, who neither knew nor cared that Sirius Black was gone forever. Sirius seemed a million miles away already, even if a part of Harry still believed that if he had only pulled back that veil, he would have found Sirius looking back at him, greeting him, perhaps, with his laugh like a bark. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I feel I owe you another explanation, Harry,\rdblquote  said Dumbledore hesitantly. \ldblquote You may, perhaps, have wondered why I never chose you as a prefect? I must confess \'85 that I rather thought\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 you had enough responsibility to be going on with.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
