\lang1033\ldblquote Bet Dumbledore wishes he could\rquote ve got rid of Trelawney for good,\rdblquote  said Ron, now munching on his fourteenth Frog. \ldblquote Mind you, the whole subjects useless if you ask me, Firenze isn\rquote t a lot better. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote How can you say that?\rdblquote  Hermione demanded. \ldblquote After we\rquote ve just found out that there are real prophecies?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry\rquote s heart began to race. He had not told Ron, Hermione, or anyone else what the prophecy had contained. Neville had told them it had smashed while Harry was pulling him up the steps in the Death Room, and Harry had not yet corrected this impression. He was not ready to see their expressions when he told them that he must be ei\-ther murderer or victim, there was no other way. \'85\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote It is a pity it broke,\rdblquote  said Hermione quietly, shaking her head.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, it is,\rdblquote  said Ron. \ldblquote Still, at least You-Know-Who never found out what was in it either \emdash  where are you going?\rdblquote  he added, looking both surprised and disappointed as Harry stood up.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Er \emdash  Hagrid\rquote s,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote You know, he just got back and I promised I\rquote d go down and see him and tell him how you two are. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh all right then,\rdblquote  said Ron grumpily, looking out of the dormi\-tory window at the patch of bright blue sky beyond. \ldblquote Wish we could come \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
