\lang1033\ldblquote WHAT?\rdblquote  shouted Ron, upending the chessboard. Crookshanks went plunging after the pieces and Hedwig and Pigwidgeon twittered and hooted angrily from overhead.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 As the train slowed down in the approach to King\rquote s Cross, Harry thought he had never wanted to leave it less. He even wondered fleet\-ingly what would happen if he simply refused to get off, but remained\lang3081  \lang1033 stubbornly sitting there until the first of September, when it would take him back to Hogwarts. When it finally puffed to a standstill, however, he lifted down Hedwig\rquote s cage and prepared to drag his trunk from the train as usual.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 When the ticket inspector signaled to him, Ron, and Hermione that it was safe to walk through the magical barrier between platforms nine and ten, however, he found a surprise awaiting him on the other side: a group of people standing there to greet him whom he had not expected at all.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 There was Mad-Eye Moody, looking quite as sinister with his bowler hat pulled low over his magical eye as he would have done without it, his gnarled hands clutching a long staff, his body wrapped in a voluminous traveling cloak. Tonks stood just behind him, her bright bubble-gum-pink hair gleaming in the sunlight filtering through the dirty glass station ceiling, wearing heavily patched jeans and a bright purple T-shirt bearing the legend THE WEIRD SISTERS. Next to Tonks was Lupin, his face pale, his hair graying, a long and threadbare overcoat covering a shabby jumper and trousers. At the front of the group stood Mr. and Mrs. Weasley, dressed in their Mug\-gle best, and Fred and George, who were both wearing brand-new jackets in some lurid green, scaly material.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ron, Ginny!\rdblquote  called Mrs. Weasley, hurrying forward and hugging her children tightly. \ldblquote Oh, and Harry dear \emdash  how are you?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Fine,\rdblquote  lied Harry, as she pulled him into a tight embrace. Over her shoulder he saw Ron goggling at the twins\rquote  new clothes.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote What are \i they\i0  supposed to be?\rdblquote  he asked, pointing at the jackets.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Finest dragon skin, little bro,\rdblquote  said Fred, giving his zip a little tweak. \ldblquote Business is booming and we thought we\rquote d treat ourselves.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hello, Harry,\rdblquote  said Lupin, as Mrs. Weasley let go of Harry and turned to greet Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Hi,\rdblquote  said Harry. \ldblquote I didn\rquote t expect\lang3081  \lang1033\'85 what are you all doing here?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well,\rdblquote  said Lupin with a slight smile, \ldblquote we thought we might have a little chat with your aunt and uncle before letting them take you home.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I dunno if that\rquote s a good idea,\rdblquote  said Harry at once.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Oh, I think it is,\rdblquote  growled Moody, who had limped a little closer. \ldblquote That\rquote ll be them, will it, Potter?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He pointed with his thumb over his shoulder; his magical eye was evidently peering through the back of his head and his bowler hat. Harry leaned an inch or so to the left to see where Mad-Eye was point\-ing and there, sure enough, were the three Dursleys, who looked positively appalled to see Harry\rquote s reception committee.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Ah, Harry!\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, turning from Hermione\rquote s parents, whom he had been greeting enthusiastically, and who were taking it in turns to hug Hermione. \ldblquote Well \emdash  shall we do it, then?\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, I reckon so, Arthur,\rdblquote  said Moody.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He and Mr. Weasley took the lead across the station toward the place where the Dursleys stood, apparently rooted to the floor. Hermione disengaged herself gently from her mother to join the group.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Good afternoon,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley pleasantly to Uncle Vernon, coming to a halt right in front of him. \ldblquote You might remember me, my name\rquote s Arthur Weasley.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 As Mr. Weasley had singlehandedly demolished most of the Durs\-leys\rquote  living room two years previously, Harry would have been very surprised if Uncle Vernon had forgotten him. Sure enough, Uncle Vernon turned a deeper shade of puce and glared at Mr. Weasley, but chose not to say anything, partly, perhaps, because the Dursleys were outnumbered two to one. Aunt Petunia looked both frightened and embarrassed. She kept glancing around, as though terrified somebody she knew would see her in such company. Dudley, meanwhile, seemed to be trying to look small and insignificant, a feat at which he was fail\-ing extravagantly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We thought we\rquote d just have a few words with you about Harry,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, still smiling.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah,\rdblquote  growled Moody. \ldblquote About how he\rquote s treated when he\rquote s at your place.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Uncle Vernon\rquote s mustache seemed to bristle with indignation. Possi\-bly because the bowler hat gave him the entirely mistaken impression that he was dealing with a kindred spirit, he addressed himself to Moody.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I am not aware that it is any of your business what goes on in my house \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote I expect what you\rquote re not aware of would fill several books, Durs\-ley,\rdblquote  growled Moody.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Anyway, that\rquote s not the point,\rdblquote  interjected Tonks, whose pink hair seemed to offend Aunt Petunia more than all the rest put together, for she closed her eyes rather than look at her. \ldblquote The point is, if we find out you\rquote ve been horrible to Harry \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\emdash  and make no mistake, we\rquote ll hear about it,\rdblquote  added Lupin pleasantly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Mr. Weasley, \ldblquote even if you won\rquote t let Harry use the fellytone \emdash\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote\i Telephone,\i0\rdblquote\lang3081  \lang1033 whispered Hermione.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yeah, if we get any hint that Potter\rquote s been mistreated in any way, you\rquote ll have us to answer to,\rdblquote  said Moody.\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Uncle Vernon swelled ominously. His sense of outrage seemed to outweigh even his fear of this bunch of oddballs.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Are you threatening me, sir?\rdblquote  he said, so loudly that passersby ac\-tually turned to stare.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Yes, I am,\rdblquote  said Mad-Eye, who seemed rather pleased that Uncle Vernon had grasped this fact so quickly.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote And do I look like the kind of man who can be intimidated?\rdblquote  barked Uncle Vernon.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Well\lang3081  \lang1033\'85\rdblquote  said Moody, pushing back his bowler hat to reveal his\lang3081  \lang1033 sinisterly revolving magical eye. Uncle Vernon leapt backward in hor\-ror and collided painfully with a luggage trolley. \ldblquote Yes, I\rquote d have to say you do, Dursley.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 He turned from Uncle Vernon to Harry. \ldblquote So, Potter \'85 give us a shout if you need us. If we don\rquote t hear from you for three days in a row, we\rquote ll send someone along. \'85\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Aunt Petunia whimpered piteously. It could not have been plainer that she was thinking of what the neighbors would say if they caught sight of these people marching up the garden path.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote  \rquote Bye, then, Potter,\rdblquote  said Moody, grasping Harry\rquote s shoulder for a moment with a gnarled hand.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Take care, Harry,\rdblquote  said Lupin quietly. \ldblquote Keep in touch.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Harry, we\rquote ll have you away from there as soon as we can,\rdblquote  Mrs. Weasley whispered, hugging him again.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote We\rquote ll see you soon, mate,\rdblquote  said Ron anxiously, shaking Harry\rquote s hand.\lang3081\par
\lang1033\ldblquote Really soon, Harry,\rdblquote  said Hermione earnestly. \ldblquote We promise.\rdblquote\lang3081\par
\lang1033 Harry nodded. He somehow could not find words to tell them what it meant to him, to see them all ranged there, on his side. Instead he smiled, raised a hand in farewell, turned around, and led the way out of the station toward the sunlit street, with Uncle Vernon, Aunt Petunia, and Dudley hurrying along in his wake.\lang3081\par
